<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>EnergyEfficient.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Energy-efficient Buildings</FONT></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task</FONT></TD> <TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>To ensure that buildings are comfortable and 
functional</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>



When confronted with the challenge of making buildings comfortable, many 
people think 
of installing effective heating and cooling equipment. But 
properly-designed buildings 
require much less heating and cooling energy, and cheaper, simpler 
heating and cooling equipment to maintain standards of comfort higher 
than can be achieved in buildings 
that are not energy efficient. Installing insulation in buildings not 
only provides 
comfort but also shuts out noise.
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Limit heat flows through ceilings and 
walls</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Insulation reduces the heat flow through walls and ceilings by up to 
90 per cent. 
Australian Standard 2627 lists recommended cost-effective insulation 
values for locations 
throughout Australia. These call for, at a minimum, reflective foil 
insulation in 
the walls and foil plus 50 mm blanket in the roof in mild climates, and 
at least R1.5 
batts in walls and R3 bulk insulation in ceilings in colder 
climates.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Installation of reflective foil is recommended in sunny areas or 
climates with cold, 
clear nights, as it improves comfort and acts as a vapour barrier. 
Reflective foil 
requires an airspace next to the shiny surface to act as an insulator. 
Ensure that 
foil is not sandwiched between the ceiling lining and the roofing, as 
this negates its 
insulating properties.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>In hot humid climates or cold climates, a vapour barrier will 
minimise the risk of 
condensation in the insulation and possible damage to the building 
structure.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Light-coloured, well-ventilated roofs are cooler than dark 
ones.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Shading roofs and walls reduces heat gain. Trees, verandahs and 
pergolas can also 
be attractive.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Limit heat flows through windows</FONT></TD></TR>


<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Heat is lost through single-glazed windows ten times faster than 
through insulated 
walls. Double glazing or a tight-fitting curtain almost halves this loss; 
double 
glazing with 'low-E' glass cuts heat loss by about 70 per 
cent.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Curtains and blinds are most effective when they seal tightly around 
the window. Fitting 
a pelmet can double the effectiveness of a curtain.</UL></TD></TR> 
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>In direct sun, a square metre of window allows in as much heat as 
that emitted by 
a single bar radiator. It is therefore important to shade windows from 
direct sun 
in hot weather. This cuts heat gain by 80 per cent.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>North-facing windows can collect large amounts of solar energy in 
winter. However, 
windows that are too large can lead to summer overheating and large heat 
losses during 
winter nights.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Control ventilation and draughts</FONT></TD></TR>


<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Where heating or air conditioning is used, limit air leakage into a 
building and avoid 
running exhaust fans for long periods, as excess outside air increases 
energy consumption 
for heating and cooling.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Controllable cross-ventilation, aided by ceiling fans and windows and 
louvres that 
seal tightly when closed, can avoid or limit the need for artificial 
cooling. The 
climate of an area must be understood before constructing a building so 
windows can 
be located to take advantage of breezes.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Designing for energy efficiency</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>The size and shape of a building, and the sizes and zoning of areas 
within it, influence 
total energy consumption.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Using rules of thumb to design for energy efficiency can be 
misleading. Heat flow 
calculations and computer analysis should be used to identify major areas 
of heat 
gain and loss.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Building design contracts should provide calculations for energy 
consumption and estimates 
of capital and running cost for a range of design options. Intelligent 
application 
of energy-efficient design principles can often achieve large ongoing 
savings at 
little or no extra capital cost when savings in the cost of heating and 
cooling equipment 
are considered.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Success stories</B></FONT>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">The main building at Kingfisher Bay Resort, Fraser 
Island, Queensland, has many energy-efficient 
design features to achieve year-round comfort, despite Fraser Island's 
warm climate. 
These include shading by native trees and roof overhangs; ventilation via 
louvred walls, large doors and windows located near the ceiling; ceiling 
fans under 
high ceilings; and light-coloured roofing.
<P ALIGN="LEFT">The accommodation units at Freycinet Lodge in Tasmania 
are fully insulated. They have 
moderately sized windows and heavy, lined curtains with pelmets, as well 
as entrances 
which act as air-locks to limit cold draughts.
</BODY>
</HTML>
