<DOCNO>WT06-B34-11</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B046-270</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://tourism.tourism.gov.au:80/publications/BPE/Dishwashing.html 192.199.45.253 19970108084934 text/html 5902
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:49:29 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 5696
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 22:28:43 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dishwashing.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Dishwashing</FONT></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5> To clean dishes, pots and pans, and kitchen 
utensils</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

Dishwashing consumes water, energy (in the form of hot water) and 
chemicals (in the 
form of detergent) and generates water which requires treatment.<P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>In accommodation</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>

<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Minimise hot water usage for 
dishwashing</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Scrape excess food off dishes rather than rinsing it off with water. 
If rinsing dishes 
as well, put the plug in the sink. Rinsing dishes under running hot water 
can waste 
several litres of water per minute.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Inefficient stacking of dishwashers is very common. Fully load 
dishwashers and pack 
efficiently to use their capacity effectively.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Select an energy and water-efficient 
dishwasher</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Different dishwashers and wash programs use very different amounts of 
water and energy. 
Choose the most water-efficient dishwasher and use a water-efficient 
cycle. For domestic 
models, refer to energy labels or <CITE>Choice </CITE>
magazine. For commercial models, ask the manufacturer about energy and 
water consumption.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Washing up in a domestic sink uses around 15 litres of water. Larger 
commercial sinks 
may require 40 litres per fill. In comparison, water-efficient domestic 
dishwashers 
use as little as 15 litres on economy cycles (generally to wash more 
dishes than 
can be washed in a sink).</UL></TD></TR></TABLE> 
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Select low-environmental impact 
detergents</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>The phosphorus compounds in many dishwashing detergents may 
contribute to environmental 
problems such as algal blooms. Many detergents now carry 'NP' (No 
Phosphorus) and 
'P' (reduced Phosphorus) labels. Given that N is the chemical symbol for 
nitrogen 
and P stands for phosphorus, these may cause confusion among some 
consumers.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Reputable manufacturers of detergents for commercial use now provide 
detailed Material 
Safety Data Sheets on request. Always ask for these and compare 
them.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>As some cleaning products are not compatible with some waste 
treatment systems, it 
is wise to check.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE><P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>On tour</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Wash dishes instead of using disposable paper and 
plastic dishes</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>On principle, ecotourism should not involve undue use of disposable 
items, no matter 
how well the waste is managed.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Cups can be colour-coded and assigned to specific individuals for a 
day, instead of 
being washed repeatedly.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Dishes can be scraped clean and stored in sealed bags until the end 
of the day, when 
all the washing up can be done at one time. This saves time and 
water.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Do not use detergents or soaps if dishwashing waste water will be 
discharged directly 
into the environment.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Wash all dishes at least 50 metres away from lakes and streams, 
scatter the wastewater 
so that it filters through the soil before returning to the 
stream.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Success stories</B></FONT>
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Odyssey Safaris in the Northern Territory uses 
colour-coded cups assigned to individual 
clients for drinking. They are washed by staff at the end of each day. 
Unbreakable 
plastic plates and dishes and stainless steel cutlery are also used. This 
approach 
saves storage space, money and time, and creates a positive environmental 
image.
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT06-B34-12</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B046-281</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://tourism.tourism.gov.au:80/publications/BPE/Handwashing.html 192.199.45.253 19970108084946 text/html 9084
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:49:40 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 8878
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 06:06:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Handwashing.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Hand-washing,showering and bathing</FONT></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>To achieve personal hygiene while minimising 
environmental impact from water supply 
(including water heating), soaps and shampoos and 
dryers</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

These activities may consume more than half of the hot water used in a 
tourism operation.<P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>Water use</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Install water-efficient 
showerheads</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Water-efficient showerheads vary greatly in cost and the quality of 
shower delivered 
(some of the cheaper ones are among the best while the more expensive 
ones are not 
as good). When shopping for shower heads, try some first and buy the 
cheapest that 
works well. To gain an AAA water efficiency rating showerheads only have 
to meet a standard 
of 9 litres per minute. Some currently on the market achieve 6 litres per 
minute 
but most people do not like using them. Models that combine showering 
quality with 
a flow rate of 6 litres per minute are being developed.</UL></TD></TR> 
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>User satisfaction with water-efficient showers is much lower if there 
is excessive 
air movement in a bathroom (from an exhaust fan or draughts), as the 
moving air evaporatively 
cools the person's body. Install an exhaust fan away from the shower, and 
do not wire the exhaust fan into the bathroom light 
switch.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>To keep existing showerheads but save water, insert a flow control 
disc/washer. These 
cost $2 to $5 and are available in 12, 9 and 6 litres per minute 
versions. Standard 
showerheads have flow rates of 18 to 24 litres per 
minute.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Fit tap aerators and flow 
controls</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Aerators reduce water flow and improve wetting. They are an integral 
part of many 
modern tap fittings or can be retrofitted to older taps.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Tap flow controls vary from simple washer-like devices to systems 
which balance water 
flow and pressures throughout a building.</UL></TD></TR> 
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Where low-flow taps are installed, 10 mm pipes may often be used 
instead of 15 mm 
pipes, reducing cost and heat losses in pipes, and halving the amount of 
water that 
must be drawn off before hot water reaches the 
tap.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Avoid mixer taps</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Most people use mixer taps with the mixer arm straight-ahead when 
they want only cold 
water. In this position, the tap delivers 50 per cent cold water and 50 
per cent 
hot water, thus wasting hot water.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Select baths carefully, to limit water 
requirements</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Standard baths hold 125 litres, while large spa baths hold 500 
litres. Select an appropriate 
size.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Prevent leaks</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>To prevent leaks select long-lasting tap washers and regularly 
inspect taps for leaks. 
Taking meter readings when little activity is occurring helps identify 
water loss.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Ensure taps are not left running</FONT></TD></TR>


<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Spring-loaded taps can be used in public/communal facilities but 
would probably be 
seen as a bit draconian in private facilities unless there were severe 
water shortages.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE><P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>Soaps and shampoos</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Use liquid dispensers</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Many operators have expressed concern about the excessive use of 
packaging materials 
involved in providing small serves of soap and shampoo. However, concern 
has also 
been expressed that clients would respond adversely to wall-mounted 
dispensers. If 
installing bulk dispensers, accompany them with explanatory material and 
still provide individual 
serves of soap and shampoo to clients who request 
them.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Minimise use while camping</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>In cases where washing waters are discharged straight into the 
environment, soaps 
and shampoos should not be used. If this is considered too stringent, do 
not use 
soaps anywhere near bodies of water.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Wash 50 metres away from streams and lakes and scatter the wastewater 
so it filters 
through the soil before returning to the 
stream.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE><P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>Drying</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Encourage the reuse of cloth towel before 
washing</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Many facilities are now successfully encouraging clients to use 
towels several times 
before putting them out for washing. The key to their success is 
providing information 
to clients and asking the clients to decide when towel-washing is 
desired.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Choosing between paper towels, electric hand 
dryers, and continuous roll cloth 
towels</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Many operators are seeking the definitive answer as to whether paper 
towels, electric 
blowers or continuous roll cloth towels are the best environmental option 
for drying 
hands in communal toilets. There is no simple answer. Recycled paper 
towels are preferable to non-recycled ones. Electric hand dryers with 
movement sensors are preferable 
to those with a push button timer. Continuous roll cloth towels without 
ready access 
to low impact laundering either on-site or within a short distance may 
not be a good 
environmental option unless usage rates are very high. Choosing between 
these alternatives 
will depend on operational efficiency and client 
preferences.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT06-B34-13</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B046-291</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://tourism.tourism.gov.au:80/publications/BPE/Refrigeration.html 192.199.45.253 19970108084956 text/html 13614
