Last-Modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 06:06:36 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Refrigeration.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Refrigeration</FONT></CENTER><HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% 
ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task</FONT></TD> <TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>To preserve food and beverages, and to chill 
drinks</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

Refrigerators play an important role in preserving food. Their energy use 
can generate 
up to 10 per cent of greenhouse gas emissions from accommodation units 
and 5 per 
cent of total emissions from a tourism operation.<P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>Refrigeration in accommodation</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Switch off equipment when it is not 
needed</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Refrigerators in vacant rooms do not have to run if no perishable 
items are left in 
them and should therefore be switched off.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Refrigerators with non-perishable drinks in them can be switched off 
overnight, achieving 
savings of up to 30 per cent. Time switches could be used to do this 
automatically.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>In quiet periods, refrigerated goods can be consolidated into a 
smaller number of 
refrigerators, so some refrigerators can be switched 
off.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Switch off lights</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Continuously operating internal lights in glass-fronted refrigerators 
and coldrooms 
use power directly and adds to the cooling load, making the compressor 
work harder. 
A 40-watt fluorescent tube and its ballast create a total load of around 
80 watts. 
Unless the lights are really needed, they should be disconnected or 
switched off.</UL></TD></TR> 
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Lighting up display signage on a drink vending machine can cost up to 
$120 a year 
to run, and generates a tonne of greenhouse gas. Unless the lights are 
really needed, 
they should be shut off.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Manage refrigeration equipment and 
supplies</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Running refrigeration equipment too cold by 1 degree can increase 
running cost by 
5 per cent. Maintain correct internal temperatures of all 
refrigerators.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Regularly check to ensure that doors shut properly and clean door 
seals to reduce 
running costs and slow build-up of frost.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Put delivered cold goods into refrigerators immediately to ensure 
they do not warm 
up.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Non-perishable goods such as soft drinks do not need to be stored in 
refrigerators 
until a few hours before they are served but should be kept in a cool 
place to minimise 
energy required to chill them.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Ensure refrigerator operation is not impaired by 
installation</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Good ventilation around coils on the backs of refrigerators is 
essential. Installing 
a bar-fridge in a timber cabinet without ventilation-common practice in 
motels-can 
increase running cost by 50 per cent and overwork the unit, so it cannot 
produce 
ice. Inlet and outlet ventilation slots, each at least 50 square 
centimetres, should be cut 
in the cabinet to allow substantial airflow. If noise is a problem, the 
refrigerator 
should be mounted on a rubber mat and the timber cabinet lined with 
sound-absorbing 
material.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Refrigeration units should not be placed in direct sun. The running 
costs for a glass-doored 
refrigerator can be doubled and the fridge's contents warmed if the 
fridge is in 
direct sun. </UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Refrigerators should not be located near hot equipment or in hot 
rooms. A 5&amp;#176;C 
increase in room temperature can increase running costs for refrigerators 
by 30 per 
cent.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Select suitable size and type of refrigeration 
equipment</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Larger refrigeration units usually use more energy although many 
cheap bar fridges 
can consume large amounts of energy.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Many commercial refrigeration units are much less efficient than 
domestic models of 
comparable capacity and cost more to buy. Evaluate whether a domestic 
unit will do 
the job.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Where it is important to minimise electricity use, such as, in 
instances when an establishment 
is not connected to the electricity grid, gas/LPG refrigerators can be 
used. Although 
more expensive to operate, gas refrigerators are 
silent.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Use energy consumption data </FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>The energy consumption numbers on energy labels of domestic 
refrigeration units are 
more useful than star ratings, as they give actual energy consumption. An 
annual 
saving of 200 kWh gives a lifetime (10-year) saving of around $300 and 
prevents the 
emission of two tonnes of greenhouse gas.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Ask potential suppliers of commercial equipment for data on running 
costs (in writing) 
so comparisons can be made. If they cannot provide such information, 
request them 
to measure energy consumption before you will consider buying, or advise 
the supplier 
in writing that you will return the appliance if its running cost is too 
high. </UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Avoid energy-guzzling equipment </FONT></TD></TR>


<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Running a drink vending machine can cost $300 or more annually and 
generate more than 
two tonnes of greenhouse gas. Running a glass-fronted fridge may cost 
$200 to $600 
annually. Minimise the number of refrigerators used.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Avoid using open refrigerated cabinets, as they are very inefficient. 
Where they are 
required, fit them with insulating blinds that can be pulled down 
overnight, or plastic 
strips that trap cold air but allow access to the produce in the 
cabinet.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Use waste heat from refrigeration 
equipment</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Use the waste heat generated by large refrigeration systems to heat 
water, provide 
space heating or dry clothes/linen (see Reference Sheet 7, 'Recovering 
Heat').</UL></TD></TR></TABLE><P>


<FONT SIZE=5><B>Refrigeration on tour</B></FONT>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Use non-perishable food</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>While on tour, use nonperishable foods which do not require 
refrigeration. Options 
include dried, tinned, vacuum-sealed, UHT-treated and long shelf-life 
foods. Aesthetics 
and client preferences will influence the degree to which these foods can 
be used.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Explore alternatives to refrigeration 
</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Frozen food and drinks, kept in a
very well insulated container, will remain cold for several days. Frozen 
containers 
of drink are particularly effective in cooling and can be used instead of 
ice blocks. 
Doubling the insulation thickness of a container can more than double the 
time food 
stays cold.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>To reduce the amount of food requiring refrigeration, obtain food 
while on tour when 
possible.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>At campsites, use Coolgardie safes or streams for 
cooling.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Select an appropriately-sized, energy-efficient 
refrigerator or freezer</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Portable refrigerators and freezers range in size from 35 to 150 
litres, and are available 
as fridges, freezers or combined fridge/freezers.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Portable units are either 12 or 24 volt DC, and 240 volt AC, or LPG 
fridges. LPG fridges 
are effective if power is not available. Twelve and 24-volt refrigeration 
systems 
can be run off car batteries, a dedicated battery during longer stops, or 
from photovoltaic panels, 240 volt fridges can be run from batteries with 
an inverter or from 
generators (which tend to be noisy and bulky). Many LPG fridges can also 
use electricity 
but are very inefficient when used this way.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>No standard tests or listings of energy efficiency exist for portable 
fridges, so 
ask suppliers for written information on energy consumption. High 
compressor efficiency 
and effective insulation are critical, as they can more than halve the 
rate of battery drain and the size of photovoltaic panel required. 
Doubling the thickness of insulation 
can halve energy consumption.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Success stories</B></FONT>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">Wild Quest Safaris, Northern Territory, uses photovoltaic 
cells to run the refrigeration 
units in its trailers. Solar power reduces running costs and eliminates 
the need 
for noisy generators.
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Odyssey Safaris in the Northern Territory uses 60-litre 
Trailblazer 12 volt refrigerators 
on tour. The brand was chosen because of its excellent insulation. The 
units run 
from the vehicle battery when on the move, and from a spare battery 
charged by a 
solar panel when stopped.
<P ALIGN="LEFT">Bungaree Earth Cottages in New South Wales are not 
connected to the electricity grid. 
LPG refrigerators are used to minimise electricity requirements, so that 
the number 
of photovoltaic cells needed to provide for basic services (lighting, 
radio) can 
be kept to an affordable level.
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
