<DOCNO>WT06-B34-22</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B046-363</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://tourism.tourism.gov.au:80/publications/BPE/FoodGarden.html 192.199.45.253 19970108085154 text/html 5401
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:51:50 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 5195
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 06:06:33 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>FoodGarden.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Food and garden materials</FONT></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task </FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>To provide food for energy and pleasant human 
modified environments</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

Food and garden waste can generally be recycled on site. Garden waste is 
often banned 
from landfill to reduce the volume of materials.
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Reduce food and garden wastes</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Reduce food waste by preparing appropriate quantities of food. 
</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Most plant food waste can be readily composted, but 
animal food waste can be more 
difficult to deal with.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Fat and oil-free cooking is healthy and reduces 
problematic waste.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Where landscaping and gardens are necessary or 
desired, maximise the use of local 
indigenous species to reduce watering, cutting and trimming, and the 
generation of 
garden waste.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Prevent discharge of oils and fats into untreated 
sewage</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Remove oils and fats from crockery with absorbent towels prior to 
washing whenever 
dishwashing effluent is released to an untreated sewage system. Use 
grease filters 
on sinks.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Medium sized and large kitchen facilities should use 
grease traps/arresters (which 
require periodic pumping) before discharge. Biological dosing systems 
which break 
down oils and fats and reduce the need for pumping are receiving approval 
from many 
water and sewerage authorities. Check if your local authority has 
approved or recommends 
any. Waste grease is increasingly being used in industrial composting and 
fertiliser 
plants. Find a pump-out contractor who recycles this 
waste.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Re-use cooking oils.</UL></TD></TR> </TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Recycle </FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Most food and green garden material is ideal for composting or worm 
farming (vermiculture). 
However, such recycling requires active management. Compost that becomes 
anaerobic 
is not just smelly; it is generating methane--a potent greenhouse 
gas.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Chip woody garden waste and use it as mulching 
material. This will assist with controlling 
weeds and reduce water requirements.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Contact suppliers, or alternatively ask your local 
council or the environment protection 
agency/department in your state or territory to find the name of a 
company that recycles 
cooking oils and fats.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Recover energy</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Burn dried wood to provide heat.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Where viable, consider establishing a system for 
anaerobically digesting food and 
plant materials to produce useable methane and soil 
conditioners.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Success story</B></FONT>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">Great Keppel Island resort runs a worm farm to process 
the island's organic wastes. 
Cardboard, paper, garden waste, sewage sludge and some food scraps (not 
oils, fats 
and sauces) are shredded, composted for three weeks, then fed to the 
worms. After 
three to four months, the worm castings are used on gardens instead of 
fertiliser. This is 
cheaper than baling and removing wastes from the island.
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT06-B34-23</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B046-369</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://tourism.tourism.gov.au:80/publications/BPE/PumpingWater.html 192.199.45.253 19970108085201 text/html 3384
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:51:58 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 3178
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 12-Dec-95 06:06:35 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>PumpingWater.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="paper3.jpg">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=6>Pumping water</FONT></CENTER>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=50% ALIGN=CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Task</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5> To supply water, remove waste water, filter and 
heat pools and cool buildings</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>

Pumps are used in many tourism operations to supply water, remove wastes, 
filter pools 
and circulate heated or chilled water. Very large amounts of electricity 
can be consumed, 
particularly when large pumps run for long periods.
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Reduce the need for pumping</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=80><UL>
<LI>Where water is pumped to a header tank, any strategy which reduces 
water consumption 
reduces pumping requirements.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Ensure that pumps operate only when 
needed.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>In many cases, pressurised water is pumped into an 
open container, then pumped (and 
re-pressurised) somewhere else. Arrange piping and controls so that water 
is delivered 
to its point of use without having to be 
re-pressurised.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5 BORDER=0><TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Action</FONT></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><FONT SIZE=5>Choose the right-sized pump and an efficient 
motor</FONT></TD></TR>

<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30><FONT SIZE=5>Issues</FONT></TD>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Avoid using an oversized pump and motor which 
unnecessarily add to capital and running 
costs.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Where loads vary, install a variable speed drive to 
improve efficiency.</UL></TD></TR>
<TR><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP COLSPAN=30></TD><TD ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP 
COLSPAN=80><UL><LI>Highly efficient motors are commercially available, 
and reduce energy consumption 
cost-effectively. Ask suppliers for written information on motor 
efficiency.</UL></TD></TR></TABLE>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>Success stories</B></FONT>

<P ALIGN="LEFT">At Yellow Waters in the Northern Territory, a pump ran 
continuously, topping up the 
header tank for the fresh water supply. Excess water overflowed and ran 
back down 
to a lagoon. To reduce energy and cut costs, a float switch was been 
installed which 
switches the pump off when the header tank is full. An effluent pump 
which used to run 
continuously and required replacement four times each year is now also 
controlled 
by a float switch, which has dramatically reduced operating time.
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
