<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Forecast Magazine - Message from the Chairman</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<P ALIGN="LEFT">
<H1><B>FOREWORD</B></H1>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<H2><B>Message from the Chairman</H2></B><IMG SRC="Chairman.GIF" 
WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=181 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 ALIGN=RIGHT>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>This issue of <I>Forecast</I> marks the completion of the Council's 
initial priority task: to develop broad-scale trip forecasts for 
domestic, inbound and outbound tourism.</B>
<P>
Detailed forecasts of international visitor arrivals to the year 2003 and 
of overseas travel by Australians to 1998-99 have been developed and are 
detailed in this issue, complementing the forecasts of domestic travel 
released in August last year.
<P>
This gives the 'big picture' of Australian tourism activity: an inbound 
sector continuing to show strong growth, with arrivals projected to 
increase at an average annual rate of 11 per cent to reach 6.3 million in 
2000; a sound domestic sector underpinning the industry and projected to 
show solid growth of 1.6 per cent a year to 1998-99; and an outbound 
sector forecast to grow at 9 per cent a year, on average, over the next 
five years.
<P>
It is encouraging to know that our recent rapid gains in tourism are 
likely to be consolidated and strengthened over the coming years, but it 
is the impact of this increased tourism that is of most interest to 
industry operators and planners.
<P>
The Council's first steps in this direction are also reported in this 
issue. The impact of international tourism growth has been quantified in 
terms of expenditure, the number of nights spent in Australia, and the 
number of nights spent in hotels, motels and guest houses. Although there 
is still some way to go before we can forecast such indicators as hotel 
occupancy rates and room rates by region, these results represent a 
quantum leap in progress in a little over 12 months.
<P>
To complement these more traditional forecasts, the Council has also 
developed leading indicators of tourism activity. Leading indicators have 
not previously been used to predict tourism activity in Australia, so 
this has been a ground-breaking initiative for the Council.
<P>
The need for more detailed forecasting is highlighted in the report on 
recent hotel activity.  Nationally, the sector is showing continuing 
improvement, but the strength of this recovery varies significantly 
between  States.
<P>
As a result, the Council's priorities now are to develop a more detailed 
picture of where tourists will be going in Australia and how long they 
will stay at their destinations.
<P>
In the next issue of <I>Forecast</I> we plan to provide projections of 
domestic visitor nights and domestic nights in hotel/motel accommodation 
to complement the international forecasts presented in this issue.
<P>
By the end of this year, the Council will provide forecasts of domestic 
and international visitation to regions within Australia, including 
demand for hotel/motel accommodation. The Council will also update its 
forecasts regularly to keep up to date with changing conditions. Revised 
forecasts of domestic travel are scheduled for this year.
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
The Council's work is progressing well. I urge investors and operators to 
take the time to become familiar with these forecasts and to use them in 
their business planning. I also invite readers to come back to the 
Council with specific suggestions about further information that would be 
helpful in their business planning.
<P>
Frank Conroy <BR>
Chairman<BR>
Tourism Forecasting Council<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<P ALIGN="LEFT"><I>
<I>APRIL 1995<I> </I><B>FORECAST</B>
</I><BR>
