Last-Modified: Wednesday, 06-Sep-95 03:41:06 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Forecast Magazine - Visitor arrivals to double by 
2000</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<H1><B>Visitor arrivals to double by 2000</B></H1>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<P>
<I>In the year 2000, 6.3 million people are expected to visit Australia - 
more than double the number that visited in 1993. For the next 10 years, 
inbound tourism is expected to grow by an average 10 per cent a year, 
maintaining its position as the fastest growing sector of Australia's 
tourism industry. </I>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Visitor.GIF" WIDTH=325 HEIGHT=429 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3  
ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>I</B>nbound tourism is one of Australia's fastest growing industries, 
employing about 130 000 people either directly or indirectly and, in 
1993-94, generating $10.6 billion in export earnings. Between 1983 and 
1993, the number of international visitors increased from 944 000 to 3 
million, an average annual growth rate of 12 per cent.
<P>
High rates of growth are forecast to continue over the next decade, led 
by the growth of the rapidly developing Asian markets. Inbound tourism 
will be an increasingly important generator of jobs and income for 
Australia. 
<P>
The Council's forecasts of international visitor arrivals were developed 
using a combination of quantitative and qualitative 
techniques.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Individual market estimates</B>
<P>
<B><I>Japan</I></B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table1p6.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=523 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3  
ALIGN=RIGHT><P>
Japan currently accounts for 22 per cent of all visitors to Australia. 
After slowing in 1994 and 1995 as a result of the economic slowdown in 
Japan, the growth in visitor arrivals from Japan is expected to be 
moderate over the rest of the forecast period.
<P>

Travel and leisure are becoming increasingly important to the Japanese 
public, and Australia is well positioned to capitalise on growth in 
several emerging market segments. In particular, given its range of 
attractions and strong image as a 'big nature' destination, Australia 
should benefit from increasing Japanese interest in ecotourism and 
independent travel. An increased marketing focus in Japan and coverage of 
the Sydney 2000 Olympics should also heighten Australia's image as a 
holiday destination for Japanese travellers.
<P>
While there are some negative factors for Australia, including increased 
price consciousness in the market and the growth in marketing costs, on 
balance the positive factors are expected to significantly outweigh them.

<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig1p7.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=168 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
The number of visitors from Japan is forecast to increase from 671 000 in 
1993 to more than 1 million by 1999 and to nearly 1.5 million by 2003 
(Table 1 and Figure 1). Growth is forecast to average just over 8 per 
cent a year, which will easily maintain Japan's position as the largest 
source country for international visitors to Australia. These forecasts 
were developed before the earthquake that devastated the region around 
Kobe on 17 January 1995. The earthquake is expected to affect overall 
outbound travel from Japan, including to Australia. The duration and 
magnitude of this effect is not yet clear but is expected to be 
short-term. 
<P>


Over the past 10 years Australia's share of the outbound Japanese market 
increased strongly. Over the forecast period, a further slight gain in 
market share is expected.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B><I>Other Asian markets</I></B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table2p7.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=517 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
Other Asian countries are becoming increasingly significant as sources of 
inbound tourism. By 1993, these countries accounted for 23 per cent of 
all visitors to Australia, with arrivals from Korea and Taiwan increasing 
by more than 50 per cent every year.
<P>

Strong economic growth, rapidly rising incomes and the easing of 
restrictions on travel have resulted in the populations of a number of 
East and South-East Asian countries travelling more extensively. 
Australia is well positioned to benefit from these developments over the 
next decade and beyond. Australia's share of outbound travel from most 
Asian countries is expected to grow over the forecast period, 
particularly in the next five years or so.
<P>
With the exception of 1983, 1984 and 1990, the Hong Kong market has grown 
rapidly since 1980 (see Table 2). Strong economic growth in <B>Hong 
Kong</B> is expected to result in continued growth in arrivals from this 
market over the period. There may be an exception in 1997, due to the 
transition from British to Chinese administration.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig2p7.GIF" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=213 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=RIGHT>
The number of visitors from Hong Kong is forecast to increase from 92 000 
in 1993 to 269 000 in 2003, an average annual growth rate of 11 per cent 
(Figure 2).
<P>
In 1993 visitor arrivals from <B>Indonesia </B>increased by 57 per cent. 
Although growth in arrivals from this market has really only occurred 
since 1986, it suggests a market 'take off'. Expectations of continued 
strong economic growth in Indonesia suggest rapid growth in visitor 
arrivals for the entire forecast period. Expanding ties with Indonesia, 
geographic proximity and the increasing propensity of a rapidly growing 
middle class to travel are all positive factors for this market. 
Increasing awareness of Australia as a tourism destination and increased 
marketing activity should also underpin growth.
<P>
Arrivals from Indonesia are forecast to increase from 72 000 in 1993 to 
more than 500 000 by 2003, an annual average growth rate of 22 per cent.
<P>
The recent growth in arrivals from <B>Korea</B> has been extraordinary - 
arrivals have increased sixfold in the past five years and nearly doubled 
in 1993 alone.
<P>
With a large population, a strong economy and a relatively low rate of 
outbound travel, Korea appears to have ample opportunity for further 
growth in travel to Australia. Factors such as a growing middle class, 
the desire to experience Western culture and the continuing impact of 
Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) promotional activities also suggest a 
very optimistic outlook for this market.
<P>
The number of visitors from Korea is forecast to reach nearly 500 000 in 
2003, which will firmly entrench Korea as one of Australia's top 10 
markets.
<P>
Growth in the <B>Malaysian</B> market has been generally strong, but 
variable, since the early 1980s. Growth was particularly strong in 1992 
and 1993, and this is expected to continue over the forecast period.
<P>
The growth in the middle class, an increased propensity for long-haul 
travel, an increased desire to visit Western countries (of which 
Australia is the closest) and new, more focused marketing by the ATC are 
all positive signs for growth. The only negative factor appears to be 
increased competition for the market.
<P>
The number of visitors from Malaysia is forecast to increase from 80 000 
in 1993 to about 330 000 by 2003, an average annual growth rate of more 
than 15 per cent.
<P>
The <B>Singapore</B> market has performed consistently for some time, 
with double-digit growth in all but two years since 1980. Arrivals are 
closely related to changes in economic growth and in the relative 
exchange rate. Given Singapore's continued healthy economic growth, the 
level of arrivals is expected to continue to increase rapidly.
<P>
Singaporeans have demonstrated a taste for travel, and anecdotal evidence 
suggests that short breaks (including those to Australia) are becoming an 
accepted part of the Singaporeans' lifestyle. An apparent move towards 
special interest travel is a further positive indicator for Australia.
<P>
The number of visitors from Singapore is forecast to increase from 155 
000 in 1993 to 424 000 in 2003, an average annual growth rate of more 
than 10 per cent. This growth will maintain Singapore among Australia's 
top 10 markets, although by the end of the forecast period its current 
ranking is likely to have been overtaken by other Asian markets.
<P>
Like Korea, <B>Taiwan</B> has recently emerged as a booming market, with 
arrivals quadrupling in the past three years to reach 108 000 in 1993. 
Strong growth continued in 1994.
<P>
The rapid expansion of the middle class is a significant factor in this 
market. In addition, the emergence of young women office workers as 
prospective travellers, an increasing interest in market segments such as 
nature-based travel, and a strong ATC promotional commitment to Taiwan 
should see this market perform well in both the short and medium term. In 
the medium to long term, however, the probability of direct air links 
with China and increased competition from other destinations may have 
some dampening effect.
<P>
The number of visitors from Taiwan is forecast to increase to just under 
500 000 by 2003, at an average annual growth rate of 16 per cent. By the 
end of the forecast period, however, growth is expected to be in single 
digits.
<P>
Tourism from <B>Thailand</B> has also grown rapidly in recent years, 
following a patchy performance in the early 1980s. Analysis suggests that 
less than 2 per cent of the Thai population currently travels. However, 
there is a rapidly expanding middle class and an increasing desire to 
experience Western culture, and travel is becoming more important 
socially. Australia appears well positioned to capitalise on growth in 
several important market segments including adventure travel and 
nature-based tourism, and the Sydney 2000 Olympics is likely to provide 
another positive stimulus.
<P>
The number of visitors from Thailand is forecast to increase from 47 000 
in 1993 to 309 000 in 2003, an average annual growth rate of more than 20 
per cent. Thailand is expected to be one of the fastest growing markets.
<P>
Although the Asian outlook certainly appears to be very bright, 
significant outbound leisure travel and rapid growth in arrivals from 
these countries has been only  a relatively recent phenomenon. As a 
result, there is significantly more uncertainty attached to the forecasts 
for many of these countries than for Australia's more established source 
markets. 
<P>
This uncertainty is greatest for tourism from <B>China</B> and 
<B>India</B>. In 1993, there were 22 300 arrivals from China and 9 800 
from India, together accounting for 1 per cent of all visitors to 
Australia. Given the large populations of these two countries and their 
potential for continued rapid social and economic change, there is a 
possibility of strong growth in outbound travel from both, which could 
have significant implications for the forecasts in the longer term.
<P>
However, given the uncertainties involved, no attempt has been made to 
separately quantify these markets. Instead, the growth in arrivals from 
both countries has been assumed to be at the same rate as for non-Japan 
Asia as a whole. This assumption will be reviewed when the forecasts are 
revised and updated.
<P>
<IMG SRC="Japanese.GIF" WIDTH=378 HEIGHT=311 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B><I>Europe</I></B>
<P><IMG SRC="Table3.GIF" WIDTH=335 HEIGHT=507 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
In 1993, Europe accounted for 21 per cent of visitor arrivals to 
Australia. This market is dominated by the United Kingdom, but Germany is 
becoming more important and France is also showing promise (Figure 3).
<P>
In recent years, the overall growth in the number of visitors from Europe 
has been moderate. There are significant differences in the rates of 
growth expected from different countries over the forecast period (Figure 
4), and by the end of 2003 Europe is expected to account for 19 per cent 
of total arrivals. Overall, only small changes in Australia's share of 
European markets is expected, but prospects vary significantly for 
individual markets.<P>
<P>
The pattern of growth in arrivals from <B>France</B> has been quite 
uneven. In its segmentation analysis, the ATC identified France as a 
market of large untapped potential, suggesting that historical experience 
is likely to underestimate growth. Arrivals from France appear to be 
highly sensitive to economic growth, with a small lag.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig3p7.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=224 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>

The number of visitors from France is forecast to more than treble, from 
31 000 in 1993 to nearly 100 000 by 2003, an average annual growth rate 
of 12 per cent. France is expected to be the strongest growing European 
market, albeit from a small base.
<P>
Apart from a slowdown in growth since 1990, the <B>German</B> market has 
performed well since 1985. A growing interest in long-haul travel, the 
possibility of air charters opening up new interest, the leverage to be 
gained from Partnership Australia, and the Sydney 2000 Olympics all point 
to a positive outlook for this market. There appears to be large 
underlying potential for growth from Germany, and the ATC proposes to 
increase its marketing activity there.
<P>
The number of visitors from Germany is forecast to increase from 106 000 
in 1993 to 317 000 in 2003, an average annual growth rate of 11.6 per 
cent.
<P>
With some isolated exceptions, the growth in arrivals from <B>Italy</B> 
is forecast to slow from about 10 per cent a year to just over 5 per cent 
by 2003. From 1994 to 2003, arrivals should double, reaching 78 000 by 
the end of the forecast period.
<P>
The Dutch market has been patchy during the 1980s and 1990s, but there is 
some evidence of growth since 1989. The number of visitors from <B>the 
Netherlands</B> is forecast to increase from 27 000 in 1993 to 56 000 in 
2003, an average annual growth rate of nearly 8 per cent.
<P>
The outlook for growth in arrivals from <B>Switzerland</B> is also 
positive, and the number of visitors is expected to more than double from 
31 000 in 1993 to 65 000 in 2003.
<P>
The <B>United Kingdom</B> is an important and well-established market. 
With 321 000 visitor arrivals in 1993, it ranked behind only Japan and 
New Zealand. Economic growth, movements in exchange rates and the level 
of past arrivals suggest that moderate growth  of between 5 and 6 per 
cent a year can be expected from the United Kingdom.
<P>
The effect of air charter operators expanding the market through low 
prices, an increasing interest in long-haul travel, and the combined 
effect of the Sydney 2000 Olympics and the Centenary of Federation should 
contribute to this growth.

<P>
The number of visitors from the United Kingdom is forecast to reach 570 
000 by 2003, and it should remain the third largest source of arrivals.
<P>
<B><I>North America</I></B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Fig4p9.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=195 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=RIGHT>
While the <B>United States</B> market performed strongly up until 1987 
and in the 1988 Expo/Bicentenary year, performance since then has been 
poor. Economic growth, exchange rates and the level of past arrivals 
suggest only moderate growth in arrivals (Figure 4).
<P>
The number of visitors from the United States is forecast to increase 
from 281 000 in 1993 to 477 000 in 2003, an annual average rate of 5.4 
per cent. Projections are that the United States will lose its position 
as Australia's fourth largest market, to be passed by Indonesia, Taiwan 
and Korea.
<P>
The number of arrivals from <B>Canada</B> is forecast to increase from 51 
000 in 1993 to 77 000 in 2003, an average annual growth rate of just over 
4 per cent.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<B><I>New Zealand</I></B>
<P>
With 500 000 New Zealanders visiting Australia in 1993, New Zealand is 
Australia's second largest tourist market. This market declined in the 
early 1980s, grew rapidly from 1985 to 1989, and has since fluctuated 
without regaining its 1989 peak. 
<P><IMG SRC="Fig5p9.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=174 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=RIGHT>
Somewhat perversely, New Zealand's economic recovery and its closeness to 
Australia may work against growth in this market - with increasing 
prosperity, New Zealanders, who are already familiar with Australia as a 
destination, may choose longer-haul destinations. An increased tendency 
to take short breaks and interest in event-related travel, however, may 
work in Australia's favour. The Sydney 2000 Olympics are expected to have 
a marked impact on New Zealand arrivals in the Games year.
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
On balance, only slow growth of about 3 per cent a year is forecast for 
this market. Arrivals are forecast to rise to 669 000 by 2003 (Figure 5). 
Even so, New Zealand should remain the second largest source of arrivals 
to Australia. 
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Summary </B>
<P>
The number of international visitors to Australia is forecast to increase 
from 3 million in 1993 to 3.35 million in 1994, 6.3 million in 2000 and 
7.6 million in 2003 (Figure 6). The average annual growth rate is 
forecast to be just under 10 per cent for the period 1993-2003, but that 
figure will vary from year to year, from 12 to 13 per cent now to about 5 
per cent by 2003.
<P>
<IMG SRC="Fig6p9.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=222 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
The Sydney Olympic Games should lead to a relatively small increase in 
the growth rate in the year 2000. However, the Games are among many 
positive factors influencing arrivals forecasts and are expected to have 
a positive impact on visitor numbers in every year of the forecast 
period.
<P>
Australian tourism clearly stands to benefit from increasing links with 
the fast - growing economies of Asia, and Australia's  share of these 
markets should continue to expand.
<P>
Japan is expected to remain the largest source country. Arrivals are 
forecast to more than double, from 671 000 in 1993 to 1.456 million in 
2003 (Figure 6). This forecast does not, however, take into account any 
effects from the 17 January earthquake that devastated the Kobe region. 
Arrivals from other Asian markets are expected to increase from 683 000 
in 1993 to 3 million in 2003, an average annual growth rate of 16 per 
cent. Indonesia, Taiwan and South Korea are all expected to provide about 
500 000 visitors a year in 2003.
<P>
From 1983 to 1993, the number of visitors from Asia (including Japan) 
increased from 205 000 (22 per cent of total visitor numbers) to 1.4 
million (45 per cent of the total). Over the next decade, this number is 
forecast to reach 4.5 million, or 59 per cent of all visitors to 
Australia.
<P>
Arrivals from established markets such as Europe and the United States 
are already reflecting the world economic recovery. The development of 
more special interest products and the additional publicity generated by 
the Olympics should see these markets grow over the medium to long term.
<P>
European markets such as Germany and France also show potential for 
strong growth, as long-haul travel becomes more popular and awareness of 
Australia as a holiday destination increases.
<P>
While the outlook is bright, some uncertainty surrounds the forecasting 
exercise. In particular, it is difficult to estimate with precision the 
potential of emerging Asian markets. South Korea and Taiwan, for example, 
are currently exhibiting extremely rapid growth, but from a fairly small 
base. Outbound tourism from these countries is a recent phenomenon and, 
as a result, the future rate of expansion, and behaviour and destination 
choices of travellers, must be estimated using scant historical data. 
Government and industry should be aware of the uncertainty involving the 
emerging Asian markets when using these forecasts for investment, 
planning and policy decisions.<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<H2><B>How the forecasts were developed</B></H2>
<P>
Economic theory suggests that the decision to travel is related to 
people's ability to pay for the travel service (<B>income</B> variables) 
and to the <B>price</B> of the travel compared with other goods and 
services (including, in this case, travel to other destinations).
<P>
Econometric models have been used extensively for forecasting tourism 
trends, and in many markets have quite high levels of reliability. 
However, they also have their limitations. For example, the historical 
relationship between arrivals and income and price variables will almost 
certainly not explain all the variation in arrivals. Changes in consumer 
behaviour, changes in government policy, or any number of other events 
may mean that the past relationship is not always a good guide to the 
future.
<P>
In addition, it is not possible to be certain about the future path of 
income and price variables, so that even if all historical variations 
could be accounted for, there would still be uncertainty about future 
trends.
<P>
The Council's approach aimed to address these difficulties. Gross 
Domestic Product was used as the broad income variable. The real relative 
exchange rate between Australia and the source market was used as the 
price variable.
<P>
Simple econometric models were then used to estimate the historical 
relationship between economic and other variables and movements in 
visitor arrivals. These models were used to project arrivals to the year 
2003, taking into account the extent to which past relationships could be 
expected to hold in the future.
<P>
Following the development of these models, a comprehensive list of 
factors likely to influence future arrivals from each source market was 
compiled, drawing on Australian Tourist Commission market information. 
These factors were classified as to whether their effect on future 
arrivals was likely to be positive or negative and weighted according to 
their likely influence. The model results were then adjusted by the 
balance of positive and negative factors in each year.
<P>
The final forecasts represent a view of the 'most likely' outcome for 
arrivals from each market. However, it needs to be remembered that 
forecasts are sensitive to the assumptions used in their derivation, and 
for that reason are subject to significant uncertainty.
<P>
The Council will continue to evaluate and refine its methodology in the 
light of feedback and consultation with users and industry experts. A 
revised set of inbound forecasts is expected to be released in about 12 
months.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
