<HEAD>
<TITLE>Forecast Magazine - International Visitor Nights and Expenditure 
in Australia</TITLE
></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<H1><B>International visitor nights and expenditure in Australia</B></H1>

<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<P><I>The boost to the Australian economy provided by international 
tourism is likely to increase significantly between now and 2003. 
Spending by international tourists is expected to grow by an average 
annual rate of 9 per cent, visitor nights by about 8 per cent a year, and 
visitor nights in hotels, motels and guest houses by almost 11 per cent a 
year.</I>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Intpeople.GIF" WIDTH=261 HEIGHT=306 HSPACE=20 VSPACE=20 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<B>I</B>nternational tourism is likely to have an increasingly 
significant impact on the Australian economy during the 10 years to 2003. 
Expenditure by international tourists is forecast to grow at an average 
annual rate of 9 per cent, from just over $6 billion in 1993 to almost 
$15 billion in 2003. Visitor nights are expected to increase at an 
average annual rate of about 8 per cent  and visitor nights in hotels, 
motels and guest houses by almost 11 per cent. 
<P>
The increase in visitor arrival numbers is the main driving force behind 
these growth rates, but the results are strongly influenced by the 
assumption that there will be a significant decline in the average 
duration of stay of visitors from the Other Asia market (all of Asia, 
except Japan).
<P>
Compared to arrivals, overall visitor nights are forecast to grow 
relatively slowly, from 69 million in 1993 to 144 million in 2003. The 
fastest growth is expected to occur in the Other Europe and Other Asia 
markets. By 2003 the Other Asia market will make up about 29 per cent of 
total visitor nights spent by international visitors in Australia - up 
from 25 per cent in 1993 but significantly below its 40 per cent share of 
total arrivals.
<P>
In contrast, visitor nights in hotels, motels and guest houses are 
expected to grow even more quickly than visitor arrivals. By the year 
2000 it is likely that about 32 million visitor nights will be spent in 
this form of accommodation - up from 15 million in 1993. Again, changes 
in the Other Asia market are mainly responsible for the variation. It is 
expected that visitors from this region will spend a greater proportion 
of nights in hotels, motels and guest houses as the market grows.
<P>
Two components of total tourism expenditure have been forecast: direct 
expenditure in Australia and the Australian component of prepaid package 
tours. No attempt has been made to forecast the balance of payments 
contribution of the tourism industry. However, the results from the other 
forecasts suggest that tourism will maintain its position as Australia's 
number one export earner over the forecast period.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Visitor nights</B>
<P>
The number of international visitors to Australia has risen over the past 
decade, but visitors' average duration of stay has declined, particularly 
since 1989. Consequently, the total nights spent in Australia by 
international visitors has not risen as quickly as visitor arrivals. This 
decline has been caused largely by a change in the type of visitors 
arriving in Australia. 
<P>
Further changes are expected in the forecast period of 1993 to 2003, 
particularly in the Other Asia and New Zealand markets. The average 
duration of stay of international visitors is expected to decline 
further.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Trends in average duration of stay</B>
<P>
<B><I>Other Asia</I></B>
<P>
The average duration of stay for visitors from the Other Asia group of 
countries has fallen quite dramatically over the past three years. This 
fall has been associated with two factors:
<P>

<UL TYPE=disc>
<LI> The proportion of holiday visitors has risen - from 54 per cent in 
1990 to 69 per cent in 1993. As can be seen in Table 1, the duration of 
stay of holiday visitors is about one-quarter that of other visitors.
<P>
<LI> The average duration of stay of holiday visitors has fallen. The 
rapid rise in arrivals from markets such as Taiwan and Korea has been 
associated with a change in the type of holiday maker arriving from Other 
Asia. In the past, visitors tended to stay for a little over two weeks; 
now they are staying a little over one week.
</UL>
<IMG SRC="Table1p13.GIF" WIDTH=337 HEIGHT=165 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Both trends are expected to continue over the next 10 years. Accompanying 
the expected tremendous growth in arrivals from the Other Asia market 
will be an increase in the proportion of holiday makers. The profile of 
these visitors is expected to be similar to that of the relatively 
short-staying Japanese. However, given established education, family and 
business links that already exist between Australia and a number of 
countries in the region (particularly Hong Kong, Singapore and Malaysia), 
it is likely that the proportion of holiday makers from the Other Asia 
market will stay below the Japanese level of 90 per cent. The lower 
proportion of holiday makers will keep the average duration of stay of 
visitors from the Other Asia market above that of visitors from Japan for 
the forecast period. By 2003, the average duration of stay is expected to 
stabilise.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B><I>New Zealand</I></B>
<P>
The average duration of stay for visitors from New Zealand has fallen 
over the past 10 years, from more than 20 nights in the early 1980s to 
about 17 nights in recent years.
<P>
This fall is not due to a change in the purpose of visit - the proportion 
of the long-staying 'Visiting Relatives' segment has remained at about 28 
per cent of New Zealand arrivals for the past 10 years. It appears, 
instead, that New Zealanders are having shorter and more frequent 
holidays to Australia.
<P>
This trend is in line with the Australian Tourist Commission's marketing 
strategy in New Zealand, which promotes Australia as a short-stay 
destination. Some further reinforcement is expected from a long-term 
decline in airfares on the trans-Tasman route. Overall, the average 
duration of stay of New Zealanders will decline over the forecast period, 
but at a decreasing rate.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B><I>United States, Japan, Canada</I></B>
<P>
The average duration of stay for visitors from the United States, Japan 
and Canada has remained relatively stable over the past 10 years, despite 
quite significant growth in total arrivals. Growth in visitor arrivals 
will continue to be steady, and there is no indication that this growth 
will involve a significant change in the mix of visitors arriving. For 
this reason it is assumed that, over the forecast period, the average 
duration of stay of visitors from these markets will be constant at 
1991-93 levels.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B><I>United Kingdom, Ireland and Other Europe</I></B>
<P>
The duration of stay for visitors from the United Kingdom, Ireland and 
Other Europe markets has varied considerably over the past 10 years, 
rising in the late 1980s and falling during the 1990s.
<P>
The recent drop in duration of stay appears to be due to changes in the 
mix of travellers. Although the proportion of holiday makers grew 
strongly from 1985 to 1991, it has been relatively stable for the past 
three years. 
<P>
There appears to have been a shift in the type of holiday maker coming to 
Australia. This shift could be due to the availability of cheaper 
airfares and more direct airline services since 1990, which have made 
shorter Australian holidays a more viable option. It is expected that 
these trends will continue for at least the next few years as the 
development of charter services and the availability of relatively cheap 
airfares make Australia a more attractive option for Europeans looking 
for two- to three-week holidays.
<P>
It is assumed that over the next few years the average duration of stay 
of visitors from these markets will continue to fall, but at a declining 
rate. It is then likely to stabilise.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Summary</B>
<P>


The forecast average duration of stay of short-term visitors to 
Australia, based on these assumptions, is shown in Table 2.
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table2p13.GIF" WIDTH=335 HEIGHT=408 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT><P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
The visitor nights projections for the years 1995 to 2003 (Table 3) have 
been calculated using forecasts of international visitor arrivals by the 
Tourism Forecasting Council and the preceding projections of average 
duration of stay.
<IMG SRC="Table3p14.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=448 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
The forecast decline in the average duration of stay significantly 
reduces the impact of the rapid growth in arrivals, particularly from the 
Other Asia market, on tourism sectors other than international transport. 
Figure 1 shows that, while arrivals from the Other Asia market are 
forecast to rise by more than 250 per cent by the year 2000, visitor 
nights are expected to rise by just over 100 per cent.
<IMG SRC="Fig1p17.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=173 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
These forecasts are very sensitive to the assumptions that have been made 
about the duration of stay of visitors from the Other Asia market (Table 
4). The forecast assumes a quite rapid decline in the average duration of 
stay of Other Asian visitors, from 25 nights in 1993, to 14 nights in 
2000. Variations in this decline can be seen to have significant 
implications for total visitor nights spent by international visitors in 
Australia, as well as visitor nights spent by visitors from the Other 
Asia market.
<IMG SRC="Table4p14.GIF" WIDTH=335 HEIGHT=165 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>International visitor nights in hotels, motels and guest houses</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table5p15.GIF" WIDTH=338 HEIGHT=201 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
At present about 23 per cent of international visitor nights are spent in 
hotels, motels and guest houses. This ratio varies considerably across 
the major markets (see Table 5)
<P>
These differences appear to be caused by variations in three factors: the 
proportion of holiday makers from each market, the proportion of visitors 
from a market visiting friends and relatives, and the type of holiday 
maker attracted from a market. For all markets, holiday travellers spend 
more nights in commercial accommodation than do non-holiday visitors. 
Travellers visiting friends and relatives spend significantly less time 
in commercial accommodation than other visitors. Visitors from Japan, who 
tend to have relatively short stays, tend to use more hotels, motels and 
guest houses than, for example, long-staying backpackers from the United 
Kingdom.
<P>
A change in the percentage of nights spent in hotels, motels and guest 
houses by visitors from a particular market would be expected if there 
were a significant change in one or more of these variables. For most 
markets (United States, Japan, New Zealand, Canada, Other Europe and 
United Kingdom) no factor could be identified that would suggest such a 
change would be likely. 
<P>
However, the Other Asia market appears to be undergoing a period of 
significant change - the proportion of holiday travellers is increasing, 
and the proportion of travellers who come to visit friends and relatives 
is decreasing. As a result, the proportion of nights spent by visitors 
from this market in hotel and motel accommodation is growing. This 
proportion is expected to continue to increase for the forecast period, 
from 18 per cent in 1993 to 42 per cent in 2003.
<P>The effect of these trends is shown in Table 6. Total nights spent in 
hotels, motels and guest houses by all international visitors to 
Australia are forecast to increase at an average annual rate of 10.6 per 
cent. 
<IMG SRC="Table6p15.GIF" WIDTH=335 HEIGHT=400 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Because many guests at hotels, motels and guest houses share a room with 
at least one other person, the figures in Table 6 give an inflated 
picture of the expected demand for rooms.
<P>
An indication of how many room nights will be sold to cater for visitors' 
needs can be calculated using the ratio of room nights to guest nights 
derived from the Australian Bureau of Statistics' Survey of Tourist 
Accommodation. These figures show that, on average, 1.76 guest nights 
currently translate into one room night. Using this ratio, it can be 
estimated that approximately 18 million room nights will be required in 
2000, 35 per cent of them by visitors from the Other Asia market. 
However, it should be noted that this ratio does not distinguish between 
domestic and international tourists.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Expenditure</B>
<P>
The Bureau of Tourism Research's International Visitor Survey (IVS) 
collects data on spending that is directly related to the Australian 
component of a visitor's trip. The survey includes both visitor spending 
in Australia and spending on packaged tours purchased outside Australia. 
In the following analysis these two components of spending are forecast 
separately. The projections are <B>not</B> intended as forecasts of 
tourism's contribution to the balance of payments.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Visitor spending in Australia</B>
<P>
Real average expenditure per person has varied considerably over the past 
six years, but has generally fallen since 1990 (see Table 7). At the same 
time, real average daily expenditure per person has been rising. 
Available data show that real average daily expenditure per person is 
inversely related to the average duration of stay, so that people on 
shorter holidays tend to spend more per day than people on longer 
holidays. Given that the average duration of stay is likely to continue 
falling, it is expected that this trend of rising expenditure per day 
will continue.<P>
<IMG SRC="Table7p17.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=201 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
The relationship between duration of stay and daily expenditure is more 
evident when the data are broken up into individual source markets. The 
markets that have had the largest decreases in average duration of stay, 
such as Other Asia and Europe, have had the greatest increases in average 
expenditure per day.
<P>
In forecasting expenditure, it has been assumed that this relationship 
will continue and the predicted fall in duration of stay will have a 
positive impact on average daily expenditure. 
<P>
The forecasts also take into account the effect of expected rises in real 
incomes in source countries. In the past, steadily rising real incomes in 
countries such as the United States and Japan have been associated with 
rises in holiday expenditure in real terms. The expected global growth in 
per capita real private expenditure is assumed to have similar effects 
over the forecast period.
<P>
Projections of expenditure have been made based on these assumptions and 
are shown in Tables 8 and 9 and Figure 2.<P>
<IMG SRC="Table8p17.GIF" WIDTH=333 HEIGHT=337 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Table9p18.GIF" WIDTH=338 HEIGHT=364 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=MIDDLE>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig2p18.GIF" WIDTH=159 HEIGHT=199 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=MIDDLE>
<P>
Although the major components of international visitor expenditure are 
yet to be forecast, 1993 visitor expenditure in Australia provides an 
indication of the major components. Of the $1 787 average expenditure in 
Australia by an international visitor: 35 per cent went on tourism 
shopping; 33 per cent on food, drink and accommodation; 9 per cent on 
transport; and 23 per cent on other costs.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Australian component of prepaid package expenditure</B>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
IVS data do not separate the Australian component of expenditure on 
inclusive prepaid package tours purchased outside Australia. However, the 
Bureau of Tourism Research has recently calculated the value of this 
expenditure by major source market for the three years 1990 to 1992. 
Owing to limited data it is not possible to determine trends.
<P>
To calculate the value of this expenditure for the years 1994 to 2003, 
two assumptions were made. First, it was assumed that the proportion of 
people travelling on prepaid package tours would remain constant for 
mature markets and increase for the Other Asian markets (from 28 per cent 
in 1993 to 58 per cent in 2003). There is a tendency for first-time 
holiday travellers to prefer to travel on package tours, and a 
significant percentage of travellers from the emerging markets are 
first-time holiday travellers. 
<P>
Second, it was assumed that the average real expenditure per person 
travelling on a prepaid package would remain constant for all major 
markets at an average of the three years 1990 to 1992.
<P>
Based on these assumptions, it was concluded that the annual average 
growth rate in prepaid expenditure would be 12.7 per cent, an increase 
from $700 million in 1993 to $2.4 billion in 2003. However, the forecast 
figure is very sensitive to the assumptions about the Japan and Other 
Asia markets, which make up more than 80 per cent of total prepaid 
expenditure. If there were a greater than expected increase in 
independent travel from Japan, and the percentage of Japanese arrivals 
travelling on prepaid package tours were to fall from 85 per cent to, 
say, 60 per cent, prepaid expenditure would fall by 12 per cent to $2.1 
billion.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Total expenditure <BR>
(direct and prepaid)</B>
<P>
Total expenditure by international tourists from each major market is 
derived by combining the estimates of prepaid expenditure and expenditure 
in Australia as presented earlier. The outcome is shown in Table 10. 
<IMG SRC="Table10p18.GIF" WIDTH=335 HEIGHT=352 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
As noted earlier, the forecast of visitor expenditure given in Table 10 
does not represent total export earnings from tourism. In addition to the 
components forecast, tourism's contribution to the balance of payments 
includes, among other items, international passenger services provided to 
non-residents by Australian airlines, expenditure of students in 
Australia under Commonwealth aid programs, and a proportion of foreign 
airline expenditure in Australia. Methods for forecasting these items are 
being developed.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<!-- Link Tag -->
