<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Forecast Magazine - Resident departures to rise rapidly</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<H2><B>Resident departures to rise rapidly</B></H2><P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<I>Continuing strong economic growth in Australia is expected 
to result in rapid increases in the level of overseas travel by 
Australians. In the next five years, resident departures are 
forecast to rise at an average annual rate of 9 per cent.</I>
<P><IMG SRC="P20.GIF" WIDTH=225 HEIGHT=294 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
<B>T</B>he number of Australians travelling overseas, whether for 
business, holidays or other reasons, is increasing, according to the 
Australian Bureau of Statistics. During the 10 years to 1993, this sector 
grew at an average rate of 6.1 per cent a year - exactly half the average 
rate of growth in visitors to Australia during the same period, but much 
higher than the annual 1 per cent growth rate for Australians travelling 
domestically.
<P><IMG SRC="Fig1p20.GIF" WIDTH=164 HEIGHT=188 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=RIGHT>
The growth rate in resident departures increased rapidly in earlier 
years (see Figure 1) - averaging 19 per cent annually from 1965 to 1975 
for example. Visitor arrivals have exceeded resident departures since 
1987, and quite markedly since 1991, when the growth rate for Australians 
travelling overseas slowed. <P>

<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Total departures</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table1p21.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=392 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Over the next five years, overseas travel by Australians is forecast to 
increase by an average of 9 per cent a year (see Table 1), due largely to 
the expected continuing strength of the Australian economy. Overseas 
travel for all purposes is strongly related to the level of national 
production or income in Australia.<P> 
The economic assumptions used in deriving these forecasts are the same as 
those used in forecasting domestic travel (see <I>Forecast </I>vol. 1, 
no. 1 for details). Over the five years to 1998-99, non-farm gross 
domestic product was assumed to grow by an average 3.6 per cent per annum 
in real terms, and household disposable income by 2.7 per cent per annum.

<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Non-business travel</B>
<P>
In 1993-94 travel for holidays or to visit relatives accounted for 72 per 
cent of overseas travel by Australians. This sector has shown the slowest 
growth in recent years, increasing by only 3.6 per cent between 1990-91 
and 1993-94 overall and actually falling in 1993-94 (see Figure 2). This 
compares with growth rates of 11 per cent in 1988-89 and 15 per cent in 
1989-90. Over the next five years it is forecast to increase at an 
average rate of 8 per cent a year, reaching 2.4 million departures in 
1998-99.
<P>
<IMG SRC="Fig2-4p21.GIF" WIDTH=508 HEIGHT=200 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
Overseas travel for other non-business purposes, including employment and 
education, accounts for about 7 per cent of resident departures. This is 
expected to recover strongly in 1994-95 and to increase by an average 11 
per cent a year until 1998-99 (see Figure 3).
<P>
In total, a 1 per cent increase in household disposable income could be 
expected to lead to a 1.8 per cent increase in non-business travel.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Business-related travel</B>
<P>
Australians travelling overseas on business account for 21 per cent of 
resident departures. About 81 per cent of this travel is for pure 
business purposes, 12 per cent is for travel to conventions and 6 per 
cent relates to people accompanying business travellers.
<P>
This sector is strongly responsive to economic conditions - business 
travel fell with Australia's economic slowdown in 1986-87 and again 
during the 1990-91 recession (see Figure 4). Since 1990-91, however, it 
has increased strongly, at an average annual rate of nearly 9 per cent.
<P>
Over the next five years business travel is forecast to increase by 
nearly 11 per cent a year, although any slowing in economic growth from 
expected rates will reduce this forecast. For example, economic growth at 
1 percentage point a year slower than forecast would reduce the forecast 
rate of growth in business travel by 3 percentage points a year.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<!-- Link Tag -->
