<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Forecast Magazine - Looking short-term with leading 
indicators</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<H1>
<B>Looking short-term with leading indicators</B>
</H1>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<I>The growth rate in short-term visitor arrivals appeared to reach a 
cyclical peak in late 1993 and should moderate over the next few years. 
This does not imply that the number of arrivals will decline, but rather 
that it can be expected to grow at a slower rate than in the early 1990s. 
The present recovery in the world economy should lead to an increase in 
the growth rate again in two to three years' time.</I>
<P>
<B>T</B>he trend rate of growth in visitor arrivals to Australia has been 
strongly positive for some time, culminating in an overall increase of 15 
per cent in 1993.  Forecasts point to continuing strong, but more 
moderate growth on average for at least the next decade (see elsewhere in 
this issue of <I>Forecast</I>). There has, however, been substantial 
variation in the rate of growth from year to year, and this variation can 
also be expected to continue.
<P>
For many of the day-to-day decisions made by businesses and governments, 
these variations around the long-term trend are vital. Leading indicator 
analysis is a valuable tool for identifying and predicting these 
shorter-term movements around the trend, providing advance warning of 
turning points between accelerations and decelerations in the growth 
rate.
<P>
Regular publication of the indicators developed for visitor arrivals will 
complement existing forecasts and help to improve the level of 
information on which tourism investment planning and policy decisions are 
made.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Cyclical movements in short-term visitor arrivals</B>
<P>
The number of short-term overseas visitors to Australia has grown from 
fewer than 60 000 in 1957, when official record keeping began, to almost 
3 million in 1993 - an average annual growth rate of 11.6 per cent.
<P>
Cyclical movements in visitor arrivals are movements around the long-term 
trend. An acceleration occurs when the growth rate is above the 
underlying long-term trend, and a deceleration when it is below. Thus, an 
observed trough or deceleration in the series does not necessarily 
represent a decline in the number of international visitors to Australia. 

<P>
<IMG SRC="Fig1p23.GIF" WIDTH=329 HEIGHT=166 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>
Since 1969 there have been 10 confirmed cyclical turning points in the 
visitor arrival series (five peaks and five troughs) and a recent peak in 
the September quarter of 1993 (see Figure 1). There are also four 
'double-turns'- that is, fluctuations in the rate of growth that are not 
large enough to be classified as genuine peaks or troughs.<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table1p23.GIF" WIDTH=326 HEIGHT=186 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>The average duration of the completed cycles is 17.8 quarters (see 
Table 1), with the average duration of decelerations (9 quarters) being 
slightly longer than the average duration of accelerations (7.5 
quarters). The most recently confirmed cyclical turning point was a 
trough in the growth rate during the September quarter 1989. The 
accelerating growth period since then has been much longer than the 
average duration of acceleration of 7.5 quarters.  A small cyclical 
deceleration has been recorded since the December quarter 1993, and it is 
possible that a peak in cyclical visitor arrivals occurred in the 
September quarter of 1993.<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Selection of leading indicators</B>
<P>
There are many potential leading indicators of visitor arrivals and a 
number were assessed for suitability.
<P>
Three leading indicators - OECD Gross Domestic Product (OECD-GDP), OECD 
Unemployment (OECD-Unemp) and the Australian Trade Weighted Index 
(AUS-TWI) - were selected from these series. Each of these series 
consistently provided advance warning of past changes in the rate of 
growth in visitor arrivals around the long-term trend.
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table2p23.GIF" WIDTH=329 HEIGHT=167 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>Australian Visitor Visa Issuances (AUS-VISAS) were identified as a 
coincidental indicator. (This means that quarterly movements in visa 
issuances tend not to give any advance warning of movements in arrivals, 
but rather move in the same way at the same time as arrivals.) 
<P>
A long lead length and low variability are two key properties for a 
leading indicator. OECD-GDP has the longest lead to the visitor arrival 
cyclical turning points, ranging from 10 to 12 quarters (see Table 2). 
This is followed by OECD-Unemp with leads of 9 to 12 quarters. AUS-TWI 
has shorter leads at 3 to 7 quarters.<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig2p23.GIF" WIDTH=334 HEIGHT=184 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>The OECD-GDP series, with its mean lead length of 11 quarters 
and a range of two quarters, therefore provides the best leading 
indicator for short-term overseas visitor arrivals (see Figure 2), with 
OECD-Unemp running a close second.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Conclusion</B>
<P>
The leading indicators identified can be used to provide between one and 
three years' advance warning of movements in cyclical activity in visitor 
arrivals. They are not designed to predict the actual levels of arrivals. 
That is the domain of forecasting. However, they provide a better 
indication of short-term prospects for the direction in the rate of 
growth. 
<P>
Leading indicators suggest that the rate of growth in arrivals peaked in 
late 1993, and can now be expected to moderate.  However, given that OECD 
economic growth is now increasing again following the downturn of the 
late 1980s and early 1990s, leading indicator analysis suggests that 
growth in visitor arrivals should increase again in two to three years' 
time.
<P>
The approach described in this report for constructing leading indicators 
for short-term visitor arrivals can be applied to other areas of tourism. 
Extending the analysis to arrivals from individual countries and to 
measures of domestic tourism activity are desirable next steps. Given the 
prospects for increased tourism from non-OECD Asia, investigating the use 
of leading indicators covering more than just OECD economic conditions is 
also desirable.<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=Center><P>
<H2>
<B>What are leading indicators?</B>
</H2>
<P>
Leading indicators provide advance warning of short-term changes or 
turning points in growth rates.
<P>
Although they have not been used previously to predict tourism activity 
in Australia, they are commonly used in the economic arena. For example, 
the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) publishes a leading indicator 
of the Australian business cycle, and leading indicators of overall 
economic activity are published for member countries of the Organisation 
for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD).
<P>
Leading indicators differ from, and complement, traditional forecasts. A 
forecast of short-term inbound tourism would predict actual numbers of 
visitor arrivals. Leading indicators, on the other hand, would predict 
turning points or long-term changes in the growth rate of visitor 
arrivals, rather than actual numbers. They are typically quicker and 
simpler to update than forecasts.
<P>
In developing leading indicators, underlying patterns in visitor 
arrivals were identified. While the long-term trend is upwards, there is 
substantial variation around that trend - periods when the rate of growth 
is above the trend and periods when it is below. 
<P>
Leading indicator analysis identifies these differences and warns of 
changes in the direction of these differences. It involves establishing a 
historical link between the cyclical movements in visitor arrivals and 
one or more of the indicator series. Cyclical series are derived from raw 
data by removing seasonal fluctuations and irregularities from one-off 
events.
<P>
A more complete description of the work involved will be published by the 
Bureau of Tourism Research as Occasional Paper 19, <I>Leading Indicators 
of International Visitor Arrivals</I>.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<!-- Link Tag -->
