<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Forecast Magazine - An encouraging but patchy recovery for hotels 
and motels</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">

<H1><B>ACCOMMODATION</B></H1>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<H2><B>An encouraging but patchy recovery for hotels and motels</B></H2>
<P>
<I>Nationally, the tourist accommodation industry has recovered from the 
recession more quickly than the economy as a whole. The recovery in the 
hotel and motel sector, however, has not been evenly distributed across 
States, with continuing evidence of difficulties faced by owners in some 
regions due to an oversupply of accommodation. Recent changes in hotel 
activity across the States highlight the need for careful analysis of 
local conditions when planning an investment.</I><P>
<P><IMG SRC="P24.GIF" WIDTH=197 HEIGHT=236 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT><P>
<B>H</B>otels and motels receive approximately 80 per cent of the total 
takings in the commercial tourist accommodation industry. Other forms of 
commercial tourist accommodation servicing the needs of holiday makers, 
business people and other tourists include holiday flats and units, 
serviced apartments and caravan parks. <IMG SRC="Fig1p25.GIF" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=205 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=RIGHT>
In some regional tourist markets, such as the Gold Coast, holiday flats and units are an important competitor to hotel and motel accommodation. Similarly, the recent construction of serviced apartments is adding to competition for 
inner-city hotels. 
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics' (ABS)   September quarter 1994 
Survey of Tourist Accommodation data showed that revenue in the hotel and 
motel sector continued to grow strongly (see Table 1 and Figure 1). Hotel 
and motel room nights sold and takings both rose significantly over the 
past year, and the national annual average occupancy rate was the highest 
since 1988-89.<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Table1p25.GIF" WIDTH=337 HEIGHT=188 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
Recently, changes in national hotel and motel average room rates have 
followed changes in occupancy rates after a lag. 
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig2p25.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=206 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT><P>Despite these indications of a continuing recovery, low 
levels of profitability in the industry since the late 1980s have 
discouraged investment in new facilities.  As illustrated in Figure 2, 
the value of commencements and work done on hotels has fallen by around 
80 per cent since 1989.

<P>
There is a need to plan for the construction of large new hotels three to 
four years in advance of opening to allow time for design, approvals, 
arrangement of finance, construction and fit-out. This long lead time 
increases the interest of hoteliers in fore-casting. On the basis of the 
current low levels of hotel commencements, only very limited additions to 
hotel supply are anticipated before late 1996.
<P>
When contemplating an investment in tourist accommodation, however, it is 
insufficient to focus only on forecasts of occupancy rates and average 
room rates at a national level. The recent significant variation between 
States and Territories further suggests that more disaggregated forecasts 
of these variables are required for investment planning.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>State profiles</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table2p25.GIF" WIDTH=335 HEIGHT=245 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3  ALIGN=LEFT>Table 2 illustrates the recent disparity in measures 
of activity for the accommodation industry across States. For example, 
over the past 12 months, the growth in takings varied across States from 
6 per cent to 14 per cent.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Table3p26.GIF" WIDTH=336 HEIGHT=137 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3  ALIGN=LEFT>
These variations between States are not just a feature of the past 12 
months but have occurred consistently over the past three years.  As can 
be seen in Table 3, growth in room nights sold in the Australian Capital 
Territory, Queensland and the Northern Territory outperformed the 
national average; growth in Tasmania, New South Wales and Western 
Australia was at, or only slightly below, the national average; but South 
Australia and Victoria recovered from the recession more slowly.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig3p25.GIF" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=225 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3  
ALIGN=LEFT>Not surprisingly, in a period of limited construction of new 
accommodation, the varying growth rates in room nights sold have had a 
major influence on the ranking of the States in terms of current 
occupancy rates.
<P>
In Victoria and South Australia there has been only a modest recent 
improvement in occupancy rates, which have remained well below historical 
levels for the past four years (Figure 3).  The effect of these 
consistently low occupancy rates has had an impact on rooms available in 
South Australia and room rates in Victoria (Table 4).  <P>
<IMG SRC="Table4p26.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=180 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P>

The recent experience of Victoria and South Australia suggests that rooms 
are not readily removed from supply even in periods of low demand. If low 
levels of activity extend over a sufficiently long time, however, a large 
contraction in supply might eventually be expected.  It also appears that 
the more rooms that are removed from supply, the less room discounting 
might be expected.
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig4p25.GIF" WIDTH=160 HEIGHT=207 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>

By comparison, average annual occupancy rates in New South Wales, 
Tasmania and Western Australia have improved more dramatically over the 
past two years (Figure 4).  However, in the early 1990s occupancy rates 
in these States fell to the lowest levels recorded since the series began 
in 1976 and are only just recovering to pre-recession levels.
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table5p26.GIF" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=177 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>In Western Australia and New South Wales a recovery 
in operator returns has been aided by small falls in the room stock over 
the past two years.  Western Australia, with the largest fall in room 
stock of these three States, had the best recovery in average room rates; 
while Tasmania, with a relatively large addition to the room stock, had 
the largest fall in average room rates (Table 5).
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<IMG SRC="Fig5p25.GIF" WIDTH=162 HEIGHT=211 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 BORDER=3 
ALIGN=LEFT>
Queensland, the Northern Territory and the Australian Capital Territory 
had an earlier and more significant improvement in occupancy rates than 
the other States. Queensland has surpassed the highest average annual 
occupancy rates achieved in the 1980s (Figure 5).
<P>
<IMG SRC="Table6p26.GIF" WIDTH=161 HEIGHT=194 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 
BORDER=3 ALIGN=LEFT>
The Northern Territory showed the largest increase in room supply and 
high growth in room nights sold, yet had a decline in real room rates 
(Table 6).<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
<B>Conclusion</B>
<P>
The historically low level of investment in new accommodation facilities 
over the past two years suggests the industry was hit hard by the 
recession. As investment is normally driven by expectations of profitable 
operation, a low level of investment suggests poor profit expectations in 
recent years, although data on profitability are not generally available.

<P>
At a national level, the recovery in takings has recently outpaced growth 
in the economy. Occupancy rates are back to 1988-89 levels and real room 
rates are now rising. This recovery is in large part due to an increase 
in demand.  
<P>
In States where demand has grown relatively slowly and the recovery has 
come later, data on occupancy rates and average room rates suggest that 
owners are still struggling to get a return on their investment (although 
there are likely to be wide variations in the profitability of individual 
establishments). 
<P>
Both room supply and real room rates did not undergo large declines 
during the recent recession and most of the adjustment during this period 
focused on occupancy rates, which fell significantly. Since the beginning 
of the recovery in 1992, adjustment has again been focused on occupancy 
rates. It is expected that only when occupancy rates reach high levels, 
as is occurring in various regional markets including Cairns, that real 
room rate increases will follow, at least until new capacity is built.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Centre><P>
