<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
A Talent for Tourism - Foward
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 

<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=253 HEIGHT=102  SRC="GIF/Foreward.GIF"></CENTER>


<P>
<IMG WIDTH=161 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 HEIGHT=256 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/Minister.GIF">
Indigenous tourism is an integral and growing part of the Australian 
tourism experience. It is a uniquely Australian product and provides a 
richly diverse attraction for both Australian and international 
tourists.<P>

This booklet showcases a selection of Aboriginal and Torres Strait 
Islander individuals, communities and companies that have achieved 
success in the tourism industry in their own right. Eleven successful 
indigenous tourism operations are profiled. They illustrate some of the 
different ways indigenous people are participating in the tourism 
industry: from selling their artwork and designs to a dealer (and thus 
having limited contact with tourists) to working directly with the 
tourist; and from owning and operating a tourist attraction to hosting 
tourists on cultural tours.<P>

Getting a tourism business up and running is, however, only part of the 
story. The other part - maintaining and building the business for the 
longer term - is more challenging. Meeting the challenge requires 
effective marketing and promotion, good management and a commitment to 
quality service.<P>

Involvement in tourism, in both the mainstream industry and indigenous 
enterprise contexts, can contribute to self-determination, 
self-management and economic self-sufficiency. It can also make a 
contribution to the process of reconciliation.
<P>


There are many organisations that can help indigenous Australians along 
the path to success in tourism. Some of these are listed at the back of 
this publication.<P>

I am particularly pleased to have had these profiles prepared during the 
International Year of the World's Indigenous People. I hope they serve as 
an inspiration to all Australians, particularly indigenous Australians.
<P>
<PRE>

</PRE>
Michael Lee<BR>
Federal Minister for Tourism<BR>
December 1993
<P>


<HR WIDTH=90% SIze=4 ALIGN=Center><P>

