<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
A Talent for Tourism - Bangarra Dance Theatre
</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg"> 
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=386 HEIGHT=159  SRC="GIF/Bangarra.GIF"></CENTER>
<P>


<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Bill Gray</B></FONT>
<P>
<I><B>Bangarra Dance Theatre is a professional contemporary dance company 
employing 23 people (21indigenous). It targets the domestic market but is 
looking to Asia, the US and UK. Bangarra is working towards having its 
own theatre/cultural centre by 1995.</B></I><P>

<P>
When Bangarra Dance Theatre officially launched itself on the national 
stage, the ceremony took place in the executive suite of the Arthur 
Andersen building overlooking Sydney Harbour.<P>

After the champagne and fancy words, it was literally back to earth for 
the new dance company at its studio in a now-demolished building in 
central Sydney.
<P>
<B><I>"The unique thing about Praying Mantis Dreaming is that it was 
totally conceived, scored and performed by Aboriginals and Torres Strait 
Islanders."</I></B><P>
Former dancer Cheryl Stone, who is still with the company, recalls: `We 
relied on school performances to make a living, dashing half-dressed in 
ochre from one performance to the next. We shared everything and became 
like a family surviving on a very basic salary'.
<P>
Bangarra has not only survived, it has established itself as a successful 
indigenous dance company.
<P>
The studio is still shared (these days with a police youth club) and the 
administration is done out of a dedicated, if cramped, office in 
inner-city Redfern. The company believes it is a year away from a complex 
of its own and a second troupe.
<P>
General Manager Rob Bryant puts the transition down to talent, 
dedication, hard work and the ability to find regular funding sources.
<P>
Bangarra (Wiradjuri word for `making fire') evolved out of the Aboriginal 
Islander Dance Theatre, part of the National Aboriginal Islander Skills 
Development Association set up by Carole Johnson, a black American, after 
she arrived from New York in the early seventies.
<P>
<I><B>Caption: Bangarra blends the best of traditional Aboriginal and 
Torres <BR>
Strait Islander dance and contemporary dance</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=395 HEIGHT=254 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT6.GIF"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
Early inspiration came from visiting black dance groups and the enormous 
success being achieved by Graeme Murphy's Sydney Dance Company. The 
decision to form an independent company followed a sharp rise in 
community interest in Aboriginal culture during the 1988 Bicentennial 
celebrations.
<P>
Cheryl recalls that the time `just seemed right' to form an indigenous 
company able to blend the best of traditional Aboriginal and Torres 
Strait Islander dance and contemporary dance.
<P>
Six graduates of the Aboriginal Islander Dance Theatre - Sylvia Blanco, 
Monica Stevens, Jasmin Gulash, Jimmy Gagai, Percy Jackonia and Richard 
Talonga - took up the challenge with enthusiasm, supported by Cheryl as 
Administrator and Carole, who provided development support.
<P>
Cheryl said the group separated from the Aboriginal Islander Dance 
Theatre to establish their own identity and financial base. Money was in 
short supply from the outset.
<P>
<I><B>Caption: Bangarra dancers as they appear in the Australian Tourist 
<BR>Commission's convention and incentive film Unconventional 
Australia</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=396 HEIGHT=218 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT7.GIF"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
`We soon attracted some corporatesponsors - two of them, Arthur Andersen 
and the AAP Group, are still with us - but the support was mainly in 
kind', Cheryl says.
<P>
Rob became General Manager in 1990 after completing a Bachelor of 
Business degree at Sydney's then Kuringai College of Advanced Education. 
An Aboriginal from the NSW north coast, his administrative skills proved 
invaluable in piecing together a strategy that would secure funding and 
build up an effective support structure for the performers.
<P>
Bangarra's first big break came in 1991 with a creative development grant 
from the Australia Council.
<P>
`From memory it was about $26 000, but it enabled us to hire our first 
artistic director and get away from the schools long enough to start 
developing a new creative direction', Rob recalls.
<P>
<IMG WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=323 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Man.GIF"><P>
The new artistic director was Stephen Page, a young Aboriginal who became 
a lead dancer with the Sydney Dance Company after graduating from the 
National Aboriginal Islander Skills Development Association in 1983.
<P>
Cheryl believes this was the turning point. `Up to that point our 
creative directors had been black Americans. Some of us were convinced 
that we needed an Aboriginal in the role, and Stephen has proved that 
right many times over.'
<P>
Stephen's creative skills have expanded Bangarra's horizons well beyond 
Australia, with tours to China, Hong Kong, the United Kingdom and the 
United States. The company's first full ballet, Praying Mantis Dreaming, 
which has completed a two-week season in Sydney, is scheduled to tour 
Darwin, Alice Springs and Mt Isa in mid-1994.
<P>
<I><B>"Unfortunately, too many people shink that if they get an artist or 
artists they have a show. That's not the case. There must be proper 
technical and management support to deliver a professional 
result"</B></I><P>
`The unique thing about Praying Mantis Dreaming is that it was totally 
conceived, scored and performed by Aboriginals and Torres Strait 
Islanders', Cheryl says. `Full credit for that must go to the talent and 
discipline Stephen has brought to the company.'
<P>
Bangarra's success has also extended to performances at the Australian 
Football League grand final in Melbourne and the World Youth Soccer Cup 
in Sydney, and the recently released opera film Black River. It is about 
to start work on another full production - `Hostels' (working title) - 
and has been invited to appear at both the Adelaide Arts and Melbourne 
International Arts festivals in 1994.
<P>
School performances are still given high priority because of the need to 
promote understanding and acceptance of Australia's indigenous cultures. 
They also remain an important income source.
<P>
Government agencies have supported Bangarra during the development phase, 
particularly the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission 
(ATSIC), the Australia Council (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander 
Arts Unit and Performing Arts Board), the Department of Employment, 
Education and Training and the NSW Ministry for the Arts. The Department 
of Foreign Affairs and Trade has provided valuable support for the 
overseas tours.
<P>
`We have a unique product, and this has assisted us in lobbying various 
government departments', Rob says.
<P>
From six dancers and two administrators in 1989, Bangarra has grown to 15 
dancers, five administrative staff and three production personnel. All 
the dancers and all but two of the support staff are Aboriginals or 
Torres Strait Islanders. Similarly, Bangarra's Board is made up mainly of 
indigenous people and draws on a wide range of professional and business 
skills. 
<P>
Rob and Carole believe there are many lessons for indigenous groups 
wanting to establish themselves in the performing arts.</P><P></P><P>`You 
have to know your product, know your audience, know how to put together a 
professional production and be as self-contained as possible', Rob says.
<P>
`Aim to spread the revenue base, with earned income, membership 
development and merchandising accounting for, say, 60 per cent and the 
rest coming from corporate sponsors and other sources.'
<P>
Carole lists the right ingredients as `a good product and infrastructure, 
lots of energy and enthusiasm, a high degree of professionalism and 
strong management to make it all happen.
<P>
`The show must go on. Unfortunately, too many people think that if they 
get an artist or artists they have a show. That's not the case. There 
must be proper technical and management support to deliver a professional 
result.' 
<P>
Rob and Bangarra are now looking for the next big break - Bangarra's own 
complex.
<P>
<I><B>Caption: From the film Unconventional Australia. The appointment of 
an <BR>
Aboriginal artistic director in 1983 marked a turning point in Bangarra's 
<BR>
creative direction and scope.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=410 HEIGHT=257 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT8.GIF"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
`Then we can really become focused. We will not abandon the schools; they 
will become the main responsibility of a junior company, leaving the 
senior group to achieve its full potential.
<P>
`Hopefully we'll have 30 to 50 performers offering a range of 
entertainment. We will even be able to provide dedicated tourism 
performances, something we're constantly being asked to do but can't 
because we do not have the resources to run regular shows. To do that 
properly we must have full creative control ourselves.
<P>
`All that will be possible when we have our own building and can 
establish a more self-contained funding base. Then Bangarra will be in a 
position to set the whole world alight.'<P>

<B>More information about Bangarra can be obtained by contacting:</B><P>
<ADDRESS>Rob Bryant<BR>
Bangarra Dance Theatre<BR>
PO Box 875<BR>
Strawberry Hills NSW 2012<P>
Telephone: (02) 319 4560<BR>
Facsimile: (02) 319 4569</ADDRESS>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>
