HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
MIME-Version: 1.0
Server: CERN/3.0
Date: Wednesday, 08-Jan-97 08:55:05 GMT
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 8091
Last-Modified: Tuesday, 17-Oct-95 03:41:07 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=429 HEIGHT=174  SRC="GIF/Brambuk.GIF"></CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Wayne Quilliam</B></FONT><P>

<B><I>Brambuk Living Cultural Centre was established by the five Koori 
communities of south-western Victoria. It has six full-time staff (five 
indigenous) and up to 20 part-time employees (the majority indigenous). 
Visitors are mainly domestic with an increasing international 
component.</I></B><P>
<P>


The Brambuk Living Cultural Centre brings back to life an almost 
forgotten culture that belongs to the Aboriginal people of south-west 
Victoria, who for morethan 5 000 years have called the majestic Gariwerd 
(the Grampians) mountain range their home.<P>

The Centre, which offers cultural exhibits and activities and an 
Aboriginal restaurant, attracts about 100 000 visitors per year - 
approximately 10 000 of them international tourists. <P>
<I><B>Caption: The Brambuk Living Cultural Centre: superbly <BR>
reflection its surrounding environment in the 
Grampians <BR>National Park</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=268 HEIGHT=420 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT9.GIF"><P>
Brambuk opened in October 1991 after 10 years of planning and 
consultation between the region's Aboriginal communities: the Framlingham 
Aboriginal Trust, the Goolum Goolum Aboriginal Co-operative (Horsham), 
the Gunditjamara Aboriginal Co-operative (Warrnambool), the Kerrup-Jmara 
Aboriginal Elders Co-operative (Lake Condah) and the Portland, Hamilton 
and Heywood Communities.<P>

Their aims were to raise awareness of Aboriginal culture while creating 
employment and generating income for the local community. Brambuk has 
successfully met these goals and is planning to achieve self-sufficiency 
within the next few years.
<P>
Brambuk's visual and audio exhibits graphically bring to life the period 
of Aboriginal history from the days before white colonisation to the 
present, including Aboriginal tools, weapons, art and photographs that 
date back to the beginning of the century.<P>

For the more adventurous there is a large selection of outdoor 
activities. Visitors can accompany one of the cultural officers on a 
short trip into the surrounding bush to taste one of the thousands of 
varieties of fruit, nuts or berries growing in the swamps and marshes or 
listen to the haunting sound of the didgeridoo. Boomerang throwing is 
also popular.<P>
<I><B>"We have to constantly change our schedule of activities to cope 
with seasonal changes--the time of the year plays a big part in what 
program we run"</B></I><P>


The most unique aspect of the centre is the Gugijela Restaurant, serving 
authentic traditional Aboriginal food, including game, seafood and 
vegetables, all prepared in traditional ways but blended with European 
style sauces and seasoning to appeal to all palates.<P>

Tim Chatfield, Brambuk's Senior Cultural Officer, says the original idea 
of the restaurant was to allow people to taste traditional Aboriginal 
food in a setting that would make the experience memorable. <P>

`The main problem was a lot of the food has a strong and gamy flavour 
which doesn't agree with most people's palates', Tim says. <P>

`A compromise was reached by incorporating a number of different European 
style sauces in the preparation.' This formula proved successful as the 
restaurant is now totally self-funding. <P>

According to Tim, the Centre runs at approximately 85 per cent 
self-sufficiency, the other 15 per cent coming from various outside 
organisations to fund cultural tours and similar projects. <P>
<I><B>Caption: Visitors learn about Aboriginal history and <BR>
culture through Brambuk's visual and audio exhibits.</B></I><IMG 
WIDTH=510 HEIGHT=335 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT.GIF"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
`Presently the gift shop generates enough income to be able to restock 
itself and cover wages, while the entrance fee covers most of the 
administration costs. <P>

`We have a variety of charges for activities conducted within the Centre 
and tours around the park; these fees were calculated by working out the 
approximate time of each session along with staff wages and vehicle 
maintenance.<P>

`Most of the major decisions on cultural projects and finance are made by 
a committee of management.' <P>

Tim has been with Brambuk since its inception. After funding for the 
project was approved by the Federal and Victorian Governments, a 
consultant was engaged to prepare a business plan for the Centre.
<P>
`The market analysis included in the Business Plan confirmed the belief 
that visitors preferred an interactive or hands-on experience and that 
tourist interest in Aboriginal culture reached across Australia and 
extended overseas', Tim says.<P>
<IMG WIDTH=295 HEIGHT=121 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Fish.GIF"><P>
`We have to constantly change our schedule of activities to cope with 
seasonal changes--the time of the year plays a big part in what programs 
we run. 
<P>


`We find traditional holidays such as Christmas and Easter are the most 
hectic but school holidays and the October wildflower festival come a 
close second.'<P>

Education has been the major focus of Brambuk and to meet the increasing 
demand from primary and secondary schools the Centre is working with 
outside training organisations to set up programs to assist more 
Aboriginals to enter the tourism industry.<P>



The centre employs up to 26 staff, 19 from the Aboriginal community, with 
an emphasis on multiskilling. Some staff are employed under formal 
apprenticeship arrangements, including a chef, landscape gardener and 
retail trainees.<P>
<I><B>Caption: Brambuk activities provide interactive and hands-on 
experience of Aboriginal culture. <BR>
Here Tim Chatfield, Brambuk's Senior Cultural Officer, hosts a visit to a 
nearby sacred site.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=477 HEIGHT=301 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT10.GIF"><P>
Tour guides are chosen and trained for expertise in understanding and 
interpreting the natural  environment, the Aboriginal relationship with 
the land, animals, birds and plants, and the influence of the environment 
in Aboriginal beliefs and culture.<P>

Brambuk is an active member of the Stawell and Grampian Development 
Association, forming an important link between the Aboriginal community 
and the established tourism enterprises of the region.<P>
<I><B>The market analysis... confirmed the belief that visitors preferred 
an interactive or hands-on experience and that tourists interest in 
Aboriginal culture reached across Australia and extended 
overseas"<P></B></I>


Brambuk has hosted many Australian and international media 
representatives and has received considerable exposure at Australian 
Tourism Exchange and international trade shows. The Centre was the focal 
point for Tourism Victoria's major Gariwerd/Grampians Promotional 
Campaign.<P>

The Centre's site in Halls Gap, in the Grampians National Park, was 
chosen for a number of reasons, particularly its proximity to Aboriginal 
sacred sites. <P>

The Cultural Centre itself is housed in a striking building that is both 
authentically Aboriginal and in harmony with the surrounding 
environment.<P>

The undulating, two-toned, corrugated iron roof represents the features 
of the local cockatoo, while the curving ramp through the centre 
represents an eel, once a staple food in the region.<P>

The landscape was designed to incorporate the thousands of indigenous 
species, all related to the Grampians ecosystem, while taking into 
account the growing and harvesting of bush tucker and medicinal plants, 
which in turn interpret the Aboriginal association with the land.<P>



<B>More information about Brambuk can be obtained by contacting:</B><P>


<ADDRESS>Tim Chatfield<BR>
Brambuk Living Cultural Centre<BR>
PO Box 43 Halls<BR>
Gap  Vic  3381<P>

Telephone:  (053) 56 4452<BR>
Facsimile:  (053) 56 4455<P></ADDRESS><P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>
