<HTML>
<TITLE></TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=478 HEIGHT=162  SRC="GIF/CampCoorong.GIF"></CENTER><P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Steve Dicks</B></FONT>
<P>
<I><B>Camp Coorong cultural tourism and

education centre employs two indigenous people. It is moving from an

original focus on the education sector towards mainstream tourism,

including ecotourism.</B></I><P>

'We're not doing this to get

rich--we're doing it to help solve a problem.<P>

'According

to Tom and George Trevorrow, co-managers of Camp Coorong, this is the

philosophy behind their cultural tourism venture.<P>

<I><B>Camp

Coorong aims for a true reconciliation and greater understanding between

two rich cultures</B></I><P>

Camp

Coorong aims for a true reconciliation and greater understanding between

two rich cultures<--presented as a two or three day study tour of an

ecologically and historically significant area. Schools use the facility

as a valuable teaching resource for their Aboriginal studies courses.
<P>


The Coorong National Park, 200 kilometres south-east of

Adelaide, is a 145-kilometre long coastal reserve where the Murray River

empties into the sea. It is one of the world's most important

sanctuaries--as a breeding site for seabirds, especially pelican, and

for the ancient history that lies buried along the dunes.<P>

The

Ngarrindjeri people have had a link with this land for at least 20 000

years and the remains of their camps are still visible.<P>

George

began organising tent camps for schools in the area when he was regional

adviser in Aboriginal education for the Education Department but his

dream was for a permanent cultural centre.<P>

His dream was

realised in 1987 when, after several months' preparation of a run-down

farm site by the local Ngarrindjeri community, the Ngarrindjeri Lands

and Progress Association was given clearance to purchase the land and

build a toilet and shower block.<P>


The Camp Coorong Race

Relations and Cultural Education Centre began to take shape, with

further grants from government agencies to build two bunkhouses, a

kitchen and offices. Today, the site still survives primarily on

voluntary labour, with George and Tom--a trained Parks &amp; Wildlife

ranger--the only two employees.<P>

Operating costs are

funded through ATSIC and running costs are partly covered by the

relatively small camping fees paid by school groups.<P>

Important

secondary aims are also being realised: to create employment

opportunities for the Ngarrindjeri community and to encourage its

younger members to learn their culture and traditional skills.<P

>Under a Government program--the Community Development Employment

Projects Scheme--24 Ngarrindjeri are working as cleaners, cooks and

gardeners, while others are being trained in farm work, using heavy

machinery, building and environmental management, office practice and

tour guide work. The Ngarrindjeri Lands and Progress Association hopes

soon to be able to put these people into full-time employment.<P>
The community followed a hands-on system of teaching before it became

fashionable. Tour groups try their hand at activities like food

gathering and weaving.<P>

Children are told the creation

story of the Murray River and are taken on bushwalks to discover local

wildlife, traditional medicine and food plants and the old community

burial sites and shell middens of their camps.<P>

`They can

understand that these environments should not be damaged further',

George says, `and that if a four-wheel drive goes straight over an

ancient site or breaks down the dunes it's not just an Aboriginal issue

but an Australian issue. <P>

`There's 5 to 6 thousand years

of history and information in those middens on the Younghusband

Peninsula.<P>
<IMG WIDTH=223 HEIGHT=231 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Woman.GIF"><P>
'While South Australian school groups make up

the majority, other visitors include interstate and overseas tour groups

(with Swedes, Finns and Britons featuring strongly), university

students, government conferences and even Chinese

archaeologists--fascinated by the remains of a well built by their

countrymen who passed through the area en route to the goldfields.
<P>


The 40-bed facility also caters for casual visitors, with three

self-contained cabins and the option of taking bushwalks and guided

tours.<P>

The ingredients for an ecotourism program are here

but Tom feels another dormitory block, a four-wheel-drive bus and a boat

are needed before the expected groups from the United States,

conventions and bigger school groups can be properly catered for. More

lobbying lies ahead.<P>

`We really need two full-time

understudies to learn the cultural teaching from us, plus full-time

employees to keep a place like this running properly', George says.
<P>


It's the stories of struggle and success--and the many

tips--that bring other Aboriginal groups to Camp Coorong. What advice do

Tom and George offer?<P>

`You've got to know your country

and believe in what you do, because otherwise it'll never happen',

George says. `The only reason this has kept going is because we set our

goals a long time ago and set a vision to begin a process of

reconciliation and to teach the true cultural history of our area.'
<P>


Truth is a vital ingredient for success according to the

brothers, who have seen other groups encouraged by some tour companies

to embellish or invent Dreamtime stories. Their credibility subsequently

disappears.<P>

`You also have to put up with a lot of

rubbish along the way from all sorts of people, even your own', George

says.<P>

Decision-making and management is a cooperative

affair, with the community running Camp Coorong through a seven-member

committee and referring all major issues back to the whole community

(around 100 in the immediate Meningie town area).<P>

`When

we first came up with the ideas, nobody wanted to touch us _ it took

quite a while before we were recognised by our own Aboriginal

departments.<P>

`Then after we'd got the land ready, the

departments wanted to come in and pour the money in and put the place up

straight away and we said they shouldn't do it that way.<P>

`We

said we had to develop Camp Coorong by developing ourselves first, so as

the place started to grow, we began to grow in understanding and

knowledge of how to operate and manage it, how to handle people and talk

to people--and discover what people really want to know.<P>

`We're

only just starting to get into marketing plans. We never even

advertised--we said the best form was word of mouth which has really

happened.<P>
<I><B>"We don't put a value on the dollar-- we put education and love and 
understanding first, and I suppose that's what may make us different 
compared with other businesses"</B></I><P>
`Now we're looking to the business side, ATSIC

is going to make people available to help us develop our business

development plan. At this stage, our turnover cannot make us

self-supporting.<P>

'It's the positive feedback from the

groups that keeps Tom and George going.<P>

`When you get the

notes from schoolkids with their little drawings of the Camp, it makes

you feel good', Tom says.<P>

`We've been told by outside

people "put your prices up" but why should we deprive children of

education on Aboriginal culture? As parents, we know how expensive it is

to send our kids on camps. <P>

`We don't put a value on the

dollar--we put education and love and understanding first, and I suppose

that's what may make us different compared with other businesses.'<P>


<B>More information about Camp Coorong can be obtained by

contacting:</B><P>


<ADDRESS>Tom Trevorrow<BR>
Camp Coorong<BR>
PO Box 220<BR>
Meningie  SA  5264<P>
Telephone:  (085) 75 1557<BR>

Facsimile:   (085) 75 1448</ADDRESS><P>


