<HTML><BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg"><CENTER><IMG WIDTH=461 HEIGHT=166  
SRC="GIF/DesertTracks.GIF"></CENTER><P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Diana James</B></FONT><P><I><B>Desert Tracks is an 
educational

ecotour teaching Aboriginal law, culture and lifestyle. It is owned by

an Aboriginal council and employs a manager and 20 casual staff (all

indigenous apart from the manager).</B></I><P>

Nganyinytja is the

elder custodian of Angatja, her father's and grandfather's country.

Angatja is an area near the Northern Territory - South Australia border,

part of the Pitjantjatjara Freehold Title Lands of South Australia.<P>



In 1988 Nganyinytja and her family invited some non-Aboriginal

friends to form a joint tour business with them. The business, Desert

Tracks, was formed with Nganyinytja and family providing the

destination, itinerary and traditional teaching, while their partners

raised the finance for vehicles, swags, equipment, marketing, booking

office and staffing.<P>

`Palya. Ngalya pitjala, nyawa

ngayuku ngura. Welcome. Come and visit my country', is Nganyinytja's

invitation.<P>

`If people wish to come and learn our way,

they can come on a trip to my homeland, Angatja. My family runs a bush

college teaching our law and lifestyle. <P>

`Many people are

ignorant of our way, wanting to learn. Office workers, teachers,

doctors, nurses, Aboriginal people from the cities come to learn--those

whose land and culture have been taken away from them.<P>

`Now

lots of people, black and white, are wanting to learn about the old law,

from our grandfathers and grandmothers. <P>

`We are happy to

share our way and pleased that they are taking back this new knowledge

to their homes--and teaching others. We need to keep the cultures

strong, need the two laws to work together.<P>

`People need

to understand that Aboriginal Law/Tjukurpa is in the land. We live on

the land and are keeping it alive, looking after it as our grandmothers

and grandfathers did, following the law.<P>

'Nganyinytja

says the business has been operating, white and black together, for six

years. It has not been an easy road financially.<P>

`It is

hard when not many people come on a tour or a group cancels. Income is

not constant or secure.<P>

' Nganyinytja's family from

Angatja had to convince the Regional Council, Anangu Pitjantjatjara,

that it was a good idea to have tourism on the Pitjantjatjara Lands, as

it provides the permits.<P>

`We are the first group to try

and look after tourists, making sure they do not go into sacred sites or

photograph things they shouldn't.<P><IMG WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=238 ALIGN=RIGHT 
SRC="GIF/Emu.GIF"><P>


`We have to work hard

looking after these city people who don't know how to live in the bush

and don't know our law. If any tourist broke our law then the tour

business would finish, no more permits from Anangu Pitjantjatjara.
<P>


`We have worked through our problems together by talking at

meetings and asking observers from the Council to come on our trips.'
<P>


Desert Tracks has obtained government assistance for physical

works projects around the tourist camps. Water is now piped to the tour

camp and a toilet has been built.<P>

Recently, finance was

secured from ATSIC to buy the joint venture partners' share of the

business. A company has been formed with all the elders on the Board of

Directors. <P>

`We employ a manager and we hope to train our

young people in running the business', Nganyinytja says.<P>

<I><B>"Much trouble has to come from people forgetting the land, the 
spirit. Many people are sick and have lost their spirit. But we can all 
learn and make our spirit strong"</B></I><P>
They

can be trained as guides, interpreters, drivers, cooks and office staff.

We want this business to be there for our grandchildren, so they can

look after this country and have a job out here.<P>

`This

business keeps alive our law and culture, and can provide skilled work

for our families.<P>

'Training to be a cross-cultural

interpreter is hard. They must speak two languages and understand

cultural differences between polite and impolite questioning, taboo

subjects and sensitive issues, as well as having good general knowledge

of the environment and culture to answer people's questions.
<P>


Manager Diana James runs the office, bookings, finances, vehicles and

equipment. She employs casual staff for trips and arranges payment to

Aboriginal guides, teachers and dancers. The number of tourists on a

trip determines how many guides and dancers can be paid to work.<P>

Desert Tracks is a seasonal business. It closes from December to

February, which is a ceremonial time for the Angatja people.
<P>


A business of this type requires vision and dedication; it may not make

money for up to five years.<P>

Desert Tracks charges around

$1 825 for an eight-day tour that takes in Uluru National Park and the

Angatja Bush College. The company offers a discount for groups and for

direct bookings.<P>

A limit of 200 people a year--ten groups

of 20 people--has been set for the tour. One to two groups a month

enables the business to break even.<P>

Desert Tracks is

promoted as a cross-cultural educational ecotour. The company advertises

through the Northern Territory `Come Share Our Culture' campaign and to

specialist cultural and environmental groups through magazines and

radio. Many organisations come back every year, often advertising among

their members.<P>

`Carefully controlled ecotourism has been

good for my family and my place Angatja', Nganyinytja says.

`It has brought many people from all over the world to share our culture

with us. I am pleased that it is growing and some other homeland

families want to have tourism.<P>
<I><B>"This business keeps alive our law and culture, and can provide 
skilled work for our families."</B></I><P>
`We will help them set up

their camps, plan their itineraries and make sure everything they show

and tell about is not secret but open to men, women and children.<P>

`They will have to get permission from the Regional Council as we did,

so all custodians must be consulted. Then our business will get bigger,

and continue for our grand daughters and grandsons.<P>

`More

people will come and learn about the land. Much trouble has come from

people forgetting the land, the spirit. <P>

Many people are sick and have

lost their spirit. `But we can all learn and make our

spirit strong. Working together builds understanding between different

people of different cultures.'<P>

<B>More information about

Desert Tracks can be obtained by contacting:</B><P>

Diana

James<BR>
Desert Tracks<BR>
PO Box 8706<BR>
Alice Springs  NT 

0871<P>

Telephone:  (089) 52 8984<BR>
Facsimile:   (089) 52 3117<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>


