<HTML><!-- Body Tag -->
<TITLE></TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=365 HEIGHT=162  SRC="GIF/Jumbana.GIF"></CENTER>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Steve Disks</B></FONT><P>
<P><I><B>Balarinji is a designer retail label created and marketed by 
Jumbana Design Pty Ltd. It employs 12 people (three indigenous). 
International tourists are reached through duty free shops. Retail sales 
of the Balarinji label in 1992-93 were up 70 per cent.</B></I></P><P></P>

<P>Aboriginal design is stepping onto the world stage and Jumbana Design 
is leading this new wave.</P><P></P>
<P><I><B>What began as a way of introducing a child to his two distinct 
cultures has blossomed into a multi-million dollar busienss at the 
forefront of Australian design.</B></I></P><P></P>
<P>`Australian' is the key word. For directors John and Ros Moriarty, 
their designs seek a cultural sharing, encouraging all Australians to own 
and be proud of the country's ancient roots.</P><P></P>
<P>Jumbana comes from John's bush name, given him by his Yanyuwa people 
from the Northern Territory. The company's flagship designer label, 
Balarinji, is their two young sons' `skin name', which denotes the 
social, family and legal obligations to their tribal group.</P><P></P>
<P>Since its beginning in 1983, this family business has grown to achieve 
an annual turnover of $4 million. Jumbana Design employs 12 staff and 
uses 15 manufacturers to work up its designs for casual fashion wear, 
swimwear and accessories such as ties, umbrellas, watches and 
sunglasses.</P><P></P>
<P>A range of pure wool carpets and designer eye wear is due for release 
soon.</P>
<I><B>Caption: A Balarinji silk Kimono for the Japanese market--<BR>
an example of Balarinji's innovative cross-cultural style.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=274 HEIGHT=400 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT22.GIF"><P>
<P>The Balarinji label has enjoyed a 70 per cent growth in sales in the 
past year and sales are expected to double in 1994.</P><P></P>
<P>Current markets include major department stores, duty free shops, 
up-market Australian boutiques and the company's licensed Concept store 
on the Gold Coast. Products also sell in Japan (50 designs commissioned 
each year) and France (Freetime casual and resort-style 
fashions).</P><P></P>
<P>`We have been very careful about our positioning within the tourist 
industry', says Ros, the 1993 South Australian Businesswoman of the 
Year.</P><P></P>
<P>`While we are claiming a large and increasing share of the 
international tourist dollar, we are not seeking an image which is a 
souvenir type of operation.'</P><P></P>
<P>Design consultancy work within the Australian corporate sector has 
included Australian National (graphic interior design for The Ghan, 
Indian Pacific and Overland railways); the Australian Tourist Commission, 
Australia Post and Budget Rent A Car (uniforms); and the Australian 
National Gallery.</P><P></P>
<P>`We have deliberately targeted companies which wanted to express their 
"Australianess" in terms of their corporate identity as this fits with 
our philosophy to get this type of generic design into high-profile 
places in Australia', Ros says.</P>
<I><B>Caption: John and Ros Moriarty with a product display. Ros says it 
is <BR>
important that Jumbana's products reflect their origins: 'The creativity 
we <BR>
want to express is bound up in being unmistakably tribal'.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=366 HEIGHT=238 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT24.GIF"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>The Moriartys established the business with their own savings and 
several years of hard work.</P><P></P>
<P>`We started at a time when there was very little recognition of 
Aboriginal art or design, so it was very difficult getting appointments 
with department stores or shops or even to get people to license or 
manufacture the products for us.'</P><P></P>
<P>When company products were accepted, they were invariably placed at 
the bottom of shelves or in corners--yet still sold out.</P><P></P>
<P>`We just kept ploughing on and really it was a good six or seven years 
before we began to show some viability', Ros says.</P><P></P>
<P><I><B>"...we've seen companies burst onto the scene overnight with 
enormous resources but they have also disappeared almost as quickley, 
like shooting stars"</B></I></P>


<IMG WIDTH=223 HEIGHT=231 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Woman.GIF">
<P>`I don't think there is ever a

big break frankly. I think business is about building blocks and often a

"lucky break" is putting a bigger building block onto the foundations

and climbing faster.'</P><P></P><P>Independence remains a key issue

for the couple and from the beginning a decision was made to avoid

government grants.</P><P></P><P>`This was important to us because

John's philosophy was against any dependence.'</P><P></P><P>John's

background explains this approach. He was taken from his family while

young and brought to Adelaide where, after a minimal amount of

schooling, he managed to put himself through university in the late

1960s--the first Aboriginal undergraduate in South 
Australia.</P><P></P><P>

The connection with both family communities is very strong but it is the

Yanyuwa people who show particular pride in the designs and who are

regularly approached for feedback on new designs.</P><P></P><P>This

was the original source of inspiration and as Jumbana expands into new

markets with new products it is also striving to maintain the essential

spark that first ignited its creative look.</P><P></P><P>`Our design

team is deliberately made up of Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal artists,'

John says.</P><P></P><P>`It's that contemporary meeting of two

cultures that we really want to express with Balarinji and they each

bring their talent and inspiration to that process.'</P><P></P><P>While

Jumbana's design, marketing and retailing is sophisticated, the issue of

maintaining its links with the earthiness and raw energy of the original

culture is very strong.</P><P></P><P>`It's the central focus of where

we're going', Ros says. `Something which is simple, functional, well

designed and reflecting its origins is sophisticated. It doesn't mean

the lines have to become slick--that wouldn't be us. The creativity we

want to express is bound up in being unmistakably tribal.'</P><P></P><P>

The company's strategies and products have won a large, appreciative and

ever-expanding audience and the couple puts this down to the strength of

its vision.</P><P></P><P>`If you have a vision, you must stick to it',

John says. `We were lucky--we could have accepted some partnerships and

would have lost the control that we wanted. As a family company, we can

pick its destiny.'</P><P></P><P>`Our other advice would be to grow

slowly', Ros says. `That's been our saving grace as we've seen companies

burst onto the scene overnight with enormous resources but they have

also disappeared almost as quickly, like shooting stars.</P>
<P>
<I><B>Caption: Ros Moriaty talks design with designers Susy Betts (left) 
and <BR>
Cathy Dunn. With Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal artists on its team, <BR>
Jambana has achieved a contemporary meeting of two cultures in its <BR>
design look.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=328 HEIGHT=214 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT25.GIF"><P>
`The

fact that we didn't have significant funds at our disposal forced us to

be disciplined and focused and to grow slowly. Even now, we're capping

development when there are many more opportunities to 
pursue.'</P><P></P><P

>With a seasoned and sharp eye on opportunities, as Australia gears up

for the 2000 Olympic Games, one design company is quietly preparing to

go for gold--on and off the track.</P><P></P><P>Just as Aboriginal

athlete Cathy Freeman is running for Australia, so is Jumbana--one of

the companies sponsoring her.</P><P></P><P>There's little doubt that

the company will be celebrating its new achievements by that time and,

like the games itself, it is actively working to make its success an

Australian one.</P><P></P><P><B>More information about Jumbana Design can 
be obtained by contacting:</B><P>
<ADDRESS>John or Ros Moriarty<BR>
Jumbana Design<BR>
PO Box 3124<BR>
Norwood  SA  5067<P>
Telephone: (08) 364 4774<BR>
Facsimile:   (08) 364 2288</ADDRESS><P>


<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>


