<HTML>
<TITLE></TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg"> 

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=458 HEIGHT=152  SRC="GIF/Kurrawang.GIF"></CENTER>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Jerry Pratley</B></FONT><P></P><P><I><B>Kurrawang Emu 
Farm is owned by a local Aboriginal community and has 11 staff (10 
indigenous). Originally breeding emus and processing their products, 
Kurrawang has added on-site
tours and a retail outlet to cater for growing tourist interest in its 
operation.</B></I></P><P></P><P>Kurrawang Emu Farm Manager Mick Roe 
believes Aboriginal people have a natural advantage in the tourism 
business.</P><P>

</P><P>Mick says international and domestic tourists are crying out for 
information about Australia's indigenous culture and the demand will only 
get stronger.</P>
<I><B>Caption: Sales of emu products and emu chicks <BR>
are now Kurrawang's main earner but tourism <BR>
continues tobe an important source of income.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=232 HEIGHT=295 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT26.GIF"><P>
<P>Kurrawang, about 20 kilometres east of Kalgoorlie-Boulder, on the 
Great Eastern Highway in Western Australia, is an example of an 
Aboriginal community that has successfully tapped into tourists' desires 
to learn more about indigenous Australians. But Kurrawang does not rely 
solely on selling Aboriginal culture. It has exploited a growing niche 
market--emu products. </P><P></P><P>Aborigines have always used emu 
products but, until recently, white Australians have ignored what the 
native birds have to offer, such as oil, meat, eggs, feathers and 
leather.</P><P></P><P>In addition to the emu product sales, tours are 
conducted and visitors are told about Aboriginal 
culture.</P><P></P><P>Kurrawang began operating five years ago with the 
help of a $350 000 Department of Aboriginal Affairs and Aboriginal 
Development Corporation grant that helped set up emu holding pens, 
infrastructure to breed and hatch the birds and a tourist reception 
centre and shop.</P><P></P><P>According to Mick, tourism was the farm's 
major source of income in the beginning but the sale of emu products and 
emu chicks is now the main earner.</P><P></P><P>After the grant and 
initial set up, it took about two and a half years for the farm to become 
self-sufficient.</P><P></P><P>It still receives employment assistance 
through ATSIC's Community Development and Employment Program but is 
otherwise a growing, self-funded operation.</P><P></P><P>Today the farm 
employs 11 people and has an annual turnover of about $250 000 (and 
growing). </P><P></P><P>Mick says one of the most important things to 
consider when setting up a tourism venture, or any business, is to 
approach it in a professional way. </P><P></P><P>`There can't be any of 
this "come to work when you feel like it" business, it has to be treated 
as a nine-to-five operation.' </P><P></P><P>He says people considering 
establishing a venture need some business knowledge but if this is 
lacking, a manager could be employed to get the operation up and running 
and provide training for the community.</P><P></P><P>A non-Aboriginal, 
Mick was employed by the Kurrawang community to get the farm going but he 
will be leaving the community in 1994 to allow it to run 
itself.</P><P></P><P>For a community wanting to establish everything 
itself, there are government-funded training schemes that provide a 
grounding in how to establish and operate a business.</P><P></P><P>`It's 
all there for the asking', Mick says.</P>
<I><B>Caption: Kurrawangstaff with some of the farm's products. Most of 
the <BR>
products are processed and retailed by the farm rather than selling raw 
produce.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=364 HEIGHT=246 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT28.GIF">
<P>`When we started, there were a range of different departments we had 
to go through because ATSIC wasn't around then, but now ATSIC can provide 
help.</P><P></P><P>`I think the success of the business could be put down 
to the way we have decided to value-add to everything we produce so we 
can retail it ourselves.</P><P></P><P>`Most farms farm their produce and 
sell it bulk, but we farm it and retail it ourselves. It cuts out the 
middle man. You farm, value-add and retail. You handle the lot.</P><P>
<I><B>"International and domestic tourists are crying out for information 
abour Australia's indigenous culture and the demand will only get 
stronger"</B></I></P>
<IMG WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=238 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Emu.GIF">
<P>`The carved eggs, for instance, are done here by the locals, we 
process the meat, the oil is quite easy to do once you've got it set up, 
we get a little bit of the leather made elsewhere but overall it is the 
cheapest way to do it.</P><P></P><P>`The major hurdles we had to overcome 
were associated with the initial setting up of the farm, getting all the 
incubators in place and just the general running 
around.'</P><P></P><P>Mick says one of the biggest influences on the 
farm's success was the self-supportive approach adopted by the Kurrawang 
community.</P><P></P><P>`We adopt a different attitude to most Aboriginal 
communities', he says. </P><P></P><P>`Our attitude was that initially we 
got funding to help set the place up then after that we wanted to fund 
everything else where possible.</P><P></P><P>`Instead of going straight 
into a Rolls Royce set-up--it has taken over four years to get where we 
are--we took things step-by-step.</P><P></P><P>`We have since had another 
one-off grant for capital expenditure.'</P><P></P><P>Another aspect the 
community considered was being close to a ready supply of tourists: 
Kalgoorlie-Boulder, an area of almost 30 000 people and Australia's 
biggest producer of gold.</P><P></P><P>`Probably 50

per cent of our visitors are local', Mick says. `It's very important to

have that local base. It's probably how we have got the numbers up

because we have promoted it to the local people.</P><P></P><P>`The

other tourists are made up of about 40 per cent from the eastern States

and 10 per cent international.</P><P></P><P>`There is a general mix of

nationalities which visit but the Asians in particular seem to be very

interested in Aboriginal culture.'</P><P></P><P>Mick says

international visitors demand a higher level of customer service than

domestic tourists. This is the next step in improving 
Kurrawang.</P><P></P><P

>`The international market is growing but we still haven't targeted it

fully', he says.</P><P></P><P>`Basically international people come by

coaches but we still have to get our bus facilities here.</P><P></P><P>`I


don't think we need anything too flash but we need proper toilet

facilities, tea and coffee and other things.</P>
<I><B>Caption: Part of the Kurrawang Emu Farm. There are plans to improve 
the tourist <BR>
acilities to make the farm more attractive to coachlines.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=418 HEIGHT=278 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT29.GIF">
<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
`It makes it

more attractive for the coachlines because if we have all the facilities

here then the people can get everything they need without having to pull

up somewhere else down the road.'</P><P><I><B>"I think the success of the 
business could be put down to the way we have decided to value-add to 
everything we produce so we can retail it ourselves"</B></I></P><P>A big 
proportion of

Kurrawang's income is earned directly through the shop, which is

responsible for catering to tourists as well as managing the general

farm business. The latter now accounts for more than half the farm's

income.</P><P></P><P>`Tourism was the main money-spinner up until

about 12 months ago but now we are putting the farm products through the

shop.</P><P></P><P>`Also, for the last two or three years we have been

selling chicks to set up other farms. That has been going very 
well.'</P><P>

</P><P>Mick says the Kurrawang community has learned a lot about

running a business and combined their knowledge of egg carving, painting

and implement making with new-found marketing and farming 
skills.</P><P></P><P

><B>More information about Kurrawang can be obtained by 
contacting:</B><P>
Mick Roe<BR>
Kurrawang Emu Farm<BR>
PO Box 618<BR>
Kalgoorlie WA  6430<P>
Telephone:  (090) 21 2845<BR>
Facsimile:   (090) 91 1023<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>


