<HTML>
<TITLE>
Talent for Tourism
</TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">




<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=409 HEIGHT=158  SRC="GIF/Manyallaluk.GIF"></CENTER><P>



<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Rob

Gill</B></FONT><P></P><P><I><B>Manyallaluk community conduct cultural 
tours of one to

four days for both domestic and international tourists. The enterprise

employs 21 people (20 indigenous). The current (non-indigenous) manager

is training the Jawoyn people to take over the day-to-day 
management.</B></I></P><P>

</P><P>Tourism has emerged as the most important of a range of ventures

aimed at developing a self-supporting community at Manyallaluk, in the

Northern Territory's Top End.</P><P></P><P>A no-frills demonstration

of the community's traditional way of life and surrounding country is

attracting a growing number of visitors from around Australia and

overseas.</P><P></P><P>What began as a low-key operation rose to

national prominence in 1993 with wins in the Northern Territory and

Australian tourism awards.</P><P></P><P>Manyallaluk, the former Eva

Valley cattle station and now Aboriginal land, lies south-east of

Katherine.</P><P></P><P>The community is based around the old bush

station buildings, which form a centrepiece for visitors. It's a modest

place, clean and well maintained--a tribute to the people who live there

and have pride in their land.</P>
<I><B>Caption: Visitors to Manyallaluk learn traditional <BR>
methods of making everyday items, such as string dilly bags.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=249 HEIGHT=371 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT30.GIF"><P>

<P>Manyallaluk operates under

a recently incorporated community council, the Manyallaluk Aboriginal

Corporation, eking out an existence for a little over a hundred people

on wages paid to only a few. ATSIC funded the construction of a store,

already self-supporting, which serves both visitors and the community.

ATSIC also provides wages through its Enterprise Employment Assistance

Scheme.</P><P></P><P>Tourism entered into the scheme of things when,

in 1990, the Jawaluk Company, representing the interests of the Jawoyn

people, approached Terra Safari Tours operator Tom Winter to investigate

the potential for Aboriginal based tourism in the area. Tom had been

operating tours in the area for some time.</P><P></P><P>His

son-in-law, Murray Dennis, was assigned the task. Both he and the local

people quickly saw that an integrated approach towards better health,

hygiene, nutrition, all-round skills development and greater self-esteem

and confidence would be the only way to make the community

self-supporting.</P><P></P><P>Community members are building new

houses with funds from the Northern Territory Department of Lands and

Housing, transforming the run-down community and gaining valuable

construction training in the process.</P><P></P><P>Manyallaluk is a

dry area--no alcohol for residents or visitors alike. While this may

seem strange in an age of international tourism, it is not out of place

in this area of savannah woodland, melaleuca swamps and sandstone

escarpment.</P><P></P><P>Murray, in association with Peter Bolgi, the

new council president Manuel Pamkal and others, formed the nucleus of

the community's tourism operation by developing the skills of six tour

guides.</P>
<P><IMG WIDTH=187 HEIGHT=140 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Ecidna.GIF"></P>
<P>Peter, who worked cattle on the old Eva Valley

run, was one of the first of those guides. Today, as supervisor, he

spearheads Manyallaluk's unique tour operation and a 19-strong

complement of guides who share the work on a week-on, week-off basis.

Peter's late father also worked on the station; although from the

coastal community of Maningrida, he was a powerful force in keeping

traditional knowledge in the area alive.</P><P>

</P><P>Peter, Richard

Miller (another former Eva Valley stockman) and other guides ensure

visitors are catered for on tours that assimilate the ancient and the

modern. </P>


<P>Terra Safari Tours uses Manyallaluk guides when

it takes visitors into the region. Murray says it is a good way for the

community to learn more about tourism without having to bear the expense

of buying and maintaining vehicles and equipment.</P><P></P><P>Visitors

can also drive their own vehicles over the dirt road to the community

but the people of Manyallaluk make it clear it is their country and they

alone have the right to show it to others.</P><P><I><B>Caption: 
Traditional bush tucker and medicine abound at Manyallaluk. Tour 
operation <BR>
supervisor Peter Bolgi shows new fruit on a green plum tree--a rich 
source of vitamin C.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=408 HEIGHT=271 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT32.GIF"></P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<P>Cars can go no

further than the homestead area, which is well-equipped with a modern

ablution block, camping sites and the store. Natural springs ensure

there is always fresh water in the nearby rock 
pool.</P><P></P><P>Manyallaluk

also brings people in by bus from Katherine, about 100 kilometres away,

for various tours.</P><P></P><P>A one-day cultural experience tells

visitors about local bush tucker and medicines and how to make billy tea

and damper. They mix with traditional owners, learning about painting

and how local artefacts are made, from gathering raw material such as

pandanus leaves for string dilly bags through to seeing the finished

article. The people of Manyallaluk are skilful hunters and their

accuracy with the spear impresses many visitors.</P><P></P><P>Another

tour incorporates an afternoon flight by light aircraft over the

neighbouring Katherine Gorge and Nitmiluk National Park.</P><P>
<I><B>"What began as a low-key operation rose to national prominence in 
1993 with wins in the Northern Territory and Australian tourism 
awards"</B></I></P><P>There's

also a four-day trek which takes visitors through rainforest and

sandstone escarpment country where they can see rock art thousands of

years old on the way down the Katherine River to the Gorge. There, they

are taken by launch for the final stage of this adventure, floating

through five spectacular gorges before being driven back to 
Katherine.</P><P

></P><P>A two-day tour is being developed for the next dry season, when

tourist traffic is at its heaviest.</P><P></P><P>Over the last 12

months the combined turnover from the tours and store totalled $280 000.

The Queensland-based Connections coach company alone took nearly 1 200

people through last season and other operators are keen to explore

Manyallaluk. </P><P></P><P>The Manyallaluk mob know that no amount of

advertising can compete with getting out and telling the world about

yourself.</P>
<I><B>Caption: Pride in what they do is reflected in the trophies won by 
the people <BR>
of Manyallaluk for their fledgling tourism venture.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=366 HEIGHT=261 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT33.GIF">
<P>Peter and Manuel regularly speak to travel

agents and tour wholesalers to familiarise them with Manyallaluk. Manuel

took part in the Northern Territory tourism roadshow through North

America in late 1993 and says that he made many good friends and

industry contacts.</P><P><I><B>"(Visitors) mix with traditional owners, 
learning about painting and how local artifacts are made, from gathering 
raw material such as pandanus leaves for string dilly bags through to 
seeing the finished article"</B></I></P><P>Winning prestigious awards in 
the

first few years of operation has increased the enthusiasm of the people

of Manyallaluk for their tourism venture. They continue to develop their

ability to interact with visitors from around the 
world.</P><P></P><P>Murray

is hopeful the operation will be self-supporting in three to four years

and, ideally, he will be out of a job.</P><P></P><P>But he and the

people of Manyallaluk know there are many potential pitfalls in ending

their successful partnership and all hope the association will continue

in some form.</P><P></P><P><B>More information about Manyallaluk can be 
obtained by contacting:</B></P>
Murray Dennis<BR>
Manyallaluk<BR>
PO Box 1480<BR>
Katherine  NT  0851<P>
Telephone:  (089) 75 4781<BR
>Facsimile:   (089) 75 4724<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>
