</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<TITLE>A Talent for Tourism - Tiwi Tours</TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=359 HEIGHT=152  SRC="GIF/TiwiTours.GIF"></CENTER><P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Garry Dembon</B></FONT><P></P>

<P><I><B>Tiwi Tours, a joint venture equally owned by the Tiwi Land 
Council and Australian Kakadu Tours, offers tours to Bathurst Island. The 
enterprise employs five people (one indigenous).</B></I></P><P>The Top 
End's Tiwi Islanders have got tourism wired. They have slipped it into 
their way of life so gently that it barely shows but at the same time it 
reaps them rich rewards.</P>

<I><B>Caption: Flying into the future: <BR>
Marius Puruntatameri and the Tiwi Tours air Taxi.</B></I>

<IMG VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT SRC="GIF/TFT34.GIF"><P>The 
handful of visitors who cross the Beagle Gulf each day from Darwin bring 
benefits far beyond their numbers. They are just one link in a chain of 
enterprises that let the Tiwi express their character and culture--and 
their entrepreneurial skills.</P>
<P>Bathurst and Melville islands lie 80 kilometres north of the Northern 
Territory capital. They are sparsely populated; more than half their 2 
000 inhabitants live at Nguiu on Bathurst Island.</P>
<P><I><B>"Following airline deregulation two years ago the company 
established its own airline, using a local charter company. Then Tiwi 
Tours really took off"</B></I></P><P>The Tiwi have embraced European ways 
and blended them with their own. Nguiu (pronounced `new you') boasts 
modern three-bedroom bungalows and carefully tended gardens. In the 
cemetery their dead lie beneath Christian headstones and traditional 
pukumani burial poles.</P>
<P>The Tiwi Land Council controls nine businesses, ranging from buffalo 
exports to a pearl farm. All began as joint ventures. Two, a timber 
plantation and a fishing lodge, are now run solely by the Council. The 
Nguiu community itself also runs two fabric design and screen printing 
houses, a clothing factory, a pottery and a cottage arts and crafts 
industry.</P><P></P><P>Organised tourism came to the islands in the early 
eighties with a small day-return operation run from Darwin. Then the Tiwi 
wanted to show more of their traditional hunter-gatherer lifestyle, and 
they recruited another Darwin company, Australian Kakadu Tours (AKT), to 
start a safari camp. In 1989 the Land Council bought the day tour and 
offered AKT a joint venture deal. Tiwi Tours was about to take 
off.</P><P></P><P>AKT was a well-established tour company with an 
international marketing network that drew 70 per cent of its custom from 
overseas, primarily Europe. Its marketing manager and founding partner, 
Darrell Tutty, had 20 years' experience. He was Darwin born and had grown 
up with Aborigines. The

Tiwi had looked carefully and found a winning combination.</P><P></P><P>

`It's very important in joint venturing to get the right person', says

Darrell. `I started with the advantage of having had close contact all

my life with Aboriginal people and having the right business

credentials.</P><I><B>Caption: Cross-cultural tour operator Darrell 
Tuttey <BR>
in the Tiwi pukumani pole display at Darwin Airport</B></I><IMG VSPACE=5 
HSPACE=10 BORDER=4  SRC="GIF/TFT36.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT><P>`Just because 
you're white doesn't mean to

say you can run a business. Likewise, just because Aborigines are black

doesn't mean they all think the same. A person living in the city has a

different outlook than a 70-year-old living on an 
island.</P><P></P><P>`So

a European going into a venture has to understand the politics of the

thing: what the community thinks, what the elders--the

powerbrokers--think; who to see to change something; who's responsible

for a particular area; how significant it is; how the market will

respond.'</P><P></P><P>It's much the same from the other perspective,

according to Tiwi Land Council manager Marius 
Puruntatameri.</P><P></P><P>

`You've got to see things both ways, the culture and European way',

Marius says. `If you've got no experience you must work with a person

who's experienced. That's how you learn. From there on you can operate

yourself and teach other people.</P><P></P><P>`We always look at the

two sides of the story before we make a decision, make sure we talk to

experts, take legal advice. And we always talk with those at the top,

those people who can make the decisions. That's our 
policy.'</P><P></P><P>

AKT and the Land Council have equal shares in Tiwi Tours but the Council

collects a $10 royalty on every visitor, so the community benefits even

if the company loses money. The company has been profitable from the

start.</P><P>
<IMG WIDTH=236 HEIGHT=217 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Turtle.GIF">
</P><P>A maximum of 2 500 tourists a year are flown to

Nguiu from the mainland and shown around the community by minibus. Their

stops are predetermined so those locals who do not want to be involved

can maintain their privacy. Visitors are not allowed to wander freely;

those seeking a deeper experience can spend a few days at the Melville

Island safari camp.</P><P></P><P>At first the returns were put back

into infrastructure. The Tiwi have since used their share of profits to

establish a school nutrition program and run a museum. The indirect

benefits, however, are much greater.</P><P></P><P>Tiwi Tours' biggest

single cost has always been airfares, but following airline deregulation

two years ago the company established its own airline, using a local

charter company. Then Tiwi Tours really took off.</P><P></P><P>`The

idea was to save money on the tours', Darrell says, `but at the same

time it gives the Tiwi people a cheaper passenger service for themselves

and a cheaper air freight service'.</P><P></P><P>Nguiu's artists,

potters, wood carvers, screen printers and dress and shirt makers have

also benefited by selling and exporting their wares. Darrell estimates

the combined value of exports from the islands is about $1.5 million a

year.</P><P></P><P>His company manages the business, handling the

logistics, sales, marketing, development and staffing, while the Tiwi

provide the artistic and cultural input. `I talk to them about

everything I do, out of courtesy and respect for them as my partners',

Darrell adds.</P><P></P><P>Both say the relationship works well and

there have been no real problems. Both also look forward to the time

Tiwi Tours will be managed and staffed by Tiwi people, while accepting

that not all jobs in tourism appeal to the Islanders.</P><P></P><P>Says

Darrell: `Tiwi Tours is a tourism business, and tourists expect certain

standards of dress, hygiene, timekeeping and behaviour. End of story. If

you want to do that job you've got to conform'.</P>
<P>
<I><B>"Be aware that the Aboriginal experience appeals to only about ten 
per cent ot the market, and it's no good trying to sell a three-day 
desert trek to a guy who's only got half a day to 
spend"</B></I></P><P>Marius

agrees: `The opportunity is there to show the outside world who we are,

what we are, and to support our future. The important thing is to

educate our children in both ways, European and Tiwi. We'd like our

students to keep doing courses that will be helpful to the community

businesses, to see this place run by Tiwi people'.</P><I><B>Caption: 
German amateur artist Karin Wahlefield <BR>
learns Tiwi techniques from Doreen Tipiloura</B></I><IMG VSPACE=5 
HSPACE=10 BORDER=4  SRC="GIF/TFT37.GIF" ALIGN=LEFT><P>Darrell

has words of warning for budding tour operators: `If the bank won't lend

the money it's not viable, so don't do it. Be aware that the Aboriginal

experience appeals to only about ten per cent of the market, and it's no

good trying to sell a three-day desert trek to a guy who's only got half

a day to spend.</P><P></P><P>`And beware the advisers and consultants,

a lot of them have their own agendas. Aboriginal people should look at

the mistakes Europeans have made and realise everyone wants value for

money and that some of the words of the white man are not real true some

of the time.'</P><P></P><P>Adds Marius: `You can't expect to make

money overnight. You've got to plan for the future and work hard for

it'.</P>
<P></P><P>

<B>More information about Tiwi Tours can be
obtained by contacting:</B>
<P>
Darrel Tutty or Eric Philp<BR>
Tiwi Tours<BR>Shop 19, Star Village<BR>Smith Street<BR>Darwin
 NT  0801<P>Telephone:  (089) 81 5115<BR>Facsimile:   (089) 81 5391</P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>
