<HTML>
<TITLE></TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg"><CENTER><IMG WIDTH=511 HEIGHT=167  
SRC="GIF/Tjapukai.GIF"></CENTER><P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>by John Schalch</B></FONT><P></P><P><I><B>Tjapukai Dance 
Theatre presents

Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander dance and theatre to domestic and

international tourists. Jointly owned by indigenous and non-indigenous

people, it has 36 full-time staff (30 indigenous) and 8 indigenous

part-time staff.</B></I></P><P></P><P>Tenacity has paid off for a group 
of

people who set their sights on attaining remarkable goals in the

cultural tourism industry and are now reaping the benefits of long, hard

early years.</P><P></P><P>Don and Judy Freeman, as the driving

partnership behind the internationally acclaimed Tjapukai Aboriginal

Dance Theatre, go out of their way to get the message of early toil

across to would-be Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander performers,

entrepreneurs or artists who are considering setting out on the

adventurous road to the top.</P><P></P><P>`It is a lot of hard work',

Judy says. `You cannot take it on and not deliver a quality 
product.</P><P>

</P><P>`Tourism is a seven-days-a-week industry and you can't just

decide one day that you're not going to get out of bed and do it _

although you might feel like it sometimes.' </P><P></P><P>Tjapukai's

success had humble beginnings in May 1987 when the Freemans decided to

use their vast overseas knowledge of community theatre to establish what

was planned to be just a small dance troupe performing in a burgeoning

tourist village--the picturesque rainforest town of Kuranda, in far

north Queensland.</P><P>
<I><B>Caption: Don and Judy Freeman inside Tjapukai's <BR>$1 Million 
theatre complex , where the dance troupe <BR>presents 17 shows a 
week</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=245 HEIGHT=354 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT38.GIF">
</P><P>With talented local Aboriginal David

Hudson and his wife Cindy, the Freemans set to work to deliver a quality

product that encapsulated Aboriginal culture in a way that would be

understood by European patrons.</P><P></P><P>It began as a black and

white friendship and developed deeper when Don, David and six young men

from the Djabugay tribe formed the Tjapukai Aboriginal Dance Theatre and

wrote a play for the tourists.</P><P></P><P>Both Don and Judy agree

they had no preconceptions of what Aboriginal people could or could not,

should or should not, do.</P><P></P><P>`Many of our friends said we

were crazy', Judy recalls. `They said it wouldn't work; and especially

when we decided to charge $7.50 entrance, our friends declared nobody

would pay that.'</P><P></P><P>Almost as soon as they opened they hit

the first of many hurdles when the national pilots' strike cut off the

supply of tourists. In its first year the Theatre traded for only six

months, closing for the tourist `off season', a mistake the Freemans

quickly recognised in what is a 24-hour, year-round 
industry.</P><P></P><P>

But in the six years that followed, the impact of the Theatre was

phenomenal--locally, regionally, nationally and internationally--with

Queensland and Australian tourism awards and international praise heaped

on the proud clan.</P><P></P><P>Tjapukai began with a $45 000 capital

base of private funds and has received no government funding apart from

assistance under Department of Employment, Education and Training Labour

Market Programs for the employment and training of Aboriginal and Torres

Strait Islander people.</P><P></P><P>Now it has built its own $1

million theatre complex, employs 44 staff (38 Aboriginal), presents 17

shows a week and last financial year recorded a 20 per cent increase in

gross revenue to more than $1.5 million.</P><P></P><P>According to

Don, the lesson for Aboriginal employment is that without the skill,

dedication and endurance of its staff, Tjapukai could not 
exist.</P><P></P><P

>He believes the most important single thing that has led to Tjapukai's

ever-increasing Aboriginal employment (up 15 per cent in the past year)

is that it is successful as a business.</P><P></P><P>`And it is a

successful business because that is its primary motivation _ it was not

formed as part of a land rights claim, or to raise the status of one

clan or language group over another, or as a social experiment', he

says.</P><P></P><P>`It is a business dedicated to providing a quality

tourism product to a dynamic industry.'</P><P></P><P>Don says the

Aboriginal operator must be willing to work within the operating

parameters of the tourism industry.</P><P></P><P>`You may think you

have something wonderful and unique, but if it is not packaged and

presented to the industry in a viable and digestible manner, it will

never provide economic self-sufficiency for Aboriginal people.'</P><P>

</P><P

>Success means moving through customer satisfaction to the level of

customer delight.</P><P>
<I><B>"You may think you have something wonderful and Unique, but if it 
is not packaged and presented to the industry in a viable and digestible 
manner, it will never provide economic self-sufficiency for Aboriginal 
people"</B></I></P>
<IMG WIDTH=295 HEIGHT=121 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Fish.GIF"><P>`That is not 
to say an Aboriginal

product needs to be in any way demeaning to the culture. But once you

have decided what portion of the culture you are going to share with the

tourists and how you are going to show it, you must deliver it in a

professional, responsible and reliable way.</P><P></P><P>`And you must

make real contact with the people; you must show some of the heart and

soul which is the core of Aboriginality. If you invite someone into your

home, culture or community, you take responsibility for them _ they are

your guests.</P><P></P><P>`Good customer service is about

inconveniencing yourself.'</P><P></P><P>Judy, Don and the staff all

echo this sentiment--working at Tjapukai is like being part of a big,

happy family.</P><P></P><P>It still amazes the Freemans how many staff

members will come to the Theatre to hang out on their day off because

they are part of what's happening there.</P><P></P><P>Willie Brim, one

of the original dance troupe, agrees wholeheartedly. </P><P></P><P>Aside

from enjoying the financial benefits of his work with the Theatre,

feeling part of a team has been crucial to a major change in his

self-esteem and his way of thinking. </P><P></P><P>`I've changed

considerably in my attitudes about whites. Instead of fighting with them

now we work together', Willie says. </P><P></P><P>Originally from Mona

Mona mission and a member of the Djabugay tribe from which Tjapukai

derives its name, Willie says racism was `bred into you on the 
mission'.</P><P

></P><P>`But this (Tjapukai Theatre) is a way to make it better.'</P><P>

</P><P>He is well aware there are some Aboriginals and Torres Strait

Islanders in the industry who harbour resentment to whites and he warns

it will ultimately hold them back in their bid for success.</P><P></P><P>


`I forget about the past. You don't look at the past any more', he 
says.</P><P

></P><P>At the same time, Willie values his culture and appreciates the

chance to rescue it from extinction.</P><P></P><P>`If this (Tjapukai)

had not been set up for another 5-10 years, the culture would die along

with the elders.'</P><P></P><P>He has some words of advice for those

keen to follow in his footsteps.</P><P></P><P>`Be careful where you

set up and make sure you have the full support of the town or area. And

make sure you consult the elders, or you'll find 
trouble.'</P><P><I><B>"Itis a hard, competitive industry, but it has the 
additional benefit that it is the very Aboriginality of the participants 
which the tourist wants"</B></I></P><P>

Tjapukai is promoted on a world scale: the group performed at  Expo '88

and the recent Australian Music Awards, and has visited almost every

major tourism country at the invitation of either the Australian

Government or the country's own government.</P><P>
</P><P>Through the

Far North Queensland Promotion Bureau and Tjapukai's own marketing

program, the Theatre attracts a cross-section of international and

domestic tourists, reflecting the general pattern of visitors to far

north Queensland.</P><P>
<I><B>Caption: Tjapukai strives to deliver a quality product that 
encapsulates Aboriginal <BR>
culture in a way Europeans can understand. The Theatre attracts a 
cross-section of international and domestic tourists.</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=412 HEIGHT=264 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT39.GIF"><BR CLEAR=ALL>
</P><P>`Those Aboriginal people who choose

tourism as a career have an equal responsibility to see that the work

they do is never short of excellent; that their primary concern is to

help, entertain and educate the tourists who create the wealth which

pays their wages', Don says.</P><P></P><P>`Tourism is a viable career

choice for Aboriginal people. But it is not a cure-all.</P><P></P><P>`It

is a hard, competitive industry, but it has the additional benefit that

it is the very Aboriginality of the participants which the tourist

wants.</P><P></P><P>`This gives the Aboriginal people an advantage in

the job market and a sense of pride in, and affirmation of, their

culture.'</P><P></P><P><B>More information about Tjapukai can be

obtained by contacting:</B></P><P><B></B>Don Freeman<BR>Tjapukai

Dance Theatre<BR>PO Box 408<BR>Kuranda  Qld  4827<P>Telephone:

 (070) 93 7544<BR>Facsimile:   (070) 93 7667<P>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>
