<HTML>
<TITLE></TITLE>
<BODY  BACKGROUND="/images/jpg/chalk.jpg">
<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=424 HEIGHT=159  SRC="GIF/Umorrduk.GIF"></CENTER><P>


<FONT SIZE=4><B>by Jack Ellis</B></FONT><P>

<I><B>Umorrduk Safaris Arnhem Land guides 
tours of Aboriginal rock art, culkture and wilderness areas, targeting

international tourists. Its two owners/employees are indigenous, with

casual staff employed as required. Umorrduk could be bought by the

Gummulkbun people within four years.</B></I><P>

Staying small is the

secret of success for Umorrduk Safaris.<P>

That's how Brian

Rooke sums up the four successful years of this all-Aboriginal tourist

safari venture in western Arnhem Land, 365 kilometres north-east of

Darwin.<P>

Brian and his wife, Phyllis Williams, specialise

in taking small groups of tourists through the Mudjeegarrdart homelands

of the Gummulkbun people, a stunning area featuring some of the world's

best rock art and unspoilt wilderness.<P>

`Aboriginal

tourism is the leading edge of tourism at the moment. It's as hot as a

pancake', Brian says of their decision to start a tourist operation.<P>
<I><B>Caption: Umorrduk Safaris' Brian Rook. <BR>
An unabashed admirer of the Gummulkbun <BR>
people's land in Arnhem Land, he is helping <BR>
to introduce a range of Australian and <BR>
International visitors to its beauty</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=175 HEIGHT=246 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT41.GIF"><P>

`Phyllis and I decided to start a business operating from her

family's land in Arnhem Land. We had a little place out there, a private

camp a bit like an outstation. It had everything, a beautiful little

creek, a waterfall, so we set up a permanent tented camp. It

indisputably has the most beautiful and prolific rock art in the world.

Nowhere will you find more rock art.<P>

'Umorrduk started on

a very small scale while the pair decided whether they liked the role of

tourism operators and gauged the Gummulkbun people's acceptance of

visitors.<P>

`We started doing drive-in tours targeting the

local market', Brian explains.<P>

`We were approached by

another local who wanted to bring people in by aeroplane. After the

first tour we decided the best way was to fly in and leave the vehicles

in the bush. That way we can concentrate on what we're good at--running

the camp and promoting the bush to the clients.<P>

'The

tropical wet season can create problems for tourist operators in

northern Australia but with the air link Umorrduk is able to soften the

impact by concentrating on day trippers.<P>

Phyllis is very

much a local. Her father, John Williams, is a traditional owner and

tribal elder of the Gummulkbun people, while her mother is a Larrakia

from the Darwin region.<P>

Brian, on the other hand, is a

long way from home. Born and raised on the Flinders Islands in Bass

Strait, he left Tasmania for a working holiday around Australia almost

20 years ago.<P>
<I><B>"Aboriginal tourism is the leading edge of tourism at the moment 
It's as hot as a pancake"</B></I><P>

`I met Phyllis in Darwin. I never did make

it around the rest of Australia', he explains. <P>

`Eventually

we set up in a gardening business and did that until the opportunity for

tourism arose. I love getting out in the bush and the opportunity came

to earn a living out in the bush.<P>
<I><B>Caption: Visitors on an Umorrduk safari climb towards an Australian 
<BR>
rock art site. Brian Rooke believes the area boasts the most beautiful 
and <BR>prolific rock art in the world</B></I>
<IMG WIDTH=329 HEIGHT=215 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT42.GIF"><P>

'The business has built

up slowly, using existing funds and operating profits rather than

borrowing finance.<P>

`Our approach to running the business

is one step after another with no debt', Brian says.<P>

He

believes there are three essential elements to running a successful

tourism business: `Reliability, reliability, reliability.<P>

`It

doesn't matter how good a guide you are or how good at bush tucker, if

you're not there to show them, it's not worth two bob. You need to put

in a lot of hard work to gain the confidence of the industry.

'<P>
<I><B>"One of the reasons we stay with small numbers is so we don't have 
any impact on the country, otherwise it just gets over-run"</B></I><P>


<IMG WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=323 ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="GIF/Man.GIF">
Brian says there was an initial reluctance to accept Aboriginal

operators as part of the tourism mainstream but this is changing as

operations such as Umorrduk continue their success.<P>

`It's

been a problem in the past, there have been operators who've let the

industry down badly. Chris Burchett at the (NT) Tourist Commission has

done a great job at breaking down that barrier.<P>

`We have

employed local Aboriginal people at the camp in various roles and as

guides.' The company has received some assistance under Department of

Employment, Education and Training Labour Market Programs.

<P>

`We pay a royalty to the clan and that money is divided up between the

people.<P>

`When we set out we knew that tourism can be

destructive to both the country and the culture. If you're careful how

you go ahead you can turn it into a positive thing which strengthens the

culture. It gives the Aboriginal people a sense of self-worth when they

realise there are people who respect and value Aboriginal culture. <P>

`One of the reasons we stay with small numbers is so we don't

have any impact on the country, otherwise it just gets over-run.<P>

'Like the operation itself, marketing the product has grown slowly but

professionally. In the early days most of Umorrduk's clients came from

the Darwin market. Brian estimates 90 per cent are now international

travellers, including more than half from the United States.

<P>

`The international market absolutely love it. Most of them have never

experienced true bush before. Where we are is real bush.<P>

`The

(NT) Tourist Commission has done a lot to assist us. We also employ a

local marketing company and I do promotional trips. I recently went to

America and last year to the ITB in Germany, to the Expo in Spain and to

London.<P>

'Marketing and promotion are made easier by

working with other operators in Arnhem Land to offer a range of

experiences in simple packages. Umorrduk is working on these packages

with major tourist ventures such as the luxury five-star Seven Spirit

Bay wilderness resort on the Cobourg Peninsula.<P>

`They

complement what we do here. We send people to them and they send some of

their people to us. We're starting to provide tours which combine a

five-star experience with what we do. Tourists don't have to shop around

for individual tours.<P>

'Brian says decisions affecting the

operation are made in close consultation with the Gummulkbun people.<P>

`Phyllis and I sit down and work out together what is best for

the business. If we want to change something we take it to the clan and

consult before we make a decision about what we can do on their land.

The clan elders decide what we can and can't do.<P>

'Looking

ahead three or four years, there could be an exciting development for

the Gummulkbun people.<P>
<I><B>Caption: Arnhem Land's beauty and variety attracts thousands of 
tourists every year, <BR>but the owners of Umorrduk Safaris have kept 
their operation small to minimise the <BR>impact on the land and retain 
the personalised service that has made their venture <BR>a sucess</B></I>

<IMG WIDTH=402 HEIGHT=264 VSPACE=5 HSPACE=10 BORDER=4 ALIGN=LEFT 
SRC="GIF/TFT44.GIF">
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
`We'd like to sell (Umorrduk) to

the people, we'll ask them if they're interested in buying the

business', Brian says. `We'd like to see more involvement by the rest of

the clan. I'd stay on as manager but they'd be more involved if they

owned the business.<P>

`They'd also be eligible for

assistance under the ATSIC policy to make any improvements to the

operation. Phyllis would like it to continue on a small scale - not to

get out of control - to retain the qualities that make the product what

it is. <P>

`There's a lot of people out there who are

willing to pay for a more personalised and exclusive experience.'<P>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<B>More information about Umorrduk can be obtained by contacting:</B>
<p>
<ADDRESS>Brian Rooke<BR>Umorrduk Safaris Arnhem Land<BR>PO Box

41086<BR>Casuarina  NT  0811<P>Telephone:  (089) 48 1306<BR>Facsimile:

  (089) 48 1305<P></ADDRESS>
<HR WIDTH=90% SIZE=4 ALIGN=CERTER><P>
