<HTML><HEAD><!-- This document was created by Adam Clarke of Computer
Law Services.-->
<TITLE>Rural Tourism Strategy - Foreword</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif">(c) Commonwealth of Australia 1994<P></P><P>ISBN 0 644 42709 H</P><P
></P><P>This work is copyright. Apart from any use permitted under the
<I>Copyright Act 1968, </I>no part may be reproduced without written
permission from the Australian Government Publishing Service. Requests
and inquiries concerning reproduction and rights should be addressed to
the Manager, Commonwealth Information Services, Australian Government
Publishing Service, GPO Box 84, Canberra ACT 2601.</P><P>Designed by
the AGPS Design Studio<BR>Typeset by Signature Jer 31:33, Canberra
</P><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">Message from the Minister
</A></H1>
<P>Rural tourism provides an opportunity for country Australia to share
in the nation's spectacular tourism growth. Through planned development
and targeted marketing of the diverse range of rural tourism products
available, country towns, local communities and individuals can benefit
from this emerging segment of the tourism industry.</P><P></P><P>Enticing
tourists to venture beyond Australia's capital cities will not only
benefit rural areas, but will demonstrate a greater diversity of tourism
product that can make Australia more competitive as an international
tourism destination. </P><P></P><P>To realise the potential of rural
tourism, it is necessary to develop and package new and better tourism
products that are responsive to the current demands of visitors, both
domestic and international. Travellers are seeking environments in rural
Australia that combine recreational, cultural, educational and social
experiences with country living. To capitalise on this demand for a
`country experience', a number of key issues must be addressed.</P><P></P><P
>The Federal Government believes that an overall policy framework for
the development and marketing of rural tourism nation-wide will serve to
optimise the benefits it offers to both Australians and tourists. The
<I>National Rural Tourism Strategy</I> encourages an integrated
approach to improvements in this industry sector.</P><P></P><P>The
Strategy has been developed in consultation with industry and the
public, including a national call for submissions on <I>Tourism
Discussion Paper No. 1--Rural Tourism </I>that was circulated for
comment in January 1993 (see Appendix A). Later that year, a Rural
Tourism Focus Group, comprising key tourism representatives from
industry and government (see Appendix B), assisted in identifying major
issues affecting rural tourism development, including product and
enterprise development, marketing, industry standards, and education and
training. </P><P></P><P>This year, a needs analysis consultancy,
funded by the Federal Government and commissioned by Australian Farm and
Country Tourism Inc., examined these issues further and its findings
have been incorporated into the National Rural Tourism Strategy.</P><P></P><P
>The Government's commitment to rural tourism is evidenced in its
provision of a $42&nbsp;million package of regional tourism development
initiatives announced in the 1993-94 Budget, including some $4 million
over four years specifically for the Rural Tourism Program.</P><P></P><P>
Under this program, a total of $933&nbsp;000 was allocated in 1993-94
for discretionary projects, consistent with the directions of the Rural
Tourism Focus Group. These projects had national application which
included support for industry leadership; education in sales and
marketing; customer-service training; international marketing,
specifically of rural tourism; and demonstration projects which have a
regional emphasis.</P><P></P><P>The Strategy will guide funding
initiatives for the remaining three years of the Rural Tourism Program,
complementing the work that is already under way.</P><P></P><P>I
believe the<I> National Rural Tourism Strategy </I>provides the
framework required for government and industry to successfully advance
the rural tourism industry into a prosperous and sustainable future.</P><P>
</P><P></P><P></P><P><B>Michael Lee MP</B></P><P><B></B>Federal
Minister for Tourism</P><P>December 1994</P><P>
</P><H1><A NAME="RTFToC2">Overview</A></H1>
<B></B><P><B>Rural tourism </B>has been defined broadly as a <B>country
experience</B>. The range of tourism products includes rural
attractions, rural adventure and nature-based tours, country towns,
rural resorts, farm stays<B> </B>and other styles of country
accommodation, country<B> </B>festivals and events, and agricultural
education.</P><P></P><P>The <I>National Rural Tourism Strategy</I>
examines the importance of rural tourism as an industry and looks at how
industry and government can contribute to its growth through considered
planning, development and management. Because tourism can have a
significant impact on the economic and social well-being of rural
communities, as well as affecting the environment, there is a need to
consider fully the variety of changes tourism can bring and to seek
outcomes that are sustainable over the medium and longer term.</P><P></P><P
>The Strategy describes the many participants in this emerging industry.
The programs and initiatives of Federal, State and Territory Governments
are briefly mentioned. </P><P></P><P>The key issues requiring action
by stakeholders have been identified through an extensive consultation
process. In addition, the Strategy incorporates comments by a needs
analysis consultancy (funded by the Federal Government) undertaken by
Australian Rural Management Services and commissioned by Australian Farm
and Country Tourism Inc. The consultancy was required to define and
analyse impediments to rural tourism growth and to suggest practical
measures to address them. </P><P></P><P>The key issues, which are
detailed in Chapter 6, are:</P><P>	increased focus on product and
enterprise development, particularly featuring regional integration;</P><P>
	the need for appropriate accreditation and industry standards to ensure
services and products are of sufficient quality and are competitive;</P><P>
	provision of opportunities for education and training for new and
experienced rural tourism operators;</P><P>	facilitation of innovative
and cooperative marketing to both the domestic and international
traveller;</P><P>	undertaking of market analysis to allow informed
policy formulation, planning, development of product and targeting of
markets, and to aid investment in rural tourism;</P><P>	provision of
strong and informed industry leadership;</P><P>	provision of transport
and infrastructure; and</P><P>	recognition of the important role of
local government in furthering rural tourism in the regions.</P><P>
</P><H1><A NAME="RTFToC3">Implementation</A></H1>
<P>The Strategy suggests actions to address each issue and indicates
notional responsibilities.</P><P>Some of the actions in which Federal
Government involvement is envisaged may be financed through the Rural
Tourism Program. This program and projects funded in its first year of
operation, 1993-94, are described in Chapter 7. </P><P></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
