<!DOCTYPE HTML SYSTEM "html.dtd">
<HTML><HEAD><!-- This document was created by Adam Clarke of Computer 
Law Services.-->
<TITLE>Regional Tourism Strategy - Chapter 1 - Chapter 6.3</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H1><A NAME="RTFToC1">CHAPTER 1 WHAT IS RURAL TOURISM?
</A></H1>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC2">1.1 Definition of rural tourism
</A></H2>
<P>Rural tourism is a multifaceted activity that takes place in an
environment outside heavily urbanised areas. It is an industry sector
characterised by small scale tourism businesses, set in areas where land
use is dominated by agricultural pursuits, forestry or natural areas.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism can represent to the traveller the essence of country
life. It would be unwise to define rural tourism too narrowly as it
involves travellers' perceptions that they are experiencing `the
country'.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism should be seen as offering a different range of
experiences to those offered in big cities. In Australia, 86 per cent of
the population live in cities with a population of 100&nbsp;000 or more,
and for many of these urban dwellers a visit to the country adds variety
to their day-to-day life. To many international visitors,<B> </B>rural<B>
 </B>Australia provides a unique experience.
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC3">1.2 The components
</A></H2>
<P><B>The emphasis in rural tourism is on the tourist's experience of
the products and activities of rural Australia. </B></P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P>A tourist<B> </B>(or visitor or traveller) is any person taking a
day trip or staying overnight who is travelling more than 40 kilometres
away from his or her normal place of residence, except to commute to and
from his or her usual place of work. This includes domestic and
international travel, whether for business or pleasure. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism<B> </B>products/activities are numerous. Activities
contributing to the experience include relaxing; sightseeing; camping;
visiting friends and relatives; discovering historic towns; travelling
to heritage sites of cultural and social significance; visiting museums
and art galleries; shopping for local arts and crafts and produce;
wining and dining; and attending festivals, rodeos, country shows and
local sporting events. People may participate in sport (golf, fishing,
local cricket games), hiking in national parks, rafting, skiing,
abseiling and caving. Holidays can involve farms, either through
agribusiness tours or farm stays. Other visitors may elect to stay in
caravan parks, country motels/hotels or resorts, bed and breakfasts or
backpacker accommodation. Tours can be taken to scenic areas, wildlife
reserves, wineries and factories, either for pleasure or educational
purposes.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism activities in Australia are often segmented into the
following categories:</P>
<UL><LI>rural attractions;</LI>
<LI>rural adventure tours, nature-based tours, and ecotourism tours;</LI>
<LI>country towns;</LI>
<LI>rural resorts<B> </B>and other styles of country accommodation;</LI>
<LI>farm and station holidays;</LI>
<LI>festivals and events, and;</LI>
<LI>agricultural education.</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>In addition, the rural tourism experience should not be confined to
what happens at the destination: the travelling involved can be an
integral part of the `country experience'.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In defining `rural Australia' for the purposes of this Strategy,
various interpretations were considered.1 In line with the broad view to
be taken in a national strategy and to encompass the wide distribution
of rural tourism products, the Department of Tourism (DoT) has adopted
the definition used in the Commonwealth Working Group's Report, <I>Rural
Data </I>(1992).<I></I>Rural Australia is defined as `those geographic
areas which exclude the Capital City Statistical Divisions and the
Statistical Subdivisions which surround other urban centres whose
populations exceed 100 000'.</P>
<P></P>
<P>This means that rural tourism can exist outside of Australian
capital cities and Canberra-Queanbeyan, Newcastle, Wollongong, Geelong,
Gold Coast-Tweed-Albert Shire Part B and Townsville-Thuringowa. While it
is recognised that this wide definition classifies some moderately large
population centres as rural, it reflects the perceptions that many
visitors, especially those from overseas, have of travelling in
Australia. It also gives people living and working in these areas the
chance to participate in programs devised to develop and promote rural
tourism.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In Australia, rural tourism is sometimes segmented into island,
coastal, hinterland, country, bush, outback or remote tourism. (Some of
these terms are overlapping and the areas they refer to can differ
according to the user.) This segmentation can, however, be used
successfully to delineate niche market destinations and the type of
travel within the broad definition of rural tourism used in this
Strategy.</P>
<P></P>
<P>1	The Australian Bureau of Statistics broadly identifies urban as a
population cluster of 1 000 or more people.  Local government areas are
classified according to population, population density and land use:  a
general measure is a population cluster greater than 20 000.  Even
within the Australian Automobile Association, definitions of `rural'
vary: `Country area, Pastoral or Agricultural' (Royal Automobile Club of
Queensland), `Outside of a City/Town limit and therefore not in settled
areas' (Royal Automobile Association of South Australia), `Rural is any
area outside the major urban areas' (National Roads and Motorists
Association); and `Rural is anything outside the urban boundary of major
centres' (Royal Automobile Club of Tasmania). </P>
<P></P>
<P>	The Tourism Committee of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD) sees `rurality as a concept ... connected with
low population densities and open space, and with small scale
settlements, generally of fewer than 10 000 inhabitants (where) ... land
use is dominated by farming, forestry and natural areas'. 
</P>
<H1><A NAME="RTFToC4">CHAPTER 2 WHY DEVELOP RURAL TOURISM?
</A></H1>
<P>In Australia, as in many countries, the value of tourism for rural
development is increasingly being recognised.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Local communities can gain significant benefits from rural tourism,
provided it is properly planned and managed. Benefits include:</P>
<UL><LI>increased non-agricultural income;</LI>
<LI>diversification of the region's economic base; and </LI>
<LI>improved employment opportunities in rural areas from associated
activities.
</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>There are also social and environmental advantages such as:</P>
<UL><LI>the use of visitor facilities for community purposes; </LI>
<LI>greater community cohesion with fewer young people drifting to the
cities to find work; </LI>
<LI>opportunities for interaction with people from differing
socioeconomic and cultural backgrounds; </LI>
<LI>the recognition of the need to preserve the `natural' landscape for
both tourists and others. Indeed, tourism can promote more interest in
repairing environments through such activities as tree planting,
sustainable farming practices, repairing coastal sand dunes, etc.; and</LI>
<LI>the enhancement of the built environment.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The development of rural areas through tourism is consistent with
the Federal Government's regional development initiatives which
emphasise the capacity of regional Australia to `help itself' and be
proactive in attracting investment. Government initiated studies such as
those of the Taskforce on Regional Development, <I>Developing
Australia: A Regional Perspective</I>, and the McKinsey Report, <I>Lead
Local Compete Global</I> (1994b), focus on the strategic modernisation
and development of regional Australia, including its tourism potential.
The White Paper on Employment and Growth, <I>Working Nation,
</I>and the Industry Commission report, <I>Impediments to Regional
Industry Adjustment,</I> also emphasise the importance of regions
increasing their self-sufficiency and focusing more on integration with
the national economy, thus enhancing the country's overall productive
capacity. </P>
<P></P>
<P>The Government's commitment to developing and diversifying regional
economies by assisting the tourism industry is evident in a number of
tourism programs that were introduced in the 1993-94 Federal Budget.
Besides the Rural Tourism Program (described in Chapter 7), the Regional
Tourism Development Program, the National Ecotourism Program, the Sites
of National Tourism Significance Program and the Backpacker Program all
have a bearing on the development of tourism in regional Australia.
These programs, including the Forest Ecotourism Program developed under
the <I>National Forest Policy Statement</I>, are administered by the
Commonwealth Department of Tourism and detailed in Appendix C.
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC5">2.1 Benefits
</A></H2>
<P>Tourism development needs to be sustainable if it is to bring about
<B>long-term </B>economic, environmental and social gains. To survive
as a viable industry, tourism must be developed with the needs of the
community and the environment in mind and in line with plans for the
development of a region as a whole. Otherwise there is a danger that
long-term benefits and the sustainability of the industry can be
sacrificed for short-term gains.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Economic benefits</P>
<P></P>
<P>As the Bureau of Tourism Research (BTR) forecasts 4.8 million
international visitors per year by the year 2000, it is important that
the economic benefits of tourism be spread to Australia's rural
communities.</P>
<P></P>
<P>While there is currently no clear estimate of the value of rural
tourism in Australia, figures from the BTR suggest that 60 per cent of
domestic tourism expenditure and around 20 per cent of international
tourism expenditure occur outside the major urban centres. In 1993,
these figures combined amounted to more than $12 billion.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism can therefore represent an additional source of income to a
rural community. The primary source of income will often be derived from
agricultural, mining, forestry or fishing industries, which in
themselves may be an attraction for visitors. This complementarity is
demonstrated in the case of the wine growing areas of Australia, where
tourism forms a profitable adjunct to an already successful and
prosperous industry.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism initiatives also have the potential to add further value to
an existing rural resource. An example of this is the Tambo Teddies
initiative in central Queensland. In this case, a small group of local
Tambo people, as a result of involvement in a Queensland
Government-supported workshop, identified the manufacture of teddy bears
from sheep skin as a viable cottage industry. Tambo Teddies has become
an additional attraction for tourists to central Queensland, adding to
such recognised attractions as the Stockman's Hall of Fame at Longreach
and extending the tourism diversity offered along the Matilda Highway.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism can provide an opportunity to expand the economic base of a
local area or region and can bring to the community a number of new
skills and employment opportunities. Accommodation, entertainment, food
provision, information services and souvenirs of the rural experience
are all parts of the tourism industry. These factors bring extra income
directly to a rural area. They also have a regional<B> </B>economic
multiplier effect as this additional income is spent by recipients.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Environmental benefits</P>
<P></P>
<P>The relationship of tourism to the physical<B> </B>environment is a
complex one. While Australia's environment remains one of the major
motivational factors for domestic and international travel in<B> </B>Australia,
it is essential that increased tourism is accompanied by proper care and
management of sensitive areas and that environmental concerns are not
ignored for short-term profit. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Recognition by both environmental and tourism interests that the two
can be compatible can assist the sustainability of each in the long
term. The economic importance of tourism to Australia and the need to
maintain the tourism product has led to increased attention being paid
to sustainable tourism practices and, hence, to environmental
conservation.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Because of increased environmental awareness both at home and
abroad, governments, as well as industry, are taking responsibility for
regulating tourism development. Australia is a signatory to a number of
international treaties which also have implications for tourism
development, for example, the Antarctic Treaty System (which includes
the Antarctic Treaty and Protocol on Environment Protection) and the
World Heritage Convention.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The principles of environmentally sustainable development in tourism
are recognised by the Federal Government in the National Tourism
Strategy, the National Ecotourism Strategy and various policies
developed in conjunction with State and Territory Governments. These
principles also underpin government programs such as the National
Ecotourism Program, the Sites of National Tourism Significance Program,
and the Forest Ecotourism Program. Tourism industry associations such as
Pacific Asia Travel Association and Tourism Council Australia (TCA),
formerly Australian Tourism Industry Association, also have developed
environmental codes.</P>
<P></P>
<P>At the same time, the relatively low concentration of tourists<B></B>in
most rural areas means that many of the negative aspects of large scale
tourism development--greater pressure on services and infrastructure,
environmental stress and upward pressure on prices--can be avoided,
provided adequate resources are available.</P>
<P></P>
<P>An element of rural tourism is travelling in the countryside.<B></B>This
aspect<B> </B>can help to disperse visitor loads and spread tourism
across a variety of sites by developing<B> </B>recognised touring
routes. A good example of this is the Matilda Highway in outback
Queensland, mentioned above, where motorists are encouraged to stop and
see a range of outback scenery, pioneering history, sheep stations and
cattle properties, fossil sites, gemfields and ancient Aboriginal sites.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism may add value to land that might otherwise have been
used solely for agricultural purposes. This will further encourage
landholders to protect and preserve their properties through careful
land management and conservation practices and involvement in movements
such as Community<B> </B>Landcare, a Federal Government initiative,
administered by the Department of Primary Industries and Energy, to
assist land, water and related vegetation projects.
</P>
<P></P>
<P>While Landcare's main objective is to preserve and sustain the rural
environment, it also fulfils an important educational function by
providing people from all walks of life, including visitors from
overseas, with an opportunity to participate in environmental
conservation. The recent advent of educational tour groups, including
international groups with farming interests, to areas where Landcare
practices are being followed, is becoming an important medium for
conveying Australia's conservation ethics and practices to the rest of
the world. Technical visits to farming areas, sometimes known as
agritourism, also have some general benefits in terms of the dollars
spent by the tour groups and the opportunity to expose the visitors to
other tourism locations and experiences.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Social benefits</P>
<P></P>
<P>The social impacts of tourism, whether from tourism infrastructure
or the tourists themselves, affect Australians in their communities.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The positive social impacts of tourism can be significant provided
the appropriate community consultative, educative and information
processes are followed. They can include:</P>
<UL><LI>a sense of community pride where residents consider the
attention of tourists to be indicative of their town's or area's
natural, cultural or historical attractiveness. This can lead to more
positive perceptions of tourism impacts and encourage new ideas and
initiatives to develop and manage tourism growth;</LI>
<LI>the maintenance of, and possible increases in, rural and regional
populations due to the decentralisation of tourism. Tourism jobs
accompanied by appropriate education and training programs may encourage
people to stay on in rural areas, thus contributing to local community
stability and sustainability;</LI>
<LI>a reduction in the isolation felt by many rural communities and the
opportunity for individuals to broaden their horizons by meeting new
people, particularly when there is direct personal contact between
tourists and hosts, as is more common in rural areas;</LI>
<LI>enhancement of lifestyle through the development of visitor
facilities and services which can also be enjoyed by the local
community;</LI>
<LI>the economic prosperity of a region generated by the extra income
derived from tourism, the circulation of which through the community can
act as a buffer against highs and lows of rural economies and hence
against reduced income cycles and their consequent social impacts; </LI>
<LI>the maintenance and enhancement of the cultural attributes of a
community through the preservation, development, interpretation and
promotion of traditional arts and crafts, heritage, rural industry and
lifestyles; and</LI>
<LI>the maintenance of environmental integrity, for example, visitor
expenditure being used for environmental preservation.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>It is important to gauge tourism's social impacts on a community so
that negative impacts, where possible, can be avoided, alleviated or
overcome. Unwanted effects could include: </P>
<UL><LI>disruption to daily life owing to invasion of privacy,
including invasion of traditional community events and activities
causing loss of heritage; traffic congestion and overcrowding;</LI>
<LI>cost burdens on local councils to meet the needs of non-residents;<B>
</B></LI>
<LI>site use conflicts where tourism developments may adversely affect
community leisure and recreation opportunities, and where, for example,
local sports facilities may become congested and overpriced;</LI>
<LI>environmental degradation as a result of exceeding carrying
capacities;</LI>
<LI>increased prices of facilities, food and services making these more
expensive than elsewhere and thus out of reach of the local community;</LI>
<LI>rent increases, accommodation shortages, inflated real estate
values and high council rates; and</LI>
<LI>the perception of increased crime rates due to the presence of
tourism.</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>Many of these negative effects can be minimised or even avoided if,
in the initial stages of planning tourism development, a community
consultation process is put in place and<B> </B>community perspectives
are obtained.<B></B></P>
<P><B></B>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC6">2.2 Challenges
</A></H2>
<P>Tourism's advantages to an area can greatly outweigh its
disadvantages. Tourism management policies at the local and regional
level which place a high priority on integrated strategic planning and
community participation can successfully alleviate potential
environmental and social problems. (One of the programs administered by
the Department of Tourism, the Regional Tourism Development Program, is
specifically designed to address the issue of strategic planning at the
local and regional levels.)<B></B></P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P>The need for careful assessment of an area's potential as a tourism
destination is an essential first step.</P>
<P>Tourism is, of course, not for every rural community. It should not
be regarded as a quick-fix for all economic ills. Factors such as long
distances from major gateways, poor scenic attractions and lack of
tourism infrastructure can mean that rural tourism may not be
appropriate for a particular region. Even communities that have the
physical assets may rightly choose not to develop tourism if they
perceive the costs to outweigh the potential benefits. Tourism is only
one option for diversification. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural Australia currently offers tourism products that are diverse,
of good quality and have the potential to satisfy the growing demand for
a `country experience'. At a time when international competition for the
travel dollar is growing, the challenge for Australians is to capitalise
on Australia's natural advantages. There is a need to continue to
improve and better package tourism products and to develop new products
responsive to shifts in market demand.
</P>
<H1><A NAME="RTFToC7">CHAPTER 3 WHY HAVE A NATIONAL RURAL TOURISM
STRATEGY?
</A></H1>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC8">3.1 tourism facts and figures
</A></H2>
<P>Tourism in the world economy</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism is one of the world's most economically significant
industries. Despite a global economic downturn, tourism worldwide
continues to be one of the few industries showing solid growth.</P>
<P>The World Tourism Organisation estimates that, in 1993, world
tourism receipts (excluding international transport receipts) increased
by 9.3 per cent to $US 324 billion.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The World Travel and Tourism Council estimates that, in the same
year, the industry employed around 127 million people worldwide,
representing 7 per cent of all jobs.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In 1993, international tourist arrivals at borders around the world
increased by 4 per cent to 500 million. The East Asia and Pacific region
was the fastest growing region, with arrivals up 12 per cent in 1993 to
68.5 million. It accounted for 14 per cent of all world arrivals. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism in Australia</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism is one of Australia's fastest growing and most economically
significant industries. In 1991-92, the industry contributed around 5.6
per cent to Gross Domestic Product. </P>
<P></P>
<P>In 1993-94, international tourism to Australia generated export
earnings of $10.6 billion (up 15.4 per cent on 1992-93), accounting for
12 per cent of Australia's total export earnings. The industry is adding
an additional $1.4 billion to export earnings annually, around 26 per
cent of all export growth. If industry growth projections are realised,
tourism is expected to generate between $15 and $21 billion (1992
prices) annually in export earnings by the year 2000.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Over the last ten years, the number of overseas visitors has more
than trebled to a record 3 million in 1993. The BTR forecasts this
figure to increase to 4.8 million by the year 2000 while, for the same
year, the Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) has set a marketing target
of 6.8 million visitors.</P>
<P>As a labour intensive industry, tourism offers considerable scope
for employment generation. In 1991-92, the industry accounted for around
467 000 jobs, either directly or indirectly, or 6.1 per cent of the work
force. Between 210&nbsp;000 and 270&nbsp;000 new jobs are expected to be
generated by the year 2000, at which time it is expected tourism will
employ around 8 per cent of the work force.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism in Australia</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism has been relatively unacknowledged as a tourism market
sector, yet estimates of domestic and international visitation to rural
areas are substantial.</P>
<P></P>
<P>As Figure 1 demonstrates, the proportion of domestic market share
attributable to rural and non-rural tourism appears to have remained
steady over the past nine years. Rural tourism in 1992-93 is estimated
to have accounted for nearly 60 per cent of the total domestic market.
It was estimated to be worth $11.2 billion to the Australian economy.</P>
<P></P>
<P>New South Wales and Queensland have the largest share of the rural
domestic tourism market (Figure 2). </P>
<P></P>
<P>Figure 3 again shows that, over the last nine years, rural tourism
has remained fairly static in the domestic market. However, the Tourism
Forecasting Council (TFC) predicts that domestic tourism will grow at an
average annual rate of around 2 per cent over the next six years (double
the annual growth rate achieved over the last decade) and rural tourism
is well placed to share in this growth. </P>
<P>The rural tourism industry is also expected to see strong growth
from the international market. Research undertaken by the ATC on
international visitors indicates that rural tourism experiences are
attractive to inbound tourists, with interest from the Asian region
steadily increasing. The ATC is currently focusing its rural tourism
marketing efforts in Asia on Singapore, Hong Kong and Malaysia, which
show substantial potential for growth. In 1993, over 20 per cent of
overseas visitors sampled rural Australia, contributing an estimated
$1.2 billion to the rural economy. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourist expenditure (domestic and international) is contributing
significantly to regional economies. In New South Wales, for example,
all the ABS statistical regions showed a healthy increase in tourist
expenditure between 1988-89 and 1992-93: the Far Western region
escalated from $43 million to $55 million; the Hunter region from $403
million to $456 million; and the Murray region from $150 to $206 million
(NSW Tourism Commission, 1994). </P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC9">3.2 Reasons for the National Rural Tourism
Strategy
</A></H2>
<P>One way of furthering the Federal Government's broad commitment to
regional development is through the development of rural tourism. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Following on from the initial identification of farm and rural
tourism in the National Tourism Strategy, the National Rural Tourism
Strategy provides the framework for its development. As such, it is
complementary to other Government tourism policy initiatives, namely,
the National Ecotourism Strategy (released in March 1994), the proposed
National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Tourism Strategy, the
Backpacker Strategic Plan and the Cruise Shipping Strategy (both due for
release in early 1995).</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Federal Government believes that an overall policy framework for
the planning, development and management of rural tourism is fundamental
to optimising the benefits tourism offers.<B> </B>The National Rural
Tourism Strategy provides a basis for rural tourism policy formulation
and planning for both government and industry.</P>
<P></P>
<P>By acting as a catalyst in developing rural tourism as part of wider
regional development initiatives, the Federal Government intends to
provide a focus and direction for rural tourism development that will
achieve economic, environmental and social gains nationally. </P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC10">3.3 The strategy development process
</A></H2>
<P>The National Tourism Strategy</P>
<P></P>
<P>The National Tourism Strategy, released by the Federal Government in
June 1992, identifies special interest tourism as an area of significant
potential and one through which the international tourism
competitiveness of Australia can be maintained. It states: </P>
<P></P>
<P>While farm tourism is growing in many regional areas, the market is
largely untapped and the challenge to industry operators is to
coordinate the sector's future development. There is a need to establish
accommodation and service standards, develop a well-planned national
marketing program and reservation network and provide tourism
educational and business advisory services to the rural sector (<I>Tourism,
Australia's Passport to Growth,</I> p. 85).</P>
<P></P>
<P>These developmental needs apply as much to other areas of the rural
tourism sector as they do to farm-based rural tourism.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural Tourism Discussion Paper</P>
<P><I></I></P>
<P><I>Tourism Discussion Paper No. 1--Rural Tourism</I>, released in
January 1993, examined the growth potential of the rural sector in terms
of domestic and international interests, covering such issues as
research priorities, standards, marketing, education, transport and
infrastructure, local government regulations, industry coordination,
business development and regional planning. Comments on the paper were
received from government departments, industry operators and
associations, local governments, community groups and educational
institutions (a list of respondents is at Appendix&nbsp;A). The
responses highlighted the need for greater integration of planning at
the regional level and more coordinated marketing efforts to diversify
the economic base in regional communities and provide jobs. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural Tourism Focus Group</P>
<P></P>
<P>To facilitate further discussion of the paper and help set a
framework for the development of the National Rural Tourism Strategy, a
focus group was convened by the Department of Tourism in early 1993. It
comprised people with expertise in rural tourism, including industry and
government representatives (a list of group members is at Appendix B).
Many of the projects funded under the Rural Tourism Program (RTP) in
1993-94 were a result of issues discussed at a meeting of the Rural
Tourism Focus Group in October 1993. These included industry
development, education and training, cooperative marketing, market
research and analysis, and product development through demonstration
projects.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Needs analysis consultancy on the rural tourism sector</P>
<P></P>
<P>Australian Farm and Country Tourism Inc. (AFACT) was granted Federal
Government funding in 1993-94 to engage a consultancy to take a critical
look at rural tourism, define and analyse impediments to its growth, and
suggest practical measures to address them. Key outcomes and
recommendations of the consultancy, conducted by Australian Rural
Management Services Pty Ltd from August to October 1994, have been
incorporated into the Strategy. 
</P>
<H1><A NAME="RTFToC11">CHAPTER 4 RURAL TOURISM PARTICIPANTS
</A></H1>
<P>In creating an overall policy framework for rural tourism, it is
important to note the various stakeholders and how they are linked. The
interests of tourists, tourist operators and their host communities are
necessarily interwoven with the interests and efforts of a large number
of other parties.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Although responsibility for developing rural tourism lies largely
with industry, government at all levels can exert considerable influence
on the tourism environment. The role of governments is explained in more
detail in section 4.2. </P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC12">4.1 Stakeholders
</A></H2>
<P>The stakeholders in rural tourism are many and varied. The degree to
which they participate in, and benefit from, the industry reflects the
extent and diversity of the product itself. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Today's <B>tourists</B> have greater spending power and more
leisure time. They are increasingly travel literate and environmentally
aware, they want to identify with the people and culture of a country,
and they want greater variety and better value for money. </P>
<P></P>
<P>In developing rural tourism it is important to ensure that visitors,
when making their travel decisions, are aware of the full range of rural
tourism products and experiences available. Likewise, it is important
for industry to be aware of the factors that influence domestic and
international travellers in their choice of a holiday destination and
that rural tourism products are developed, packaged and marketed to take
account of these preferences. </P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P><B>Private operators</B> have prime responsibility for supplying
suitable rural tourism product. Operators range from the large inbound
tourism businesses to the smaller specialist agricultural tour groups;
the rural accommodation sector which includes farm-host, bed and
breakfast, country motel, hotel, caravan park and rural resort
operators; the rural tourism attraction and adventure tour operations;
and organisers of country events and festivals. </P>
<P></P>
<P>To succeed in the industry, operators need to consider factors such
as the uniqueness of their product; its suitability for tourism
purposes; its development, packaging and marketing; its price; the
markets (both domestic and international) that can be targeted most
profitably and their needs; and the competitive advantage that can be
achieved and maintained over other suppliers, including overseas
operators. Also important is a knowledge of the structure and
functioning of the tourism industry, the operator's business skills and
tourism training, the pursuit and maintenance of standards and reliable
service and, where appropriate, industry coordination, particularly on a
regional basis. </P>
<P></P>
<P>The support of <B>host communities</B> can be essential to the
successful development of rural tourism. Community involvement is seen
as particularly important with the integration of tourism into local and
regional development programs becoming an essential component of an
area's overall economic development. Also important is that the host
community itself is often a vital part of the rural tourism `product'.</P>
<P><I></I></P>
<P><I>AussieHost</I>, a national program which has been assisted by
the Federal Government, has been designed to increase awareness of the
importance of tourism to Australia. It deals with developing and
improving customer-service skills, and has been embraced by rural
communities around Australia.</P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P><B>Tourism industry bodies</B> which operate at local, regional,
State and national spheres are important players in the growth of the
rural tourism sector. Issues such as industry leadership and
organisation, product development, education and training, marketing,
accreditation and standards are best managed and driven by industry
itself.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Tourism industry bodies involved in rural tourism include:</P>
<UL><LI>Australian Farm and Country Tourism Inc. (AFACT) which is the
national peak industry body for farm and country tourism;</LI>
<LI>Tourism Council Australia (TCA) which, in line with government
moves to support regional development, has established a National
Committee on Regional Tourism to investigate opportunities for
developing a National Regional Tourism Strategy; and</LI>
<LI>Inbound Tour Operators of Australia (ITOA) which brings tour groups
to country Australia and is responsible for introducing the <I>AussieHost
</I>program.</LI></UL>
<P><B></B></P>
<P><B>Non-tourism industry bodies</B> are also involved in the
industry. For example, the Australian Automobile Association (AAA) is
examining ways of refining its current accommodation classification
system to encompass alternate accommodation such as farm-host
properties, bed and breakfast accommodation, and country retreats. </P>
<P></P>
<P>There are also some specifically `rural' industries which are
benefiting from the interaction of agriculture and tourism. The
Australian Rice Growers' Cooperative in Leeton, part of the Murrumbidgee
Irrigation Area, has established a rice interpretation centre which
caters for special interest and technical tours, and is favoured by
Japanese visitors. Apart from visits to rice farms to study current rice
research and technology, a major drawcard is meeting the people and
experiencing genuine Australian country hospitality. The region as a
whole benefits from the `rice' tourists who may stay in the nearby towns
of Narrandera and Griffith and visit other rural attractions in the
vicinity such as fruit growing operations and wineries.</P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P><B>Transport operators</B> (airline, coach, rail, road and ferry)
stand to gain from, and can assist the growth of, rural tourism. The
provision of efficient, competitively priced and high quality transport
which gives easy access to country tourism markets is essential to meet
the high travel demands of consumers, particularly those from overseas.</P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P><B>Educational institutions,</B> including universities and
colleges of technical and further education (TAFEs), perform an
important role in developing rural tourism through both research and the
provision of training and course work. Tourism Training Australia (TTA)
has responsibility for coordinating developments in tourism training.
Information on higher education institutions which offer tourism courses
are listed in Beck and Richardson's (1993) <I>Tourism Education
Directory</I> <I>1994</I>.</P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P><B>Financial institutions</B> are an important avenue of assistance
for rural tourism enterprises. In the past, assistance for tourism as a
whole was not always forthcoming because lending institutions were
reluctant to fund what was commonly perceived as a risky industry (if,
in fact, it was even recognised as an industry in the first place given
its intangible nature). Progress has been made towards a better
understanding of each other's needs with the production of such
publications as the Australian Bankers'Association's <I>The Business of
Tourism --A Financial Management Guide for Tourism-based Businesses
</I>(1993).<I></I></P>
<P><I></I></P>
<P>Although not a stakeholder, the <B>media</B> plays an important
role in presenting the case for rural tourism and the opportunities it
offers communities willing to treat the industry as a serious
undertaking, on a par with agriculture. Of particular importance are the
specifically rural-based media such as the nationally televised <I>Cross
Countr</I>y program and the more locally-based newspapers, radio and
television networks which can all help to increase awareness of rural
tourism at the grassroots level.<B></B></P>
<P><B></B>
</P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC13">4.2 The role of governments
</A></H2>
<P>The primary responsibility for developing rural tourism lies with
private sector operators themselves, although it is recognised that the
responsibilities in many areas are shared with other stakeholders,
including government. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Research and planning are conducted at all levels of government to
help industry achieve a balance between the supply of tourism product
and the likely growth in demand. The Federal Government through, for
example, its Regional Tourist Development Program, encourages integrated
tourism planning at the regional level and, through this and other
programs, assists the development and modelling of appropriate
infrastructure.</P>
<P></P>
<P>While there will always be areas of industry activity that require
government intervention through legislation or regulation, the Federal
Government seeks to encourage the tourism industry to develop
self-regulation and accreditation as preferred options wherever these
can be successfully implemented.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Governments provide incentives and support through small business
enterprise development programs, financial assistance through the
Commonwealth Development Bank, depreciation and development allowances,
and support of demonstration projects and best practice programs. In
addition, government agencies provide business advice.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Governments are also involved through their partial subsidisation of
the costs of production wherein they provide infrastructure or invest
public money<B></B>for development from which the private sector
ultimately derives a benefit.<B> </B>The provision of infrastructure
and education and training via government bodies can give impetus for
tourism growth. </P>
<P></P>
<P>The McKinsey Report (1994b, p. 94) sees governments, as `change
leaders' and describes the role of governments as `to act as facilitator
and to help businesses perform ... This includes increasing the number
of opportunities available to businesses, relieving bottlenecks,
structuring incentives and building skills'. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Federal Government</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Minister for Tourism, the Hon Michael Lee MP, in a speech to the
ATIA Tourism Conference held September 1994 in Adelaide, talked about
four vital areas where the Federal Government is concentrating its
tourism effort:</P>
<UL><LI>setting the framework to allow the industry to prosper and
getting the fundamentals right (which includes floating the dollar;
introducing enterprise bargaining; reforming aviation with deregulation
of domestic airways--fares are 25 per cent lower than they were in 1990
and 50 per cent more people now travel by air; and allowing depreciation
provisions through the taxation system);</LI>
<LI>increasing awareness of the importance of tourism (both the
National Tourism Strategy and the National Ecotourism Strategy have
received international acclaim);</LI>
<LI>addressing market failures (by providing a package of programs
totalling over $42 million over four years aimed at spreading the
economic and employment benefits of tourism growth, with emphasis on
rural and regional Australia--this package includes the Rural Tourism
Program); and</LI>
<LI>providing information for the industry (through the BTR, and the
newly-formed TFC which provides activity forecasts to guide new
investment in infrastructure, and through publication of the new <I>Tourism
Assistance Guide: Commonwealth Government Programs and Initiatives for
the Tourism Industry,
</I>a comprehensive directory of federal initiatives for the tourism
industry. The guide is a useful reference for tourism operators,
consultants and associations, State, Territory and local Government
authorities, and people planning to start a tourism business. A free
copy can be obtained by contacting the Department of Tourism's
Information Officer on 008 804 465 or by fax on (06)&nbsp;248&nbsp;0734).</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>In addition, a key priority for Federal Government involvement in
tourism is the marketing of Australia overseas. The ATC, a statutory
authority administered under the provisions of the <I>Australian
Tourist Commission Act 1987, </I>received an appropriation of $77.817
million in the 1993-94 Budget, including $2 million for the
implementation of Partnership Australia. Additional funding of $290 000
was also provided to the ATC, in 1993-94, under the Rural Tourism
Program.</P>
<P></P>
<P>State and Territory Governments</P>
<P></P>
<P>While the Federal Government has prime responsibility for marketing
tourism internationally (through the ATC) and for setting and
implementing policies at a national level (through the Department of
Tourism in Canberra), State and Territory tourism authorities have prime
responsibility for promoting and marketing of State attractions and
developing specific tourist facilities. Cooperation amongst governments
is highlighted in the Partnership Australia initiative which aims to
market Australia more effectively overseas by combining some of the
planning and financial resources of the ATC and the State and Territory
tourism authorities. Federal Government programs are set out in Appendix
C and a summary of State and Territory initiatives and contact officers
is in Appendix D.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Local governments</P>
<P></P>
<P>Local governments are particularly important in facilitating rural
tourism, given their closeness to the rural communities. While local
governments focus on providing and maintaining infrastructure and public
facilities for their rate payers, many councils strongly support their
local tourism industry, often being the major funding sources for
tourist associations, visitor centres and caravan parks.<B> </B>Integrated
local area planning, based on proper consideration of all relevant
aspects of development, environment quality and service provision,
facilitates the best use of local resources.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The role of local government is discussed in more detail in section
6.9.
</P>
<H1><A NAME="RTFToC14">CHAPTER 5 FACTORS AFFECTING RURAL TOURISM
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC15">5.1 Development opportunities for rural tourism
</A></H2>
<P>In Australia, agricultural employment has decreased as a result of
falling farm incomes and technological change. This, in turn, has
resulted in a decrease in rural services such as professional services,
shops, educational institutions and transportation. There is a
recognised need for diversification if rural areas are to survive, let
alone prosper. Introducing tourism is sometimes a solution. A working
farm, for example, might accept paying guests who participate in work on
the farm or simply observe farm life. Part-time employment in the rural
tourism industry, such as casual bar work or sales to tourists, can also
supplement the major income source. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Few barriers to entry mean that it is easy for new businesses to
establish themselves, though this can mean that people enter tourism
without the necessary planning, skills or financial backing.</P>
<P>The typical small size<B> </B>of many rural tourism enterprises can
lead to a desirable concentration on niche marketing. Farm stays are a
case in point which often use these tactics to sell the `hosted
experience' to small groups of visitors. The propensity to service small
groups of people or individuals fits well with the upsurge of free and
independent travellers coming to Australia, as reported by the ATC.</P>
<P></P>
<P>To maximise the impact of their products in the marketplace,
operators will generally need to cooperatively market with other `like'
products, for example, farm stays at regional, state and/or national
level. Similarly, operators with complementary product within regions
should combine to market the diversity of experiences in the regions,
thereby increasing the attractiveness of the area to the visitor.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Trends</P>
<P></P>
<P>Current tourism trends are generally favourable to rural tourism. In
<I>Tourism Strategies and Rural Development</I>, a discussion paper
prepared for the OECD, a number of factors are identified as being
responsible for the growth in rural tourism overseas. These factors are
applicable to Australia and include:</P>
<P>	an increase in leisure time, disposable income and a tendency to
short breaks (although in Australia, short breaks can restrict trips to
easily accessible destinations);</P>
<P>	higher levels of education which bode well for rural tourism as
`research shows that increasing levels of education correlate with
increased interest in outdoor recreation, ecotourism and special
interest holidays';</P>
<P>	a rise in popularity of `green' issues: rural holidays, though not
necessarily environmentally focused, are perceived as wholesome.
Nature-based tours and those with a defined educational and
interpretative content managed in an environmentally sustainable way
(ecotourism) are enjoying popularity;<B></B></P>
<UL><LI>a growing interest in speciality food and beverages, which can
feature `clean-green' rural produce;</LI>
<LI>a greater appreciation of heritage, both built and natural;</LI>
<LI>the search for authenticity in a material world which rural
holidays can provide, assisted by dealings with friendly locals;</LI>
<LI>the need for peace and tranquillity, particularly as a stress
reducer;</LI>
<LI>the ageing of an active population, with the time, money and
inclination to travel widely, often choosing rural holidays for health
reasons, to discover non-urban experiences or to recapture youthful
times spent in the country;</LI>
<LI>health consciousness--leading to more active outdoor recreation,
encouraged by better outdoor clothing;</LI>
<LI>the recognised emergence of REAL travel (rewarding, enriching,
adventuresome and a learning experience) often linked with
individualism;</LI>
<LI>improvement in transport and communications (though distances in
Australia can be formidable in terms of time and cost); and</LI>
<LI>increasing participation by rural agencies such as those involved
with national parks, arts and crafts, community welfare, economic
development and transport, in encouraging and developing rural tourism.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>Coates (1991) and Kusler (1992) suggest further trends that are
shaping the relationship between tourism and the natural environment,
including:</P>
<UL><LI>new demographic groups such as two-income households and baby
boomers reaching the peak of their earning capacity;</LI>
<LI>increased exposure to new and remote places through the media;</LI>
<LI>increased attention to indigenous and cultural tourism; and</LI>
<LI>increased concern about crowding at existing destinations.</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>Whether rural tourism can capitalise on these trends, and to what
extent, will depend largely on the initiative, commitment and
professionalism of rural tourism operators. In turn, tourism operators
will require the support of strong industry associations, an
enthusiastic and cooperative local community, and appropriate government
policies and programs. </P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC16">5.2 Overcoming impediments to rural tourism
development
</A></H2>
<P>There are impediments to rural tourism development which need to be
addressed. These range from community inexperience and inertia to a lack
of professional and business expertise among operators, industry
fragmentation, distance and a lack of infrastructure.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Community participation</P>
<P></P>
<P>Community participation and support is an important part of
considering the suitability of tourism as an industry for an area. It
can prove worthwhile, both in the short and long term.</P>
<P>In some cases, communities may not wish to pursue tourism
development. Other communities, however, will wish to assess what their
areas have to offer tourists and, in return, what tourism has to offer
their community. Manuals have been produced to guide community groups
through this process, as well as programs such as <I>Mainstreet</I>, a
community-based program to improve the business activities in key areas.
</P>
<P></P>
<P>Care must be taken to assess realistically an area's appeal for
travellers, including ease of access. The remoteness and isolation of an
area can deter some tourists (owing to time and cost constraints and
other factors), although, paradoxically, others will want to visit an
area for these very reasons. </P>
<P>While some tourists do not regard the journey as part of the holiday
experience, `touring' to others is an important element of getting out
into the country. As a marketing tool, and to overcome distance
limitations, the travel itself can be made a part of the total rural
tourism `experience'. Taking `the track' from Alice Springs to Darwin
(the Stuart Highway in the Northern Territory) and stopping at
identified places of interest along the way can be as much an
`experience' as it is a means of getting from one place to another. In
this way an impediment can be turned into an asset.</P>
<P></P>
<P>It is necessary to compare an area's tourism appeal with that of
other regions. While civic pride can lead people to think their area has
great products to offer, an unrealistic appraisal of tourism assets can
result in a waste of resources. Should a community decide to promote
tourism, it must find ways to help itself establish and develop this
industry. In developing rural tourism, communities should:</P>
<UL><LI>take advantage of existing assets (scenery, historic
buildings);</LI>
<LI>maintain any competitive advantages; and</LI>
<LI>target suitable markets.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>In establishing tourism, it is essential to have leadership.
Sometimes, a small group of committed people may perform this role.
Often, planners and professionals already employed in the community
become the leaders, injecting enthusiasm tempered with realism into
investigation of the potential of tourism.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Sometimes, communities will be lucky enough to have people with
appropriate skills, necessary for tourism development, in their midst.
Using local resources (people and goods) helps to bolster a region's
economy. The necessary skills for operating successful tourism
enterprises (e.g. marketing) may not, however, be freely available
within the community. If the skills are not present in the local
community, then they will either have to be developed or paid for.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Operators and the rural tourism industry</P>
<P></P>
<P>It is generally agreed that small business makes up 70 to 80 per
cent of businesses in the tourism industry. The majority of these small
businesses are scattered across rural Australia, sometimes as members of
an umbrella industry organisation. Small businesses have a high failure
rate: some 80 per cent of new businesses fail in their first two years
of operation and, of the remainder, only one-third are still operating
after ten years (New South Wales Small Business Advisory Centre). One
way to keep rural tourism operators in business is to improve their
overall business skills.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The commonly used example is that of a farmer diversifying into farm
hosting. While the farmer knows about agriculture, he or she will need
to acquire tourism expertise if the secondary business is to do well.
</P>
<P></P>
<P>The lack of profitability in some segments of the industry can
impede development. Sometimes, individual businesses that would not be
profitable on their own are able to succeed by uniting with others in
the region to offer package deals combining products such as transport,
accommodation, attractions and activities. Often, networking can allow
business to be spread across a region. It is important to remember that
a business's major competitor is often not what is offered down the road
but what is available in a region perhaps some 1000 kilometres away.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The small, diverse, scattered nature of rural tourism operations can
make it difficult to have a united industry presence. To overcome this
industry fragmentation, there is a strong need for cooperation and
collaboration across all levels of government and industry sectors in
forming and executing tourism plans. This is particularly important at
the local government level, concerned as it is with community
involvement and the integration of tourism with other regional planning.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Other businesses and industries</P>
<P></P>
<P>The business of rural tourism affects, and is dependent on, other
types of businesses and enterprises. Visitors to rural Australia expect
to be able to get fuel and vehicle repairs, buy basic foodstuffs, dine
at cafes and restaurants of an acceptable standard and find decent
accommodation. Tourism operators, communities and other services in
country towns need to recognise their shared dependency. By working
together, they can develop and present an inviting environment for the
visitor for mutual benefit.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Several submissions to <I>Tourism Discussion Paper No. 1-- Rural
Tourism</I> commented that financial institutions did not like to lend
for rural tourism ventures. When they did (it was reported), loans
failed to be structured to suit the cash flow and payment ability of
rural tourism operators. The needs analysis consultancy examining rural
tourism found a different situation: financial institutions were lending
to tourism businesses if those businesses could submit strong business
plans. Through the TFC and by working with the Australian Bankers'
Association, the Federal Government is seeking to further improve the
climate for financial institutions' involvement in the tourism industry
and to prepare tourism operators better for the financial obligations of
running a tourism business.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Whatever the opportunities and impediments, it is important that a
holistic approach be taken to rural tourism development which involves
strategic planning and an integrated approach to development in country
areas as a whole. Essential to achieving the correct balance is the
`bottom up' approach where communities participate in the planning
process at every stage. This ensures that development is not imposed
from outside and that those who live in rural Australia are committed
to, and participate in, the development of rural tourism.</P>
<P></P>
<H1><A NAME="RTFToC17">CHAPTER 6 KEY ISSUES, STRATEGIES AND ACTIONS
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC18">6.1 Future directions for rural tourism
</A></H2>
<P>This section examines the issues that must be addressed in
developing rural tourism, as identified by public submissions, the Rural
Tourism Focus Group and the needs analysis consultancy. It raises issues
in the following areas: </P>
<UL><LI>product and enterprise development;</LI>
<LI>accreditation and industry standards;</LI>
<LI>education and training;</LI>
<LI>marketing;</LI>
<LI>market analysis;</LI>
<LI>industry leadership;</LI>
<LI>transport and infrastructure; and </LI>
<LI>the role of local government.</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>Strategies and actions to address these issues are proposed. </P>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC19">6.2 Product and enterprise development 
</A></H2>
<P>Product refers to the actual product (or service) being offered. In
the case of rural tourism, it is the total `country experience'. Product
is a combination of the bricks and mortar, the activities, the
atmosphere and the part played by the host. It is what the traveller has
paid for and constitutes his or her memories of a good or bad tourism
experience. Good experiences will be rewarded by other visits; bad
experiences recounted to many with whom the traveller comes into
contact. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Product development, incorporating business development, is
essential for a healthy, sustainable and prosperous industry in that it
lifts industry standards, increases the range of attractions available
to visitors and is able to sustain growth. Because of the competitive
nature of the tourism industry, what Australia offers tourists must be
unique and of a standard commensurate with the rest of the world.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Good product development will be achieved through measures such as:</P>
<UL><LI>identification of major and ancillary attractions and their
inclusion in regional packaging. For example, a package for Kangaroo
Island, South Australia, includes sea/air transport, local touring
opportunities and specific activities such as scuba diving;</LI>
<LI>recognition of the expectations and needs of tourists and the
appropriate creation and modification of product. For example, the New
England Development Board in New South Wales is integrating different
tourism and business aspects in the areas of agriculture, education and
Aboriginal culture to expand the tourism product being offered in the
region. Australia-wide, the Australian Hotels Association, in a bid to
turn hotels into safe, friendly establishments for families, is
introducing child-minding and outdoor playgrounds to encourage stays by
more families;</LI>
<LI>value-adding to tourist products or other types of products (for
example, the Hamilton Sheep Centre, Tasmania, which was purpose-built to
cater for the Japanese coach market, is now having wool grown on the
property knitted into up-market pullovers for sale as souvenirs at the
Centre); and</LI>
<LI>competitiveness (perhaps through offering superior product, paying
attention to price, and/or tailoring promotion to suit the clientele).</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>In addition, cooperative networks amongst operators with similar
products can result in access to larger markets. The practice of
farm-stay and bed and breakfast operators banding together to
accommodate large coach groups needs to be accepted as regular business
practice by a greater number of operators.<B></B>Interaction with other
businesses in assembling suitable tour packages incorporating
accommodation, attractions, transport, restaurants and retail outlets
can provide a better product for inbound tour operators. </P>
<P></P>
<P>The needs analysis consultancy into rural tourism noted the need for
different types of packages: </P>
<UL><LI>theme-based packages, for example, tours of unusual farming
enterprises such as historical farms (Clydesdales, antique machinery,
etc.), aquaculture enterprises (yabby farm, trout farm, etc.), alpaca
studs and emu farms;</LI>
<LI>complementary packages featuring a combination of rural product
because of some spatial, logical or transport connection (for example,
in Victoria, operators and Tourism Victoria are working cooperatively to
promote a travel circuit encompassing the Great Ocean Road, the
Grampians and the Goldfields, a trip which usually takes at least three
days); and</LI>
<LI>packaging specifically for wholesalers' programs (for example,
AFACT's international marketing program targeting South-East Asia).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The consultancy also discussed the development of landscape
packages, that is, providing visitors with information about an area
whether it be the cultural history, natural environment (land types,
vegetation and animal species, geology), farm systems (what is grown
where, how, seasonal occurrences), mining or local Aboriginal groups.
</P>
<P></P>
<P>The recognition of high quality product can provide examples of best
practice and inspire other operators to improve their businesses. State
government and industry tourism awards highlight the achievements of
excellence in tourism enterprises and set high standards for tourism's
development. In addition, TCA organises the Australian Tourism Awards to
recognise outstanding achievement in the travel, tourism hospitality and
leisure industries. In 1994, rural tourism winners included the Tjapukai
Dance Theatre (category of Significant Local Attractions); Manyallaluk
Tours (Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Tourism); Port Fairy Folk
Festival (Significant Local Festivals and Special Events); Kingfisher
Bay Resort &amp; Village (Environmental Tourism), Unforgettable
Houseboats (Specialist Accommodation) and Australian Bushman Tours (Tour
&amp; Transport Operators--National).</P>
<P></P>
<P>Enterprise development </P>
<P></P>
<P>The majority of operators in the rural tourism industry are small
businesses. As a result, the concerns of and constraints to small
business are also relevant to the rural tourism industry. Macro-economic
issues such as interest rates, inflation, taxation and government
charges, and growth within the national and local economy will continue
to be areas of concern for all small operators. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Advice on business matters is available from: </P>
<UL><LI>the small business network which has been instrumental in
improving the professionalism of small business operators within the
tourism industry;</LI>
<LI>regional economic and development organisations which, through
their incorporation of tourism into local economic development plans,
have also been instrumental in encouraging rural tourism growth;</LI>
<LI>regional tourism associations;</LI>
<LI>tourism industry associations; and/or</LI>
<LI>State and Territory tourism authorities.</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>The ATC also offers advice to new operators and to those seeking to
move or expand into a new market. The ATC's 1993 publication <I>International
Tourism Marketing Manual </I>is considered a vital tool for those
seeking information on the international market.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Besides these organisations, business assistance is available
through AusIndustry (located within the Commonwealth Department of
Industry, Science and Technology), the development of which was one of
the key industry assistance initiatives outlined in the Government's May
1994 White Paper
<I>Working Nation. </I>The establishment of AusIndustry has enabled
improved coordination and delivery of programs, bringing together under
a unified marketing structure all of the Federal Government's business
assistance programs.</P>
<P></P>
<P>AusIndustry includes:</P>
<P>	BusinessLink, a scheme whereby the Federal Government is working
cooperatively with State and Territory Governments to develop
computer-based information for small to medium-sized enterprises (it
will provide information about export services; tenders and other
business opportunities; finance; business assistance measures and
programs; technology and product information; licensing requirements;
taxation; industrial awards; management advice and training; and
industry assistance measures and services); and</P>
<P>	the National Industry Extension Service, which helps small and
medium-sized Australian firms in the manufacturing and services sectors
to become internationally competitive through enterprise improvement.
</P>
<P></P>
<P>Operators need to be aware that new tourism ventures or businesses
might not be profitable in their first few years, and cash deficiencies
might be experienced over a period. The Australian Bankers' Association
(ABA) has published <I>The Business of Tourism: A Financial Management
Guide for Tourism-based Businesses,
</I>which explains the process of formulating a successful loan proposal
and effectively managing the finances of a tourism business. It also
discusses many of the special problems that beset tourism operators and
suggests how to effectively manage these problems. This guide can be
obtained from the ABA by telephoning 008 033 652.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In seeking to develop their product, operators should avail
themselves of the business advice offered by small business centres,
regional tourism associations, regional economic development
organisations, tourism industry bodies and State/Territory tourism
authorities. Other sources of advice are facilitators/rural counsellors
under the Business Advice for Rural Areas (BARA) scheme and the Rural
Counselling Program (RCP), administered by the Commonwealth Department
of Primary Industries and Energy. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Under BARA, the Federal Government provides grants to rural
community groups to meet part of the costs of employing a business
facilitator. The facilitator helps rural communities to diversify,
stabilise and expand income opportunities by assisting local
entrepreneurial capacity, fostering business talent and ideas, and
improving individual and rural economic diversification. Under the RCP,
grants are offered to local community groups in rural areas experiencing
severe economic stress to assist with the employment of financial
counsellors who provide free, confidential financial advice.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Local communities also need to be able to access advice about the
prospects for tourism in their area. Sound consideration of tourism
development by community groups will involve a wide cross-section of the
community in a manner that is most likely to result in informed
discussion and debate. The communities will need to assess the potential
benefits and possible disadvantages that may accrue from tourism
development within their area. To this end, it may be useful to prepare
appropriate `how-to' material for communities that wish to develop
economic opportunities through tourism, and to do so in a manner that is
systematic, informed and most likely to lead to success. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Issues</P>
<P></P>
<P>The needs analysis consultancy recognised the benefits of self-help
and mutual aid being practised by some rural tourism operators. Through
these means, operators are able to learn about (and improve) their own
business by comparing themselves with others. The consultancy identified
enterprise best-practice workshops as a means of providing this product
development. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Similarly, the consultancy identified that in some regions
organisations involved in regional tourism development require a better
understanding of how successful tourism developments occur. It has been
suggested that `best practice' examples of rural tourism businesses
(farm stays, rural resorts, rural adventure holidays, rural attractions,
festivals and events, and nature-based tourism) could increase
understanding.</P>
<P></P>
<P>There are also a number of specific issues that prospective rural
tourism operators face in the development of product.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In some instances, government requirements in the areas of
transport, liquor licensing, health, food and hygiene may affect the
services offered by hosts to guests in the rural tourism environment.
The particular circumstances of smaller operations may not always have
been taken into account in the formulation of these requirements.
Operators need to be aware of the various requirements and mindful of
the penalties for non-compliance.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Insurance to cover both people and property can also be a source of
concern for some rural tourism enterprises. Operators of adventure
tours, farm stays offering horse riding as part of their package, and
owners of heritage buildings can find the high cost of insurance
premiums daunting, if in fact they can find a company willing to insure
them at all.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Many travellers now demand that operators offering white water
rafting, abseiling or other adventure sports possess appropriate
certificates or licences. Operators therefore need to have the
appropriate qualifications and must keep them up-to-date.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism operators should also be mindful of the recent High
Court decision and European consumer protection provisions giving
consumers access to compensation if the product is not provided as
advertised or the holiday fails to meet their expectations. Travel
agents and tour operators without professional indemnity insurance
should review the public liability insurance policies available.</P>
<P></P>
<P>STRATEGY: Encourage the sustainable development of high quality
tourism products and product variety in rural areas.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Actions </P>
<UL><LI>	Support diversity and quality in rural tourism product
development through measures such as developing and disseminating `how
to' information material and examples of best practice, and conducting
enterprise best-practice workshops (all spheres of government, industry
associations, regional tourism associations, educational
institutions/private consultants, marketing organisations, operators).</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>Funding has been provided under the RTP for discrete demonstration
projects (described below) promoting product development:</P>
<P></P>
<P>	(a) the development of astronomy tours in New South Wales which
will encourage the wider promotion and marketing of tourism facilities
associated with the astronomy centres at Narrabri, Coonabarabran,
Gilgandra, Parkes and Tidbinbilla together with other local tourist
attractions and facilities in each of these areas ($46&nbsp;000);</P>
<P></P>
<P>	(b) the development of farm tours in the Huon Valley, Tasmania, to
assist the development of a quality rural tourism product and
demonstrate how agricultural resources in rural areas can be diversified
($80&nbsp;000);</P>
<P></P>
<P>	(c) the installation of suitable communications technology at the
old repeater stations--initially Alice Springs, Barrow Creek, Tennant
Creek and Darwin (later Pine Creek and Newcastle Waters)--which will
simulate conditions and experiences of an earlier era. Visitors will be
able to use the facilities at these interpretative centres for sending
and receiving telegrams ($80&nbsp;000);</P>
<P></P>
<P>	(d) the creation of an assets register, conduct of perceptual
research and establishment of a marketing identity for the Swan Valley
in Western Australia ($40&nbsp;000); and</P>
<P></P>
<P>	(e) the development of a formal system of accreditation to ensure
that high standards of accommodation and professional service in farm
and country tourism can be recognised by both tourists and other tourism
operators ($75&nbsp;000).</P>
<P></P>
<P>These projects will have national applicability. It is planned that
a demonstration booklet will be compiled and distributed.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Funding of $30&nbsp;000 has been provided under the RTP for further
analysis of the ATC's international visitor segmentation studies to
identify target visitors specifically for rural tourism.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Results of the analysis will be available to rural tourism operators
to enable them to undertake appropriately focused improvements in
product development.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The RTP has also funded attitudinal case studies undertaken as part
of the recently conducted AFACT needs analysis consultancy into major
issues in rural tourism (total consultancy grant of $102&nbsp;000
provided). The results of these studies may lead to initiatives to
improve the general public's awareness of rural tourism.</P>
<UL><LI>Examine the applicability to Australia of community-based
rural tourism schemes developed overseas, such as the Alberta (Canada)
and Minnesota University models, and, if appropriate, develop and
promote a package to assist community involvement in rural tourism
(Federal Government).</LI>
<LI>Encourage individual operators to work cooperatively to develop
multi-product packages (all spheres of government, industry
associations, regional tourism associations, regional development
organisations, operators).</LI>
<LI>Encourage development of innovative packages to provide visitors,
on their arrival in rural areas, with information on the local region
(regional tourist associations, regional development organisations,
visitor information centres, private operators).</LI>
<LI>Encourage the adoption of ecologically sustainable development
principles by rural tourism operators and tourism bodies (all spheres of
government, industry associations).</LI>
<LI>Encourage individual operators of small accommodation businesses to
form cooperative networks to cater for larger tourist groups (AFACT and
other industry associations).</LI>
<LI>Encourage liaison between regulatory bodies and rural tourism
industry representatives to ensure regulations are formulated to take
account of the particular circumstances of small business in rural
tourism, such as licensing laws on the provision of food and liquor for
paying guests (AFACT, other industry associations, operators,
government). </LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>This role is one of the specified tasks of the AFACT Executive
Officer position, funded under the RTP ($100&nbsp;000 in 1993-94, $150&nbsp;000
in 1994-95).</P>
<UL><LI>Encourage operators to join industry associations to access
associated benefits such as networking, knowledge dissemination,
lobbying strength, reduced insurance premiums, etc. (AFACT, other
industry associations, government).</LI>
<LI>Ensure local and regional tourism bodies are aware of the
availability of funding ($80 million) to be administered by the
Department of Housing and Regional Development under its Regional Best
Practice Program (Federal, State and Territory Governments).</LI>
<LI>Support awareness of tourism as a business in small business
development centres, local governments, regional tourism associations
and regional development organisations (all spheres of government).</LI>
<LI>Ensure facilitators/rural counsellors within existing government
rural extension programs such as BARA and the RCP are sufficiently
informed to advise operators about rural tourism (Federal Government).</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC20">6.3 Accreditation and industry standards
</A></H2>
<P>Over the past decade, Australia's tourism industry has developed
rapidly. Not only has the number of tourists multiplied, but tourists
have become more sophisticated and discerning. This means that the
quality of the tourism product or `country experience' has become just
as important as its novelty or newness.</P>
<P></P>
<P>At a time when international competition for the tourism dollar is
growing and when many countries already have firmly established rural
tourism industries, it is imperative that Australia be able to compete
effectively in attracting visitors to rural areas. In Australia's case,
the impetus to offer the potential customer `that little bit extra' is
much stronger because of the difficulties (perceived or substantiated)
in travelling to this country owing to distance and cost.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A number of industry bodies are already investigating accreditation
in specific areas of the tourism industry. Current industry-wide tourism
accreditation and standards include the National Tourism Competency
Standards, ACCESS--the Hospitality Skills and Recognition Program, and
the Australian Travel Agent Qualification program. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Industry review panels such as the Tourism Training Review Panel and
the Australian Hospitality Review Panel, established through Tourism
Training Australia (TTA), are accreditation/recognition bodies that
primarily set standards and ensure courses seeking industry recognition
have the appropriate content, facilities and staff.</P>
<P></P>
<P>An accreditation scheme for professional guides has been introduced
by ITOA with Federal assistance. A Federal Government-funded (through
TCA), industry led steering committee is investigating a national
accreditation scheme for ecotourism operations. Standards for backpacker
hostels are also being examined through a consultancy being funded by
the Federal Government.</P>
<P>While all the above have implications for the rural tourism sector,
accreditation schemes currently being developed and implemented by the
Victorian Tourism Operators Association (VTOA) and by ITOA, in the form
of its AussieHost customer service program, touch more directly on the
sector's needs. The AAA is also considering developing a national
classification scheme for guest house, bed and breakfast, and host farm
accommodation. </P>
<P></P>
<P>The considerable number of accreditation programs and benchmarking
studies, either in use or being developed in the tourism industry, has
been discussed by the Australian Standing Committee on Tourism. As a
result, in October 1994, the committee initiated a working party,
including industry, to undertake an initial audit to investigate and
evaluate current programs, models and options.</P>
<P>The success of accreditation schemes will depend on how well
consumer expectations are satisfied. Such schemes might involve a cost
to the operator such as undertaking additional training or investing in
new infrastructure, but outlays are likely to be recouped through
increased length of stays and repeat visits over time.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Issues</P>
<P></P>
<P>The needs analysis consultancy noted that operators have
responsibilities to maintain high standards, and gave an example of an
operator attempting to contact a bed and breakfast in another region to
arrange a couple of days accommodation. Four establishments were
selected, and each was telephoned. At the first, there was no answer,
the second was answered by a young child, and the third had an answering
machine with different messages for two or three different businesses.
Finally, the fourth was answered by the operator. </P>
<P></P>
<P>In working to improve the capability of rural Australia to attract
international and domestic tourists, the development of service
excellence and professionalism in country areas is a priority. The
introduction of highly regarded national accreditation schemes for the
rural tourism sector could help to establish the reputation of Australia
as a high quality tourism destination.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In developing such schemes, whether through the modification of
established procedures to encompass the special requirements of rural
tourism operations or through the introduction of new schemes, a number
of factors need to be considered. These include:</P>
<UL><LI>an emphasis on the `experiential' factor of a farm stay, rural
tourism attraction or tour. The `hosting' component is the most
difficult area to evaluate as part of an accreditation scheme;</LI>
<LI>the need for operators to have a high level of commitment to
tourism (people operating tourism businesses primarily for motives other
than profit such as lifestyle choice would be less likely to be
attracted to the accreditation process);<I> </I></LI>
<LI>the need for a scheme that assists operators to reach minimum
standards and identify improvement opportunities in their business;</LI>
<LI>the importance of consumer feedback as part of the quality
assurance process and as a means of ensuring that operators respond to
the changing demands of the market;</LI>
<LI>the need for a scheme that rewards operators who are prepared to
invest in their business and provide high quality facilities and
hosting;</LI>
<LI>the need to cater for increasing environmental awareness of rural
tourism consumers through the introduction of environmental standards
and conservation practices;</LI>
<LI>the potential role and structure of educational programs to support
the introduction of an accreditation scheme. Training and accreditation
bodies such as TTA need to be consulted when developing and implementing
accreditation schemes; and</LI>
<LI>administration, including monitoring of new schemes, whether it be
by an independent and self-funded agency, possibly across all industry
sectors, or by some form of licensing by State authorities for business
operations and facilities.</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>STRATEGY: Support accreditation and introduction/recognition of
standards for rural tourism ventures.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Actions<B></B></P>
<UL><LI>	Encourage the development and implementation of industry
standards for rural tourism as a basis for industry self-regulation and
examine options for developing national rural tourism accreditation
schemes (industry associations, TTA, educational institutions, all
spheres of government).</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>Under the RTP, the Federal Government has provided funding for the
establishment of an Executive Officer position within the national
farm-host organisation, AFACT.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A major function of this position is to promote higher and
consistent standards through development and training, and to
investigate opportunities for accreditation in the farm-stay sector.</P>
<P>Under the RTP, funding of $75&nbsp;000 has been provided to VTOA for
a pilot project to develop appropriate accreditation standards for farm
and country tourism accommodation and services in Victoria.</P>
<P></P>
<P>This project is to serve as a basis for national accreditation
standards for the farm and country tourism sector.</P>
<UL><LI>Support industry-led initiatives to develop appropriate
accreditation schemes, including the AAA accommodation classification
scheme, VTOA's accreditation scheme and ITOA's Tour Guide Accreditation
Program and AussieHost scheme (TTA, educational institutions, all
spheres of government).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>Under the RTP, funding of $50&nbsp;000 has been provided to ITOA to
expand the AussieHost scheme in regional Victoria. This is in addition
to the $92&nbsp;000 already allocated by Federal tourism sources to the
AussieHost scheme and some State contributions.</P>
<UL><LI>Encourage liaison among industry organisations and training
bodies such as AFACT, ITOA, TCA, AAA, VTOA and TTA and their respective
State chapters on accreditation issues to ensure consistency, avoid
duplication and determine their respective roles in the accreditation
process (industry associations, TTA, educational institutions, Federal,
State and Territory governments).</LI>
<LI>Encourage the establishment of recognisable insignia/logos for use
by accredited rural tourism operators (State and Territory tourism
authorities, industry associations, operators, marketing organisations).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
</BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
