<HTML><HEAD><!-- This document was created by Adam Clarke of Computer 
Law Services.-->
<TITLE>Regional Tourism Strategy - Chapter 6.4 to End</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H2><A NAME="RTFToC21">6.4 Education and training
</A></H2>
<P>According to research by TTA, many small business operators in
tourism have little or no experience either in hospitality or in small
business operation. If expected industry growth in country tourism over
the next decade is to be effectively harnessed, skills in these areas
will have to be developed and upgraded.</P>
<P></P>
<P>At the national level, TTA is the peak tourism industry training
body. It comprises government, industry and union representatives, and
is funded jointly by Federal and State/Territory Governments and the
industry. It was established to advise Governments and industry on
tourism training matters and works with a network of State and Territory
committees to develop and implement tourism training strategies. It
determines competency standards for the hospitality and tourism
industries and has completed the national competency standards for all
major sectors of the industry. TTA also develops resource material to
meet individual needs as well as community training needs.</P>
<P>A May 1992 report prepared for TTA, <I>Tourism 2000: Key Directions
for Human Resource Development</I>, identified and advised on critical
education and training issues. It also outlined a detailed plan to meet
language and cultural skills needs for growth in the Japan, Other Asia
and Other European markets. </P>
<P></P>
<P>State training plans are the main way of identifying training needs.
Almost every State/Territory in the Tourism Training Network produces a
training plan which identifies training needs across all sectors of the
industry. Victoria, for example, in developing its training plan for
1996-98 consulted a wide range of industry associations and identified
key areas for exploring new methods of delivering training, to encourage
greater participation in training amongst smaller tourism operators in
regional areas.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In planning for tourism training, the characteristics of the
industry have to be taken into consideration. Firstly, the tourism
industry is highly decentralised, a fact which is demonstrated on a
national basis with 56 per cent of all accommodation rooms being located
outside Australia's capital cities (ABS March 1994). As well, 80 per
cent of all tourism businesses employ fewer than 20 people (BTR 1990).
</P>
<P></P>
<P>Such small businesses often lack the staffing flexibility of larger
operations. The needs analysis consultancy found that lack of time to
attend formal training sessions was the key reason for owner/operators
not undertaking training. Special delivery mechanisms such as videos and
manual information kits, which recognise that rural tourism operators
are frequently in isolated regions where training resources (e.g. TAFEs)
are not easily accessible, can help to overcome these barriers. Such
packages also recognise that small tourism businesses are
seven-day-a-week operations and allow training to be self-paced and
flexible.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A number of business packages exist for rural tourism operators.
Tourism Training Victoria(TTV) has produced `Getting into Tourism'--a
video/manual information kit for intending, new and existing small
businesses. The Queensland Tourist and Travel Corporation distributes
the `Getting Started' and `Getting Smarter' video series, self-help
education programs which highlight the important decisions to be
considered before establishing a new tourism business and how to improve
business practices once they are up and running. Small Business Victoria
has produced ten booklets in a tourism series including advertising,
feasibility studies and guidebooks dealing with Japanese visitors and a
rural tourism specific farm tourism guidebook. AFACT produces starter
kits for farm-stay operators. State and Territory tourism authorities
have other relevant publications also. The ATC provides information kits
and has published the <I>International Tourism Marketing Manual</I>.</P>
<P></P>
<P>To meet community needs there are a number of tools, including a
Training Needs Analysis Resources Kit being prepared by TTV, that will
enable areas to assess their own tourism training and educational needs.
Corowa, in New South Wales, has acted to improve business activities
through the <I>Mainstreet</I> program which recognises links between
town centre revitalisation, the attraction of new businesses and tourism
development. Other models, specifically for the use of local people in
the planning, development and marketing of local and regional tourism,
could be appropriate.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In 1990, TTA estimated that over 18 000 students were
undertaking tourism-related courses (certificate level or courses of one
or more years duration). Of these, three-quarters were doing hospitality
courses. </P>
<P></P>
<P>More general training in a number of subject areas is available
through industry seminars and conferences. For example, at the first
Rural Tourism Conference, held at the University of New England in
Armidale, NSW, in September 1994, speakers addressed issues such as
marketing, advertising, pricing, quality, computer software programs,
public liability and networking.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The needs analysis consultancy found that some operators and
organisations were concerned that there was a shortage of skills
available locally to prepare funding submissions for government training
programs and that there was a need for a clear understanding of the
eligibility requirements for each scheme. The Department of Employment,
Education and Training, including the Office of Labour Market
Adjustment, can sometimes provide funding for the preparation of such
submissions and, in other cases, local governments are able to supply
expertise.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Department of Employment, Education and Training has a number of
initiatives which rural tourism operators may find useful. Training
programs linked to employment can be particularly beneficial, providing
direct benefits for both the unemployed and the rural tourism industry.
The Jobtrain (Commonwealth Employment Service) river guide course
conducted in Tasmania in early 1994 resulted in 11 graduates securing
jobs in the adventure tourism industry. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Graduates also received AussieHost certificates which are recognised
throughout the industry as a standard of customer-service training (that
is, trained to gauge the needs, wants and expectations of customers and
to deliver). Since AussieHost's inception in July 1993, over 5000 people
have received training at some 450 workshops. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Issues</P>
<P></P>
<P>The current skills base in the rural tourism industry may not be
sufficient for rural tourism to reach its maximum potential return.
Unmet educational and training needs can restrict the ability of
individual rural tourism operators to maximise returns and contribute to
national gain.</P>
<P></P>
<P>One of the tasks of the needs analysis consultancy into rural
tourism was to investigate the applicability of the available training
programs and indicate any gaps. The consultancy found a substantial
range of basic materials, generally of high quality, for people wanting
to establish rural tourism enterprises, particularly farm-stay or bed
and breakfast establishments. However, the consultancy found a lack of
awareness among some operators, particularly newcomers, of the
availability of such training material and associated training programs,
indicating a need for reference or contact points for operators.</P>
<P></P>
<P>There is a need to communicate the availability of tailored programs
to those who can benefit from them. Many rural operators may be linked
into networks providing agricultural education (e.g. TAFE colleges)
which could be used to deliver information on tourism programs. Local
and regional bodies might also benefit from greater awareness and
understanding of the tourism industry.</P>
<P>One way to improve training provision is to have improved
communication between the training bodies and those wanting training.
TTV advises that, in Victoria, some regional areas have set up industry
advisory bodies which communicate local industry needs to the regional
TAFE college which has the capacity to work out appropriate solutions.</P>
<P></P>
<P>It is not only in areas specifically relating to the management of
the business that education is required. The needs analysis consultancy
found a lack of general knowledge about tourism industry associations
and industry structure among both operators and regional tourist
associations. The consultancy also noted a lack of awareness among
operators of the nature of other tourist attractions in their own
region.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Besides meeting the needs of operators, it may also be that the
provision of training can be used to improve the attractiveness of
membership of regional tourism associations. The needs analysis
consultancy suggests that a program be developed for providing
professional advice to operators to be delivered as a part of regular
meetings. The consultancy suggests one hour be set aside to workshop one
theme, idea or aspect of business such as `capital gains tax
implications on the sale of renovated heritage buildings' and `effective
radio interview techniques'.</P>
<P>In preparing training strategies or packages for rural tourism, it
may not be necessary to train new educators specifically for rural
tourism development. Existing trainers in other fields, such as business
advisers in rural areas, may be able to complement their repertoire of
general business knowledge with a tourism component.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The needs analysis consultancy also reported problems with the
recent growth of four-wheel-drive vehicle ownership and increasing
incidents of vandalism and irresponsible behaviour by visitors to
country areas. Travellers need to be made more aware of their broad and
specific responsibilities in using the countryside, whether it be on
publicly- or privately-owned property. There are already some codes of
conduct, such as the 4Rs in Cape York, Queensland. </P>
<P></P>
<P>STRATEGY: Ensure the educational and training needs, with regard to
tourism, of tourists, rural tourism operators, rural communities, local
government authorities, regional tourism associations, regional
development organisations and all spheres of government, are known and
are being met.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Actions</P>
<UL>
<LI>Encourage industry training for rural tourism operators (all
spheres of government, industry associations, TTA, regional tourism
associations).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>Under the RTP in 1993-94, a grant of $50  000 was given to ITOA
to further AussieHost activity in regional Victoria. This grant is in
addition to $42  000 funded in 1991-92 by the Commonwealth
Department of Tourism and $50  000 funded by the ATC in 1992-93.
</P> 
<P></P>
<UL>
<LI>	Establish education programs to increase the tourism skills base
of local government, and regional tourist and economic development
officers, as to rural tourism as an industry--its needs, requirements
and relevant regulations (all spheres of government, educational
institutions).</LI>
<LI>	Continue to work with educational and training institutions,
particularly TTA as the peak coordinating body for industry training, on
developing relevant training materials and effective use of distribution
channels (Federal, State and Territory Governments, industry
associations, TTA, educational institutions).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>Under the RTP in 1993-94, a grant of $130  000 was given to TTV
to develop a sales and marketing package specifically directed to assist
rural tourism operators nationally.</P>
<P></P>
<P>The Federal Government also provided, through the Department of
Tourism, $15  000 to TTA in May 1994 to establish international best
practice benchmarking for the Australian tourism industry.</P> 
<UL>
<LI>Develop appropriate training courses to encourage adherence to best
practice principles (industry associations, TTA, educational
institutions).</LI>
<LI>Encourage appropriate organisations to compile basic information on
type and availability of educational courses and training, the structure
of the tourism industry, and relevant industry associations and their
roles for use by newcomers and potential entrants to rural tourism,
produced on a State/Territory basis (Federal, State and Territory
Governments, AFACT and other industry associations, regional tourist
associations, TTA).</LI>
<LI>Develop methods for raising awareness amongst operators of other
tourist attractions in their own region to increase understanding of how
their product fits into a broader industry picture to enhance
cooperative marketing (all spheres of government, regional tourist
associations).</LI>
<LI>Examine the need for a mechanism to make rural tourism operators
more aware of benefits to be gained through training (TCA, AFACT) and,
if a need exists, develop ways to convey this message to operators (TCA,
AFACT, TTA, educational institutions).</LI>
<LI>Encourage rural tourism operators to participate with industry
groups so they may benefit from sharing experiences and learn by
attending organised seminars and conferences (industry associations,
regional tourism associations). </LI>
<LI>Develop and distribute a simple code of conduct for visitors using
the countryside (Federal, State and Territory Governments, regional
tourist associations, industry associations, hire car operators).</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC22">6.5 Marketing 
</A></H2>
<P>Marketing can be defined as `analysing consumer needs and desires
and developing and promoting products that will meet these needs at
prices mutually acceptable to both producer and consumer' (Dickman 1989,
p. 224). Traditionally, it has also included the four Ps--product,
place, price and promotion. In the tourism and hospitality industry,
people also play an important role. This is particularly relevant in the
rural tourism sector where the enjoyment of a rural holiday can be
strongly influenced by the nature of the personal contact between guests
and hosts. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Global competition for the tourism dollar is such that being able to
target a potential consumer market skilfully, develop an interesting
product that meets that market's expectations, and then promote widely
and creatively to the specific market will determine how successfully a
country's tourism industry performs against that in other countries.
This requires governments, regional associations and industry to work in
cooperation to achieve a coordinated marketing strategy.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism is an industry segment which has the capacity to add
to the variety of product and to play an integral role in making
Australia more competitive in the world tourism market.</P>
<P></P>
<P>In January 1994, the ATC launched its Partnership Australia
initiative, a national cooperative marketing venture between Federal,
State, Territory and industry tourism bodies. The Partnership Australia
initiative aims to convert consumers' desire to visit Australia into
holiday bookings by helping the industry to develop and market a greater
variety of product, improve the distribution of information and product
to the international travel industry and consumers, and broaden industry
and consumers' knowledge of Australia.</P>
<P></P>
<P>This philosophy of cooperation to achieve marketing economies of
scale is a significant ingredient in successful marketing and can be
applied equally well at the operator level as at the national
`Partnership' level. A strong cooperative marketing approach is
essential (whether it be within the context of a rural tourism body such
as AFACT or with other operators). The Blue Mountains region in New
South Wales is a good example where operators have worked closely
together in association with the local tourism authority to present a
wide combination of product and a strong national and international
image.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Cooperative or joint marketing through informal groups of operators
or through regional, State or national marketing organisations such as
the ATC or AFACT, allows marketing to be achieved in a most efficient
and profitable manner. One of the benefits to operators of belonging to
a national organisation such as AFACT is that marketing can be more
focused and sustained than if they were to act on their own.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Other benefits of cooperative marketing include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>increased cost-effectiveness where the pooling of resources can
lead to better quality and larger scale promotions and advertising and,
usually, higher returns;</LI>
<LI>a greater variety of market opportunities where more markets can be
targeted in a wider variety of locations;</LI>
<LI>better representation at industry functions and trade shows which
can provide extensive information on industry-wide trends and activities
and also serve as a good conduit through which to promote rural tourism
products;</LI>
<LI>more credibility in the eyes of wholesalers and inbound tour
operators who tend to regard a cooperative marketing entity as more
likely to provide a quality product (A significant component of the
ATC's rural tourism price/product campaign in Asia involves
familiarising agents and conducting road show programs to educate sales
counter staff on the extent and variety of Australian rural tourism
product available.);</LI>
<LI>better access to information through networking opportunities and
increased negotiating and purchasing power; and</LI>
<LI>a greater variety of product for the tourist to enjoy, which might
affect the length of time spent in an area.</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>The packaging of a combination of country accommodation and cuisine,
horse riding, shopping opportunities, country fairs, ecotourism and
heritage visits, with appropriate transport, is an example of the
diversity of rural product that might be required to attract
wholesalers, inbound tour operators and tourists themselves. Event
marketing, including conventions and incentives, is an expanding market
sector, and there are ample opportunities for spin-offs to rural
tourism. There is potential for a greater number of smaller workshops,
seminars and conventions to be held outside the capital cities, tying in
with local events such as festivals. In such cases, through thoughtful
marketing, the delegates may be enticed to visit the area before the
convention or remain in it afterwards.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism operators will benefit from the ATC's five-year theme
year program, which is promoting the rich diversity of Australia's
unique character and heritage to the international market. In 1995, the
theme is `Celebrate Australian Art and Culture' and in 1996 it will be
`Experience the Festivals of Oz'.</P>
<P></P>
<P>As well as innovative packaging, high quality, locally made
merchandise is a good marketing tool to advertise the product to others
when the visitor returns home. Rural Australia, particularly where there
are traditional forms of agriculture, life style and transport (e.g.
horse drawn vehicles, paddle steamers and so forth) has a popular image.
The plying of old trades is also a tourist draw card. Successful
merchandising, however, is dependent on operators and local communities
having the appropriate market knowledge and skills to make and sell
products representative of a particular region. </P>
<P></P>
<P>The Cobb and Co. Museum in Toowoomba, Queensland, fulfils a number
of functions including education (the teaching of old trades such as
coach building, wheelwrighting and saddle making to young people), the
preservation of coaches and equipment, and tourism. It also has a strong
merchandising aspect where the history of horse-drawn vehicles is
profitably marketed in books, postcards, posters and other items. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Individual operators have a responsibility to ensure their
advertising budgets are used to best advantage. To this end, operators
should collect data to research target markets and the most effective
advertising avenues for their particular products. Operators also need
to be aware of their position in the market to realistically target the
competition by delivering a superior product for the consumer.</P>
<P>A summary of market needs, <I>Rural Travellers to
Australia--Summary</I>, commissioned by the ATC, provides an overview of
the types of travellers to rural areas from the major international
markets targeted by the ATC. This publication is available from the ATC.<B>
</B></P>
<P><B></B></P>
<P>Issues</P>
<P></P>
<P>Rural tourism operators who rely solely on individual marketing
efforts and fail to take advantage of coordinated marketing strategies
may deprive themselves of additional custom and therefore profitability.
They may retard regional growth and even affect overseas interest in,
and bookings for, rural holidays. </P>
<P></P>
<P>While the small scale of many rural tourism operations is their
major strength in terms of the special holiday experience they can
offer, in relation to marketing it is one of their weaknesses. This can
be overcome in part by packaging rural activities and attractions at the
regional and national levels and establishing strong links with
distribution and publicity networks. </P>
<P></P>
<P>Strong links into distribution and publicity networks are necessary
to ensure that rural tourism product is easily available to all those
who wish to access it. Unless these networks are firmly in place, travel
agencies and other trade outlets are unlikely to recognise rural tourism
as a serious product worth selling. This situation may be alleviated
slightly by the increasing numbers of free and independent travellers
(FITs), both domestic and international, now emerging as major buyers of
tourism and who may generate individual demand at travel agencies.
However, difficulties may arise even in this situation as many FITs do
not use normal trade channels to obtain travel information but get it
from travel magazines and books such as the <I>Lonely Planet</I> and
<I>Let's Go</I> guides.</P>
<P></P>
<P>STRATEGY: Promote coordinated and cooperative marketing of rural
tourism opportunities.</P>
<P>Actions</P>
<UL>
<LI>Continue to support the development of a coordinated approach by
the ATC to targeting key overseas markets, extension of promotions and
trade servicing (industry associations, Federal, State and Territory
Governments).</LI></UL>
<P></P>
<P>The Federal Government has provided funding for the Partnership
Australia initiative in which marketing efforts are being channelled
into a unified, national approach to market Australia overseas (in
1994-95, total contributions from the Federal, State and Territory
Governments will be at least $17.6 million).</P>
<P></P>
<P>A key benefit of the initiative will be the development of a strong
consumer push beyond traditional destinations and into regional tourism
areas.</P>
<UL>
<LI>Encourage regional marketing cooperation (operators, industry
associations, regional tourist associations and development
organisations, marketing organisations, all spheres of government).
</LI>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>AFACT recently launched its privately-funded `Host Farm and Country
Stays' international marketing program. The program is aimed at
increasing the profile of, and visitation to, rural Australia and began
with the Travel Australia Britain Seminar (TABS) in Bangkok in September
1994. AFACT's Executive Officer attended the seminar with funding
assistance from the RTP.</P>
<P></P>
<P>AFACT has received funding under the RTP to investigate the
feasibility of developing a national information database for rural
tourism products. AFACT intends to supplement this with a reservations
capacity which will simplify procedures for making bookings, an
important aspect of successful marketing.</P>
<P></P>
<P>A rural tourism price/product campaign is currently being run by the
ATC in Asia. The campaign, which received funding of $200  000 under
the RTP in 1993-94, is designed to convert into bookings the high level
of interest already being shown in rural Australia by Asian tourists. A
rural tourism project officer position is also being funded under the
RTP ($60  000 in 1993-94 and $40  000 in 1994-95) in conjunction
with the campaign.</P>
<P></P>
<P>Under the RTP, funding of $40  000 has been provided to the Swan
Valley Tourism Council in Western Australia to enhance its regional
marketing base through the development of a tourism assets register, the
conduct of perceptual research and the establishment of a marketing
identity for the region.</P>
<P></P>
<P>This project demonstrates the importance of taking stock of tourism
attractions already available in a region, determining how these
attractions are viewed by visitors and what action can be taken to
develop and package products such that they meet the expectations of
established and emerging markets.</P>
<P>	Encourage the rural tourism industry to ascertain and focus on
target markets which are most likely to demand the product and services
it has to offer. These might include, for example, people interested in
short breaks, families, special interest groups and seminars (operators,
industry associations, marketing organisations).</P>
<P></P>
<P>Under the RTP in 1993-94, the Federal Government provided funding of
$30  000 to the ATC to undertake further analysis of the
Commission's segmentation studies to ascertain the type of international
visitors rural tourism operators should target and to assist in the
appropriate development of rural tourism products and marketing
programs.</P>
<UL>
<LI>Encourage better knowledge and usage of the distribution and
publicity networks available for providing travel agents, wholesalers,
inbound tour operators and FITs with more information on rural tourism,
particularly packages involving a combination of activities and
attractions (operators, industry associations).</LI>
<LI>Encourage the rural tourism sector's efforts to strengthen its
profile and connections with the broader tourism industry, through such
activities as industry attendance and participation in such annual
events as the ITOA symposium, TCA's Australia Tourism Conference and
National Seminar Program (the latter is run in conjunction with the
ATC), and where appropriate, the ATC's Australian Tourism Exchange and
Dreamtime trade shows and, where possible, overseas events such as TABS
and International Tourismus Borse (operators, industry associations,
marketing organisations).</LI>
<LI>Encourage regional cooperation and the marketing of a mix of
tourism enterprises in the area for the benefit of visitors and the
local tourism sector (operators, regional tourism associations and
regional development organisations, marketing organisations, industry
associations, all spheres of government).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC23"
>6.6 Market analysis
</A></H2>
<P>The BTR provides the basis for most tourism market analysis in
Australia through two national travel surveys, the Domestic Tourism
Monitor and the International Visitor Survey. These surveys are
complemented by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) Integrated
Regional Database, a collection of data from different ABS surveys,
particularly the Survey of Tourist Accommodation. These surveys provide
data on tourism activity at the national, State/Territory and regional
levels.</P><P></P><P>In addition to these surveys, the Commonwealth's
major responsibilities for tourism research are:</P><UL>
<LI>tourist expenditure surveys;</LI>
<LI>research in support of policy formulation at the national level;</LI>
<LI>market analysis of tourism data through both the ATC and the BTR;
and</LI>
<LI>estimation of the economic significance of tourism at the national,
State and Territory levels.</LI></UL><P></P><P>The States and
Territories contribute to many of these undertakings through their
partial funding of the BTR. In addition, many of the States and
Territories collect their own data and do research to complement the
information available from the national surveys. For example, New South
Wales conducts research into rural tourism (Country Holiday, Domestic
Holiday research project) and also produces estimates of tourism
activity at the local government area level. Queensland, Tasmania and
the Northern Territory conduct their own tourism surveys to collect
regional data. South Australia has produced a range of publications
focusing on tourism in its various regions. Western Australia has in the
past conducted a detailed survey designed to produce reliable regional
data.</P><P></P><P>The problem of obtaining reliable tourism data for
the lesser visited regions from the national tourism surveys prompted
BTR to develop the methodology for a Regional Tourism Monitor. This
methodology is being adopted in 1994-95 by both Victoria and Western
Australia.</P><P></P><P>Issues<B></B></P><P><B></B></P><P>Where
rural tourism enterprises have been developed on an ad hoc basis without
reference to relevant data, research on market trends and related
strategic issues, there is a danger that the full potential of this
industry segment has not been realised.</P><P></P><P>Planning for
sustainable rural tourism should include market analysis (e.g.
visitation to regional areas including length of stay, visitor profile
data, associated spending, visitor satisfaction levels, visitor
expectations and return visits). Reliable visitation data is essential
for informed policy formulation, the planning of regional tourism
strategies and product development.</P><P></P><P>There seems to be an
expectation in many parts of the tourism industry that government should
satisfy their research needs. As TCA recognised in its Chairman's report
of 1992: `There is always a strong temptation to look to the government
to do the necessary research, but this would not give us commercial
outcomes'. Industry, as well as government, has responsibility for data
collection and analysis.</P><P></P><P>STRATEGY: Encourage the
provision of reliable regional data and research on rural tourism
supply/demand factors.</P><P></P><P>Actions<B></B></P><UL>
<LI>Encourage the provision of reliable data to be used for rural
tourism development (Federal, State and Territory Governments, industry
associations).</LI></UL><P></P><P>The TFC has been established to
improve the quality of information available for tourism investment
decision makers.</P><P></P><P>The Federal Government has provided a
grant of $30  000 to enable the ATC to analyse their market
segmentation data from a rural perspective to identify potential
overseas markets for the rural tourism product.</P><P></P><P>This
information will be disseminated to industry when available.</P><P></P><P>
The BTR has developed a methodology for a Regional Tourism Monitor which
is currently being adopted by Victoria and Western Australia as a basis
of monitoring regional tourism trends.</P><UL>
<LI>Rural tourism operators should avail themselves of applicable
research and data produced by the BTR, ABS, State Governments and
regional authorities (operators).</LI>
<LI>In instances where rural tourism operators do not feel confident in
interpreting the statistics, the regional development organisations and
regional tourism authorities should have staff or publications available
to assist them (operators, regional development organisations, regional
tourism associations).</LI>
<LI>Encourage all State AFACT Associations to collect monthly visitor
statistics and data from operators--the AFACT Executive Officer is to
standardise the format of the questionnaires for comparative purposes
(AFACT).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC24">6.7 Industry
leadership
</A></H2>
<P>Both the McKinsey and <I>Working Nation</I> reports emphasise the
importance of committed and energetic leadership to the development of
regional Australia. Strong regional leadership which, at its best,
consists of a group of committed people drawn from all parts of the
community, can favourably influence the local business and investment
environment, generating regional growth and new jobs.</P><P></P><P>Rural
tourism fits well into this framework. While it has the potential to
contribute to the diversification of both the tourism industry and rural
areas, it can only do so if there are people in industry and the local
community willing and able to direct its growth and development.</P><P></P><P
>At present, industry-wide leadership is undertaken by such major
tourism organisations as TCA and ITOA. The issues they deal with tend to
have national implications for the tourism industry as a whole (for
example, TCA's evidence to the current parliamentary inquiry into
tourism and taxation), although as mentioned above in section 4.1, TCA
is devoting increasing attention to regional issues, for example through
the proposed development of a National Regional Tourism Strategy. More
directly involved with rural and regional tourism are the rural-oriented
tourism organisations such as AFACT; the State-based operation, Country
Victoria Tourism Council (CVTC); and the marketing body, Tasmanian
Holiday Retreats. Although the newly-formed Bed and Breakfast Council
will represent all areas of Australia, the potential involvement of bed
and breakfasts, which are estimated to number over 2  000 in rural
Australia (approximately three-quarters of all bed and breakfasts
Australia-wide), could give this organisation significant rural
presence.</P><P></P><P>Industry leadership, no matter how committed
and progressive, cannot work effectively without community support and
involvement. At the regional level, community leaders can include
representatives from local government, regional development boards,
regional tourist associations, local businesses, community groups and
the general public. Community leaders working together with a strong
shared vision of what a region can become are essential to the
successful development and management of tourism in country areas.</P><P>
</P><P>Issues</P><P></P><P>Without strong leadership and strategic
planning at the regional and national levels, rural tourism may not
develop its full potential. The industry's decentralised nature, its
preponderance of small businesses and the diversity of its product
highlight the need for a cohesive leadership structure which can
represent the interests of rural tourism operators as a distinct tourism
industry sector, both regionally and Australia-wide.</P><P></P><P>A
strong national representative body could, on behalf of its members:</P><UL>

<LI>market rural tourism products nationally and internationally;</LI>
<LI>develop and monitor accreditation as well as higher and consistent
standards, and promote the merits of such schemes;</LI>
<LI>communicate with Government and liaise with tourism and non-tourism
bodies on rural tourism issues;</LI>
<LI>act as a conduit for rural tourism information; and </LI>
<LI>investigate such matters as sponsorship, insurance, and training
and education.</LI></UL><P></P><P>Success in achieving these
objectives would determine the extent to which rural tourism operators
would be able to take advantage of combined buying power, increased
market share, and enhanced communication and networking structures.</P><P>
</P><P>To be effective, members of the tourism industry and interested
parties must know about industry organisations and their roles. AFACT is
looking at this issue on behalf of its own members. The needs analysis
consultancy found a lack of general knowledge amongst both operators and
regional tourist organisations concerning industry associations and
industry structure. (This issue is addressed at section 6.4.)</P><P></P><P>
STRATEGY: Encourage and support industry and community leadership as a
means of developing tourism in rural areas and contributing to regional
growth. </P><P></P><P>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Develop industry and community leadership as a medium for
progressing the interests of rural tourism (industry associations, all
spheres of government, rural communities).</LI></UL><P></P><P>Under
the RTP, funding has been provided to AFACT for the engagement of an
Executive Officer to enhance the leadership capacity of the
organisation.</P><P></P><P>A priority of the Executive Officer is to
extend the organisation's membership to be more representative of the
rural tourism sector of the industry through the development of
sponsorship, partnership and membership arrangements so that AFACT
becomes self-sustaining.</P><P></P><P>Under the RTP, the Federal
Government has also provided funding of $70  000 for two rural
tourism scholarships ($35  000 in 1994-95 and $35  000 in
1995-96) on the Australian Rural Leadership Program (ARLP).</P><P></P><P>
The ARLP is designed to develop future leaders of the rural sector.
Strong and informed leadership will assist in establishing more
competitive, profitable and sustainable industries, including rural
tourism.</P><P></P><P>Benefits include the opportunity to spread the
word about tourism to prospective leaders in rural Australia and build
stronger links and strategic alliances between tourism and other rural
industries.</P><P>	Encourage tourism industry associations in their
endeavours to make people (not only tourism operators) aware of their
existence (all spheres of government, industry associations). </P><P>	Support
industry initiatives which focus on regional and rural tourism
development issues (all spheres of government, rural communities,
regional tourism associations and development organisations).
</P><H2><BR>
<A NAME="RTFToC25">6.8 Transport and infrastructure
</A></H2>
<P>Rural tourism products are often found in relatively remote regions
with low population density. The availability of reliable and
competitively priced transport infrastructure is therefore important to
the development of rural tourism. </P><P></P><P>A number of
submissions to <I>Tourism Discussion Paper No. 1--Rural Tourism
</I>identified transport infrastructure as a constraint to such
development. While transport issues identified in the submissions
varied, in general they related to regional issues such as the poor
state of roads (which can add to travelling time and stress the motoring
tourist), lack of reliable transfer services and strict licensing
regulations for transport providers. </P><P></P><P>In particular,
respondents identified irregular bus and train services to regional
hubs, inadequate facilities at those hubs, and inadequate signage in
many parts of rural Australia. Signage is very important for developing
touring routes and enhancing the rural product through interpretation.</P><P
>The reluctance of some tourists, particularly international visitors,
to travel on dirt roads to reach rural attractions can be exacerbated by
hire car firms either not providing cars for use on dirt roads or
charging greater accident premiums which reflects the insurers'
perception of risk. Cutting premiums for higher risk would require
cross-subsidisation by lower risk users, an action which could affect
other sectors of the tourism industry.</P><P></P><P>Although concerns
have also been expressed about train services, including the lack of
catering on particular lines and limitations of advance booking
facilities, rail travel in some areas is assisting in the development of
rural tourism. For example, Countrylink, the business unit of State Rail
which operates long distance passenger trains and an interlinking coach
service across New South Wales, is offering travel packages to
destinations right across New South Wales and interstate. These packages
provide highly competitive deals for accommodation, tours and other
interesting activities. Among the packages offered are a variety of
Central West and outback New South Wales tours including a two-day
safari covering the Western Plains Zoo and a five-day golf enthusiasts
tour of the North Coast.</P><P></P><P>Issues </P><P></P><P>There are
two key aspects of rural tourism transport infrastructure. One is the
availability and the cost of transport to rural tourism regions and the
other is the provision of transport infrastructure within these regions.</P><P
></P><P>In general, access to rural tourism regions has been enhanced
in recent years as a result of various micro-economic reforms of the
transport sector, including aviation reforms. These reforms have
resulted, in most cases, in lower fares and a wider choice of services
for visitors travelling to major regional centres. </P><P></P><P>The
reform of the domestic and international aviation sectors, in
particular, has opened up opportunities for operators to provide new
services demanded by consumers. For example, the liberalisation of the
international charter policy has resulted in some regional centres being
used for direct international flights, offering tourists convenient and
less expensive access to these regions. </P>
<P></P><P>The recently announced privatisation of FAC airports also
allows some opportunities for regions to become more involved in the
operation of airports, with potential benefits for rural tourism.</P><P></P><P
>In addition, reforms of the road and rail sectors currently under way
have the potential to increase the competitiveness of these modes of
transport with likely benefits to rural tourism. In particular, the
recent changes to road funding arrangements and the Australian Transport
Council's national review of road funding needs, due to be completed in
April 1995, have the potential to contribute to road transport
improvements to the benefit of rural tourism. </P><P></P><P>Under the
new road funding arrangements introduced in 1994, Federal Government
responsibility for the funding of roads is confined to the construction
and maintenance of the National Highway System (NHS). The NHS circles
Australia linking the mainland capitals and other major cities and
includes certain urban roads which provide links to the National
Highway. The Federal Government will provide $820 million during 1994-95
to fund the NHS program.</P><P></P><P>The responsibility for all other
roads rests with State and Territory Governments and local governments.<B>
 </B>In 1994-95,<B> </B>the Federal Government will provide $350
million and approximately $325 million, respectively, in untied grants
to State and Territory Governments and local governments as
discretionary funding to help these governments discharge their road
funding responsibilities.Councils throughout Australia currently spend
about $2.5 billion per annum on roads.</P><P></P><P>At the regional
level, public transport sometimes offers travellers limited itineraries,
irregular services and inappropriate time tabling as schedules are
arranged to suit the major users first. While this inconvenience can be
frustrating and deter potential country visitors, there is a limited
likelihood of change without a corresponding increase in demand. It will
be incumbent on operators to direct visitors to the most favourable
services.</P><P></P><P>The establishment of National Rail which is
likely to act as a catalyst for structural improvements to other rail
services, including rural services, and the development of uniform
regulations of driving hours and road worthiness for buses may also
benefit rural tourism. </P><P></P><P>In some States, tourist operators
report their businesses are being adversely affected by the requirements
of State licensing laws pertaining to the transport of passengers
(tourists) from and to airports, bus and railway stations. It is
sometimes a requirement that the transport vehicle (which for small
operators can be, in effect, the family car) be licensed in the same
manner as a coach service and the driver may be required to possess the
same standard of licence as a coach driver.</P><P></P><P>Tourism
infrastructure needs in rural areas necessarily reflect the type and
level of rural tourism. `Hard' adventure travellers may prefer to look
after themselves, but the majority of rural tourists will expect to be
provided with at least basic facilities. In rural areas with limited
exposure to tourists, requirements may include easier access and the
provision of basic facilities such as a toilet block, while in more
tourist-developed areas, parking facilities and information boards may
be expected. To encourage higher levels of visitation further facilities
may be required such as developed heritage/walking trails, signage,
parks and information services (which could be offered as an adjunct to
another business such as a grocery store or garage). In turn, regional
centres, which act as a nucleus for tourist exploration, will require
more comprehensive visitor information centres than the local areas.</P><P>
</P><P>Providing appropriate public infrastructure is important to the
growth of rural tourism. It can be either purpose-built, modified,
renovated or simply opened up according to the needs of the types of
visitors envisaged. Whether this provision occurs at a basic level or
the infrastructure itself is made into a feature of the area will depend
on the innovativeness of local people and available funding.</P><P></P><P>
The low population density of regions providing rural tourism product
can often mean local demand is inadequate to justify the provision of
regular transport services. On the other hand, it is unlikely that
demand for transport services and related infrastructure created by
travellers would in itself justify provision of these services. Tourist
facilities of this nature can only be justified if supported by demand
from all users and should only be provided with the support of the wider
community, which in most cases will carry a large part of the financial
burden. This raises the issue of the capacity of local communities to
finance public infrastructure to support tourism and the possible need
for assistance from State and Federal Governments.</P><P></P><P>On the
other hand, rural tourism generated demand for transport infrastructure
could, in some cases, enhance returns on investment in the existing
infrastructure. Some rural communities might benefit if the demand
generated by a growing tourism industry makes it less likely that
transport services to rural areas will be discontinued due to
insufficient patronage.</P><P></P><P>Meeting the cost of
infrastructure for tourism is likely to continue to be a contentious
issue. This must be addressed when communities are deciding whether, and
how, tourism is likely to be viable in their particular area. If tourism
is decided upon, then it will be necessary to convince the community
(the rate payers) of the benefits of tourism so that they are able to
see the justification for changes in local funding priorities (or rate
increases) where it is necessary to cover infrastructure costs.
Communities must also understand the pros and cons of cost-recovery
measures and how they can best be implemented.</P><P></P><P>STRATEGY:
Encourage improvements in rural transport and infrastructure.</P><P></P><P>
Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Examine the potential for increased transport demand to specific
regions in light of expanding tourism opportunities to convince local
transport operators of the commercial opportunities available to them as
a result of growth in tourism, and encourage them to take up these
opportunities by providing transport services which cater for visitors
(AFACT, other industry associations).</LI>
<LI>Liaison between State and Territory Governments and industry
concerning licensing laws pertaining to the transport of tourists
(industry associations, State and Territory Governments)</LI>
<LI>Consider local transport needs,<B> </B>including roads, in the
preparation of overall regional and local development strategies,
including those specifically for tourism (all spheres of<B> </B>government,
regional development organisations, regional tourist associations).</LI>
<LI>Ensure that the economic benefits of rural tourism gain appropriate
attention in the consideration of road and infrastructure funding needs
and planning (State and Territory Governments, local governments).</LI>
<LI>Promote the regions to charter operators with the view to
encouraging direct flights to regional areas, where appropriate, or to
encouraging linkages with key charter programs for on-carriage of
visitors to more remote areas not accessible by direct flights or which
cannot justify direct flights because of low passenger numbers (all
spheres of government, regional tourism and development associations).
</LI>
<LI>Seek greater involvement by regional interests, where appropriate,
in the management and/or ownership of regional airports with a view to
promoting the attractiveness of their regions to airlines and potential
visitors (State and Territory Governments, local governments, regional
development associations).</LI>
<LI>Raise awareness in rural communities which have significant tourism
potential of the benefits from investing in public infrastructure to
support tourism (local governments, regional tourism associations.)</LI>
<LI>Provide funding for rural tourism infrastructure development and
for demonstration projects to develop best practice models for tourism
related local infrastructure (all spheres of government).</LI></UL><P></P><P
>Grants for the provision of infrastructure may be available through the
RTDP, the NEP, the SONTS program and the FEP. These programs are
described in the
<I>Tourism Assistance Guide</I>.</P><P></P><P>The establishment of
the Regional Strategic Infrastructure Fund ($10 million in 1994-95 and
then $20 million per year to 1997-98) by the Federal Government (to be
administered by the Department of Housing and Regional Development) is
designed to further the provision of infrastructure of regional
significance.</P><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC26">6.9 role of local
government
</A></H2>
<P>Local government is a significant player in influencing the
development of tourism in rural Australia. While the tasks of the ATC
and of the State and Territory tourism authorities are to attract
tourists to Australia and the States and Territories, respectively, a
significant part is played by local governments and local tourist
associations in encouraging them to stay. </P><P></P><P>In many rural
areas, local government is operating effectively, and it is the main
provider of services and infrastructure essential for tourism and
general economic development. Local government is already a major
financial contributor to tourist associations and information centres in
much of rural Australia and is also a very significant tourism operator
in its own right (through caravan parks, local museums etc.).</P><P></P><P>
Planning for tourism development takes place at all levels, with State
and Territory Governments setting the broad regulatory framework. Within
this framework, local government is responsible for implementing the
planning and development processes for the assessment and approval of
projects, and, in so doing, finetuning those processes to reflect local
conditions. A Tourism Planning and Development Project (administered by
the Office of Local Government in the Department of Housing and Regional
Development) is currently examining mechanisms which facilitate the
effective coordination, integration and delivery of tourism services at
the local level. The Office of Local Government has also begun a Local
Approvals Review Program (LARP)--Business Regulations project which will
look at reform of business regulation by State and local governments
that affects small to medium-size businesses at the local level.</P><P></P><P
>The role of local government in developing the economic strengths of a
region is complex. Although accountable to State Governments through a
range of Acts, and in some cases constrained by this legislation, local
governments may have significant autonomy in the planning and
development decisions they make and in the way, and extent to which,
they exploit opportunities for economic growth. The situation varies
considerably from State to State. Both the McKinsey and the <I>Working
Nation </I>reports emphasise the importance of regions being able to
help themselves and bear more responsibility for their own development.
Planning for tourism needs to be proactive, and local government has a
leading role in ensuring that this occurs.</P><P></P><P>As part of
local government efforts to improve the quality of management at the
local level, the Australian Local Government Association (ALGA) has
developed a guide, <I>Integrated Local Area Planning</I>, which sets
out a recommended approach to local area planning and management. Many
of the major principles underlying integrated local area planning are
applicable to rural tourism development. These include the need to take
a holistic view of local areas when developments are planned, to ensure
community involvement in planning and management processes, and to
recognise that local areas and communities differ and therefore require
distinct responses and solutions according to their circumstances.</P><P>
</P><P>Local government involvement in, and support for, tourism
development can take many forms. They include: </P><UL>
<LI>flexible regulation of development and land use zoning controls
such that tourism projects can be easily accommodated<B> </B>(subject
to the framework established by State Governments). Consideration needs
to be given to how well current planning policies and practices cater
for the needs of tourism, and the extent to which the lack of
consistency in local government regulations and charges across the
nation impedes the development of rural tourism;</LI>
<LI>identification of the tourism strengths of an area and capacity to
cater for new and emerging markets such as backpackers and special
interest groups like agricultural education tours, which have different
implications for local area planning and decision making;</LI>
<LI>extensive consultation with, and provision of advice to, the local
community, the private sector and other government bodies on how best to
plan, develop and promote tourism in a local area;</LI>
<LI>preparation of local area tourism plans and strategies which ensure
that tourism development takes place according to the `economic vision'
set down for an area, including in the context of wider regional plans
and strategies, and which seek to maximise coordination and cooperation
between private and public interests. Environmental and social issues
also must be considered;</LI>
<LI>formulation of local area policies which facilitate the
establishment of tourism businesses, tourism infrastructure and local
beautification works in the form of streetscapes, tourist circuits, shop
fronts, town entrances and effective signposting; and</LI>
<LI>promotion of tourism through support for local tourist associations
and information centres.</LI></UL><P></P><P>Issues</P><P></P><P>While
many local government authorities have successfully taken up the tourism
cause, some have yet to come to terms with tourism as a viable economic
alternative to other rural-based industries such as mining and
agriculture, and as a sector deserving active promotion. However, an
appreciation of the potential benefits of tourism, by itself, is not
sufficient: there is a need to convert this knowledge into
implementation.</P><P></P><P>As local government exercises day-to-day
management in the environment in which the tourism industry operates at
the grassroots level, it needs to appreciate tourism issues, benefits
and opportunities and be able to deal with inquiries from the private
sector about developing new, or improving existing, tourism businesses
in rural areas. A lack of understanding of tourism specific issues may
result in missed opportunities.</P><P></P><P>There is a need to
identify best practice studies for tourism development and other
initiatives which include establishing specialised education programs to
increase the tourism skills base of interested local government and
regional tourist and economic development officers.</P><P></P><P>Equally,
operators need to cooperate with local government and be aware of the
current issues with which it is dealing; the aspirations it holds for a
region; and the planning, zoning, environmental and social impact issues
that affect its decision making. </P><P></P><P>STRATEGY: Further
enhancement of local government understanding of the benefits and
requirements of tourism, and the value of integrated industry and
government planning.</P><P></P><P>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Encourage more local councils to consider tourism as a viable
income-producing sector for local areas, and as a means by which to
raise the quality of life, and to integrate it into overall economic and
community development frameworks (all spheres of government, industry,
rural communities, regional development organisations and regional/local
tourist associations).</LI></UL><P></P><P>In 1993-94 the Federal
Government established the RTDP which is designed to assist regional
areas, through responsible planning and management practices, to develop
tourism opportunities that guarantee long-term employment and
sustainable tourism businesses.</P><P></P><P>Under the RTDP, grants
are available to local government authorities, regional tourism
associations and regional development organisations for integrated
regional tourism planning, tourism infrastructure development and
coordination of tourism information at a regional level.</P><UL>
<LI>Consult with local communities and the private sector on how and to
what extent tourism development should take place, including the
provision of timely and accurate advice to potential developers and
investors (local governments, rural communities, private sector).</LI>
<LI>Support the ALGA's Integrated Local Area Planning program, which
promotes the adoption of strategic approaches to urban planning and
service delivery by local government (all spheres of government,
industry, rural communities, regional development organisations and
regional/local tourist associations).</LI>
<LI>Increase local government awareness of Federal and State
initiatives and programs established to assist, either directly or
indirectly, the development of tourism in local areas (all spheres of
government, regional development organisations, regional/local tourist
associations).
</LI></UL><H1><A NAME="RTFToC27">CHAPTER 7 THE RURAL TOURISM PROGRAM
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC28">7.1 The Rural Tourism Program
</A></H2>
<P>The Rural Tourism Program is part of a wider $42 million package
announced in the 1993-94 Budget to stimulate tourism development in
rural and regional Australia.</P><P></P><P>Aim of the RTP</P><P></P><P>
The aim of the program is to develop rural tourism opportunities that
provide both domestic and international visitors with a broad range of
tourism experiences and to ensure the benefits of rural
tourism--increased business and employment growth--accrue to country
communities.</P><P></P><P>How the RTP works</P><P></P><P>The RTP is
a discretionary grants scheme. To date, projects funded under the RTP
address issues which reflect the input from earlier public submissions
(arising from <I>Tourism Discussion Paper No. 1--Rural Tourism</I>
released in January 1993) and industry consultations, particularly
through the Rural Tourism Focus Group. </P><P></P><P>The program has
been directed at supporting the industry development, education and
training, standards and marketing needs of the rural tourism sector.</P><P>
</P><P>An important focus of the RTP has been the use of demonstration
projects to develop innovative product ideas. Reports on these projects
will be disseminated to a wide audience, illustrating the benefits of
diversifying the product base and value-adding in rural areas.</P><P></P><P
>All projects funded to date under the RTP have been required to
demonstrate a capacity for<I> </I>national application or benefit. </P><P>
</P><P><B>Funds allocation. </B>It was announced in the 1993-94
Federal Budget that some $4 million over four years (nearly $1 million
per year) would be available for the RTP.</P><P></P><P><B>Projects
funded. </B>Funding in 1993-94 encompassed discrete projects to address
product development, marketing, standards, business development and
education and training. Approved projects and funds allocated to each
are detailed in Table 1.</P><P></P><P>To date, in 1994-95, the second
year of the program, funding has been provided for marketing and
industry leadership projects (some continuing). </P><P></P><P>Future
of the RTP</P><P></P><P>The direction of the program over the three
remaining years will reflect the outcomes of the National Rural Tourism
Strategy (this document) which incorporates accepted findings of a
recent needs analysis consultancy into major issues in rural tourism.</P><P>
</P><P>Role of the RTP in implementing the Strategy</P><P></P><P>Further
funding under the RTP in 1994-95 will concentrate on particular actions
identified in the Strategy. Projects will address accreditation, product
development, and education and training.</P><P>Projects to be funded in
1995-96 and 1996-97 will continue to reflect actions set out in the
Strategy.</P><P></P><PRE>                               Table 1.

Projects funded under the Rural Tourism Program in 1993-94

