</PRE><P><B>Regional Tourism Development Program (RTDP). </B>The
Commonwealth Government is encouraging the development of regional
Australia to generate long-term economic and employment growth. A
significant element of its commitment to regional Australia is the RTDP
which aims to spread the economic benefits of tourism to rural and
regional Australia by providing assistance for strategic tourism
planning, infrastructure projects and tourism information coordination
within a region. This kind of regional development will improve the
capacity and ability of regional Australia to attract international and
domestic tourists.</P><P></P><P>The RTDP will provide total funding of
$23 million over the four years to 1996-97 to local government
authorities, regional development organisations and regional tourism
associations for:</P><UL>
<LI>the development of regional tourism plans;</LI>
<LI>the provision of tourism infrastructure to increase the capacity of
a region to support a range of tourism attractions;</LI>
<LI>the diversification of the product base in regional areas to
increase their drawing power; and</LI>
<LI>the coordination of information at a regional level.</LI></UL><P></P><P
><B>National Ecotourism Program (NEP).
</B>The National Ecotourism Strategy was released in March 1994. It aims
to identify the major issues affecting the planning, development and
management of ecotourism in Australia and to develop a national
framework to guide ecotourism operators, natural resource managers,
planners, developers and all levels of government in addressing those
issues.</P><P></P><P>The Government has committed $10 million to
implement the Strategy through the NEP for projects that assist with:</P><UL
>
<LI>the development of appropriate ecotourism infrastructure;</LI>
<LI>the monitoring of tourism impacts through baseline studies to
assess and manage ecotourism impacts;</LI>
<LI>the integration of ecotourism in regional planning; and</LI>
<LI>the organisation of ecotourism conferences and workshops.</LI></UL><P>
</P><P><B>Forest Ecotourism Program (FEP). </B>The FEP aims to
encourage and facilitate ecotourism in forests throughout Australia on a
sustainable basis. It is directed towards developing opportunities for
visitors and tourism operators to understand and appreciate forest
environments while encouraging the sustainable management of natural
resources.</P><P></P><P>The program is a competitive grants program
developed under the National Forest Policy Statement. The 1992-93 budget
included $1.9 million over four years for forest ecotourism initiatives.
Fifteen projects were funded in 1992-93 and 17 in 1993-94. Individual
grants under the program are usually limited to $30  000.</P><P></P><P>
A wide range of projects will be considered for funding. These may
include minor infrastructure projects (such as tourist boardwalks,
viewing platforms and interpretative signs), education and awareness
activities, applied research, development of forest ecotourism planning
and management strategies, and tour operator training workshops and
seminars.</P><P></P><P><B>Sites of National Tourism Significance
Program (SONTS).
</B>The SONTS program was announced in the Prime Minister's Statement on
the Environment in December 1992. It aims to encourage and facilitate
the ecologically sustainable management and use of natural sites of
national tourism significance. The Government will provide $2 million
over three years from 1993-94 to fund the program.</P><P></P><P>The
program is directed at:</P><UL>
<LI>State and Territory Governments and local government authorities
that contribute to the development, management and conservation of
natural sites of national tourism significance;</LI>
<LI>natural areas of current national and/or international tourism
significance where the environmental values are under threat by
increasing levels of tourist activity;</LI>
<LI>natural areas of potential or emerging national and/or
international tourism significance where the environmental values are
likely to be under threat by increasing levels of tourist activity; and</LI>
<LI>projects that contribute to ecologically sustainable tourism
development, natural resource management, site planning, visitor and
operator education and training, and applied research.</LI></UL><P><B></B></P><P
><B>Backpacker Program. </B>Broadly, the Backpacker Program is expected
to reduce impediments to growth, expand marketing networks, improve
standards of backpacker accommodation, encourage a strategic approach to
the development of the backpacker tourism market and ensure a positive
return to the economy. </P><P></P><P>Through funding of almost $4
million over four years to 1996-97, the program aims to:</P><UL>
<LI>facilitate the development of a viable, professional and
internationally competitive backpacker industry;</LI>
<LI>facilitate wider dispersion of the employment, economic and social
benefits of tourism through the Australian community; and</LI>
<LI>provide opportunities to broaden the tourism product base and cater
for a wider cross-section of visitors.</LI></UL><P>In August 1994,
Tourism <B>New South Wales</B> released its <I>Regional Tourism
Strateg</I>y. One of the key aims of the strategy is to establish
regional tourism organisations that are able to represent the interests
of the industry and government in their area, both in marketing and
development of tourism for their region. Area-specific tourism
strategies have also been produced for the North Coast, Illawarra,
Hunter, South Coast and Murray regions.</P><P></P><P>As part of the
ongoing development of tourism there has been a greater focus on the
marketing of rural tourism through increased promotion of farm and
country experiences to both domestic and international markets. A
`Country Holidays' brochure has been released as part of the Seven
Wonders of New South Wales campaign.</P><P></P><P>Other initiatives
undertaken include increased training for rural tourism operators,
better roads and signage, ecotourism and cultural awareness programs.</P><P>
Contact officer:</P><P>	Mr Keith Baker</P><P>	Projects Coordinator</P><P>
	Strategic Planning and Liaison</P><P>	Tourism New South Wales</P><P>	Ph:	(02)
931 1485</P><P>	Fax:	(02) 931 1490</P><P></P><P>Tourism <B>Victoria</B>
through its Strategic Business Plan identifies regional tourism
development as an important and integral part of Victoria's tourism
strategy. Ten product regions have been identified based on the State's
natural attractions. Regional tourism development and marketing plans
are progressively being prepared for each of these areas. </P><P></P><P>
Strategic planning projects are also being developed for specific
industry segments such as bed and breakfasts, farm stays, nature-based
tourism, backpackers and Koori tourism all of which have implications
for the development of rural tourism. A regional marketing program
provides funding to the State's product areas and an opportunity for
direct participation by rural tourism organisations and operators.</P><P>
</P><P>There are strong links between the Victorian Tourism Commission
and State tourism bodies, a number of which affect the development of
rural and regional tourism. These include the Country Victoria Tourism
Council, the peak organisation representing country tourism in that
State, the Victorian Tourism Operators Association, the Victorian
Accommodation Association, the Victorian Host Farms Association, the
Caravan Parks Association, and the Victorian Wineries Tourism Council
(recently established to develop and promote wineries tourism).</P><P></P><P
>To counter deficiencies in information about regional tourism in
Victoria, a regional tourism monitor has been established. It collects
detailed information about visitor characteristics and accommodation use
and quantifies the contribution tourism makes to the Victorian economy.</P><P
>Contact officer:</P><P>	Mr Wayne Kayler-Thomson</P><P>	Manager
Industry Development</P><P>	Tourism Victoria</P><P>	Ph:	(03) 653 9718</P><P
>	Fax:	(03) 653 9744</P><P><B></B></P><P><B>Queensland</B> is
developing a tourism strategy to provide a basis for the sustainable
development of its tourism industry. The issues raised by the strategy
will have an impact on rural tourism.</P><P></P><P>The Queensland
Government recently created the Office of Rural Communities, which
provides policy advice for Government to generate fair access for rural
communities to social and economic opportunities. </P><P></P><P>In
addition, a number of regional tourism strategies are being undertaken
which identify tourism as a means for diversifying rural and regional
economies.</P><P></P><P>To support this focus on rural tourism,
increased marketing research is being undertaken along with greater
promotion of outback Queensland.</P><P>Contacts:</P><P><B>	</B>Tourism
Policy Bureau</P><P>	Department of Tourism, Sport and Racing</P><P>	Queensland</P><P
>	Ph:	(07) 237 1611</P><P>	Fax:	(07) 235 4023</P><P>	Regional Tourism
Coordinator</P><P>	Queensland Tourist and Travel Corporation</P><P>	Ph:	(07)
833 5367</P><P>	Fax:	(07) 833 5421</P><P></P><P><B>South Australia</B>
is particularly active in developing and promoting rural tourism.
Tourism development strategies as well as regional marketing plans have
been prepared for a number of rural regions. A visiting journalist
program, State marketing and funding programs, and support for such
initiatives as festivals are contributing to the growth of rural
tourism. </P><P></P><P>South Australia also administers a tourism
development fund<B> </B>to assist tourism development initiatives,
including those in rural and regional areas. Development projects which
have received assistance to date include tourist information and
interpretative centres in rural regions, information bays and rest
areas, sign posting and specific rural attractions such as the penguins
at Penneshaw on Kangaroo Island.</P><P></P><P>Contact officer:</P><P>	Mr
John Myers</P><P>	Development Adviser</P><P>	South Australian Tourism
Commission</P><P>	Ph:	(08) 303 2327</P><P>	Fax:	(08) 303 2339</P><P></P><P
><B>Western Australia</B> has been active in the development of rural
tourism. A regional tourism plan is expected to be published in late
1994 and a number of publications on rural tourism have been produced,
including <I>Towards a Nature</I> <I>Based Tourism Strategy for
Western Australia</I> and a discussion paper, <I>Getting into Host
Tourism</I> and <I>Farm, Station and Country Retreats</I>. The `Value
of Tourism'<I> </I>campaign, in November 1994, was targeted at local
communities and groups as well as local government to raise awareness of
tourism's contribution to town and regional economies and employment
opportunities. The campaign addressed the prospect of generating
confidence and optimism in rural Western Australia, through tourism, and
as a result, encouraged people to recognise the industry not only as a
business opportunity, but also as a major contributor to local
economies.</P><P></P><P>The State Government also has a number of
funding programs which are specifically directed to rural and regional
tourism. For example, grants are provided to country tourism
organisations which promote <B>a</B> region's tourism products.</P><P></P><P
>Contact officers:</P><P>	Mr Steve Crawford</P><P>	Manager Tourism
Product</P><P>	Western Australian Tourism Commission</P><P>	Ph:	(09)
220 1700</P><P>	Fax:	(09) 220 1702</P><P>	Mr Bernie Whewell</P><P>	Regional
Services Manager</P><P>	Western Australian Tourism Commission</P><P>	Ph:	(09)
220 1700</P><P>	Fax:	(09) 220 1702</P><P><B></B></P><P><B>Tasmania</B>
is currently preparing an industry development plan which will
incorporate aspects of rural and regional tourism. The plan is expected
to be available in December 1994. </P><P></P><P>Individual tourism
operations such as the historic grazing properties of Woolmers and
Brickendon at Longford have strategic management plans to assist their
development as major rural tourist attractions.</P><P></P><P>As in
South Australia, a Tourism Development Scheme provides an important
source of funding for rural tourism with farm stays, local fine foods
and wines, and industrial tourism benefiting. Special events, such as
the Targa prestige car rally and the Great Tasmanian Bike Race, are also
sponsored to encourage the spread of economic and social benefits to
rural areas and improvements in regional infrastructure.</P><P></P><P>The
Tourism Business Information Service, along with the Tasmanian Visitor
Survey, provide all operators with relevant research, information and
market analysis on the various sectors of the tourism industry. A
handbook entitled
<I>Being a Successful Tourism Operator</I> has been prepared along with
more detailed publications on legal forms of business, government
regulations and licences, training resources and a specimen business
plan.</P><P></P><P>Contact officer:</P><P>	Mr Satwant Calais</P><P>	Acting
Deputy Director</P><P>	Industry Development</P><P>	Department of
Tourism, Sport and Recreation</P><P>	Ph:	(002) 308 360</P><P>	Fax:	(002)
308 355</P><P></P><P>The<B> Northern Territory</B> released its
Tourism Development Master Plan in June 1994. The plan identified a
range of planning and development issues relating to rural areas. These
cover parks and conservation, Aboriginal cultural tourism, services and
training. In addition, four regional development plans have been
produced to assist the implementation program.</P><P></P><P>Contact
officers:</P><P>	Mr George Dunne</P><P>	Regional Manager Top End</P><P>
	Northern Territory Tourist Commission</P><P>	Ph:	(089) 893 807</P><P>	Fax:	(089)
893 847</P><P>	Mr Ian Blevin</P><P>	Regional Development Officer
Central Australia</P><P>	Northern Territory Tourist Commission</P><P>	Ph:	(089)
518 540</P><P>	Fax:	(089) 518 550</P><P></P><P>The <B>Australian
Capital Territory</B> has a number of projects which will have an impact
on rural tourism. Chief amongst these is the development of a ten-year
tourism development strategy for the ACT and region. An ecotourism
strategy is also being developed.</P><P></P><P>Contact officer:</P><P>	Mr
Richard Pollack</P><P>	Manager--Tourism Development</P><P>	Canberra
Tourism Commission</P><P>	Ph:	(06) 205 0666</P><P>	Fax:	(06) 205 0629</P><P
