<TITLE>National Ecotourism Strategy - Sections 5.6  - Appendix F</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/images/yellow_rock.gif"><H2><A NAME="RTFToC100">5.6 Impact monitoring
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>The planning, development and management of
any type of sustainable activity is dependent on the availability and
application of high-quality information. Ecotourism has developed with
relatively little data and knowledge on which to base effective
decisions.  This issue is of particular importance for the management of
visitor impacts and has been highlighted throughout the process of
developing this Strategy--in academic literature, workshops and public
submissions.  </P><P></P><P>Effective decision-making would be aided
by improved data and knowledge relating to the immediate and cumulative
impacts of tourism, and ecotourism, on the natural and cultural
environments.  Systems for monitoring impacts must be clearly understood
by all affected parties and not remain the sole domain of the scientific
community (Queensland Department of Tourism, Sport and Racing,
submission 562).  It is essential that research findings are widely
disseminated so that others may learn from them and put them into
practice.</P><P></P><P>Impacts of ecotourism</P><P></P><P>Biological
and physical impacts</P><P></P><P>Natural resource management requires
a sound scientific knowledge base for land capability assessment and for
the prevention, containment and monitoring of visitor impacts.  The
application of modern scientific techniques, such as geographic
information systems, predictive computer modelling and monitoring, can
assist in determining:</P><UL>
<LI>sustainable levels of usage in different environments; </LI>
<LI>which activities relate to which environmental impacts; and</LI>
<LI>how to avoid or control degradation.</LI></UL><P></P><P>A number
of important initiatives are currently under way.  The CSIRO Division of
Wildlife and Ecology has developed methodologies capable of monitoring
and predicting the outcomes of various management regimes in different
environments, and various State resource management agencies are also
conducting valuable research programs.  The Environment Strategies
Directorate of the Commonwealth Department of the Environment, Sport and
Territories is developing a set of environmental indicators, embracing
tourism's impact on natural resources, through its development of a
National State of the Environment Reporting System.  Internationally,
the World Tourism Organisation is developing a set of internationally
acceptable environmental indicators to strengthen planners' and
managers' understanding of the principal factors influencing the tourism
industry's long-term sustainability and prosperity (Hawkes and Williams
1993).</P><P></P><P>In the workshops and submissions that contributed
to the development of this Strategy, the general consensus was that the
scientific work on the impacts of tourism is insufficient and
under-resourced.  For example, the Australian Science and Technology
Council (submission 118) stated that the further development of
ecotourism in tropical Australia will require continued support for
baseline studies on the effects of tourism on environmental and cultural
features.</P><P></P><P>While there is a need for greater study and
documentation of impacts, a more sophisticated, integrated and
complementary approach to research and the dissemination of results is
required to formulate long-term sustainable management strategies. 
There is a role for government in advancing this objective.</P><P></P><P>
Economic and social impacts</P><P></P><P>Ecotourism cannot be measured
solely in economic terms.  Social and environmental factors are
interdependent with, and equally important to, economic development.  A
sustainable approach to ecotourism can only be achieved if attention is
also given to the social context within which tourism development
occurs.  There is a need to consider the broader effects of ecotourism
on local communities and the heritage values of an area (Hall,
submission 119).  In addition, the gathering and use of Aboriginal and
Torres Strait Islander cultural information must recognise intellectual
property rights and requires appropriate authorisation (ATSIC
Queensland, submission 546).</P><P></P><P>Chapter 4 highlights the
current lack of information on the economic, social and cultural
benefits and costs of ecotourism.  These have yet to be adequately
distinguished from the benefits and costs of tourism generally.  Further
study is required to assess the level of development and tourist
interaction that communities can sustain and the economic significance
of ecotourism at the national, regional and local levels.  </P><P></P><P>
Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Develop the information base of natural and cultural attractions
and ensure that this information is imparted to visitors clearly and
accurately (tourism marketing bodies, research organisations, industry).
 See also section 5.7, `Marketing'.</LI>
<LI>Investigate relevant indicators to monitor the environmental,
social and cultural impacts of tourism (academic institutions, research
organisations, all levels of government).</LI>
<LI>Undertake ecological baseline studies and investigate the limits of
acceptable change for ecotourism destinations (natural resource
managers, academic institutions).</LI>
<LI>Initiate long-term monitoring of the impacts of current tourism and
recreation activities within, and adjacent to, protected areas and
fragile ecosystems, and review past experience (academic institutions,
research organisations, all levels of government).</LI>
<LI>Investigate means by which the ecotourism industry could contribute
to research and monitoring of ecotourism impacts (industry, conservation
organisations, all levels of government).</LI>
<LI>Investigate the economic and social significance of ecotourism
(nationally, regionally and locally) and its impact on associated
communities (Bureau of Tourism Research, Australian Bureau of
Statistics, academic institutions).</LI>
<LI>Promote and facilitate the wide dissemination of ecotourism data to
encourage an integrated approach to the planning, development and
management of ecotourism (all levels of government, industry, research
institutions, natural resource managers).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC101"
>5.7 Marketing
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>Australia is yet to realise its full potential
as an ecotourism destination. Australia's international tourism
marketing often features the natural environment, with an emphasis on
areas such as the Great Barrier Reef, Kakadu and Uluru.  In addition, a
full range of natural and cultural experiences are available.</P><P></P><P>
Concern has arisen over the misuse of the term `ecotourism', since
expectations about what constitutes an ecotour vary, both in Australia
and overseas.   This presents a problem of definition for ecotourism
operators and planners and an ethical problem for marketers.  If
operators claim credentials in ecotourism, their practices must measure
up as sustainable and their products as authentic in this very
discerning market; for many tourists, the term creates an expectation of
certain standards of environmental quality and awareness. (There are now
legal implications in the European market if the product does not meet
advertised claims.)  Related to this is the issue of whether the
activities or destinations presented in promotional materials can be
sustainably delivered.  </P><P></P><P>Accurate marketing would lessen
the degree to which controls need to be placed on operators and their
clients.  Visitor management strategies, such as access management and
signs, need to be in place to cater for the increased tourist numbers
that could result from a successful marketing campaign.  Ideally,
therefore, marketing strategies should be based on plans of management
and developed after those plans are in place.</P><P></P><P>There are
numerous problems--for example, variations in quality and availability--
associated with marketing a sector that consists of many small operators
with a diverse range of products and a lack of uniformity or agreed
standards for the ecotourism product.  These problems can be reduced
through the cooperation of industry associations, government marketing
authorities and researchers.  </P><P></P><P>Ecotourism relies on the
development of quality, authentic products and the effective marketing
and delivery of these products to potential travellers.  As ecotourism
is a new area of activity, little specific marketing data is available. 
This lack of data is therefore a significant impediment to maximising
ecotourism growth.  The type of data required includes information
relating to:</P><UL>
<LI>the travel motivations of ecotourists--the distinction between
those for whom ecotourism experiences are the primary motivator for
travel and those for whom it is a secondary component of any travel
(ATC, submission 590);</LI>
<LI>the purchasing patterns of ecotourists (Tasmanian Department of
Tourism, Sport and Recreation, submission 561);</LI>
<LI>what ecotourists are looking for--desired experiences (ATC,
submission 590); and</LI>
<LI>perceptions of Australia as an ecotourism destination versus other
potential and competitor ecotourism destinations (ATC, submission 590;
Mielewski, submission 601).</LI></UL><P></P><P>The ATC has
commissioned a re-analysis of its segmentation studies, which were
conducted in all major markets in 1991 and 1992.  The re-analysis will
attempt to derive more information about the travel motivations and
desired experiences of potential travellers to Australia, and the ATC
has been asked to consider ecotourists specifically.  The ATC considers
that, while the re-analysis will provide some further information on the
topic, more work needs to be undertaken.</P><P></P><P>Characteristics
of the market</P><P></P><P>There are variations in the level and type
of tourist participation in nature-based activities.  For example,
`ecotourists' may include a mix of independent travellers, people who
travel in organised groups of a scientific, educational or recreational
nature, and individuals or families who are interested in an ecotourism
experience as part of a varied holiday.</P><P></P><P>A large
proportion of tourists attracted by the natural environment are in fact
not seeking a `total immersion' experience but rather wish to stay in an
urban or resort setting and venture out for short visits to observe
nature.  While such experiences are not generally considered ecotourism,
if effectively managed they can provide an efficient and sustainable
means for relatively large numbers of people to enjoy some exposure to
the natural environment with a much lower impact than would occur if
they were to seek a `total' nature-based experience involving camping
overnight and other outdoor activities.  </P><P></P><P>The market
profile for ecotourism requires more detailed analysis.  General
information can, however, be taken from available data such as visitor
surveys, the personal comments and perceptions of operators, and
international data. From these, the `ecotourist' appears to be well
educated, professional/semi-professional, 20-50 years of age,
independent and individualistic, looking for alternatives to the
traditional tourist destinations and experiences, and with significant
spending power.  It also appears that more females than males
participate in ecotourism activities. This information is, however,
based on limited sources and a more reliable profile of the ecotourist
is needed.</P><P></P><P>Supply</P><P></P><P>The supply of ecotourism
opportunities in Australia is largely undocumented and this has
implications for product development and marketing.  Growth will be
limited unless tourists are aware of the range of opportunities
available and their expectations are met.  Seasonal variation in
international visitation and domestic supply compounds the difficulty of
matching visitor expectations with available product.</P><P>There is
currently no complete inventory of ecotourism operators and products in
Australia, although recent publications such as <I>Ecotourism and
Nature Based Holidays </I>(Richardson 1993) and the ATC's <I>Natural
Holiday Guide
</I>go part of the way to meeting this need.  </P><P></P><P>In public
consultations for this Strategy, there was a consistent view that
ecotourism should be supply driven in response to the capacity of
natural areas to deliver sustainable tourism experiences.  An emphasis
on effective planning and management will help to ensure the continued
supply of ecotourism opportunities and a stable future for the industry.</P><P
></P><P>Demand</P><P></P><P>The exact size and nature of the market
for ecotourism is uncertain.  Interest in the natural environment,
however, is indicated in the International Visitor Survey conducted by
the Bureau of Tourism Research and in the ATC's market segmentation
studies.  The results suggest that international tourists rank factors
such as beautiful scenery, vastness, cleanliness, natural wonders,
wildlife and good beaches as major attributes influencing their choice
of Australia as a travel destination.  Over 85 per cent of Japanese
visitors ranked these factors as important, and over 70 per cent of
European and American long-haul travellers identified similar attributes
as key elements in their travel decisions.  </P><P></P><P>Many
visitors desire an authentic Australian experience that is different to
their everyday lives.  In addition, ATC research indicates a discernible
shift away from highly urbanised locations to relatively undeveloped
places of natural beauty.  The growth in visitation to national parks
and World Heritage areas supports this trend.  For example, visits to
national parks in Victoria exceeded 10 million in 1990-91 and are
increasing by 1 million annually (Victorian Department of Conservation
and Environment 1992).  </P><P></P><P>The primary role of nature in
attracting tourists to specific destinations is generally understood and
utilised.  However, more accurate measurement is required of the
significance of the environment in influencing international visitors to
choose Australia as a destination.  Also, further study is needed into
the perceived and realised benefits to the tourist of this form of
tourism (Valentine 1992).  </P><P></P><P>Conventional measures of
marketing success, such as visitor numbers and length of stay, are not
always appropriate for ecotourism.  Quality of experience and visitor
satisfaction are perhaps more appropriate to this type of tourism.</P><P>
</P><P>The need for qualitative data, such as that flowing from visitor
motivation and satisfaction studies, has also been identified by
ecotourism operators since most operators have limited opportunity and
capacity to undertake research into distant or untapped markets.  With
improved marketing knowledge, operators can make more realistic choices
about their target markets and develop specific markets ahead of
Australia's competition.</P><P></P><P>Market development will also be
enhanced by a greater understanding of the motivations and expectations
of domestic ecotourists since most tourist activity in Australia is
generated domestically and most operators work predominantly with this
market.   </P><P></P><P>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Undertake market research to assess international and domestic
demand for ecotourism (government, research institutions, industry).</LI>
<LI>Undertake qualitative studies on visitor behaviour, attitudes,
expectations and satisfaction levels relating to ecotourism experiences
to assist in product development and marketing (government, research
institutions, industry).</LI>
<LI>Encourage the development of a national inventory of ecotourism
opportunities (industry).</LI>
<LI>Investigate collective approaches to international product
promotion and distribution, such as through the ATC's Partnership
Australia (industry, ATC).</LI>
<LI>Distribute pre-visit information which links visitor expectations
with sustainable activities and opportunities in natural areas
(industry, tourism marketing bodies, natural resource managers).</LI>
<LI>Promote cooperation between the ecotourism industry and natural
area managers that encourages the incorporation of the principles of
ecotourism into the marketing effort (all levels of government, natural
resource managers, industry).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC102">5.8
Industry standards and accreditation
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>As discussed in chapter 3, `ecotourism' has
been used to describe a variety of tourism products, services and
experiences, ranging from any nature-based activity to those with a
strong emphasis on environmental sustainability and a high interpretive
content.  This variation is evident in standards of service delivery,
differences in ecotourism practices and approaches to marketing.</P><P></P><P
>Diversity in standards has prompted some ecotourism operators and
natural resource managers to call for accreditation systems for
accommodation, tour guides and field operations that would identify
their products in the marketplace, enhance the desirability of products
and minimise impact on the natural environment.  </P><P></P><P>Accreditation
systems involve formal acknowledgment of adherence to agreed standards
and would:</P><UL>
<LI>encourage the delivery of high-quality, sustainable tourism
products and the provision of accurate interpretive services;</LI>
<LI>enhance the reputation of Australian ecotourism in domestic and
international markets;</LI>
<LI>acknowledge the use of sustainable practices by ecotourism
operators to provide a marketing advantage; and</LI>
<LI>allow natural resource managers to monitor ecotourism operations
and guides working within their region.</LI></UL><P></P><P>National
accreditation systems could provide a basis for industry self-regulation
and provide consumers with useful information on which to make
comparative assessments of different enterprises and activities.</P><P>The
introduction of such systems would be complicated if a large number of
agencies were involved.  Presently, involved agencies could include
educational institutions, industry associations, government agencies,
conservation groups, training bodies, indigenous groups and professional
associations.  The range of interests of these agencies and the
diversity of locations would make it difficult to develop national
standards that also address site specific concerns, although more
specialised criteria could be developed and applied at the local level
if required.  One option could be to set up an advisory body that would
ensure a wide range of expertise was fed into the process.</P><P></P><P>
If accreditation systems are to be successful in the long term they
should be financially self-sufficient, although in the short term
government funding may be used to provide the initial impetus for
developing suitable systems in consultation with industry.  For example,
the Inbound Tourism Organisation of Australia has a national tour guide
accreditation scheme which was established with Federal Government
assistance.  Such a scheme could be developed to deliver specialised
modules for ecotourism training and accreditation.</P><P></P><P>Accreditation
systems need to be developed and implemented by the industry in
conjunction with existing training and accreditation bodies such as
Tourism Training Australia.  This organisation can provide general
advice to industry associations on the development and implementation of
core competencies and standards.</P><P></P><P>Pearson (submission 582)
suggests that tour operators, guides and educators should be licensed
and trained under an appropriate national standard, and then should be
able to operate under a regional or local code of practice determined by
the natural resource management agencies responsible for the day-to-day
control of natural tourism assets.  Pearson also recommends that
education courses and guidelines be established for the setting up of
sustainable ecotourism business enterprises.</P><P></P><P>The success
of ecotourism accreditation systems will depend on the degree to which
industry standards meet the expectations of consumers and natural
resource managers.  This may involve a cost to the operator (such as
undertaking additional training or implementing energy efficient
operating systems) in meeting these agreed industry standards.  </P><P></P><P
>Examples of relevant accreditation systems and environmental codes of
practice are provided at appendix E.</P><P></P><P>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Develop and promote industry standards for ecotourism as a basis
for industry self-regulation (industry, natural resource managers, all
levels of government).</LI>
<LI>Investigate methods to identify and give recognition to ecotourism
operators who establish and adhere to high standards (industry, all
levels of government, natural resource managers).</LI>
<LI>Examine options for developing a national ecotourism accreditation
system (professional associations, industry, natural resource managers,
training bodies, conservation groups, all levels of government).</LI>
<LI>Develop environmental education modules to encourage the adoption
of best practice in ecotourism (industry, conservation groups, tertiary
education institutions).</LI>
<LI>Explore the use of a logo for the marketing of ecotourism products
(industry and marketing organisations, natural resource managers,
training bodies, relevant indigenous groups).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC103"
>5.9 Ecotourism education
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>Appropriate tourism behaviour contributes to
high-quality tourism and brings the greatest possible benefit to all
participants--travellers, the host population and the tourism
business--without causing intolerable ecological and social damage. 
Sustainable tourism can be achieved partly by educating tourists about
the consequences of inappropriate behaviour.  It is the cumulative
effect of this behaviour that damages communities, cultures and natural
environments (Krippendorf 1984, p. 106).</P><P></P><P>Ecotourism
education can influence tourist and industry behaviour and assist the
long-term sustainability of tourist activity in natural areas.  The
development and delivery of education and interpretive services for
ecotourism requires:</P><UL>
<LI>well-trained operators and guides who can deliver accurate and
informative materials and presentations.  Tour leaders and operators
should have a good knowledge of ecology, cultural issues, conservation
and minimal impact practices, and be skilful in interpretation. 
Initiatives like the National Adventure Guiding Project commissioned by
the Australian Committee for Training Curriculum will go part of the way
to addressing this need.  This also links with accreditation;</LI>
<LI>multifaceted approaches to appeal to all visitors, regardless of
educational background or prior knowledge of the environment;</LI>
<LI>easily accessible, accurate and stimulating information (pre-travel
and during the ecotourism experience) to encourage responsible behaviour
and an ongoing interest in tourism, the environment and conservation
after the visit;</LI>
<LI>interactive learning models, such as role-plays and other
participative techniques.  These lead to the greatest information
retention, especially if combined with supporting discussions and
pictures or films (Oliver 1991); and
</LI>
<LI>the messages conveyed by television and documentary films to be
based on ecological sustainability and appropriate for the environments
involved.  The visual media can be a very powerful and effective way of
conveying best practice and increasing environmental understanding.</LI></UL><P
></P><P>The success of the learning process can be measured in
behavioural change. Management goals will be assisted through more
thoughtful and informed use of natural areas by visitors and operators. 
Ecotourism can provide a means for a wide audience to develop an
understanding of the natural world and its conservation. 
</P><P></P><P>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Review the ecotourism education needs of the public, the media,
tour operators and natural resource managers, recognising existing
training systems and prior learning (all levels of government, industry,
training bodies).</LI>
<LI>Investigate the development of new, or modification of existing,
courses in environmental science, interpretation, communication and
minimal impact practices for tour leaders and operators as a basis for
accreditation (industry associations, natural resource managers,
tertiary education institutions).</LI>
<LI>Investigate methods whereby ecotourism education can be effectively
delivered to regional and remote communities and operators through, for
example, distance learning modules (educational institutions, industry
associations, all levels of government).</LI>
<LI>Develop educational resources such as videos and documentaries to
encourage environmentally responsible behaviour by tourists and increase
their understanding of the impacts of their activities (government,
natural resource managers, the media, industry associations).</LI>
<LI>Incorporate ecotourism education into curriculums to demonstrate
the links between ecologically sustainable tourism and community
benefits (educational institutions, government, non-profit
organisations, professional associations).</LI>
<LI>Encourage the use of participative techniques for environmental
education, such as tourist involvement in research programs (natural
resource managers, educational institutions).  </LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC104"
>5.10 Involvement of indigenous Australians
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>Interest in cultural diversity is integral to
the desire for ecotourism experiences and provides an opportunity for
indigenous Australians to be involved in ecotourism.  A 1993 Australia
Council study of international visitors and Aboriginal arts revealed
that a substantial number of international visitors to Australia were
interested in seeing and learning about Aboriginal arts and culture at
their source as well as in museums and art galleries.  Any ecotourism
ventures that involve indigenous Australians should be developed through
a process of consultation and negotiation with Aboriginal and Torres
Strait Islander communities, ensuring that they have the opportunity to
make decisions about the nature of their involvement.</P><P></P><P>Ecotourism
relies on people being able to experience natural and cultural resources
in an environmentally sensitive manner.  This is often done in areas
considered to be `wilderness'.  A substantial proportion of such areas
is owned by indigenous Australians in regions such as Cape York
Peninsula, central Australia, the Kimberley region and the Northern
Territory.</P><P></P><P>Because of its focus on natural and cultural
resources and its emphasis on minimal impact tourism, usually involving
small groups and valuing the expertise of the guide, ecotourism offers
an opportunity for indigenous Australians to be involved in tourism on
their own terms should they so desire.
</P><P></P><P>Indigenous participation in ecotourism has the potential
to provide many social and economic benefits, depending on the level of
involvement.  The exposure of aspects of Aboriginal lifestyle, culture
and mythology to tourists helps to promote interracial understanding. 
It also provides employment opportunities for indigenous Australians,
and so contributes to economic self-sufficiency, in areas such as
service delivery, management, interpretation, ranger activities,
recording and management of sacred sites and other culturally important
places, construction of visitor facilities and preparation of management
plans.</P><P></P><P>However, the potential economic benefits of
tourism may be offset by related social and cultural costs to Aboriginal
communities (Western Australian Aboriginal Affairs Planning Authority,
submission 130).  Consultation with indigenous communities during the
planning stage will assist an understanding of what ecotourism involves
and help to minimise impacts.</P><P></P><P>Ecotourism is not always
appropriate for all indigenous communities. Successful participation by
indigenous Australians will depend on achieving a long-term balance
between three variables:  commercial success, the resilience of cultural
integrity and social cohesion, and the maintenance of the physical
environment.</P><P></P><P>Native title, initially recognised by the
High Court, was given further recognition and protection by the passage
of the Commonwealth Government's
<I>Native Title Act 1993</I>.  The Act protects indigenous peoples'
native title rights and interests over traditional lands.  As many of
these areas are currently Crown land or national parks, it is expected
that native title will have implications for the development of
indigenous tourism and ecotourism.</P><P></P><P>National Aboriginal
and Torres Strait Islander Tourism Strategy</P><P></P><P>In line with
the Government's commitments under the National Tourism Strategy, and in
response to the Royal Commission into Aboriginal Deaths in Custody, the
Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC) and the
Department of Tourism are jointly developing a National Aboriginal and
Torres Strait Islander Tourism Strategy.  </P><P></P><P>A Tourism
Industry Advisory Committee has been established to develop the
strategy, which is expected to be available in draft form by mid-1994. 
The Committee is made up of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
representatives, tourism operators, and representatives of tourism
industry organisations and Commonwealth, State and Territory agencies,
and is chaired by an ATSIC commissioner.</P><P></P><P>It is intended
that the strategy include information on employment and training, the
development of economic opportunities and the nature of tourism. Because
many potential indigenous tourism products will be ecotourism based, the
National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Tourism Strategy will be
linked to the <I>National Ecotourism Strategy </I>and programs.</P><P></P><P
>The Tourism Industry Advisory Committee considers it important to
involve regional and remote communities and tourism industry operators
in the process of developing the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islander Tourism Strategy.  It has met in varied locations to facilitate
this involvement.</P><P></P><P>The Committee has determined that,
before detailed work can begin on the development of the strategy, there
is a need for more information on the current level of indigenous
involvement in the industry.  To this end, two major consultancies have
been commissioned to provide national statistical and attitudinal data
on such involvement.</P><P></P><P>A multimedia campaign calling for
submissions to the Committee (`Have your Say') was undertaken in May
1993.  In addition, in February 1994 the Committee distributed an issues
paper to stimulate further discussion.  </P><P></P><P>As an initiative
under the 1993 International Year of the World's Indigenous People, a
booklet profiling successful indigenous tourism enterprises--titled
<I>A Talent for Tourism--was </I>released in February 1994.</P><P></P><P>
Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Ensure that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities and
organisations are included in the development and implementation of
ecotourism programs (ATSIC, Department of Tourism).</LI>
<LI>Involve regional and remote communities and tourism operators in
the process of developing the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait
Islander Tourism Strategy and meet in varied locations to discuss the
issues with the people concerned (ATSIC, Department of Tourism).</LI>
<LI>Recognise the contribution of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
communities to resource management and the conservation of cultural
heritage in developing the <I>National Ecotourism Strategy </I>and
programs (ATSIC, Department of Tourism, indigenous communities).</LI>
<LI>Encourage Aboriginals and Torres Strait Islanders to participate
across the full range of ecotourism development, planning, management,
decision-making, regulation and implementation (ATSIC, Department of
Tourism, indigenous communities).</LI>
<LI>Facilitate cross-cultural training to overcome identified
difficulties such as inappropriate conduct in areas of cultural
importance to indigenous people (ATSIC, governments, indigenous
communities).</LI>
<LI>Develop specialised training opportunities for Aboriginals and
Torres Strait Islanders to prepare them for involvement in tourism
(educational institutions, Department of Employment, Education and
Training).</LI>
<LI>Ensure that specific aspirations and issues identified in the
development of the National Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander
Strategy are linked with the <I>National Ecotourism Strategy</I>, as
appropriate (ATSIC, Department of Tourism).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC105"
>5.11 Viability
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>Ecotourism has the potential to be
economically beneficial on a national level by attracting inbound
visitors (thus generating foreign exchange), by encouraging domestic
tourism, and through the creation of local employment and markets. 
These national economic impacts are discussed in chapter 4.</P><P></P><P>
It appears that the structure of parts of the tourism industry favours
large-scale activity, especially in market research and product
distribution. Although ecotourism is generally suited to small-scale
operations and personalised service it is not necessarily profitable
even though the price per day to the visitor may be comparatively high. 
This raises concerns about the long-term viability of some ecotourism
ventures.  </P><P></P><P>Many of the challenges and impediments to
establishing ecotourism businesses are similar to those applying to
other small tourism operations:</P><UL>
<LI>Minimal impact practices can involve additional costs since
recycling and waste minimisation services are not easily available in
some areas.</LI>
<LI>Economies of scale, which may affect the cost of maintaining an
office or undertaking market research, are often not available to small
operators.</LI>
<LI>Small developments may be less profitable because the provision of
environmentally responsible facilities and services may be more
cost-effective on a large scale.</LI>
<LI>The distance from markets and the seasonal nature of some
operations increases distribution and promotion costs.</LI>
<LI>Public liability insurance has proved to be expensive for many
ecotourism operators.</LI>
<LI>Small operators are required to have a range of skills to lead
tours, manage an office and interact in the marketplace, as it is not
possible to employ specialists in each of these areas.</LI></UL><P></P><P>
Although these factors may represent additional costs to operators, they
are a necessary part of ecotourism.  Viability may be improved by
operating on a large scale, although large visitor numbers may produce
unsustainable levels of impact and a failure of the experience to meet
visitor expectations of ecotourism.  Some minimum impact practices--for
example, energy conservation, use of alternative fuels and water
conservation--would be economically advantageous in the long term; small
operators could also investigate the possibility of collective
purchasing or asset sharing to achieve economies of scale.</P><P></P><P>
The viability of ecotourism operations is frequently affected by the
availability of adequate capital.  Difficulty in attracting financing
often occurs because business planning is inadequate.  This can be
addressed through greater access to existing business development
programs (for example, the Queensland Tourist and Travel Corporation's
Self-Help Training Package).  In addition, approaches such as
accreditation may enable operators to compete more effectively in the
marketplace.  </P><P></P><P>Many operators view their businesses in
lifestyle terms and believe there is a need to assess viability in ways
other than net profit.  Ecotourism operations will fail, however, if
profits do not adequately cover costs and risk.  </P><P></P><P>There
is considerable potential to overcome or minimise the impediments to the
viability of ecotourism operations.  Many of the actions identified in
this paper will positively assist operators to become more viable.  </P><P>
</P><P>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Reduce the costs of implementing ecologically sustainable practices
through further investigation of the practical application of new
technology to ecotourism (all levels of government, research
institutions, natural resource managers).</LI>
<LI>Collect and disseminate practical information on cost-effective,
minimal impact practices and provide case studies of how these can be
applied to ecotourism (all levels of government, industry, conservation
groups, natural resource managers).</LI>
<LI>Investigate and promote existing measures that assist ecotourism
operators in small business development and management (all levels of
government, financial institutions).</LI>
<LI>Encourage cooperative approaches to problem solving as a means of
compensating for the small size and isolation of operators (industry
associations, ATC, marketing bodies, natural resource managers).  </LI>
<LI>Develop affordable training courses in business skills for
ecotourism operators, including home study programs, seminars and
workshops held in regional areas (all levels of government, educational
institutions, industry).
</LI>
<LI>Investigate the wide application of industry public liability
insurance schemes that provide cost savings to ecotourism operators
(insurance bodies, industry).</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC106">5.12
Equity considerations
</A></H2>
<P>Issues</P><P></P><P>Ecotourism is one of the purposes for which
some public and private land can be utilised.  Alternatives include
commerce, recreation, cultural activity and conservation.  Ecotourism is
compatible with some of these uses but may also, at times, conflict with
them.  Forms of land use may also have differing equity implications for
community and business groups.</P><P></P><P>A number of approaches are
available to manage access and protect fragile areas, including:</P><UL>
<LI>control of visitor flows--for example, advance bookings, queuing,
or the use of a ballot or other forms of quotas.  These approaches are
not based on the ability of the tourist to pay for access to an area;
and</LI>
<LI>economic instruments--for example, user charges, development
charges, access rights or tradeable permits, subsidies, or rates or
taxes that place some kind of value on resources.  Economic instruments
can be used to fund management of natural areas, manage the level of
visitation or control tourism impacts.  </LI></UL><P></P><P>Equity
considerations relate to the distribution of the costs and benefits
associated with various uses of public resources and the balance of
these costs and benefits. 
</P><P></P><P>Failure to use economic instruments may mean a heavier
burden on the wider community through taxes, with the main benefits
accruing to tourists and operators (who may not directly support the
resource).  On the other hand, economic instruments bear more heavily on
low-income groups because they are not generally adjusted on an income
basis.</P><P></P><P>Each of these options will be subject to practical
constraints.  These are often site specific and relate to available
access, topography, management regimes, the administrative costs of
collection and alternative management priorities.  </P><P></P><P>The
control of visitor flows or use of economic instruments may have
implications for operators' marketing and financial planning--for
example, operators may be required to offer definite schedules for a
minimum of three years in order to participate in the international
market, as well as five-year business plans for financial institutions
(On Track Consultants, submission 556; and Richardson, submission 578).
 </P><P></P><P>Management of equitable access to the natural
environment will depend on the resilience of the environment and its
capacity to sustainably accommodate tourists, as well as on management
priorities, since resources may be valuable for reasons other than
revenue generation.  </P><P></P><P>The use of particular management
tools will be constrained by administrative issues such as methods of
collection and whether the cost of collection is high relative to the
revenue raised.  </P><P></P><P>A mixture of techniques, depending on
the particular circumstances of the site, could be used to allow access
to ecotourism opportunities for all tourists. The use of these
techniques should be equitable and consistent, linked to an actual
service provided and capable of cost-effective implementation.</P><P></P><P
>Actions</P><UL>
<LI>Incorporate equity considerations into the decision-making process
by including community and industry representatives in management
decisions that affect access to natural areas (all levels of government,
industry).</LI>
<LI>Identify socially equitable approaches that can be used to manage
access to natural areas and associated services (all levels of
government, natural resource managers).</LI>
<LI>Investigate the use of economic instruments to fund management of
natural areas and to allow for increased participation in ecotourism
(all levels of government, industry).</LI>
<LI>Seek to ensure that ecotourism activities benefit host communities
and contribute to natural resource management and conservation (all
levels of government, industry).</LI></UL><P></P><H1><A NAME="RTFToC107">
6. IMPLEMENTATION
</A></H1> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC108">6.1 How will it happen?
</A></H2>
<P>Chapter 5 identified issues that have--or are likely to have--an
effect on the planning, development and management of ecotourism in
Australia.  The objectives and actions suggested have been framed to
address some of the limitations posed by each issue and to encourage the
effective delivery of ecotourism products and services in Australia. 
</P><P></P><P>While some of the actions identified in this Strategy
can be undertaken by individual agencies, many require coordination and
commitment within and between governments and industry; this is
reflected in the notional responsibilities allocated after each proposed
implementation action.</P><P></P><P>It is anticipated that the
government agencies and industry bodies involved will take
responsibility for actions relevant to their functional charter and
develop complementary strategies and programs.</P><P></P><P>The
Commonwealth Government has committed $10 million, over the period
1993-94 to 1996-97, to fund programs for the development and
implementation of the <I>National Ecotourism Strategy</I>.  The various
program components will aim to reduce barriers to the development of
ecotourism and spread its economic and employment potential throughout
Australia.</P><P></P><P>The program initiatives described in section
6.2 represent the priorities of the Commonwealth Government for
implementation of the Strategy.</P><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC109">6.2
Commonwealth Government priorities and programs
</A></H2> 
<H3><A NAME="RTFToC110">Program A:	Accreditation
</A></H3>
<P>This program will explore the development and implementation of an
industry-led national system of accreditation for ecotourism operations.
 This will involve extensive consultations with agencies that have
experience in, or are likely to be affected by, an accreditation system.</P><P
></P><P>Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Draw together existing experience and expertise in tourism
accreditation to investigate the establishment of identifiable and
nationally applicable standards for ecotourism.</LI>
<LI>Maximise Australia's international competitive advantage by
assuring high-quality ecotourism experiences and operations.</LI></UL><P>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC111">Program B:	Market Profiles and Research
</A></H3>
<P>This program will facilitate further market research to supplement
studies already conducted by the ATC, the Bureau of Tourism Research,
State and Territory government agencies and other organisations.  The
results of this research will be published and widely available.</P><P></P><P
>Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Undertake studies into visitor motivation and levels of
satisfaction and assess the demand for ecotourism in existing
international and domestic markets.</LI>
<LI>Publish the results of this market research and promote its use
among operators to enable the industry to develop ecotourism product and
target new markets.</LI></UL><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC112">Program
C:	Energy and Waste Minimisation Practices
</A></H3>
<P>This program will promote the use of cost-effective energy and waste
minimisation practices in ecotourism contexts.</P><P></P><P>Objectives</P><UL
>
<LI>Investigate current ecotourism initiatives in energy and waste
minimisation and assess their cost effectiveness for ecotourism
operations.</LI>
<LI>Disseminate information that demonstrates how such initiatives can
be practically applied to ecotourism.</LI></UL><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC113"
>Program D:	Infrastructure Projects
</A></H3>
<P>This program will fund infrastructure projects in and adjacent to
ecotourism destinations.  For the purpose of this program,
infrastructure may include construction or restoration projects,
protective structures such as boardwalks and viewing platforms, and
projects that demonstrate innovative eco-design and the application of
environmentally friendly technology.  Information on the applicability
of these projects will be disseminated to ecotourism operators, natural
resource managers, State and Territory Governments, local governments
and other interested organisations.</P><P></P><P>Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Support the development of best practice technology in ecotourism
by assisting the construction of new facilities or the upgrading of
existing facilities.</LI>
<LI>Encourage the adoption of minimal impact technology for ecotourism
by demonstrating the practical application of such technology in a range
of sensitive natural environments.</LI></UL><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC114"
>Program E:	Ecotourism Education
</A></H3>
<P>This program will develop and implement a communications strategy
that promotes an increased level of awareness and understanding of the
principles and practices of ecotourism to a range of audiences,
including the media, the tourism industry, education and training
bodies, and consumers.  The program may also allow for wider industry
training on ecologically sustainable practices through TAFE or distance
education modules.</P><P></P><P>Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Enhance appreciation of the principles and practices of ecotourism
among target groups and increase understanding of the potential impacts
of tourism activities on the natural environment and ecological
processes.</LI>
<LI>Encourage promotional activities that convey realistic expectations
of ecotourism experiences that can be sustained in the long term.</LI>
<LI>Encourage cross-cultural training for ecotourism operators who work
with indigenous Australians.</LI></UL><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC115">Program
F:	Baseline Studies and Monitoring
</A></H3>
<P>This program will provide assistance for projects--such as baseline
studies, predictive modelling and monitoring--that assess and contribute
to the management of changes to natural environments caused, or likely
to occur, as a result of ecotourism.  Such research activities link with
improved management practice.</P><P></P><P>Objective</P><UL>
<LI>Encourage the establishment of indicators and the collection of
data at ecotourism destinations to provide a more informed basis for
decisions by planners, operators and natural resource managers.</LI></UL><P>
</P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC116">Program G:	Integrated Regional Planning
</A></H3>
<P>This program will fund pilot projects or case studies that
demonstrate the effective integration of ecotourism planning at the
regional level.  Projects will involve collaborative approaches between
local communities, natural resource managers, local governments and
other levels of government.</P><P></P><P>Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Incorporate ecotourism into the regional planning process and
provide examples of integrated approaches that can be readily adapted by
other areas.</LI>
<LI>Sustain the long-term future of ecotourism in regional Australia by
encouraging recognition that ecosystems cross more than one
administrative unit or local government area.</LI></UL><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC117"
>Program H:	Business Development
</A></H3>
<P>This program will aim to improve the level of business skills among
ecotourism operators through workshops, short courses or distance
education modules focusing on business practices and ecotourism
management issues. </P><P></P><P>Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Improve the business skills and environmental knowledge base of
ecotourism operators and so increase the viability of operators and
their capacity to provide ecotourism experiences in an ecologically
sustainable manner.</LI>
<LI>Encourage the establishment of networks for cooperative marketing,
purchasing and skill sharing to provide competitive advantages for small
or developing ecotourism businesses.</LI></UL><P></P><H3><A NAME="RTFToC118"
>Program I:	Conferences and Workshops
</A></H3>
<P>Limited support will be available to assist the organisation of
major national and international ecotourism conferences in Australia. 
Funding may also be provided for regional workshops or to produce
material that can be distributed in Australia and overseas.</P><P></P><P>
Objectives</P><UL>
<LI>Broaden knowledge of ecotourism, including current trends in
ecotourism planning, development and management (both in Australia and
overseas), across the community.</LI>
<LI>Promote the application of best practice in ecotourism planning,
development and management by facilitating access to high-quality,
practical information.</LI>
<LI>Encourage the exchange of views to help ecotourism operators to
form networks and address common problems through cooperative or
collaborative projects.</LI></UL><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC119">6.3
Realising the vision
</A></H2>
<P>Australia is well advanced in its development of policy and
commitment to planning for ecotourism, as reflected in the policies of
State, Territory and local governments and through the interest of the
industry, land managers, conservation groups and individuals in
contributing to the development of this Strategy.  Steps toward
translating these policies and planning initiatives into practice are
identified in the objectives and actions in this Strategy.
</P><P></P><P>The implementation of this Strategy, through the actions
outlined in this chapter and the continuing development of complementary
strategies and programs by other agencies, will direct Australia towards
an ecologically and culturally sustainable ecotourism industry and, at
the same time, make a major contribution to environmental conservation
and management.</P><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC120">APPENDIX A
</A></H2> 
