></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC124">APPENDIX C
</A></H2> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC125">GLOSSARY OF TERMS
</A></H2>
<P><B>Baseline study:  </B>assessment of the present situation in
order to measure changes in that environment over time.</P><P><B></B></P><P
><B>Biological diversity:  </B>the variety of all life forms: the
different plants, animals and micro-organisms, the genes they contain,
and the ecosystems they form.  It is usually considered at three levels:
genetic diversity, species diversity and ecosystem diversity (ANZECC
Task Force on Biological Diversity 1993).  </P><P><B></B></P><P><B>Carrying
capacity:  </B>the maximum number of people who can use an area without
an unacceptable alteration in the physical environment and a decline in
the quality of the experience.  It refers not only to physical and
biological factors but also to social issues.  </P><P><B></B></P><P><B>
Commodification:  </B>the process whereby something of intrinsic or
cultural worth is turned into a commodity that has commercial value.</P><P>
<B></B></P><P><B>Conservation:  </B>the protection, maintenance,
management, sustainable use, restoration and enhancement of the natural
environment (ANZECC Task Force on Biological Diversity 1993).</P><P><B></B></P><P
><B>Ecologically sustainable development:  </B>`using, conserving and
enhancing the community's resources so that ecological processes, on
which life depends, are maintained and the total quality of life, now
and in the future, can be increased' (Ecologically Sustainable
Development Working Groups 1991).</P><P><B></B></P><P><B>Ecosystem: 
</B>a dynamic complex of plant, animal, fungal, and micro-organism
communities and the associated non-living environment interacting as an
ecological unit (ANZECC Task Force on Biological Diversity 1993).</P><P><B>
</B></P><P><B>Green jobs:  </B>new or existing jobs that benefit or
rehabilitate the environment or reduce negative impacts on the
environment through such processes as energy and waste minimisation,
cleaner production, recycling and pollution control.</P><P><B></B></P><P>
<B>Limits of acceptable change:</B>  `is used to help establish the
maximum "damage" level for a resource that society is prepared to accept
as custodian of resources for both present and future generations and to
define the maximum level of use consistent with that damage level'
(RACCoastal Zone Inquiry Information Paper No. 8, 1993).</P><P><B></B></P><P
><B>Natural:  </B>existing in, or formed by nature; non-urban; also
incorporates cultural aspects.</P><P><B></B></P><P><B>Sustainable: 
</B>able to be carried out without damaging the long-term health and
integrity of natural and cultural environments.</P><P><B></B></P><P><B>
Protected areas:  </B>terrestrial and/or marine areas reserved under
Commonwealth, State or Territory legislation, primarily for nature
conservation purposes.</P><P><B></B></P><P><B>Bioregion:  </B>aterritory
defined by a combination of biological, social and geographic criteria
rather than by geopolitical considerations; generally, a system of
related, interconnected ecosystems.</P><P></P><H2><A NAME="RTFToC126">APPENDIX
D
</A></H2> 
<H2><A NAME="RTFToC127">EDUCATION</A></H2>
<PRE><B>Institution                 Courses available</B>
Charles Sturt               A BAppSc in Ecotourism due to start 1995. Similar to 
University--Albury          the BAppSc in Parks, Recreation and Heritage Management 
NSW                         with new units in ecotourism.
 
Taronga Zoo--               Currently developing a training scheme, the Australian 
Mosman, NSW                 Conservation Training Initiative, for hands-on training 
                            for professionals in the tourism industry, in Australia 
                            and overseas.  The scheme would be managed by the
                            Zoological Parks Board of NSW and supported by the
                            Australian International Development Assistance Bureau 
                            and the NSW National Parks and Wildlife Service.
 
Univerity of                Bachelor Social Science (Recreation and Tourism) has one
Newcastle--Newscatle,       subject called Leisure Tourism and Environmental Issues.
NSW                         Postgraduate research available in ecotourism.

University of               Both postgraduate and undergraduate courses in Leisure
Technology--Sydney,         and Tourism Planning incorporate ecotourism as a topic 
NSW                         and a specialist elective is available.
 
University of NSW--         Bachelor Arts and Science (Faculty of Geography) offers
Sydney, NSW                 the subject Recreation and Tourism, which includes
                            aspects of ecotourism, including a seminar done by the 
                            students on the subject.
 
University of Sydney--      No course work available but a number of postgraduate 
Sydney, NSW                 students in the Department of Geography are working on
                            ecotourism.
 
Deakin University--         Undergraduate and graduate diploma in applied science 
Melbourne, Vic.             have a unit in ecotourism available.  This unit will 
                            also be available for a full fee paying Graduate 
                            Certificate in Ecotourism and as a single subject.
 
Victoria University--       The Degree in Business has three units that deal with
Melbourne, Vic.             ecotourism related issues.  The faculty is working
                            towards a specific ecotourism subject.
 
Bond University--           The Master of Laws (Tourism) includes two subjects,
Gold Coast, Qld             Travel and Tourism Law and Special Topics in Tourism 
                            Law, that include elements of ecotourism.
 
Griffith University--       Postgraduate studies in science and business have some 
Gold Coast, Qld             ecotourism included.  Undergraduate studies in science 
                            and business have a subject, Ecotourism, which covers 
                            environmental management.
 
James Cook University--     Undergraduate Administration and Tourism course has a 
Townsville, Qld             unit called Tourism and the Environment; the graduate
                            diploma has a specialist option, Ecotourism and the
                            Environment.  Also potential for PhD and masters in
                            ecotourism.
 
Cairns TAFE--Cairns,        Currently has a Certificate in Heritage and Interpretive Qld                         Tourism going for accreditation; this should be 
                            available for part-time study in March 1994 and full-
                            time in mid-1994.  A Diploma in Heritage and 
                            Interpretive Tourism is to be ready for accreditation in                             mid-1994.  The current Tour Guide course will be able to
                            convert over to the certificate.
 
SA TAFE                     The Adelaide campus has a Diploma in Tourism Studies 
                            which offers a core subject called Cultural and
                            Environmental Tourism and electives: Ecology and the 
                            Australian Environment, Coastal and Marine Tourism and 
                            Arid Lands Tourism.  Cultural and Environmental Tourism 
                            is also available for the certificate and pre-vocational
                            certificate courses on other campuses (Barossa, South 
                            East, Riverland and Whyalla).
 
Aboriginal Community        Certificate in Aboriginal Cultural Instruction/Tourism 
College--Adelaide, SA       is available in Adelaide and may become available in 
                            Port Augusta.  The course is regionally specific and 
                            designed for Aboriginal people who wish to become
                            involved in tourism.
 
University of Canberra      A masters in tourism is in draft form.  It will focus on Canberra, ACT               sustainability of tourism development.

</PRE>
