<!--This file created 96.12.27 5:57 PM by Claris Home Page version 2.0b1--><HTML><HEAD>   <TITLE>MR. NAKED EVIL</TITLE>   <META NAME=GENERATOR CONTENT="Claris Home Page 2.0b1">   <X-SAS-WINDOW TOP=62 BOTTOM=713 LEFT=105 RIGHT=854></HEAD><BODY TEXT="#124599" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"><P><IMGSRC="/Bald%20Eagle/Desktop%20Folder/tnet%20project/Asssorted%20Theft/home_welcome.gif%20copy"WIDTH=365 HEIGHT=33 X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeightALIGN=bottom></P><P ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="graphics/SparkyDevil.gif" WIDTH=218HEIGHT=268 ALIGN=bottom></P><P>&nbsp;</P><H1>Hello, I'm Sparky!</H1><H2>Paradise is exacty like where you are right now, only much, muchbetter...</H2><P>I was born in Paisley, Scotland on 16 December 1966. That makes me29.</P><P>I grew up in a small town called Irvine, 30 miles south ofGlasgow. It's on the sea. Scotland is a beautiful country.</P><P>I don't remember my childhood very much. I remember I had aChopper bike. It was cool. One day I fell off on some gravel andscraped my arm. I was never very close to my parents. They are prettyyoung. My father has been sick most of his adult life and doesn'twork. My mother works in an office.</P><P>I went to Strathclyde University when I was 16. I took a five-yearcourse called Manufacturing Sciences and Engineering. I met MaryMcQueen-Molloy (now Mary Devlin), my partner, on my first day atuniversity. We have gone through a lot but we're still together andhaving fun after 13 years. <IMG SRC="SparkyTheBoyGenius.gif"WIDTH=192 HEIGHT=234 X-SAS-UseImageWidth X-SAS-UseImageHeightALIGN=left></P><P>The picture on the left was taken in August 1968. Such a cutie!</P><P>We moved to Glasgow in 1984. Glasgow was undergoing a hugecultural renewal and the spirt of the city was very positive.</P><P>We had to work in the summer as a course requirement. I worked at<A HREF="http://www.linn.co.uk">Linn Products</A>, a famous hi-ficompany and at GEC where everyone in the office stared at the walland I screwed accelerometers into the inside of power stationgenerators. You can feel the power.</P><P>In 1985 I went to Live Aid at Wembley.</P><P>Manufacturing Sciences was too hard so I left after four yearswith an Honours degree in Production Engineering and Management. Ihad the idea I wanted to start a recording studio. I got 11,000poundsas a loan from the bank but we could not find suitable premises. Iknew I had to leave Glasgow to get a decent job.</P><P>I decided to come to Japan because London was too near. I soldsome tape recorders that I got from the university for free and leftwith 400pounds in my pocket. When I went to the bank in Tokyo I had abig problem-half of the notes were Scottish and useless.</P><P>I worked as an English teacher for Time/Life. I was always missingclasses because it's natural for me to stay up late. One day I wentdrinking with my students-they had to carry me home.</P><P>Then I was an editor of financial reports.</P><P>I left that job on Tuesday and was hired on Thursday to be managerof a PC network for East West Consulting. I also did some financialanalysis for them. I left them because they had a policy of takingone day off of your holiday if you were late more that five times inone month. I really did try, but...In that month I worked 17 hoursovertime. I was late a total of 15 minutes. They took one day off. Ileft.</P><P>I was unemployed for four months and getting a bit desperate. Itook the advice of one of my headhunter friends and started callinground companies instead of waiting for letters. Bingo! In 2 weeks Iwas Network Manager for Jardine Fleming Securities. They had about100 Macs which acted as a giant fax machine. The analyst would visita company, write the report into a template, hit the button and itwould be faxed to hundreds of clients around the world.</P><P>I like computing not computers.</P><P>My favourite book is Angel Love by Tadanori Yokoo. His photoshoppaintings are great and it has something special about it. It's agood present 'cos it's in Japanese and English and it only costs&#165;1999!</P><P>I am very optimistic person. I truly believe that anything ispossible. That makes me hard on people sometimes. I also like toanalyse things a lot.</P><P>Around this time I discovered Techno. It's a shame Tokyo clubsdon't play more positive energy dance music. The best</P><P>Simplicity, Reuse of a few core elements and</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>&nbsp;</P><P>I don't drink much and don't like smoking anything. I don't likecoffee.</P><P>In the past I used to like fast, positive energy techno. Now Iprefer slower, more emotional tracks. Emotional Techno? Try RenegadeLegion's "The Weeping Waste'. The best peice of music ever made thatI heard today.</P><P>My contract at Jardine Fleming ran out and I thought I was goingto have to look for another job, but they rehired me as a consultant.I became the world's most highly paid Filemaker Pro programmer. I wasmaking databases for them for 17,000yen ($170) an hour.</P><P>So I only worked a few days in a month. Until they gave me a lotof work at once. Mary had been working at UBS but when her contractfinished, due to the gloomy Tokyo market she had trouble finding ajob. I had money for the first time.</P><P>A few years ago I went back to Scotland to take my motorbike test.My mother's husband decided to have a physical fight with me becauseI was on the phone too long. Local call. My dad found out and blamedme for what happened and disowned me. He apologised later and we talknow. I don't have any contact with Ruth, my sister. She is 24 andlives in England.</P><P>In September 1993 Mary and I started Tokyo Classified with afriend. He had to pull out later. We used our own money which wasn'treally enough. We also started STROBE, a free paper about the TokyoUnderground party scene. We run parties too. They are a lot of fun.We are currently building an internet version of Strobe. It will comeout in the new year.</P><P>I used to play the guitar pretty well, but I gave it up to makeTechno. I have a studio in my apartment. I have not recorded manytracks, but what I have recorded has been well received. I was veryhappy when I heard my track on Tokyo Pirate FM. I used to play itevery few days. I'm not making music at the moment because I don'thave a computer at home and I can't afford to buy one.</P><P><IMG SRC="Wedding.gif" WIDTH=227 HEIGHT=374 X-SAS-UseImageWidthX-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=right></P><P>I only started to work on Tokyo Classified seriously after I cameback from India. At that time I was designing each issue and makingall the ads using Quark XPress. I also designed the companyinformation system (which needs to be updated).</P><P>When we first started we had to go to National Azabu, write downall the ads on the noticeboard and put them in the issue. We had over1000 classifieds in the</P><P>I drive a Steed 400cc motorbike. I live in Bunkyo-ku on the sixthfloor. I like looking out over the city and lying in bed looking atthe sky. I don't like ornamentation so the place is stark. I have nodesire to have children.</P><P>We have been publishing for almost two years. We have seven staffand a leased line. We moved into a big office and need some cactus tomake it more homely.</P><P>We have been working on<A HREF="/tokyoclassified/Default.html">Tokyo Classified</A>, ourinternet classified ads system for a while and just released it tothe public. So far so good. It's hungry for ads so please feed it. Wehave all been working hard and we hope to see rewards in a fewmonths. The big news is that Mary and I got married in September.Sometimes you just have to grab onto something good.</P><P>Things I'd like to do:</P><UL>   <LI>Skydive (well we did this in Hawaii the day after we got   married)      <LI>Buy the ultimate hi-fi and the room to play it in      <LI>Make a good album      <LI>Go to the beach      <LI>Write the book-It's coming along</UL><P>Remember, in the land of the blind the one-eyed man is deaf.</P><P>So now you know...<BR>But maybe I just made it all up.</P><P>Sparky &lt;..&gt;<BR><BR><BR><BR><IMG SRC="SparkyProduct.gif" WIDTH=451 HEIGHT=36 X-SAS-UseImageWidthX-SAS-UseImageHeight ALIGN=bottom></P><P>Copyright Mark Devlin 1997</P><P>Any comments? Send mail to<A HREF="mailto:sparky@crisscross.com">sparky@crisscross.com</A></P></BODY></HTML>
