<html>
<head>
   <title>PMJPS</title>
  
</head>
<body text="#FAAA68" link="#97694F" vlink="#FFFFFF" background="backround3.gif">
<center>
<table BORDER=5 CELLPADDING=0>

<td COLSPAN=18 ALIGN="middle" VALIGN="left">

<IMG border=0  WIDTH=470 HEIGHT=55 ALIGN=middle SRC="pmjs.gif">


</table></center><p>


<font SIZE=-1>This page looks best with Netscape 2.0</font> 
<br></p>

<center><p>
<hr></p></center>
<p><font SIZE=-2>Modified May 30, 1996</font></p>
<h2 align=center>---Welcome to Alex's Home-Page---</h2>

<p>
<hr></p>

<p><font SIZE=+2>What is the <b>Post Modern Juxtaposer's Society</b> (besides just a hokey name)
? I'm hoping that it is as yet undefined, and that it's name will keep it like
that for some time. The name itself should both define it's members and
keep it's members from being truly defined. We are post-modern it that
we accept that we are not simply defined, and do not define ourselves by
one label. We create ourselves from childhood by what we see around us,
and not by just one image, but by several, dozens, hundreds, or perhpas
millions of them. We juxtapose these images one over the other, taking
a bit from each to create ourselves, both our self image and the image
we show others. We recreate ourselves continuously every day. In this recreation,
it appears that we are all a bunch of posers, people who take on new styles,
for whatever reason, that seem strange when contrasted with the styles
that we used to have. Of course, we have all done this to some degree or
another, and not just in the fashion sense, but in a perceptual and philosophical
sense. You are probably not the same as you were at age 5, but are you
still the same person? Is there some core you that remains as the other
aspects of you change? You could say that some people are bigger posers
than others, but I can't help but see everyone as such. Now I ask you,
we ask you, is this wrong? Tell us what you think and believe. </font></p>

<p>
<hr></p>

<p><font SIZE=+2>Actually, I have had a bit of input on this while off-line,
from a very artistic and gothic friend here in Tokyo. She found the whole
idea of taking on new identities, posing in a sense, depressing especially
when it involved anything commercial. Tokyo is an especially commercially
oriented city, and both of us often find ourselves trying to escape this,
but I could point out many instances where we had failed. I then began
to discuss with her how I found it difficult to devote myself to any particular
art form, when it is almost always commercialized. For instance, a Blues
song that was once probably an incredible expression of the artist's life
has now become the theme music for a whiskey commerical. Rolling Stone's
songs sell beer (and the operating system that I use). I cannot help but think that NIN will be used to advertise
chocolate chip cookies someday. What is new, outside, different and original
today is used to sell things tomorrow, or at least the essense of it is
stolen and used. Of course, it is depressing, but I think it is so because
we stake too much of our identities on these external expressions. Does
a particular type of music or art express you or a part of you? Well then,
of course you're going to be upset when you wake up in a few months and
find that a picture that moved you, that touched something in your heart,
is glued to the outside of a roll-on deodorant. I wouldn't mind writing
down my personal answers to these questions here (my own philosophy), but
I don't want to yet. I want more imput from you. The PMJS is a place to
discuss such things, not a church where the answers are given. I doubt
that my answers would satisfy you anyway, since they are just that; mine.
I should say that I am not usually depressed by the posing I see around
me, and for the most part, neither are my close friends. How do you deal
with the modern world (or post-modern, or whatever), or do you even try?
</font></p>

<p>
<hr></p>

<p><font SIZE=+2>Interested at all in my <i><a href="http://www.crisscross.com/users/aleaxndr/biography">biography?</a></i>
</font></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>As I'm writing this, I'm listening to <a href="http://www.realaudio.com/contentp/npr.html ">National
Public Radio</a> which is not that strange except that I'm listening to
it in my apartment in Tokyo, Japan through my new Pentium 166 with 28.8 modem.
  This is a big improvement over my old PowerMac 7100/66 which only had a 14.4 modem
and was falling behind in the new technologies race on the internet.  Don't get me wrong, 
it was very difficult giving up my Mac and its ease of use, but I saw the future (at least
 an immediate future) where I will have to know the Windows operating system.  Anyway, 
I use a program called RealAudio to listen to NPR and it works very well.  I love keeping up
 with the latest news, and this allows me to even while I'm in Japan.  Best of all, it's all free,
 so check it out.
</font></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>So, I'm studying on an exchange program in Tokyo, Japan
at Sophia University and I only have about 2 more months left!  I really can't wait to 
get away from this school and back to UCSD.  Of course, Sophia is not entirely bad (there 
are a couple of exceptionally good teachers of non-Japanese language courses), but I
 came here to learn Japanese and I don't think that their program is very good.  I guess
 that I had just hoped for a lot more...</font></p>


<p>
<hr></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>My older sister lives and works in Portland Oregon. Her
best friend opened an alternative music store a few years back that is very good
. They have a vary large selection of hard to get recordings, and they can special order 
<i>anything.</i>
They are even on the web...<a href="http://www.teleport.com/~ozone/">The
Ozone.</a> </font></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>I think that eventually I'm going to set up a couple of
different pages that will relate to different subjects, like a page for
stories contributed by friends, a page for my own philosophical impressions,
and pages for things I've yet to <b>consider</b>. So, send your ideas to
me, or your stories, and I'll put them on my pages.</font></p>

<p>
<hr></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>Two of my good friends, Travis and James, work at a great
little computer company called PFMagic in San Francisco. I worked there
a bit a long time ago (I painted a wall in one of their offices) but they've
since grown quite a bit. They have a great new program for your computer
that gives you a pet to play with <a href="http://fido.dogz.com/dogz/">Dogz</a>.
The founder of the company, Rob something or other, wrote Demon Attack
and the Atari 2600 version of Missle Command which I loved to play when
I was in the third grade. So check out!</font></p>

<p><font SIZE=+1>This is my new home-page, my first attempt ever at writing
one (I think I'm getting the hang of HTML), and I'm wondering what everyone
thinks of it. Tell me what <b>you</b> think, give me some tips on how I
can improve it, tell me if you can even view in on your browser (I'm using
Netscape 3.0bGold), criticize it and send it all to the E-mail address that
I'm sharring (the others will read my mail, but I will get it eventually)...<b><a href="mailto:aleaxndr@crisscross.com"><i>aleaxndr@crisscross.com</i>
</a></b></font></p>

<center>
<TABLE BORDER=3 CELLPADDING=0><TD COLSPAN=18 ALIGN="middle" VALIGN="left"><A HREF="TheGallery"><IMG border=0 IMG SRC="TheGallery3.gif"></table><p>

<font size=4 align= left><a/>
This is a good friend of mine here in Tokyo.  Her name is Mirei, and she has a page set up by another friend of mine to display some of her art.
<br>
<A HREF="TheGallery"><IMG SRC="Mireiface2.gif" alt= "TheGallery"></A><p>
Also check out Aleaxander's Page<br><A HREF="ThePrecipice"><IMG SRC="Theprecipice2.gif" alt= "ThePrecipice"></A>
</font><br><hr size=2>
<p>
The following picture is an attempt to entice a certain friends to obtain web-browsers by pointing out that their pictures are now on the world wide web.  This picture is now over two years old, it was taken during a summer concert near San Francisco, and I was exploring a new style I called, "Clashing Brazilian Maternity Wear".
<p>
<TABLE BORDER=22 CELLPADDING=0>

<TD COLSPAN=18 ALIGN="middle" VALIGN="left">


