<html>
<A NAME = "GS"><HEAD>
<TITLE>Doug Berger, M.D., Ph.D., Psychiatrist, Psychotherapist in Japan</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODYBGCOLOR=#123456>
<FONT SIZE[S>
<A HREF=http://www.crisscross.com/></A>
<P>


<CENTER><BR><TABLE BORDER="5"><TD><img src="Images/Aso.gif" ALT="Volcanic plain, Aso-Kuju National Park, Kumamoto (Kyushu), Japan." width=450 height="240"@></TD></TABLE></CENTER>

<BR><HW_SUPPLEMENTAL>





<HW_AFFILIATION>

    

</HW_AFFILIATION>

<BR>


<P>

<h2 align=center>About Dr. Berger</A></h2>


<P>

<BR><HW_SUPPLEMENTAL>





<HW_AFFILIATION>

    

</HW_AFFILIATION>

<BR>


<P>
 <ul>            <LI><A HREF=default.html>Return To page 1</A>
@@@<LI><A HREF=bunken.html>Medical Papers</A>            <LI><A HREF="bunken.html#MH">Mental Health Search/Links</A>@@@@<LI><A HREF="bunken.html#PT">Picture index</A>@@@@<LI><A HREF=Page2.html>Click Here For Japanesei{j</A>
        </ul>



</NOBR>





<HW_INSERT>

<HW_TWIS>



<P>

<BR><HW_SUPPLEMENTAL>


    <P>Dr. Berger graduated from the <A HREF="http://www.uconn.edu/">University of Connecticut</A> in 1980 with a double major in biology and pathobiology and a minor in anthropology. He obtained his M.D. from  <A HREF="http://www.nymc.edu/">New York Medical College</A> in 1985. He then completed a 4-year residency in psychiatry at New York Medical College from 1985-89.</P> 
     <P>After residency, Dr. Berger did a one-year fellowship at the <A HREF="http://www.aecom.yu.edu/">Albert Einstein College of Medicine</A> in New York and is currently an Assistant Professor of <A HREF="http://quark.aecom.yu.edu/psychlab/quark.htm">Psychiatry at the Albert Einstein College of Medicine.</A>  Dr. Berger's training included over 5 years of receiving supervision as a psychotherapist. He has had a private practice of psychiatry/psychotherapy since 1989, in addition to seven years of university hospital-based experience in the United States. Dr. Berger is Board Certified in Psychiatry from the <A HREF="http://www.psych.org/med_ed/abpn_sec1.html">American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology.</A></P> 
     <P>Dr. Berger first came to Japan as a medical exchange student in 1985 where he studied psychiatry and neurology at <A HREF="http://mfs.med.u-tokai.ac.jp/medsch.html">Tokai University,</A> and as a researcher in psychiatry also at Tokai in 1988 on a grant from the <A HREF="http://www.ortge.ufl.edu/fyi/v22n19/fyi037.html">Matsumae International Foundation</A>. He has been in Japan now since 1992 as a psychotherapist and psychiatric researcher,  receiving a Ph.D. in Medical Science from <A HREF="http://www.u-tokyo.ac.jp/index.html">Tokyo University</A> in 1994 while on a research grant from the <A HREF="http://www.nih.gov/fic">U.S. National Institutes of Health</A> sponsored by the Japan Society for the Promotion of Science.  He is bilingual in English and Japanese.</P></A>
<P>
Dr. Berger often uses the metaphor of a computer with his patients. Although a computer has a garbage can to throw away unneeded or disturbing documents, humans have no way to permantly rid themselves of emotional waste. Humans can only rearrange their feelings and memories, though they often try to "forget" painful things. One of Dr. Berger's approaches is to help patients rearrange these ideas, memories, and their associated feelings in a better way than they have up to now using  a psychodynamic, object relational, and cognitive-behavioral framework.
<P>
Some other analogies Dr. Berger has noticed between the human mind and computers are: 1.) that there is an "unconscious" behind the screen that is doing things the user can't readily see that sometimes causes glitches;  2.) Programming a computer, or putting in the system software, is like bringing up and educating a child: resultant functioning reflects the initial input;  3.) If your hardware is broken, like in a stroke (actual brain damage), new software (experiences, learning, relationships) will usually not fix the damaged areas easily.  

Some differences between humans and computers is that although they do relate to each other (ie. networks), computers have no feelings, and they don't grow up, play, or romance with each other (not they have told us about yet).


<P>
About being in Japan, most of the problems seen in the foreign community seem to be part of difficulties people have had well before they came to Japan.  Although there are many stressful situations related to being a foreigner in Japan, and these can cause lots of frustration with the Japanese, some people seem to project <I>their own</I> problems onto the Japanese (ie. label them as the cause of their problems). Dr. Berger is now doing a study on expatriate adaptation and has developed the "Expatriate Adaptation Inventory" data base to look at a number of issues on living in Japan. One's stress, perception of stress, and ability to cope with stress are important factors that likely predict one's adaptation to foreign culture. Interest in the culture and language of Japan, and keeping a balance of Japanese and Western friends of both sexes, is of course, important to decrease stress and improve coping. When these fail, it is often important to look into that person's pattern of early relationships when they were growing-up, in addition to a possible biological basis for the problem.


</P>
<hr>




