<html>
<head>
<title>1996-1997 Recruiting</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">
<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>1996-1997<br>Recruiting</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<CENTER><TABLE width=80%>
<TR><TD><A HREF="#Intro">Introduction</A></TD><TD><A HREF="#SAP">Summer Associate Program</A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><A HREF="#H&C">History & Composition</A></TD><TD><A HREF="#PHC">Preferred Hiring Criteria</A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><A HREF="#Practice">Practice</A></TD><TD><A HREF="#EO">Employment Opportunity</A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><A HREF="#AD&T">Associate Development & Training   </A>
</TD><TD><A HREF="#Contact">How to Contact Us</A></TD></TR>
<TR><TD><A HREF="#C&B">Compensation & Benefits</A></TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P><HR><P>
King & Spalding is a growing Firm with on-going employment opportunities. The Firm interviews second year law students in the fall to participate in the summer associate program. In addition, the Firm seeks to hire qualified third year law students and judicial clerks to start at the Firm in the fall of 1997. The Firm is also looking for lateral hires with current needs in the following areas: banking and finance; corporate; product liability; real estate; environmental; public finance; tax; trust and estates; contracting, construction and procurement; and healthcare. <P>
<H3><A NAME="Intro">Introduction</A></H3><P>
King & Spalding is a Firm of over 350 lawyers with its principal office in Atlanta, home of the 1996 Olympic Centennial Games. Over its 110-year life, King & Spalding has enjoyed prosperity and stability rivaled by few other U.S. law Firms. With additional offices in New York, Washington and Houston, King & Spalding is able to offer its lawyers a sophisticated practice of national and international scope, while maintaining a high degree of collegiality and institutional loyalty.<P>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="H&C">History and Composition</A></H3><P>
<P>
King & Spalding was founded on January 1, 1885 by Alex C. King and Jack J. Spalding. Mr. King later became Solicitor General of the United States and a judge on the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit. Judge Griffin B. Bell returned to the Firm in 1979 after having served as Attorney General of the United States and as a judge on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals. Many of the Firm's lawyers have held distinguished positions in the American Bar Association, the State Bar of Georgia (including four presidents), and other professional and civic organizations. The Firm encourages individual lawyers to participate in professional, civic, charitable and pro bono activities of their choice. <P>
The Firm has experienced significant growth over the years as a result of the tremendous growth in Atlanta and the Southeast and our ever-increasing national and international presence. As of September 1996, the Firm has 388 lawyers (219 associates, 141 partners, and 28 lawyers who serve as counsel or senior attorneys to the Firm). Associates come from 36 states, 6 foreign countries and 69 law schools. King & Spalding recruits nationally, and 44 percent of the Firm's associates are from outside the Southeast. 36 new associates joined the Firm in September, 1996. The Firm employs 85 paralegals who assist attorneys in all areas of the Firm's practice.<P>
King & Spalding's Atlanta offices are located at 191 Peachtree Street, a landmark office tower located in the heart of downtown Atlanta. This new building is located within easy walking distance of the hub of MARTA (the City's rapid rail system), Georgia State University and Olympic Centennial Park. King & Spalding is located on the top eleven floors of the building. Our office features state of the art technology, legal support systems and a top-floor lawyer dining room and conference center and will expand to an additional floor in 1997.<P>
The Firm opened a Washington, D.C. office in 1979. The Washington office presently has 64 full-time lawyers with an active practice in the areas of tax, food and drug, governmental affairs, antitrust, litigation, white collar crime, commercial banking, international trade, and environmental law.<P>
In 1990, King & Spalding established a small office in New York which has grown to 40 lawyers practicing in the areas of banking and finance, domestic and international taxation, project finance, workouts, bankruptcies and creditors rights, corporate finance and acquisitions, energy and independent power, real estate, commercial litigation, international transactions and special matters.<P>
King & Spalding opened its office in Houston, Texas in early 1995. The decision to establish an office in Houston resulted from our commitment to serve the needs of our existing clients. The recent growth and diversification of the economy in Houston have created an attractive market for our newest office. Our Houston office presently has 8 full time attorneys concentrating their practice in commercial litigation.<P>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Practice">Practice</A></H3>
<P>
King & Spalding is engaged in the general practice of law and is organized around 23 specific practice areas. These practice areas are identified as follows: antitrust and trade regulation; banking and finance; bankruptcy; commercial litigation; construction and development; corporate; energy and independent power; environmental; food and drug; governmental; healthcare; intellectual property and technology; international; international trade regulation and customs; labor, ERISA and employment law; product liability; project finance; public finance; real estate; special matters; tax/domestic and international; toxic tort; and trust and estates.<P>
In Atlanta and the Southeast, King & Spalding serves a preeminently strong base of clients for which it acts as general or special counsel. These clients include some of the leading Fortune 500 companies in Atlanta, the Southeast and the nation. In the past decade, the Firm has also assumed a steadily expanding role in its representation of many multinational businesses in their affairs both in the United States and internationally. The Firm's dynamic and broad-based client base provides a challenging work experience. The Firm also represents many other clients less known to the general public, including emerging "high-tech" businesses and numerous charitable, educational and healthcare institutions. The Firm's client base is extremely diverse, and no single client or specialized type of practice accounts for a substantial portion of the Firm's practice.<P>
The Firm has served as general counsel to the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Centennial Games, which was charged with the responsibility of organizing and conducting the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta. Three of our partners were part of the "Atlanta nine" that spearheaded the effort to bring the games to Atlanta. The Firm assisted in all aspects of the Games, including legal services relating to the world wide television rights, merchandising and other licensing agreements, sponsorship contracts, site acquisition and leasing, venue construction contracts, trademark issues, etc. <P>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="AD&T">Associate Development and Training</A></H3>
<P>
The Firm expects to hire approximately 50 new associates in 1997, with approximately 40 to be located in Atlanta. Associates are assigned to specific practice areas upon their arrival at the Firm, and every effort is made to accommodate personal preferences and Firm practice needs. For administrative purposes, the Firm is divided into 19 teams, with some teams managing several broad areas of practice. Team leaders are responsible for work load, assignment of new matters and planning for their teams. The Firm conducts an intensive orientation and training program for all new associates shortly following their arrival. <P>
The nature of King & Spalding's practice provides the opportunity for associates to have significant client contact and responsibility early in their career. Many matters involve attorneys from numerous areas of the Firm's practice and require a team effort. <P>King & Spalding enjoys a rich history of community involvement and public service. This widespread, significant involvement of King & Spalding lawyers in community service and public interest activities provides a ready avenue for interested associates to get involved. King & Spalding also supports public interest law internships with NAPIL as a Public Service Challenge Benefactor.  The Firm has also been involved in numerous pro bono matters, including Habitat for Humanity home closings, Saturday Lawyer Program and significant litigation.<P>
<H3><A NAME="C&B">Compensation and Benefits</A></H3><P>
The starting salary for new associates in 1996 is $67,000 in Atlanta and Houston, $72,000 in Washington, D.C. and $82,000 in New York. The Firm advances up to $5,000 of the starting salary in May before the associate begins work. The Firm also provides group life and medical insurance (with two HMO options), dental insurance and disability insurance. The Firm has a maternity leave policy and Pretax Flexible Spending Accounts. Associates may participate in a voluntary 401(k) plan to which the Firm does not contribute, but through which associates can build retirement savings on a tax efficient basis. Associates are eligible to participate in the plan as of the first January 1 or July 1 following completion of one year of service with the Firm. The Firm pays associates' moving expenses, professional fees and dues and continuing legal education expenses.<P>
<H3><A NAME="SAP">Summer Associate Program</A></H3><P>
The Firm plans to employ approximately 65 summer associates for the 1997 program, with approximately 55 in Atlanta. The 1996 summer program included 54 summer associates representing 21 law schools. The summer associate program is important to the Firm's hiring efforts and provides a substantial number of the new associates hired each year. The number of summer associates hired by the Firm is based on the projected needs of the Firm, and the Firm does not hire more summer associates than necessary to meet these projected needs. Therefore, the Firm has a very high offer rate to summer associates, and the percentage of offers made to each summer class has averaged approximately 95% during the last five years. <P>
Summer associates rotate through several of the Firm's practice groups and are encouraged to meet and work with as many lawyers as possible. The Firm assigns an advisor to each summer associate to help ensure that the summer experience is professionally rewarding and enjoyable. The Firm actively encourages summer associates to experience the city and area and to take time to appreciate and enjoy the fine quality of life available in these cities. <P>
For students interested in public service work, King & Spalding has adopted a policy of sponsoring second half public service clerkships for any summer associate who spends the first half of the summer with the Firm and the second half with an approved public interest internship or pro bono activity. During the summer of 1996, nine summer associates took advantage of this program.<P>
The Firm permits students to split their summers with other Firms. The Atlanta office requires that these students spend the first half of the summer at the Firm and stay at least six weeks. In 1996, summer associates received a weekly salary of $1,075 in Atlanta and Houston and $1,250 in Washington.<P>
<H3><A NAME="PHC">Preferred Hiring Criteria</A></H3><P>
Candidates must offer high academic achievement; should have demonstrated the ability to excel in related academic areas such as law review, moot court, etc.; and have established a record of achievement or leadership in extra-curricular activities.<P>
<H3><A NAME="EO">Employment Opportunity</A></H3><P>
The Firm hopes to hire approximately 65 summer associates, with approximately 55 in Atlanta. The summer program is limited to second year law students and third year law students who participate after graduation and prior to starting a judicial clerkship. The Firm also hopes to hire numerous third year law students and judicial clerks to start in the fall of 1997. Therefore, the Firm is interested in interviewing well-qualified applicants for these openings. <P>
King & Spalding is committed to a policy of equal employment opportunity. The Firm will not discriminate in any aspect of its employment practice against any qualified applicant or employee on account of race, color, creed, religion, sex, sexual orientation, national origin, age, disability, marital status, or Vietnam-era or other veteran status.<P>
<HR><H3><A NAME="Contact">How to Contact Us:</A></H3>
<UL>
<LI>If you are interested in a position in <STRONG>Atlanta</STRONG> or <STRONG>Houston</STRONG>, please contact:<P>
<em>Laterals</em> - <A HREF="mailto:rnewton@kslaw.com">rnewton@kslaw.com</A><P>
<em>Summer Associates and New Associates</em> - <A HREF="mailto:pblitch@kslaw.com">pblitch@kslaw.com</A><P>
<LI>If you are interested in a position in <STRONG>New York</STRONG>, please contact: <A HREF="mailto:tgremillion@kslaw.com">tgremillion@kslaw.com</A><P>
<LI>If you are interested in a position in <STRONG>Washington, DC</STRONG>, please contact: <A HREF="mailto:smcmanus@kslaw.com">smcmanus@kslaw.com</A><P>
</UL>

<P>
<CENTER><H4><EM>Thank you for visiting us on the Internet and for your interest in King & Spalding.</EM></H4></CENTER><P>
