<head>
<title>Aircraft Financing Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Aircraft Financing Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding has substantial experience in representing participants in leveraged lease financings for commercial carrier aircraft.  Its clients in these financings have included airline companies, equity participants, debt providers and equipment manufacturers.
<P>
King & Spalding serves as counsel for a large airline in its aircraft financing transactions.  In addition to the traditional sale-leaseback aspects of these transactions, the Firm also has represented the airline in connection with the private placement and public offerings of debt associated with the leveraged leasing transactions.  
<P>
The Firm's Tax Practice represents a large foreign manufacturer of aircrafts in connection with its U.S. aircraft sales and leasing business.  The Firm also represents the company in U.S. tax controversies arising from its aircraft leasing business.
<P>
Another King & Spalding client serves as agent in syndicating short-term bank debt for aircraft leveraged leases.  King & Spalding has represented this client in connection with the syndication of over one billion dollars of short-term debt for aircraft financings.  Some of these financings involved the use of foreign sales corporations.
<P>
The Firm has also served as counsel to large domestic financial companies and institutions in the leveraged leasing of other equipment, including trucks, buses, rolling stock and manufacturing and cogeneration facilities.
<P>
<STRONG>Aircraft Finance Practice Group</STRONG>
<P>
King & Spalding's practice in the area of aircraft financing primarily involves lawyers from the Firm's Corporate Finance, Creditors' Rights and Tax Departments.  Included among the lawyers who have worked extensively in this area are Russell Richards, Philip Theodore and Jeffrey Stein, who are in the Corporate Finance Department; David Epstein and Kathrine McLendon, who are in the Creditors' Rights Department; and Robert Woodward, Jackie Levinson and Sandra Hallmark, who are in the Tax Department.  The transactions are headed by partners in the Corporate Finance Department, namely Russ Richards, Philip Theodore and Jeffrey Stein. 
<P>
<STRONG>Russell B. Richards</STRONG>.  King & Spalding partner Russ Richards has primary responsibility for aircraft transactions.  Mr. Richards' practice focuses on corporate acquisitions, corporate financings and aircraft financings.  His work in the aircraft area has included representation of airlines, equity participants, lenders and underwriters; it has involved both public and private transactions.  Mr. Richards has extensive experience negotiating and drafting all types of legal documentation related to these transactions.  Mr. Richards received a Bachelor of Science degree in accounting, with high honors, from the University of Tennessee in 1971 and passed the National Uniform Examination for Certified Public Accountants.  In 1974, he received a Juris Doctor, with high honors, from Duke University School of Law, where he served as Executive Editor of the <EM>Duke Law Journal.  </EM>Mr. Richards joined King & Spalding in 1974 and was elected partner in 1980. 
<P>
<STRONG>Philip A. Theodore</STRONG>.  Phil Theodore has represented a number of public and private companies in complex financial transactions, including equity and debt offerings, acquisitions and reorganizations.  In addition, Mr. Theodore is one of a team of King & Spalding lawyers representing the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games, Inc. in its financing transactions for the 1996 Summer Olympic Games.  In the area of aircraft financing, Mr. Theodore has principally represented airlines in sale-leaseback transactions.  Mr. Theodore graduated from the University of Tennessee at Chattanooga in 1975.  He received his law degree from the University of Cincinnati in 1978, where he was Editor-in-Chief of the <EM>University of Cincinnati Law Review.  </EM>Mr. Theodore joined King & Spalding in 1981 and was elected partner in 1986.  
<P>
<STRONG>Jeffrey M. Stein</STRONG>.  Jeff Stein has experience in a broad range of finance and securities transactions, particularly in public offerings and aircraft leasing transactions.  In public offerings, Mr. Stein has represented corporate issuers and underwriters in "shelf" registrations of investment-grade debt securities, medium-term note programs, high-yield securities and initial public offerings of common stock.  In the area of aircraft finance, he has represented airlines and lenders in leveraged lease transactions, with both privately placed and publicly offered debt participation.  Mr. Stein attended Yeshiva University (B.A., 1977) and Harvard University Law School (J.D., 1980), and practiced in New York City from 1980 until 1985.  He joined King & Spalding in 1985 and was elected partner in 1988.
<P>
<STRONG>David G. Epstein. </STRONG>David Epstein is a member of the Firm's Bankruptcy Group.  He graduated in 1966 from the University of Texas Law School and received his masters in law from Harvard University in 1969.  He has been involved in bankruptcy law for more than twenty years, both as a law professor and a practicing attorney in Arizona, Texas and Georgia. During his academic career, he taught bankruptcy and related commercial law courses at a number of law schools throughout the country.  He also served as dean of the University of Arkansas and Emory University law schools.  He has written numerous law review articles and books on bankruptcy. His bankruptcy casebook and student text are used by law students around the country.  Since joining King & Spalding in 1989, Mr. Epstein has been involved not only in representing the trustee in a major airlines bankruptcy, but also in working for institutional lenders, asset purchasers, trade creditors, and debtors in business bankruptcy cases and out-of-court restructurings.  
<P>
<STRONG>Kathrine A. McLendon</STRONG>.  Kathrine McLendon is a member of King & Spalding's Bankruptcy and Commercial Litigation Group in New York. She joined the Firm in 1990 and was elected partner in 1991.  Prior to joining King & Spalding, she practiced in the bankruptcy department at Simpson Thacher & Bartlett in New York.  Ms. McLendon has focused her practice on bankruptcy and creditors' rights since 1983, with an emphasis on institutional creditor representation in Chapter 11 reorganizations and out-of-court restructurings.  Particular areas of concentration in her practice include commercial real estate and airlines.  Ms. McLendon is the Vice Chair of the Subcommittee on Bankruptcy Aspects of Business Transactions of the Business Bankruptcy Committee of the ABA Business Law Section.  In addition, she serves as the Chair of the Task Force on Project Finance and Leveraged Leasing.  She is a contributing editor of <EM>Norton Bankruptcy Law & Practice </EM>and lectures frequently on bankruptcy topics.  Ms. McLendon received her undergraduate degree, magna cum laude, from Davidson College in 1977 where she was Phi Beta Kappa. She received her law degree with high honors from the University of North Carolina in 1980 where she was a member of the <EM>North Carolina Law Review </EM>and the Order of the Coif. She is admitted to practice in New York, Georgia and North Carolina.

<P>
<STRONG>Robert G. Woodward.  </STRONG>Bob Woodward is a tax partner in the Atlanta Office of King & Spalding and is responsible for administration of the Firm's Tax Practice.  He joined the Firm in 1975 and was elected partner in 1981.  Mr. Woodward's practice covers a broad range of business tax issues, with particular emphasis on corporate mergers, acquisitions, restructurings and financings.  He also has significant experience in tax issues relating to closely held businesses and their owners and in representing corporations and individuals in a wide variety of federal and state tax controversies.  From 1981 to 1984 Mr. Woodward served in the Office of Tax Legislative Counsel of the United States Treasury Department, first as an Attorney-Adviser, then as Associate Tax Legislative Counsel, and ultimately as Tax Legislative Counsel.  In those positions he was involved in the development of federal tax legislation, regulations and rulings.  Mr. Woodward graduated from Washington and Lee University in 1971 and received his J.D. degree in 1975 from Yale University Law School, where he was an Editor of the <EM>Yale Law Journal.  </EM>He is a member of the Committee on Corporate Tax and the Committee on Capital Recovery and Leasing of the Tax Section of the American Bar Association and serves as a Trustee of the Atlanta Tax Forum.
<P><STRONG>
Jackie S. Levinson.  </STRONG>Jackie Levinson has been a partner with King & Spalding's Washington, D.C. Tax Practice since 1985.  She joined the Firm in 1983.  Ms. Levinson has a wide range of practice experience, including tax controversy work, tax planning involving complex partnership structures, bilateral income tax treaties, U.S. taxation of multinational corporations, financial instruments, leveraged lease transactions, tax indemnification agreements, and unrelated business taxable income for tax-exempt organizations, and tax legislation.  Before joining the Firm, Ms. Levinson served as attorney-advisor, Associate Tax Legislative Counsel, and Deputy Tax Legislative Counsel in the Office of Tax Legislative Counsel under the U.S. Treasury Assistant Secretary for Tax Policy.  She began her career in private practice in New York City.  Ms. Levinson received her undergraduate degree magna cum laude from Vassar College in 1969 and her law degree from Yale University in 1972. 
<P>
<STRONG>Sandra W. Hallmark.  </STRONG>Sandy Hallmark joined King & Spalding's Washington, D.C. office in 1987 and was elected partner in 1993.  Ms. Hallmark's practice covers a broad range of business tax issues, with particular emphasis on the taxation of partnerships. She also has significant experience representing clients in complex partnership and structured financing transactions.  Ms. Hallmark is a co-author of the treatise <EM>Federal Taxation of Partnerships and Partners: Structuring and Drafting Agreements.</EM>  Prior to joining the Firm, Ms. Hallmark served as Attorney-Advisor in the Legislation & Regulations Division of the Internal Revenue Service Office of Chief Counsel.  In that position she assisted in the development of tax regulations, rulings and other tax policy matters. Ms. Hallmark received her undergraduate degree from Brandeis University in 1977.  She received her law degree from the Benjamin N. Cardozo School of Law in 1983 and a Masters of Laws in Taxation from Georgetown University in 1986.
<p>
For more information, contact:<br>
Russ Richards (404) 572-4695<P>
