<head>
<title>Intellectual Property & Technology Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Intellectual Property &amp; Technology Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
The lawyers in the Intellectual Property and Technology ("IPT") Practice Group have broad experience with the acquisition, creation, protection, and licensing of intellectual property rights; the negotiation and implementation of joint venture transactions involving technology rights and the acquisition, merger or creation of technology based companies. This Group also advises clients on the competition and regulatory aspects of mergers and acquisitions, advertising, marketing, and franchising activities; and handles litigation arising out of intellectual property or technology rights.
<P>
<STRONG>Trademark and Copyright</STRONG>.  The Firm's trademark and copyright practice includes representation of clients in acquiring, protecting, and defending proprietary rights. King & Spalding serves as general counsel to the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games, Inc. ("ACOG"), the legal entity organizing the 1996 Summer Olympic Games. The members of the IPT Group have formulated and are directing the worldwide trademark and copyright protection program for the 1996 Games. 
<P>
<STRONG>Intellectual Property & Technology Rights</STRONG>.  King & Spalding has been involved in transactions exploiting intellectual property and technology assets in a wide range of industries, including computer software, telecommunications and biotechnology. Clarence Ridley, coauthor of a treatise on protection of computer software, is a key member of the Group.
<P>
<STRONG>Joint Ventures, Acquisitions</STRONG>.  The Firm is involved in all aspects of corporate law and finance, including the creation, acquisition and merger of technology-based companies and joint ventures. 
<P>
<STRONG>Telecommunications</STRONG>.  King & Spalding has substantial experience in telecommunications transactions. The Firm represents a major telecommunications provider seeking to be awarded cellular licenses in several foreign countries in both its dealings with its local partners and the respective governmental entities. The Firm represented another major telecommunications provider in the acquisition of its interest in a high capacity transatlantic fiber optic cable and in the formation of a worldwide telecommunications marketing alliance.
<P>
<STRONG>Communications Law</STRONG>.  The Firm also represents various broadcast and print media interests in transactions and disputes concerning news access, programming rights, piracy, and libel and privacy claims. Members of the IPT Group represented ACOG in the formation of the Host Broadcasting Organization and in the sale of worldwide television rights for the 1996 Olympic Games.
<P>
<STRONG>Antitrust and Regulatory Issues</STRONG>.  Lawyers in the IPT Group in the Washington office have represented clients before the Federal Communications Commission, the Antitrust Division of the Department of Justice, the U.S. Trade Representative, and the State Department's Bureau of International Communications and Information Policy.
<P>
<STRONG>Litigation</STRONG>.  The IPT Practice includes the litigation of intellectual property disputes involving patents, trademarks, copyrights, trade secrets, and other claims of unfair competition.  Lawyers in this Group have represented corporations in major patent infringement actions both in federal courts and before the U.S. International Trade Commission. Lawyers have handled a wide variety of litigated trademark, trade dress, copyright and product counterfeiting matters. This Group also handles contested opposition and cancellation trademark proceedings before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office.
<P>
The IPT Group includes lawyers with general commercial litigation experience. Due to the increasing importance of intellectual property rights in contracts and business transactions, litigation often includes issues of breach of contract, fraud, misappropriation of trade secrets, and unfair competition. 
<P>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<BR>
Joseph R. Bankoff (404) 572-4796
<P>
<hr>
<p>
