<head>
<title>International Trade Regulation & Customs Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>International Trade Regulation &amp; Customs Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
The International Trade Regulation and Customs Practice Group, headquartered in the Firm's Washington, D.C. office, handles a broad range of international trade regulatory and customs matters.  Lawyers in the Group practice before the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative, the U.S. Department of Commerce, the U.S. International Trade Commission, the U.S. Customs Service, the U.S. Court of International Trade, the Office of Foreign Assets Control, NAFTA binational panels,  and various other governmental and administrative bodies.  The lawyers in this Group have experience in antidumping and countervailing duty cases, GATT, NAFTA, export controls, and other international trade and customs matters.  <p>

King &amp; Spalding's trade lawyers constitute a subsection of the Firm's Litigation Group and have broad experience in civil litigation.  The Group is experienced in handling trade remedy litigation before the U.S. International Trade Commission and the Department of Commerce and in litigating
customs disputes before the U.S. Court of International Trade.<p>

The Group has won antidumping and countervailing duty cases involving imports from Mexico, Japan, Taiwan, Korea, Canada, Venezuela and the People's Republic of China.  For example, in recent years the Group won two antidumping cases on behalf of U.S. cement producers, an industry which had lost antidumping cases in 1976, 1978, 1983 and 1986.  Antidumping duties averaging 58 percent were entered against cement imports from Mexico, and antidumping duties averaging 64 percent were entered against cement imports from Japan.  A third cement antidumping case was successfully resolved by a "suspension agreement," under which Venezuelan cement producers agreed to revise their pricing to eliminate sales at less than fair value.  As a result of these cases, cement imports from Mexico, Japan and Venezuela dropped 84 percent from their 1988 peak to 1994, and the U.S. cement industry is enjoying greater output and higher prices.<p>
<p>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<br>
Joseph W. Dorn (202) 626-5445<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h4>Partners/Counsel in the</b> <b>International Trade Regulation &amp; Customs Practice
Practice:</h4>
<a href="/htm/dorn.htm">Joseph W. Dorn</a><br>
<a href="/htm/mabile.htm">Michael P. Mabile</a><br>
<a href="/htm/mcnerney.htm">Martin M. McNerney</a><br>
