<head>
<title>Investment Fund Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Investment Fund Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding has had extensive experience in representing numerous sponsors and underwriters of both on-shore and off-shore investment funds, including funds offered publicly and privately in the United States to U.S. investors, and funds offered outside the United States to non-U.S. investors. The investment goals of such funds have included investing in venture capital situations, middle-market companies, publicly and privately traded securities portfolios, emerging market debt and equity assets, real estate, and the securities of financially troubled companies. Certain funds have focused on specific industries, such as cable television and theatrical and television film productions. 
<P>
The Firm's fund sponsor clients have included U.S. investment banks and U.S. venture capital fund sponsors/managers, U.S. insurance companies, Dutch real estate and venture capital fund sponsors/managers, German merchant banks and venture capital fund sponsors/managers, a consortium of European venture capitalists and two Kuwaiti merchant banks. The Firm also counsels fund investment advisors.
<P>
As one example of a fund organized by King & Spalding, when two prominent general partners of a New York-based investment banking firm decided to resign their partnerships, form their own merchant bank and establish funds for investment in corporate turnaround situations, they looked to King & Spalding for the legal and tax work involved. Their first fund raised approximately $180 million of capital. As another example, King & Spalding recently represented a Kuwaiti Islamic bank in organizing the bank's first U.S. real estate fund. The fund will operate in accordance with Islamic principles and has invested approximately $50 million thus far. King & Spalding has represented numerous other fund sponsors with regard to proposed funds.
<P>
King & Spalding also has had experience in organizing and representing funds that invest in the debt and equity assets of specific countries and regions. For example, the Firm organized on behalf of a large bank an open-ended fund that invests in Mexican debt instruments. The Firm is currently organizing a $60 to $80 million fund that will invest in Central and Eastern Europe and two funds aimed at investing a total of approximately $150 million in South Africa. Several of such funds will utilize investment guaranties provided by the U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation.
<P>
In representing a fund sponsor, the Firm typically structures and organizes the legal entity that will serve as the fund vehicle, taking into account tax, operational and other considerations. The Firm also consults with the fund sponsor concerning the various business issues involved in establishing the fund, such as devising the management and incentive fees or other compensation to be paid to the fund manager and determining the kind of preference returns, if any, to be paid to fund investors.
<P>
In addition, the Firm typically advises the fund sponsor on legal issues that may arise in connection with the organization and offering of the fund. Such issues usually include determining where to organize the fund vehicle, resolving any U.S. Investment Company Act issues raised by the offering, assuring compliance with U.S. and other securities laws applicable to the offering, dealing with all disclosure and other issues that arise in preparing the prospectus or placement memorandum for the fund, and determining how to minimize the overall tax burden on the fund and its intended investors. To the extent a fund anticipates attracting significant investment by U.S. pension funds, complex ERISA issues may also need to be addressed.
<P>
With respect to cross-border funds in which certain of the fund investors may be situated outside the United States, King & Spalding offers additional services. King & Spalding typically acts as the "lead firm" in coordinating all U.S. and non-U.S. advisors, in preparing the necessary documentation for the fund, in coordinating the offering to a successful closing and in effecting investment and disposition transactions thereafter. Such funds generally are not registered under the U.S. securities laws. Interests in such funds are sold outside the United States without registration pursuant to Regulation S.
<P>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<br>
Bernadette Drankoski (404) 572-4687 or<br>
Isam Salah (212) 556-2140
<p>
<p>
<center>
