<head>
<title>Biotechnology Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Biotechnology Practice</h1>
<P><HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding's lawyers, and particularly those practicing in the Food and Drug, Intellectual Property, and Environmental Practice Areas have substantial experience handling issues unique to the biotechnology industry.
<P>
The Firm's clients in the Food and Drug, Intellectual Property, and Environmental Practice Areas include trade associations and companies of all sizes representing every segment of industry regulated by federal and state governments, including foods, human and veterinary pharmaceuticals, medical devices, industrial and agricultural chemicals, and cosmetics.  The Firm's lawyers handle the full range of regulatory matters, including product approval matters; counseling on compliance with agency requirements; representation before government agencies on enforcement, policy, and rulemaking issues; administrative hearings; debarment actions; litigation, including patent litigation; and legislative matters.
<P>
With its broad regulatory practice, the Firm's Washington, D.C. office has the unique capability to respond to the full range of issues confronting biotechnology companies, and has counseled clients on matters involving the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), the Department of Agriculture (USDA), the Occupational Safety and Health Administration, the National Institutes of Health (NIH), the Federal Trade Commission, the Department of Transportation, the Customs Service, and other governmental agencies in the United States and abroad.
<P>
The Firm's lawyers, several of whom have handled biotech and biotech-related issues as senior officials at federal agencies, are experienced in dealing in particular with FDA, EPA and USDA in securing marketing authorizations for regulated products of biotechnology.  Partners involved in our Biotechnology Practice have written and spoken extensively on the subject of genetic engineering in the United States and abroad, and have extensive experience in risk assessment techniques applied by the major regulatory agencies.  Our experience allows us to provide assistance in all areas to clients who are attempting to move from the regulation phase into the marketplace.
<P>
In addition to genetically engineered pharmaceuticals, enzymes and diagnostics for use in the human health field, regulated products include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>foods and food additives; 
<LI>plants and plant pesticides;
<LI>microbials with diverse applications (e.g., agricultural, industrial, pollution control); and
<LI>veterinary pharmaceuticals.
</UL>

<P>
The Firm also advises clients on the NIH Recombinant DNA Guidelines and other federal provisions related to contained experiments and field trials involving recombinant organisms.
<P>
King & Spalding routinely advises manufacturers, researchers, and trade associations on issues pertaining to product development; access to expert review and consultation; federal, state and international regulatory requirements; submission of appropriate marketing authorization applications; and legislative affairs.  For example, in the area of plants and plant pesticides, King & Spalding attorneys have experience in dealing with USDA officials on Plant Pest Act issues, securing experimental use permits and subsequent registrations and tolerances from EPA on pesticides and plant pesticides, and negotiating with FDA on the array of food adulteration, "GRAS," food additive and labeling issues that accompany the potential marketing of food products of recombinant DNA technology.
<P>
King and Spalding's Food and Drug, Intellectual Property, and Environmental lawyers can draw as necessary on the full resources of the Firm.  King & Spalding has one of the largest Litigation Departments in the country, with substantial experience in product liability and health and safety-related matters, including toxic torts.  The Firm also has well-established groups of lawyers active in the healthcare, patent, trademark, tax, antitrust, real estate, public and commercial financing, and general corporate areas of practice, and does substantial corporate merger and acquisition work.
<P>
The Firm is uniquely qualified to assist start-up and early-development companies in obtaining regulatory approval and financing in order to develop products and services for the marketplace, while at the same time protecting and enhancing their intellectual property rights.
<P>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<BR>
John C. Staton, Jr. (404) 572-4985
<P><center>
