<html>
<head>
<title>Islamic Finance & Investment Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Islamic Finance & Investment Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding lawyers have for a number of years advised on, structured and implemented finance and investment transactions intended to comply with Islamic principles. In recognition of the continued growth of Islamic financial institutions and their specialized legal needs, the Firm has formed a multi-disciplinary group focusing on this emerging practice area.
<P>
The Islamic Finance and Investment Practice Group brings together those lawyers in the Firm whose experience is frequently called on in Islamic transactions, such as banking and finance, corporate, taxation and real estate. The Practice Group also includes an attorney with extensive experience in Islamic financial law. Lawyers in the Practice Group have experience with Islamic banking, finance and investment transactions.  Lawyers in the Practice Group are based in three of the Firm's offices and include: 
<P>
<STRONG>Atlanta</STRONG>:  Corporate partners Don Knight and Jack Capers, real estate partner Scott Arnold and tax partner Suzanne Feese have been instrumental in advising the Firm's Islamic institutional and private clients on the structuring and implementation of their real estate, securities and corporate investments throughout the United States. Mr. Knight is the author of <EM>Structuring Foreign Investment in U.S. Real Estate </EM>(second edition co-authored by Professor Richard Doernberg of the Emory University Law School), which is considered to be the leading treatise on its subject.  Mr. Capers is the administrative head of the Firm's practice in the Middle East and focuses in representing the Firm's non-U.S. clients as to their activities in the United States involving corporate and securities transactions. Mr. Arnold represents clients with respect to transactions involving U.S. real estate, including non-U.S. clients with substantial direct and indirect investments in U.S. real estate. Ms. Feese has significant experience in designing equity, leasing and other financing and investment structures that are U.S. tax efficient and comply with Islamic Shari'a principles.
<P>
<STRONG>New York</STRONG>:  Banking and Finance partner Isam Salah, President of the Arab Bankers Association of North America, has been involved in numerous Islamic banking transactions, representing both Islamic institutions and intermediary banks. Mansoor Khan, most recently a visiting researcher with the joint Harvard Law School/Harvard Business School project on Islamic investment products, has also consulted with various Islamic institutions on the development of such products. Mr. Khan has held a research internship with the legal department of the IMF during which he focused on the modernization of the Pakistani banking system in line with Islamic banking practices.
<P>
<STRONG>Washington, D.C.</STRONG>:  Tax partner Hap Shashy, formerly Chief Counsel of the Internal Revenue Service, has advised on the U.S. tax implications of various Islamic transactions. 
<P>
Most recently, members of the Group have been called on to advise on the development of new investment structures (including a U.S. tax-favored fund for investment in U.S. real estate), investment instruments acceptable to Islamic financial institutions and Islamically-acceptable U.S. real estate financing methods. The Firm's experience with project financing and international financial institutions has also resulted in the Practice Group being called on to develop project financing models that would combine Islamic funding with funding available from Western commercial sources and international financial institutions. 
<P>
For additional information regarding this practice area, contact:<BR>
W. Donald Knight, Jr. (404) 572-4764<BR>
Isam Salah (212) 556-2140<P>
