<HEAD>
<TITLE> Communications Practice</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif">
<P></P>
<H1>Communications Practice</H1></CENTER>
<HR>
<P>King &amp; Spalding has extensive experience representing companies in
communications and communications-related industries, including both carriers
and content providers.  The Firm's lawyers have provided a broad array of
corporate, securities, regulatory and litigation advice to clients engaged in a
range of communications markets, including:
</P>
<UL>
<LI>Broadcast Companies
</LI>
<LI>CATV Companies
</LI>
<LI>Interexchange Companies
</LI>
<LI>Local Exchange Carriers
</LI>
<LI>Communications Equipment Suppliers
</LI>
<LI>Global Network Services Providers
</LI></UL>
<P>The enactment of the Telecommunications Act of 1996 will make the
communications markets increasingly competitive.  As existing market
participants expand to new markets and new ventures and technologies seek to
compete in those markets, King &amp; Spalding can respond to the full range of
legal, regulatory, business and strategic planning issues confronting firms in
the new global communications environment.
</P>
<P>	Lawyers in King &amp; Spalding's Atlanta and Washington, D.C. offices are
experienced at handling a broad range of communications-related issues,
including the representation of communications companies before state and
federal regulatory bodies. One of the Firm's partners is a former Assistant
Chief of the Communications and Finance Section of the Antitrust Department at
the United States Department of Justice.  The Firm's Antitrust Practice, in
particular, is adept at securing the necessary regulatory approvals for the
implementation of communications-related mergers, acquisitions and joint
ventures.  The Firm was recently instrumental in obtaining regulatory clearances
in both the United States and the European Union for the launch of a major
global telecommunications joint venture.
</P>
<P>	King &amp; Spalding's lawyers in the communications area can also draw on
the full resources of the Firm to assist its communications clients with
important tax planning and strategic issues.  For example, King &amp; Spalding
is acknowledged as having one of the preeminent Tax Practices in matters of
partnership taxation.  This capability is valuable to communications clients as
the communications industry responds to regulatory and market changes through
the formation of complex alliances, joint ventures and other partnering
arrangements.  In addition, the Governmental Affairs Group at King &amp;
Spalding closely follows legislative developments in the telecommunications area
and can keep clients apprised of the latest developments, as well as offering
the Firm's communications clients the opportunity to have timely input into the
process.
</P>
<P>	King &amp; Spalding's Litigation Department has substantial experience in
handling complex business, patent and antitrust litigation.  The Firm recently
provided litigation representation to a large telecommunications carrier, and
provided subsequent structuring advice in connection with the proper legal
status and characterization of the client's billing and collection arrangements
to other telecommunications providers serviced by the client.
</P>
<P>	The Firm also has broad experience in representing companies involved in
creating and licensing programming content, and in representing communications
related clients in trademark, intellectual property, marketing, radio and
television broadcast matters and trade regulation.  For example, since 1990, the
Firm has represented the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games, Inc. (&quot;ACOG&quot;),
the organizing committee for the 1996 Summer Olympic Games, and Atlanta
Centennial Olympic Properties, ACOG's marketing joint venture with the United
States Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>For additional information about this practice area, contact:<BR> Joseph R.
Bankoff  (404) 572-4796<BR> Timothy F. Coen  (404) 572-4684<BR> Kevin R.
Sullivan  (202)626-2624
</P>
<H3>A transcipt of a Roundtable discussion on the Telecommunications Act of
1996's appears in the December 1996 issue of Corporate Legal Times. The
Roundtable was held at King &amp; Spalding and was moderated by
<A HREF="/htm/bankoff.htm">Joe Bankoff</A>. </H3>
<HR>
