<html>
<head>
<title>Corporate Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Corporate Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding's Corporate Practice has substantial experience in the complete range of domestic and international corporate transactions, including corporate finance, mergers and acquisitions, and other major corporate matters. The growth of the Firm's transactional practice has been enhanced by the awarding of the 1996 Summer Olympic Games to Atlanta. King & Spalding serves as general counsel to the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games, Inc. (ACOG), the legal entity that has the rights to conduct the 1996 Games. The Firm is representing ACOG in its negotiations with domestic and international businesses involved in the 1996 Olympic Games. 
<P>
Major areas of the Firm's corporate practice are described below:
<P>
<STRONG>Mergers and Acquisitions Practice. </STRONG>The Firm represents clients in a wide range of corporate merger and acquisition matters, including:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>the acquisition and divestiture of public and private companies;
<LI>the representation of management, targets and lenders in corporate buyouts, including "going private" transactions;
<LI>the structuring and formations of strategic joint ventures;
<LI>counseling of companies and their boards of directors in planning for or responding to takeovers (both hostile and friendly); and
<LI>advising financial intermediaries in evaluating and facilitating M&A transactions.
</UL>
<P>
The Firm has extensive experience in structuring, negotiating and completing purchase and sale transactions involving general and limited partnership entities and partnership assets. In addition, the Firm has substantial experience structuring equity and mezzanine investments on behalf of its investor client base.
<P>
Recently the Firm has served as lead outside transaction counsel for a large telecommunications company in its proposed $30 billion merger with a large data processing company; its international joint venture to provide global telecommunications services; and its multi-billion dollar domestic alliance with three leading U.S. cable companies to create an alternative national telephone company and a new national wireless carrier.
<P>
<STRONG>Corporate Finance Practice. </STRONG>King & Spalding for many years has been very active in representing underwriters and issuers nationwide in connection with public offerings of securities, including initial public offerings. Since 1985, the Firm has represented 26 different investment banking firms acting as managing underwriters in offerings involving corporate equity and debt and limited partnership interests. 
<P>
The Firm has represented sponsors and underwriters in numerous partnership offerings, including entities formed to invest in cable television, hotel properties, theatrical television film interests, and securities of distressed issuers.
<P>
<STRONG>Regulated Industry Transactions. </STRONG>The Firm has broad experience in transactions in regulated businesses. King & Spalding represented a large telecommunications company in its acquisition of a 50% interest in a high-capacity trans-Atlantic fiber optic cable; in negotiating the sale of telecommunications capacity to resellers; and in the formation of a worldwide telecommunications marketing alliance. In connection with regulated industry transactions, lawyers in the Firm's Washington office have represented clients before the Federal Communications Commission, the Antitrust Division of the Department of Justice, the U.S. Trade Representative, and the State Department's Bureau of International Communications and Information Policy.
<P>
<STRONG>International Transactions. </STRONG>The Firm's international clients include U.S. companies with international operations, as well as European, Japanese and Middle Eastern businesses and investment entities and Middle Eastern government investment agencies. Since 1985, the Firm has completed more more than 50 acquisition transactions for a large British corporation.
<P>
In 1990, the merger of the New York firm of Kageneck & Witthuhn with King & Spalding significantly enhanced the Firm's capabilities in matters involving both U.S. and German legal and tax issues. King & Spalding represents a substantial number of German industrial companies, financial institutions and high net worth individuals.
<P>
<STRONG>International Investment Funds. </STRONG>King & Spalding has extensive experience in representing sponsors of international investment funds, including funds offered privately to non-U.S. investors for investment in the United States and funds offered privately to U.S. investors for investment outside the United States. Such funds have invested in venture capital situations, leveraged buyouts, publicly and privately traded securities portfolios, and real estate. The Firm's fund sponsor clients have included German merchant banks, Dutch real estate and venture capital fund sponsors and managers, a consortium of European venture capitalists and several Kuwaiti merchant and investment banks, as well as U.S. investment banks.
<P>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<br>
Randolph C. Coley (404) 572-4732<BR>
Michael J. Egan III (404) 572-4753<p>
<hr>
<p>
