<html>
<head>
<title>Product Liability Practice</title>
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Product Liability Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King &amp; Spalding has an active practice dedicated to the defense of personal injury tort
litigation in product liability.  During the past 10 years, tort litigation against
institutional and corporate defendants has steadily escalated in scope and potential
exposure.  As the Firm's corporate clients have required increasingly sophisticated
defenses to personal injury claims, the Firm has participated as statewide, regional, and
national tort counsel to various corporations.  At the same time, the Firm has achieved
cost-effective representation through careful staffing of tort matters, reliance on an
experienced staff of legal assistants, and substantial past experience in discovery and
trial practice.<p>

The Firm has trial experience throughout the country, particularly in the Southeast. 
Because of the volume and widespread geographic distribution of its tort practice, King
&amp; Spalding has developed an extended and useful network of local counsel
throughout the country. Similarly, the Firm has worked with a number
of talented expert witnesses in various areas.  The Firm has taken a leadership role in
coordinating nationwide discovery for its clients and in developing sophisticated
computer-based litigation support systems for tort litigation.<p>

King &amp; Spalding lawyers have also been involved in advocating changes to the tort
law
to redress some of the disadvantages experienced by corporate defendants in litigation. 
King &amp; Spalding lawyers have actively participated in the debate over federal reform
of
the tort laws; former Attorney-General Griffin Bell has testified before Congress on
federal product liability laws, and the Firm's Washington office has counseled with
Georgia lawmakers concerning various product liability and environmental issues. 
Members of the Firm's tort section participated in the drafting and eventual adoption of
a tort reform package in Georgia, and King &amp; Spalding has litigated the
constitutionality of those reform provisions after their passage.  In addition, King &amp;
Spalding is heavily involved in the activities of the Product Liability Advisory Council,
an association of approximately 80 major national corporations formed to submit briefs
as friend of the court on pivotal issues of product liability and environmental law.  The
Firm has authored a number of successful amicus briefs for PLAC, and a King &amp;
Spalding partner currently serves on the Executive Committee of that organization.  As
appellate counsel for PLAC and the Firm's other manufacturer clients, King &amp;
Spalding has been responsible for recent significant developments in the law of attorney-client
privilege and work product, summary judgment, automobile crashworthiness, and
preemption.<p>

The Firm's tort defense lawyers are regular speakers at seminars and symposia on
product liability and environmental issues.  King &amp; Spalding lawyers are members of
the American College of Trial Lawyers, the Product Liability Committee of the Defense
Research Institute, the Product Liability Committee of the Litigation Section of the
American Bar Association, the Georgia Product Liability Committee, the Georgia
Defense Lawyers, and the Product Liability Advisory Council.  The Firm is also a
member of the Industrial Defense Library.<p>

The Firm's Product Liability Practice has included representation of a wide variety of
clients and products, including automotive, pharmaceutical, medical device, tobacco,
heavy equipment, and consumer product manufacturers.  In the medical and
pharmaceutical areas, the group has been assisted by food and drug lawyers in King &amp;
Spalding's Washington office, many of whom worked at the Food &amp; Drug
Administration before coming to the Firm.  King &amp; Spalding's product liability practice
has involved traditional trial and appellate work and, more recently, support of and
participation in methods of alternative dispute resolution, such as arbitration and
mediation.<p>

Examples of King &amp; Spalding's representations in product liability defense
include:<p>

<b>Automotive</b>:  The Firm has represented the largest domestic automobile
manufacturer
for more than 25 years, representing that client statewide in personal injury cases and
serving as regional and/or national counsel in various types of recurring litigation.  King &amp; Spalding also represents most of
the Japanese auto manufacturers on a regional basis and has served as defense counsel
for various European motor vehicle manufacturers.  Because of the substantial volume
of product litigation in the automotive area, King &amp; Spalding's involvement in this
practice means that it regularly litigates product liability questions of first impression
which will have subsequent importance for the Firm's non-automotive clients, including
issues of discovery, confidentiality and protective orders, federal and state civil
procedure, the constitutionality of various punitive damage laws, applicable burdens of
proof, and evidentiary issues such as admissibility of similar incidents, competency and
qualification of experts, the admissibility of state-of-the-art evidence, and affirmative
defenses peculiar to the products area.<p>

<b>Tobacco</b>:  The Firm has participated in the national organization of the smoking and health litigation.  The Firm has managed approximately 45 tobacco cases in Texas and has represented a major client as coordinating counsel amongst the major cigarette manufacturers.  This practice has involved the Firm in examination of significant legal issues related to warnings and preemption.<p>

<b>Drugs and medical devices</b>:  King &amp; Spalding has represented a variety of pharmaceutical and medical device companies with regard to their medical products, devices, and services.  The Firm has represented certain drug companies in responding to regulatory investigations, and has served as defense counsel in civil litigation brought by individual consumers of pharmaceutical products.  The Firm recently represented a national provider of healthcare services in a variety of tort liability cases related to the provision of laboratory services.<p>

<b>Food and beverage companies</b>:  The Firm has provided product liability advice to food and beverage companies on various issues of quality control and regulatory compliance.<p>

<b>Heavy equipment</b>:  King &amp; Spalding has defended manufacturers of heavy
industrial
equipment and earthmoving equipment against claims of personal injury arising out of
the design, manufacture, and/or operation of such products.<p>

<b>Consumer products</b>:  The Firm has counseled manufacturers of consumer products about product liability concerns and state and federal regulation.  The Firm has also developed programs of preventive measures for its clients and has served as defense counsel in suits over the safety of consumer products.<p>

<b>Insurance issues</b>:  Because of the increased exposure posed by products liability,
insurers have subjected existing and proposed insurance coverages to close scrutiny. 
The Firm has provided counsel to its insured clients on issues of coverage, the
insurability of punitive damages, and similar questions.<p>

<b>Issues of attorney-client privilege and work product</b>:  Given the increasing reliance
of
manufacturers on in-house legal staffs to advise design personnel of possible product
liability exposure and to oversee environmental compliance, issues of attorney-client
privilege and work product have arisen with particular frequency.  The group has
accordingly developed expertise in both counseling and litigation involving these areas.<p>

For additional information regarding this practice area, contact:<br>
Robert D. Hays (404) 572-4674<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h4>Partners/Counsel in the Product Liability Practice:</h4>
