<head>
<title>Energy & Independent Power Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Energy & Independent Power Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding's Energy and Independent Power Practice is primarily based in its New York office, but is substantially integrated with practice groups in the Firm's Atlanta, Washington, D.C. and Houston offices due to the interdisciplinary nature of many energy-related matters.
<P>
Despite deregulation in certain areas, most energy transactions still take place within a complex regulatory environment. Increasing the difficulty of these circumstances are state and federal initiatives aimed at restructuring the role of utility companies, and the dynamic stresses of rapidly increasing competition among natural gas and electricity suppliers, utilities and customers.  Clients considering, or engaged in, energy-related transactions require counsel with broad regulatory and technical expertise to identify critical issues and emerging opportunities, and to create viable project solutions in the face of substantial uncertainty.
<P>
The Firm has an extraordinary breadth of energy experience, stemming both from its nationally-renowned practices in project and public finance, and from experienced energy lawyers with distinctive backgrounds. One served as a senior project finance banker in a major U.S. bank.  Two have a total of over 28 years experience representing independent energy producers and large electric consumers, and others have represented gas and electric utilities in regulatory, corporate, and finance matters.
<P>
These skills have been applied successfully across a broad spectrum of undertakings. We have represented project developers and energy-intensive industrial companies in regulatory proceedings in over forty states and before federal agencies, and have advised on project contracts and structures for projects in the U.S., Latin America, Europe and Asia. The Firm has recently completed or is currently engaged in such matters as negotiating the utility buy-out of a power project, establishing the right of inside-the fence generators to backup power, negotiating electric rates and contracts for industrial customers, organizing and representing groups of financial institutions in several precedent-setting federal and state regulatory proceedings, lobbying federal policy makers on PURPA repeal, and advising power marketers on both strategy issues and transactions. 
<P>
In the past year, the Firm has also played major roles in forming a joint venture between a utility subsidiary and a non-utility company to acquire the energy assets of the world's largest integrated brewery and to provide long-term energy services to the brewery and others on a contract basis and, in another matter, assisting an electric utility subsidiary in maximizing its control of several PURPA qualifying facilities. Thus, while King & Spalding continues to maintain a strong traditional Project Finance Practice, the Firm is also at the forefront of newly emerging energy issues.
<P>
For additional information regarding this practice area, contact:<br>
Bernays T. Barclay (212) 556-2180<br>
Erik J. Swenson (212) 556-2234<p>
<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h4>Partners/Counsel in the Energy Practice:</h4>
<a href="/htm/barclay.htm">Bernays T. Barclay</a><br>
<a href="/htm/swenson.htm">Erik J. Swenson</a><p>
