<html>
<head>
<title>Environmental Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Environmental Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding's Environmental Practice lawyers advise, counsel, and litigate on federal, state, and local environmental laws. Our experience in various environmental practice areas is summarized below.
<P>
<STRONG>Superfund</STRONG>. The Firm's superfund experience is reflected in the following descriptions of our role in CERCLA cases. 
<P>
King & Spalding has served as chairperson of Steering Committees at the following CERCLA sites:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Jadco-Hughes, Belmont, North Carolina;
<LI>Yellow Water Road, Baldwin, Florida;
<LI>Ellis Road, Jacksonville, Florida;
<LI>Carolawn Site, Ft. Lawn, South Carolina;
<LI>Chemresol Site, Brunswick, Georgia;
<LI>Mowbray Site, Greenville, Alabama;
<LI>Medley Site, Gaffney, South Carolina;
<LI>Aqua-Tech Site, Greer, South Carolina; and
<LI>Pickettville Road Site, Jacksonville, Florida.
</UL>
<P>
King & Spalding has served as liaison counsel or common counsel for groups of defendants and third-party defendants at the following sites:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Chem-Dyne Site, Hamilton, Ohio;
<LI>Review Avenue Site, Long Island City, New York; and
<LI>Flemington Landfill, Wilmington, North Carolina.
</UL>
<P>
King & Spalding has actively litigated superfund cases in federal courts in Georgia, Florida, North Carolina, South Carolina, Missouri, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, and Tennessee. The Firm has represented individual PRPs in more than 100 sites across the United States.
<P>
This CERCLA work includes claims by EPA, states, cities, and private party cost recovery actions.The CERCLA litigation includes not only settlement but litigation on behalf of individual PRPs, including full trial of a CERCLA case. The primary personnel who would be available to provide representation in CERCLA matters are Chet Tisdale, Patricia Barmeyer, Les Oakes, Kathy Rhyne, and Steve Rahaim. 
<P>
King & Spalding has served as an allocation consultant to formulate an allocation of costs for PRP Groups at ten sites:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Metamora Landfill, Metamora, Michigan;
<LI>Forest Waste Landfill, Genessee County, Michigan;
<LI>Hunt's Disposal Landfill, Caledonia, Wisconsin;
<LI>Blosenski Landfill, Chester County, Pennsylvania;
<LI>East Bethel Landfill, East Bethel, Minnesota;
<LI>Ewan Landfill, Shamong Township, New Jersey;
<LI>Motor Wheel Site, Lansing, Michigan;
<LI>Sharkey Landfill, Pine Brook, New Jersey;
<LI>Muskego Landfill, Muskego, Michigan; and
<LI>Sturgis Wellfield, Sturgis, Michigan.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>RCRA</STRONG>. King & Spalding has significant experience in representing clients with RCRA problems relating to Part B applications, closure problems, corrective action orders, and general issues relating to RCRA, including solid and hazardous waste. The Firm has represented parties in major enforcement cases brought by EPA and by various states and in solid waste litigation involving state permits. The primary personnel involved in handling RCRA matters are Jimmy Kirkland, Les Oakes, and Patricia Barmeyer. Two published RCRA decisions which illustrate the Firm's work in this area are:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>A rulemaking petition on behalf of four porcelain enamel companies which successfully 	 challenged EPA's interpretation of its hazardous waste regulations for spent pickle liquor, 51 Federal Register 19320 (May 28, 1986); and<P>
<LI><P>A successful challenge to EPA and state efforts to extend RCRA jurisdiction to activities which the state, the company, and its local counsel had presumed to be subject to RCRA regulation. In the matter of: Adcom Wire, EPA Environmental Appeals Board, 3 EPA Administrative Law Reporter 255 (1994).
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>Clean Water Act. </STRONG>King & Spalding has represented clients with Clean Water Act problems since the enactment of the 1972 amendments to the Federal Water Pollution Control Act. The Firm has extensive experience in permit negotiations, enforcement proceedings for permit violations, citizens suits, and litigation of NPDES permit terms. The principal lawyers with experience in the Clean Water Act area are Kathy Rhyne, Les Oakes, Jimmy Kirkland, Chet Tisdale and Patricia Barmeyer. 
<P>
<STRONG>Clean Air Act. </STRONG>King & Spalding has represented clients on Clean Air Act questions since the enactment of the Clean Air Act in 1970. This representation has included negotiation of permits for new sources, modifications to existing sources, PSD permits, defense of enforcement proceedings, and citizens suits. Les Oakes and Jimmy Kirkland have significant experience in this area because of their backgrounds as engineers, their work for Georgia EPD in the air section, and their understanding as lawyers of the technical and legal issues associated with the Clean Air Act.
<P>
<STRONG>TSCA and Chemical Regulation. </STRONG>Stan Abramson was EPA's Associate General Counsel for Pesticides and Toxic Substances before joining King & Spalding. He served as EPA's principal legal advisor on regulation of industrial, agricultural, and consumer chemicals, including PCBs, asbestos, DDT, ethylene, dibromide, dioxin, and ethylene oxide. His work at EPA included significant regulatory and enforcement matters. Since joining King & Spalding, he has developed a significant practice in TSCA and chemical regulation issues representing companies and several trade associations.
<P><STRONG>
Risk Assessment. </STRONG>Chemical risk assessment is an area of increasing importance in environmental regulation. King & Spalding has been involved in a number of important risk assessment issues. Kathy Rhyne and Stan Abramson have significant experience in working with toxicologists, epidemiologists, and statisticians to critique agency risk assessment. Kathy Rhyne has prepared comments on health and risk assessment documents for the American Forest Products Association and for a number of manufacturers. She has extensive experience in risk assessment issues relating to chemicals in Clean Water Act, CERCLA, and OSHA proceedings. Stan Abramson serves on the Neurotoxicity Advisory Board for the Office of Technology Assessment. He has worked extensively in the areas of chemical risk and food safety.
<P>
<STRONG>OSHA Proceedings. </STRONG>Kathy Rhyne has significant experience in occupational safety and health matters including regulatory proceedings and litigation regarding standards for hazardous chemicals and compliance advice under chemical specific standards. 
<P>
<P>
For additional information regarding this practice, contact:<BR>
Charles H. Tisdale, Jr. (404) 572-4820<BR>
Katherine L. Rhyne (202) 626-3743
<p><hr>
<h4>Partners/Counsel in the Environmental Practice:</h4>
<a href="/htm/tisdale.htm">Charles H. Tisdale, Jr.</a><br>
<a href="/htm/barmeyer.htm">Patricia T. Barmeyer</a><br>
<a href="/htm/abramson.htm">Stanley H. Abramson</a><br>
<a href="/htm/rhyne.htm">Katherine L. Rhyne</a><br>
<a href="/htm/oakes.htm">Les Oakes</a><br>
<a href="/htm/shaw.htm">Harold M. Shaw</a><br>
<a href="/htm/kirkland.htm">Jimmy F. Kirkland</a><p>
<p>
<center>
<HR>
