<HEAD>
<TITLE>Food &amp; Drug Practice</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif">
<P></P>
<H1>Food &amp; Drug Practice</H1>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>The Food and Drug Practice Group of King &amp; Spalding consists of thirteen
lawyers, all practicing in the Washington office.  They handle FDA-related
matters, including counseling on compliance with FDA requirements; product
approval matters; representation before the agency on enforcement, policy and
rulemaking issues; administrative hearings; federal court litigation; and
legislative matters. The Group also handles issues involving biotechnology,
controlled substances, pesticides, meat and poultry inspection, and other
related issues before the Drug Enforcement Administration, the Environmental
Protection Agency, the Federal Trade Commission, and the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.</P>
<P>The Firm's current clients include trade associations and companies
representing all segments of industry regulated by the FDA. These include foods,
human and veterinary pharmaceuticals, medical devices, and cosmetics.</P>
<P>Before joining King &amp; Spalding, Ed Basile, Gene Pfeifer, Jess Stribling,
Fred Degnan, and Mark Brown all served in the Chief Counsel's Office of the Food
&amp; Drug Administration for a collective period of time of over 40 years.
Dvorah Richman, Tony Howard, Sandra Kalter, Jill Klein, Elizabeth Schmidtlein,
Holly Dolbey, and Elaine Tseng  bring additional diversified backgrounds to the
practice.</P>
<P>Mike Taylor recently rejoined King &amp; Spalding after five years in public
service as Deputy Commissioner for Policy of the Food and Drug Administration
(1991-1994) and as Administrator at the Food Safety and Inspection Service at
the U. S. Department of Agriculture (1994-1996). During most of his tenure at
USDA, Mr. Taylor also served as Acting Under Secretary for Food Safety.  </P>
<P>The statutory scheme for regulation of food, drugs, cosmetics, and medical
devices is complex and evolving. Between 1980 and 1994, Congress enacted 31
distinct laws enlarging, and often complicating, FDA's responsibilities in these
areas. King &amp; Spalding lawyers have been actively involved in the
legislative process.  Gene Pfeifer helped draft the legislation regarding
generic human drugs. Jess Stribling did the same for generic animal drugs. Fred
Degnan helped draft the legislation regarding infant formulas. Ed Basile and
Dvorah Richman are recognized authorities in interpreting the most recent
amendments to FDA's authority over medical devices.</P>
<P>The Food and Drug lawyers utilize the services of several practice areas
within the Firm. These include a large litigation practice with substantial
experience in product liability and health and safety related matters, and
lawyers in the healthcare, legislative, environmental, patent, trademark and
general corporate practices.</P>
<P>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<BR> Edward M.
Basile (202) 626-2903</P>
<HR>
