<head>
<title>Special Matters</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

</HEAD>
<P>
<center>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></a>
<P>
<H1>Special Matters Practice</H1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
The Special Matters Group consists of trial lawyers experienced and knowledgeable in criminal and civil investigations. The Group was formed in part as a result of King & Spalding's participation in two public internal corporate investigations, E.F. Hutton and Exxon Valdez, which demonstrated the Firm's ability to respond rapidly and effectively to major catastrophic corporate events. Those investigations, led by former United States Attorney General Griffin B. Bell, established the Firm as a leader in corporate internal investigations and related litigation. The Special Matters Group has since been involved in numerous internal investigations for a host of companies, small and large, ranging from confidential investigations to investigations involving high-profile matters of public interest.
<P>
The volume of work and number of lawyers involved in an internal investigation vary based on the confidentiality and scope of the representation. Whether the matter is a short-term, confidential investigation handled by one lawyer, or an extensive analysis involving matters of public interest, internal corporate investigations and related criminal and civil litigation require the highest degree of care and sensitivity. These investigations are generally performed for a corporate board of directors, the outside directors or for the Chief Executive Officer, although they may be performed for an independent committee of the board of directors or after a shareholder derivative suit has been filed. The primary objectives in these matters are to assess responsibility, defend against any charges and structure creative solutions to the problems which give rise to the investigations. Examples of issues that may be confronted in connection with such an investigation are:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>the manner in which the investigation is conducted;
<LI>who conducts it;
<LI>evidentiary issues involving the attorney-client privilege and the attorney work product doctrine;
<LI>testimony before a state or federal grand jury or Congressional committee;
<LI>dealing with governmental agencies in connection with regulatory investigations;
<LI>evaluation of legal issues such as antitrust, RICO, the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, the possible criminalization of unintentional negligence, and other regulatory laws involving government procurement fraud and securities violations;
<LI>evaluation of possible vicarious liability of a corporate parent for acts of one of its employees or of an employee of a wholly-owned subsidiary;
<LI>considerations relating to presentations to government officials to avoid prosecution;
<LI>negotiating with government officials concerning criminal charges and civil fraud claims; and
<LI>preparing trial defenses while conducting the internal investigation.

</OL>
<P>
In addition to conducting internal investigations, the Special Matters Group defends corporations and individuals in a wide variety of criminal, Congressional or regulatory investigations. Corporations and corporate officers facing a broad spectrum of charges or related shareholder derivative litigation have retained Special Matters lawyers, who have also represented businesses that have been victimized by dishonest employees, vendors or others. The Group also assists in legal audits and counsels preventive law, such as advice about compliance programs and systems that monitor corporate and individual conduct. The Group frequently has assisted corporations and individuals in avoiding prosecution through compliance efforts and early investigative steps followed by presentations to the government.
<P>
Government regulatory investigations are on the rise and Special Matters lawyers frequently will join forces with lawyers in the Firm's substantive regulatory practice areas, including FDA, Environmental, Healthcare and Antitrust. Critical to this area of practice is the ability to respond rapidly to corporate crises, precipitated by any of a wide variety of events, including civil suits, whistleblower complaints and sudden government investigations accompanied by the execution of search warrants and/or the issuance of subpoenas. The Group has the expertise to handle matters from their inception through trial and appellate phases if necessary.
<P>
The Special Matters Group includes: former U.S. Attorney General Griffin B. Bell; former Independent Counsel of the HUD investigation and U.S. Attorney Larry D. Thompson; former Department of Justice Chief of the Criminal Fraud Section William C. Hendricks, III; former Acting U.S. Attorney Stephen S. Cowen; former Deputy Independent Counsel of the Whitewater Investigation William S. Duffey, Jr.; and former Assistant U.S. Attorney and U.S. Senate Special Counsel J. Sedwick Sollers III.
<P>
For further information about this practice area, contact:<BR>
Larry D. Thompson (404) 572-3431<p>
<hr>
<p>
