<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Government Contracts Practice</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<H1>Government Contracts Practice</H1><P>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>
King & Spalding's Government Contracts Practice has developed a very substantial base of experience in federal and state procurements involving information technology.  Depending on the expertise required,  we often assign attorneys from the Intellectual Property and Technology, Civil Litigation, and Special Matters Practice Groups to assist with government contracts matters.  These attorneys work under the leadership of our experienced government contracts practitioners.  This team approach has proven to be cost-effective for our clients especially in large, complex matters and has given us a substantial surge capacity.  Some representative government contracts matters are described below.
<P>
<STRONG>Contract Formation.  </STRONG>King & Spalding assisted a major computer systems integrator in the negotiation of a $150 million contract with the New York City Police Department for the design and implementation of two new E911 public safety answering centers for the City of New York.  King & Spalding also assisted this client with the negotiation of the subcontracts for this project.  The negotiations leading to the prime contract and subcontracts took place in New York City over a four month period.  King & Spalding continues to be part of the client's E911 project team.  We have also counseled clients competing for major government contract awards in preparing proposals and negotiating with the government.  We have negotiated with federal and state procurement officials on behalf of our clients.  
<P>
<STRONG>Bid Protests.  </STRONG>King & Spalding has represented clients in protests involving the award of federal government contracts.  Two of these protests were filed with the General Accounting Office.  The other protest involved computer resources and was filed with the General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals.  The clients had been selected for award but were forced to intervene when protests were filed by unsuccessful bidders.  We successfully defended both awards.  King & Spalding also filed a bid protest with the State of Maryland on behalf of a major computers systems integrator which facilitated resolution of a related contract dispute.
<P>
<STRONG>Contract Disputes.  </STRONG>King & Spalding has represented clients in disputes involving government contracts at both the federal and state levels.  We currently represent a client in a subcontractor claim following the termination of an equipment lease by the General Services Administration for the convenience of the government.  The client had financed computer based publishing equipment that had been installed in government sites in Atlanta and Fort Worth.  We currently represent a major oil company in a dispute over the price of crude oil that it provided to the Defense Fuel Supply Center for the U.S. strategic petroleum reserve.  The matter is pending before the Armed Services Board of Contract Appeals.  King & Spalding successfully represented a major computer systems integrator in a dispute with the State of Maryland involving the implementation of a statewide information system to determine welfare eligibility and entitlements.   Also, we recently successfully resolved a claim against the State of Oregon arising out of a software development contract. 
<P>
<STRONG>Special Matters.  </STRONG>Government contract compliance issues have been an important part of King & Spalding's Government Contracts Practice.  We have represented several clients in federal suspension and debarment proceedings.  In one matter, we negotiated a two-year compliance agreement with the Department of the Navy, in lieu of debarment, after the client pleaded guilty to one count of making a false official statement in connection with a Navy charter party contract during Operation Desert Shield/Desert Storm.  In another matter, we were successful in persuading the Environmental Protection Agency not to proceed with suspension or debarment because the client had taken sufficient corrective actions following a serious environmental violation.  We represented a major healthcare client in the defense of a <EM>qui tam </EM>action brought by a former employee.  We have conducted internal investigations for several major defense contractors in response to allegations of wrong doing or noncompliance by employees in connection with the companies' government contracts and have assisted clients in making voluntary disclosures to the government.  
<P>
<STRONG>Counseling.  </STRONG>Besides the matters discussed above, King & Spalding has counseled clients on other government contracts in a variety of issues involving contract performance and compliance with government cost accounting issues.   
<P>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center></BODY>
