<html>
<head>
<title>Governmental Practice</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Governmental Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
King & Spalding's Governmental Practice Group offers effective advocacy before legislative and executive branch decision makers.  The Group consists of two lawyers, Ted Hester and Bill Talmadge, and three non-lawyer legislative specialists, Dean Mitchell, Allison Dowd and Lakon Holloway.  All worked on Capitol Hill earlier in their careers and have maintained their working relationships with Congress.  The Group has substantial experience working with various executive branch agencies, and understands the political implications that accompany government work.  The Governmental Practice Group is supplemented by the extensive resources of King & Spalding which include former Attorney General Griffin Bell and other lawyers throughout the Firm who have held various positions in governmental departments and agencies. 
<P>
<STRONG>Congressional Investigations</STRONG>.  Congressional committees occasionally develop interests in matters that involve our clients, usually because of the committees' oversight responsibilities for executive departments or agencies that regulate or contract with our clients.  Frequently, the committees will ask to review confidential or proprietary information or information that is the subject of pending litigation.  Protecting a defendant's proprietary information and litigation posture while balancing the impact of negative publicity can be a real challenge.  The Governmental Group has represented a number of clients in connection with congressional investigations.  
<P>
<STRONG>Legislative Representation and Governmental Intervention</STRONG>.  The Governmental Group regularly represents clients before Congress, executive departments and independent agencies.  When feasible, the Governmental Group prefers to establish a continuing relationship with clients in order to take advantage of evolving opportunities and to deflect emerging problems.  The Group is able to efficiently monitor relevant legislative and regulatory developments from a client's perspective by utilizing its non-lawyer legislative specialists.  
<P>
The Governmental Group has been involved in a wide range of legislative and regulatory activities for the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games ("ACOG").  Remarkably, ACOG is a primary beneficiary of two freestanding bills that have been enacted into law with the Governmental Group leading the effort.  In 1992, Congress passed the Atlanta Centennial Olympic Commemorative Coin Act which will raise significant revenues to help defray the cost of the Olympic Games.  In 1994, Congress passed a bill providing for duty free entry of goods that will be brought into the United States for the Olympic Games and similar events.  The Governmental Group also has coordinated efforts for ACOG on various authorization and appropriations bills that have led to funding for security measures and buses that will be provided during the Games.  Additionally, the Governmental Group has worked directly with the White House and executive agencies to coordinate a variety of Olympic issues, one current example being negotiations with the Department of State to expedite the entry of participants in the Games into the United States.

<P>A Firm client who belongs to several trade associations has elected to have the Governmental Group monitor the Congressional Committees that have jurisdiction over mental health and substance abuse issues.  The Governmental Group is representing its interest in having mental health benefits included in any nationally guaranteed benefits package that may be enacted as part of health care reform. Another Firm client has retained our Governmental Group on an ongoing basis as consultants on defense authorization and appropriations issues.
<P>
The Governmental Group is working with King & Spalding's International Trade Group to represent a coalition of cement companies in connection with the formulation of implementing legislation for the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs.
<P>
A Georgia based Chamber of Commerce hired the Governmental Group to represent the community's interest when a local Marine Corps Depot appeared on the Base Closure Commission's list of military bases that might be closed or realigned.  Working closely with Congress and directly with the Base Closure Commission and its staff, the Governmental Group prepared and presented the case for maintaining the present capacity at the Marine Depot.  The Base Closure Commission adopted that position.
<P>
<STRONG>Federal Election/Government Ethics Laws.  </STRONG>The Governmental Group advises on questions relating to the federal election laws and action committees.  Since a major legislative goal of the 103rd Congress and the Clinton Administration is to reform the lobbying laws and current PAC reporting requirements, the Governmental Group has been following the reform bills as they move through the legislative process.  It is expected that if reform legislation is enacted, the Governmental Group will counsel clients on changes in the law and guide them in their compliance efforts.
<P>
For additional information about this practice area, contact:<br>
Theodore M. Hester (202) 626-2901<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h4>Partners/Counsel in the Governmental Affairs Practice:</h4>
<a href="/htm/hester.htm">Theodore M. Hester</a><br>
<a href="/htm/talmadge.htm">William C. Talmadge</a><p>
<p>
