<head>
<title>Trusts & Estates Practice</title>
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 6.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<center><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<h1>Trusts &amp; Estates Practice</h1>
<HR><p>
</center>
<p>
Since its founding in 1885, King &amp; Spalding has placed major emphasis on serving as counselor to families in Georgia and the Southeast regarding the transfer of wealth.  Firm lawyers have consistently taken a leadership role in estate and trust law and transfer tax developments on the state and national levels.  The Trusts and Estates Practice includes John A. Wallace, past President of the American College of Trust and Estate Counsel and Chairman of the Section of Real Property, Probate and Trust Law of the American Bar Association.<p>

The Trusts and Estates Practice is divided into six general areas:<p>

<b>Estate planning and drafting wills and trusts.  </b>Lawyers advise clients on advantageous estate planning opportunities as they apply within the context of the particular family situation.  The drafting projects are typically quite sophisticated due to the complexity of the estates of many clients.<p>

<b>Estate planning with closely held businesses and significant investment assets.  </b>Lawyers work closely with the Tax, Corporate, and Real Estate Groups to effect tax efficient transfers of closely held business and other special assets.  The Firm's representation of foreign clients, both resident and nonresident, requires the lawyers also to maintain an expertise in the international tax area.<p>

<b>Administration of estates and trusts.  </b>Lawyers advise corporate and individual fiduciaries regarding estate and trust administration, including post-mortem tax advice and return preparation.  The lawyers handle the Firm's representation of a U.S. bank which has the largest personal trust department in the Southeast.<p>

<b>Charitable and exempt organization representation.  </b>Lawyers represent private foundations, universities, hospitals and other charitable organizations of regional and national importance.  In addition, lawyers assist clients with the establishment of private family foundations and other charitable and nonprofit corporations, as well as structuring various types of lifetime and testamentary charitable gifts and bequests.<p>

<b>Tax controversy matters.  </b>Trusts and Estates lawyers frequently represent clients before the Internal Revenue Service and, if necessary, in various state and federal courts, in connection with estate and gift tax audits, and other tax controversies.  Lawyers usually work on these matters in conjunction with the Firm's Litigation attorneys.<p>

<b>Will contest and other court proceedings.  </b>Trusts and Estates lawyers handle will contests and litigation seeking the proper construction of wills and trusts.  They have opportunities to appear before numerous courts and call upon the support of lawyers from the Litigation Practice in the case of contested matters.<p>

For additional information about this practice area, contact: <br>
John A. Wallace (404) 572-4932<p>
<hr>
<p>
<h4>Partners/Counsel in the Trusts &amp; Estates Practice:</h4>
<a href="/htm/wallace.htm">John A. Wallace</a><br>
<a href="/htm/lanier.htm">George H. Lanier</a><br>
<a href="/htm/bokman.htm">David I. Bokman</a><p>
