<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>Stanley H. Abramson</TITLE>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

</HEAD>
<P>
<center>
<img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></a>
<P>
<H3><B>Stanley H. Abramson</B></H3></center>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/abramson.jpg">
<P>
Stan Abramson is a partner in the Environmental and Governmental Affairs Group in King & Spalding's Washington, D.C. office.  Mr. Abramson's practice emphasizes product counseling and chemical regulatory issues under health, safety, and environmental laws such as FIFRA, TSCA, EPCRA, the Food and Drug Act, the OSH Act, and the Hazardous Materials Transportation Act. 
<P>
Mr. Abramson assists clients in obtaining approvals for new agricultural, industrial, and consumer products, including products of modern biotechnology.  He deals with a wide variety of product-related matters, including advertising, labeling, testing, export/import clearances, release and adverse effects reporting, and trade secret protection.  Mr. Abramson represents corporations in federal enforcement actions and assists companies in developing corporate compliance and environmental audit programs.  
<P>
Mr. Abramson works extensively with risk assessment and risk management issues and has led interdisciplinary teams that have successfully defended pesticides, food products, and pharmaceuticals before regulatory agencies and the courts.  He has been particularly active in challenging actions by EPA that have threatened valuable crop protection products under the "zero risk" Delaney Clause.  Mr. Abramson serves as legal counsel to the International Life Sciences Institute on pesticide issues and was a member of the Neurotoxicity Advisory Board of the Office of Technology Assessment. 
<P>
Results obtained in selected recent matters include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Withdrawal of enforcement actions in five EPA regions that sought a total of nearly $5 M for alleged violations of the PCB disposal rules under TSCA.<P>
<P>
<LI>Court-ordered stay of an EPA rule that threatened to significantly erode the market share of a major pesticide product that EPA acknowledged causes no significant risk.<P>
<P>
<LI>Precedent-setting approvals from EPA, FDA, and USDA for genetically-engineered crops that produce their own insecticides.<P>
</UL>
<P>
Mr. Abramson has over 20 years of experience in environmental law and served as the EPA's Associate General Counsel for Pesticides and Toxic Substances from 1982-1988.  He chairs the American Bar Association's subcommittee on the Toxic Substances Control Act and serves as an editor of the Environmental Law Institute's <EM>Law of Environmental Protection.</EM>  He received his law degree from Rutgers University and his engineering degree from Drexel University, and is an associate member of the National Society of Professional Engineers.<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/envir.htm">Environmental Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
<HR>
<p></A>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center>
