<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>Joseph R. Bankoff</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Joseph R. Bankoff</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/bankoff.jpg">

Joe Bankoff is a senior partner with more than 20 years experience in technology and communication disputes and contracts. He currently chairs the Intellectual Property and Technology practice at King & Spalding.
<P>
Mr. Bankoff has significant experience in media and technology matters. He represents both media and rights granting organizations in litigation and contract negotiations. He has handled lawsuits relating to television programming, news access and program content (including ownership, libel and privacy issues). He also represents firms in litigation relating to their software, patents, copyrights, trademarks and distribution channels. He has represented two of the major television networks, and many of the world's largest high-tech manufacturers.
<P>
Mr. Bankoff served as Television Counsel to the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG). In this capacity, he has negotiated the sale and the contracts for the Television Rights for the 1996 Olympic Games in the United States, Canada, Europe, Australia, Latin and South America. He also represented the Sydney Olympic Committee in the sale of the Television Rights for the 2000 Games to NBC.
<P>
In 1992 Mr. Bankoff visited at the Max Planck Institute for Foreign and International Patent, Copyright and Competition Law in Munich, Germany where he focused on the European satellite television directive. He has since successfully represented German broadcasters in US litigation concerning satellite programming in Europe. He has also assisted in the Firm's representation of a large telecommunications company in its European joint venture.
<P>
Mr. Bankoff has played a role in telecommunications public policy. He chaired the Policy Working Group of the Georgia Center for Advanced Telecommunications Technology (GCATT). He helped to draft the 1995 legislation in Georgia that opened local telephone service to competition. He now serves as a member of the Executive Committee of the Federal Communications Bar Association.
<P>
Mr. Bankoff is also a member of the Board of Trustees of the National Institute for Trial Advocacy. He lectures and teaches courses in trial advocacy, television and marketing law. He co-authors the Libel Defense Resource Center summaries on Libel and Privacy law in Georgia and the 11th Circuit. He also chairs the King & Spalding Technology Committee.
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/ipt.htm">Intellectual Property & Technology Practice</A><P>
