<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Edward M. Basile</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Edward M. Basile</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/basile.jpg">
<P>Edward M. Basile is a partner and leads King &amp; Spalding's twelve lawyer
FDA Practice Group.  Mr. Basile has over twenty years of experience interpreting
the laws and regulations of the Food and Drug Administration.</P>
<P>Mr. Basile's current practice includes representing large, medium, and small
medical device, pharmaceutical, and biotechnology companies.  Mr. Basile has
advised these clients on strategies for obtaining FDA approvals of new products
and on compliance issues, including criminal investigations, inspections,
recalls, labeling issues, and proposals to ban or withdraw approval of products.
 Mr. Basile has also represented clients in litigation with FDA.</P>
<P>Representative matters as Lead counsel include:</P>
<UL>
<LI>Completed strategies for start-up and larger companies to obtain expedited
marketing clearance and for maximizing revenues pending approval.  
</LI>
<LI>Serving as national FDA counsel for clients involved in the breast implant
and pedicle screw mass tort litigation and representing these clients in a
variety of related FDA product clearance and compliance issues.  Potential
liability is in the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</LI>
<LI>Assisting groups of manufacturers to obtain reclassification of medical
devices, such as automated differential cell counters, automated blood cell
separators, and cardiopulmonary bypass pumps.  Saved companies involved millions
of dollars by avoiding PMA filings.
</LI>
<LI>Helping companies respond to FDA inspections, warning letters, and criminal
investigations.
</LI>
<LI>Representing HIMA in negotiations on the Safe Medical Devices Act of 1990,
and representing companies before Congressional Committees, including preparing
testimony, responding to Congressional inquiries, and otherwise working with
Congressional Committees.
</LI></UL>
<P>Mr. Basile has published numerous articles on FDA law and is a frequent
lecturer on a variety of FDA law issues for the Food &amp; Drug Law Institute
and other organizations sponsoring educational programs.</P>
<P>Prior to joining King &amp; Spalding, Mr. Basile served as Deputy General
Counsel for the Health Industry Manufacturers Association (HIMA), the primary
trade association for the medical device industry.  At HIMA, Mr. Basile
established himself as one of the nation's leading authorities on the
interpretation of the federal laws governing FDA's regulation of medical
devices.  Mr. Basile also served in the Chief Counsel's Office of FDA from
1975-1985 as Associate Chief Counsel for Drugs &amp; Biologics and Associate
Chief Counsel for Enforcement.  While at FDA, Mr. Basile had extensive
litigation experience, including civil and criminal enforcement cases and major,
complex defensive litigation and advised top agency management on issues of
national importance, such as licensing of AIDS tests, aspirin warnings for Reye
Syndrome, and the marketing status of over-the-counter drugs.</P>
<P>Mr Basile received a B.S. in mechanical engineering from Lafayette College
in 1969 and his law degree in 1972 from the National Law Center, George
Washington University, where he graduated Order of the Coif.</P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/food.htm">Food &amp; Drug Practice</A></P>
