<HEADER>
<TITLE>Herschel M. Bloom</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Herschel M. Bloom</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/bloom.jpg">

Herschel Bloom is a tax partner in the Atlanta office of King & Spalding.
He joined the Firm in 1969 and was elected a partner in 1975.
<P>
His practice concentrates in corporate, partnership and real estate
tax matters.  Mr. Bloom is particularly qualified in the tax law applicable
to real estate investment trusts and life insurance companies, and in
Georgia state tax issues.  He has extensive experience in federal and
state tax controversies, including the defense of criminal tax investigations
by the Internal Revenue Service.
<P>
Mr. Bloom was a faculty member at the Emory Summer Program for Lawyers
(1979-1980), a Guest Lecturer at the University of Virginia Law School
(1979), a Trustee of the Georgia Tax Conference (1980-1984), and currently
serves as a Trustee of the Southern Federal Tax Institute, a position
he has held since 1980.  He is a member of the American Law Institute,
the American College of Tax Counsel, and the Committee on Partnerships
of the Tax Section of the American Bar Association.  He speaks on corporate and partnership tax subjects in seminars sponsored
by the Practising Law Institute and other national seminar programs.
<P>
A graduate of Vanderbilt University (B.A., magna cum laude, 1965),
Mr. Bloom received his law degree from Harvard University Law School
(cum laude, 1968).  He was an Associate Professor of Law at the University
of Mississippi Law School from 1968-1969 and Chairman, Tax Section,
of the Georgia Bar Association, 1979-1980.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/tax.htm">Tax Practice</A><P>
