<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>David I. Bokman</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>David I. Bokman</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/bokman.jpg">

David Bokman is a counsel in King & Spalding's Trusts and Estates Practice and was elected partner effective January 1, 1997. Mr. Bokman worked in the Atlanta office from 1991 to 1994 and rejoined the Firm in June, 1995 after spending eighteen months as a senior tax manager with Arthur Andersen's family wealth planning practice in Charlotte, North Carolina.  He focuses his practice on helping the owners of closely held businesses minimize income, gift and estate taxes while planning for transfers of such businesses to younger generation family members or third parties.  He also assists a broad range of clients with testamentary planning, trust and estate administration, charitable planning and related issues. 
<P>
Representative recent transactions include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Use of limited partnership to leverage tax benefits of a $160 million transfer of public stock to grantor retained annuity trust ("GRAT") for the benefit of children without relinquishing senior generation control.<P>
<LI>$20 million leveraged sale of closely held stock to long-term, generation skipping trusts for children and grandchildren to optimize income and transfer tax consequences of sale of business to third party.<P>
<LI>Restructuring of $200 million estate to maximize surviving spouse's flexibility to coordinate tax planning with creation of new charitable foundation.<P>
<LI>Advice to minority shareholder of $40 million closely held business to help resolve intra-family conflict by restructuring equity ownership of the business.

</UL>
<P>
Mr. Bokman has served as a Vice Chair of the American Bar Association Section of Real Property, Probate and Trust Law, Current Legislation Committee and as a contributing editor to that Section's Probate and Property publication.  He also served as a member of the State of Georgia Fiduciary Law Section's Current Legislation Committee.  He speaks frequently on the practical application of sophisticated planning techniques to owners of closely held businesses.
<P>
Mr. Bokman received his B.A. in economics, summa cum laude, in 1984 from Yale University and earned his J.D. in 1988 from Yale Law School. He also worked as an investment banker for The First Boston Corporation in New York prior to joining King & Spalding.<P>
<A HREF="/menu/trusts.htm">Trusts & Estates Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
<HR>
</center><p><center>
