<HEADER>
<TITLE>Sarah Robinson Borders</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Sarah Robinson Borders</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/borders.jpg">
<P>
Sarah Borders is a partner in King & Spalding's Bankruptcy and Commercial Litigation Group. Ms. Borders' practice focuses on the restructuring of real estate indebtedness and the representation of multi-creditor groups.
<P>
Ms. Borders recently completed the representation of thirty-one lending institutions in the out-of-court restructuring of over $1 billion of indebtedness owed by a large real estate developer. The transaction consolidated the developer's worldwide real estate holdings by converting competing project loans into publicly registered debt and equity in a newly created entity. The restructuring required the unanimous consent of each lender and was the culmination of five years of intense negotiations among the creditors and the various debtors.
<P>
Currently, Ms. Borders is responsible for the representation of a leading lending institution in the restructuring of thirty-eight nonperforming real estate loans totaling $200 million. The loans were purchased as part of a $1 billion portfolio auctioned by the Secretary of Housing and Urban Development.  Ms. Borders has successfully negotiated the consensual restructuring of a substantial portion of the portfolio and continues to prosecute claims in the numerous single asset real estate cases filed by the remainder of the borrowers.
<P>
In 1995, Ms. Borders completed the restructuring of $100 million of indebtedness owed to a Japanese lender and secured by a prominent Atlanta office building. The restructuring was completed under supervision of the bankruptcy court and in a manner calculated to mitigate adverse tax repercussion for the Borrower.
<P>
Ms. Borders also represented the committee of unsecured creditors for a chain of 128 convenience stores. A bankruptcy plan was confirmed, which provided for payment in full of all claims owed to creditors.
<P>
Ms. Borders is native of Louisiana, a 1984 graduate of Louisiana State University, a 1988 graduate of the University of Virginia School of Law and a former law clerk for Judge Henry A. Politz of the U.S. Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals.<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/bankrupt.htm">Bankruptcy & Commercial Litigation Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
