<HEADER>
<TITLE>George Busbee</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>George Busbee</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/busbee.jpg">
<P>
Former Georgia Governor George Busbee is a retired partner at King & Spalding and remains Counsel to the Firm, which he joined in 1983. He is the first Georgia chief executive ever to be elected to two consecutive four-year terms, and made economic development and quality education the hallmarks of his administration.
<P>
In each of the last five years of his terms as governor, Mr. Busbee helped attract new and expanded industrial investment exceeding $1 billion to the state, with particular emphasis on high technology industry, as is evidenced by the establishment of the Advanced Technology Development Center in conjunction with the Georgia Institute of Technology. The major thrust of improvements in Mr. Busbee's last budget as governor was the expansion of high technology training capability in Georgia's 26 vocational-technical schools, with emphasis on micro-mechanics and machine tool skills.
<P>
Mr. Busbee was chosen by his fellow governors to head the Southern Growth Policies Board, a consortium of Southern States aimed at enhancing the region's competitive edge in economic development. His highest honor came in 1980-81 when he was unanimously elected by his fellow governors from throughout the nation and the U.S. Territories as Chairman of the National Governors' Association. Prior to that election, Mr. Busbee served as Chairman of the NGA's Committee on International Trade and Foreign Relations. As chairman of that committee, he was instrumental in helping congressional committees write the Export Administration Act of 1979 and the Trade Procedures Simplification Act of 1980.
<P>
In 1976, Mr. Busbee joined with Mr. Norishige Hasegawa, Chairman of the Sumitomo Chemical Co., Ltd., to promote the founding of the Japan/S.E.U.S. Association. President Carter paid tribute to Mr. Busbee's extensive experience in international trade by naming him to the President's Export Council. He was reappointed to the Council by President Ronald Reagan in 1981 and continued to serve during the Reagan Administration until 1985.
<P>
Mr. Busbee is Past Chairman of the Atlanta Metro Chamber of Commerce, Past Chairman of the Japan-America Society of Georgia and Past President of the Metro Business Forum. He current serves as Chairman of the Steering Committee of Vision 2020 (a long-term planning project of the Atlanta Regional Commission) and is a member of the Boards of Directors of Union Camp Corporation, Delta Air Lines, Inc. and Rose's Stores, Inc. In January 1993, Mr. Busbee was elected to an international technology firm based in Ottawa, Canada known as SHL SystemHouse, Inc.
<P>
A native of Vienna, Georgia, Mr. Busbee attended Abraham Baldwin Agricultural College, Duke University and the University of Georgia. After receiving his law degree from the University of Georgia School of Law, Mr. Busbee moved to Albany, Georgia, where he entered the practice of law.  Mr. Busbee served for 18 years as a member of the Georgia House of Representatives, having been elected in 1956 at the age of 29. In 1967, he was elected as the House's first majority leader, a position he retained until taking the oath of office as Governor in 1975.<P>
<p>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/inter.htm">International Practice</A><P>
