<HEADER>
<TITLE>William A. Clineburg, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>William A. Clineburg, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/clinebur.jpg">

Bill Clineburg has focused his practice on employment litigation since 1973, representing Fortune 100 automotive, chemical, tobacco, computer, oil, textile and retail companies as well as hospitals and colleges in state and federal courts throughout the country. Recent significant lawsuits in which he has been involved include: 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Defending two colleges against the Justice Department's challenges to their male-only admission policies as discriminatory;<P>
<LI>	
<LI>Represented a predominently women's college when State Board of Education recommended closing it;<P>
<LI>Defeated class certification and won trials of  individual claims in plant-wide, across-the-board racial discrimination actions brought by hourly and salaried tobacco workers & automobile manufacturing employees;<P>
<LI>Utilized mediation to settle multi-million dollar sexual harassment claims against Fortune 100 companies;<P>
<LI>Won numerous jury trials in which individuals alleged major corporations discriminated against them;<P>
<LI>Defending temporary services company in a purported nationwide Wage-Hour class action seeking $10 million in overtime pay for technical employees, procedure writers, and trainers;  <P>
<LI>Won summary judgments in ERISA cases involving (a) preemption of plaintiff's state law claims that he was defrauded out of enhanced retirement benefits; and (b) preemption of a state statute seeking to regulate the relationship between pharmacies and employee welfare benefit plans.

</UL>
<P>
Mr. Clineburg is a graduate of Brown University and the University of Georgia School of Law (1970). While in law school, he was an editor of the <EM>Law Review, </EM>helped found and edit the <EM>Georgia Journal of International and Comparative Law, </EM>and was a member of the National Moot Court team. He was a law clerk to Judge Roger Robb on the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit in 1970-71. He joined King & Spalding in 1971, and became a partner in 1977.<P>
<A HREF="/menu/labor.htm">Labor, ERISA & Employment Practice</A><P>
