<HEADER>
<TITLE>Albert H. Conrad, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Albert H. Conrad, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/conrad.jpg">

Chip Conrad is the head of King & Spalding's Banking and Finance Practice Group in Atlanta and concentrates in representing banks and other lending institutions in private debt financings.
<P>
In addition to extensive representation of various bank subsidiaries of a "superregional" U.S. bank holding company, Mr. Conrad has served as the responsible partner at King & Spalding for a large foreign bank and a large domestice financial coporation. He also regularly represents other lender clients of the Firm and serves as the principal outside lawyer for a number of the Firm's corporate clients in major financing transactions.
<P>
Mr. Conrad has lectured on lending-related topics and served
as Chairman of the 1991 Corporate and Banking Law Institute sponsored
by the State Bar of Georgia.  Mr. Conrad has served as Chairman of the
Uniform Commercial Code Committee and Chairman of the Corporate and
Banking Law Section of the State Bar of Georgia.  In 1992, Mr. Conrad
coauthored an article published in the <EM>Mercer Law Review </EM>on proposed
revisions to the Uniform Commercial Code.
<P>
In 1972, he graduated with highest honors from the University of Tennessee,
receiving his undergraduate degree in Industrial Engineering.  He obtained
his law degree from the University of Virginia School of Law (J.D.,
1975), where he served as a member of the editorial board of the <EM>Virginia
Law Review.  </EM>He is a member of the Atlanta Bar Association, the State
Bar of Georgia, and the American Bar Association.
<P>
