<HEAD>
<TITLE>Stephen S. Cowen</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Stephen S. Cowen</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/cowen.jpg">
<P>Steve Cowen joined King &amp; Spalding in 1994 as a partner in the Special
Matters Practice Group.  He practices in the Atlanta office, focusing on white
collar criminal defense, civil fraud litigation and internal corporate
investigations. 
</P>
<P>Formerly the court-appointed U.S. Attorney in Atlanta in 1986, he was First
Assistant and Chief of the Criminal Division in that office from 1983-1986, and
Chief of the Civil Division in 1982.  From 1980-1982, he handled federal
prosecutions in the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Middle District of Florida. 
Prior to that, he was in the Civil Division of the U.S. Attorney's Office for
the District of Columbia, with responsibility for a wide variety of civil
matters on behalf of the Government.  
</P>
<P>Mr. Cowen is a member of the bar in the District of Columbia, Georgia and
Florida.  He is the immediate past chair of the Criminal Litigation Committee of
the American Bar Association's Litigation Section, and has served as a member of
the Practitioner's Advisory Committee to the U.S. Sentencing Commission.  He is
a frequent lecturer on defending criminal and civil fraud allegations, and
conducting corporate investigations. 
</P>
<P>A 1969 graduate with highest honors from Emory University, he received his
J.D., cum laude, in 1972 from Harvard University.</P>
<P></P>
