<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>H. Lane Dennard, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>H. Lane Dennard, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/dennard.jpg">

Lane Dennard has represented both unionized and union-free employers in the field of labor and employment law for almost 25 years. This representation has included successful litigation in a broad range of labor/employment law cases in state and federal courts including arguments in the U.S. Circuit Courts of Appeal and U.S. Supreme Court. During 1994 and 1995, Mr. Dennard served as lead defense counsel in 12 employment law cases including:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>representation of a large Georgia employer in a sexual harassment case brought under federal and state law alleging $20 million dollars in damages. A judgment in favor of the employer was recently affirmed by the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals; and<P>
<LI>representation of a Florida employer sued by the EEOC under Title VII. After trial of the case, judgment was entered for the employer on all claims.
</UL><P>
Mr. Dennard also spends considerable time assisting clients with training and the development of policies designed to achieve legal compliance and avoid litigation. For example, he has been involved with the development and implementation of approximately 10 restructuring/downsizing programs during the past 5 years. He has also been actively involved in alternatives to the litigation of employment and labor cases in court. During 1994 and 1995, Mr. Dennard:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>served as lead counsel in the defense of a major class action alleging racial discrimination by an employer in facilities located throughout the Southeastern United States. This case was recently settled on a basis favorable to the client without protracted litigation or adverse publicity; and<P>
<LI>conciliated a pattern and practice case alleged by the EEOC involving numerous facilities in several states.
</UL>
<P>
Mr. Dennard has recently collaborated with Dr. Herbert Northrup, Professor Emeritus of Management, The Wharton School, in the publication of articles on labor and employment law that have appeared in <EM>The Labor Lawyer,</EM> the <EM>Georgia Law Review</EM> and <EM>The Employee Relations Law Journal</EM>.  In November of 1995, he presented a paper on contingent employment at the National Press Club in Washington. This paper will be published in the Spring 1996 edition of the <EM>Journal of Labor Research</EM>.
<P>
Mr. Dennard graduated from Mercer University in Macon with an A.B. degree in 1966. He served in the Army as a Captain and Company Commander in Vietnam. His decorations include the Silver Star, Air Medal and Purple Heart with Oak Leaf Cluster. Mr. Dennard attended the University of Georgia School of Law where he received the J.D. degree in 1972. After graduation Mr. Dennard practiced with the Ogletree firm and served as managing partner of their Atlanta office. He joined King & Spalding as a partner in 1991.
<P><P>
<A HREF="/menu/labor.htm">Labor, ERISA & Employment Practice</A><P>
