<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Joan L. Dillon</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Joan L. Dillon</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/dillon.jpg">
<P>Joan Dillon has over 30 years experience in the practice of trademark law. 
She is a member of the Firm's Intellectual Property &amp; Technology Practice
Group.  She regularly litigates in the federal courts and before the Trademark
Trial &amp; Appeal Board.  She has led in several successful and reported cases
including <I>Opticians Association v. Independent Opticians</I>, <I>Blue Cross
and Blue Shield Association v. Blue Cross Mutual Clinic</I>, and <I>Swanson v.
Georgetown Collection</I>.</P>
<P>Ms. Dillon's substantial and varied Intellectual Property Practice
experience comes from serving for many years as in-house trademark counsel to
such major international companies as Ralston-Purina Company, United States
Steel and Levi Strauss &amp; Co.  When in San Francisco, with Levi Strauss she
assisted the LAOOC in the protection and maintenance of its Olympic trademarks
and copyright properties.  In Atlanta, she was central in formulating and she
executed the underlying trademark protection program which allowed the Atlanta
Committee for the Olympic Games to so successfully market its intellectual
properties.</P>
<P>` Ms. Dillon is an active member of the trademark bar.  She is presently
Vice-Chair of the International Trademark Association's Public Relations
Committee.  She has served on its select amicus brief committee and in that
capacity was singularly honored to draft INTA's brief amicus in support of L.A.
Gear's petition for certiorari to the U.S. Supreme Court.  She also assisted in
the drafting of INTA's brief amicus in <I>Qualitex v. Jacobsen</I>.  She is a
past member of INTA's Trademark Reporter Advisory Board and has made numerous
presentations before INTA.  She has guest lectured at Washington University
School of Law, Georgia State University and Georgia Tech.  She regularly speaks
to business and trade groups about trademark concerns and has written numerous
articles on trademark law.</P>
<P>Ms. Dillon is a graduate of Washington University School of Business where
she majored in retailing.  Her retailing and marketing education and background
combined with her legal education and corporate experience enables her to
understand and appreciate the timing and financial needs of her clients.  Ms.
Dillon was selected as one of Washington University's School of Law
Distinguished Alumni for 1996 and is a member of the Law School Alumni Executive
Committee.  Ms. Dillon assists some of the largest companies in the United
States in protecting their trademarks. She is also proud to represent numerous
small to mid-size companies in trademark matters. </P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/ipt.htm">Intellectual Property &amp; Technology Practice</A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER></CENTER>
