<HEAD>
<TITLE>Joseph W. Dorn</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Joseph W. Dorn</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/dorn.jpg">
<P>Joe Dorn joined King &amp; Spalding in 1994. He is experienced in
international trade regulation, customs law and complex business litigation.</P>
<P>Mr. Dorn has prosecuted trade remedy actions on behalf of U.S. industries
against imports from Canada, Japan, Taiwan, Korea, Spain, Mexico, Venezuela, the
People's Republic of China, Australia, New Zealand, Portugal, France and other
countries.  He represents a Guatemalan industry in the first antidumping case
ever prosecuted in Central America. He has handled a wide variety of trade
remedy investigations, including antidumping and countervailing duty cases,
escape clause cases under Section 201 of the Trade Act of 1974, unfair methods
of competition cases under Section 337 of the Tariff Act of 1930, agricultural
price support program cases under Section 22 of the Agricultural Adjustment Act
of 1934, and cases to remove duty-free treatment under the Generalized System of
Preferences. He has also petitioned for accelerated elimination of duties under
the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement and the North American Free Trade
Agreement.</P>
<P>Mr. Dorn has served as Chairman of the Subcommittee on Trade and Customs Law
of the International Bar Association, Vice Chairman of the Antitrust and Trade
Law Committee of the International Bar Association, and as Assistant Editor of
the <I>Newsletter</I> of the ITC Trial Lawyers Association. He has also served
as a Special Assistant Attorney General for the States of Georgia, Oregon and
Washington. He is admitted to practice in the District of Columbia and in
Georgia. He has spoken at seminars in Europe, Asia and North America on customs
and trade law issues and has testified before Congressional Committees
concerning international trade legislation.</P>
<P>Mr. Dorn is a 1970 graduate of the University of North Carolina, where he
was a Morehead Scholar and a member of Phi Beta Kappa. He received his law
degree in 1973 from the University of Virginia, where he served on the <I>Virginia
Law Review</I> and was elected to the Order of the Coif.</P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/itrc.htm">International Trade Regulation and Customs
Practice</A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<CENTER></CENTER>
