<HEADER>
<TITLE>Walter W. Driver, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Walter W. Driver, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/driver.jpg">
<p>
Walt Driver is a partner in King & Spalding's Banking and Finance Practice Group. He served as Chairman of the Firm's Policy Committee for the maximum term from 1990-1993.
<P>
Mr. Driver represented over thirty money center banks in structuring, negotiating and closing the restructuring of over $1 billion of liabilities of a large real estate developer and its affiliates. The transaction provided liquidity for creditors by converting competing project loans into publicly registered debt and equity in a newly created entity. The November 1995 closing concluded five years of intense negotiating among the creditors and against the various debtors.
<P>
Mr. Driver has been the principal U.S. lawyer representing a large multi-national bank in one of the largest and most complex bank fraud cases in U.S. history, involving billions of dollars in finance to Iraq. This affair generated high political visibility during the 1992 U.S. presidential campaign and several books have been written on the subject. Through King & Spalding's involvement, officers outside of the rogue Atlanta employees avoided criminal prosecution. Mr. Driver led the client through Congressional committee investigations and hearings, successfully resolved a protracted Federal Reserve inquiry and achieved substantial economic recoveries, including $400 million from the United States government.
<P>
He was responsible for the representation of one of the largest money center banks in connection with its substantial real estate lending portfolio in the Southeast, as well as successfully litigating a case of first impression involving banking fraud and negotiable instrument liabilities.
<P>
Mr. Driver is involved with many aspects of representation of financial institutions, including structured transactions, real estate finance, work-out and bankruptcy and banking investigations. He has advised institutional investors in highly leveraged and tax sensitive transactions, working with King & Spalding's tax lawyers in complex cross-border financings. Mr. Driver represents money center banks, regional banks, international banks and large non-bank financial corporations, and coordinates King & Spaliding's legal work for a number of major financial clients.
<P>
He has chaired the Legal Division of the Atlanta United Way and has served as a member of the Board of Directors and Executive Committees of several civic organizations, including Central Atlanta Progress, Peachtree Golf Club and the Georgia State Golf Association. A graduate of Stanford University and the University of Texas School of Law (1970), he joined King & Spalding in 1970 and became a partner in 1976.
<P><P>
<A HREF="/menu/bankfin.htm">Banking & Finance Practice </A><P>
<p><center>
<HR>
</center><p><center>
</a>
</A></center><P><center><A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center>
