<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>David G. Epstein</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>David G. Epstein</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/epstein.jpg">

David Epstein is a partner in King & Spalding's Bankruptcy and Commercial Litigation Group. He graduated in 1966 from the University of Texas Law School and received his masters in law from the Harvard University in 1969.  He has been involved in bankruptcy law for more than twenty years, both as a law professor and a practicing attorney in Arizona, Texas and Georgia. During his academic career, he taught bankruptcy and related commercial law courses at a number of law schools throughout the country.  He also served as dean of the University of Arkansas and Emory University law schools.  He has written numerous law review articles and books on bankruptcy. His bankruptcy casebook and student text are used by law students around the country.
<P>
Since joining King & Spalding in 1989, Mr. Epstein has been involved in representing the trustee in a major airline's bankruptcy, and in working for institutional lenders, asset purchasers, trade creditors, and debtors in business bankruptcy cases and out-of-court restructurings.  Recent work assignments include representing a publicly held company in its Chapter 11 case, the primary secured creditor of a Denver television station in Chapter 11, a trade creditor on the Official Committee of Creditors in a major airline's bankruptcy case, a North Carolina savings and loan holding company that filed for Chapter 11, the primary trade creditors of a steel company in Chapter 11, the purchasers of the assets from a chemical company bankruptcy in Tennessee, and the Official Committee of Unsecured Creditors in the Chapter 11 case of a multi-state retailer pending in Florida.  Mr. Epstein recently concluded his service as court-appointed examiner in a major Chapter 11 case in Atlanta and as court-appointed representative for a class of future claimants in a major Chapter 11 case in Florida.
<P>
Mr. Epstein continues to fulfill an important role in the development and construction of our bankruptcy laws by lecturing on bankruptcy law at Federal Judicial Center programs for federal district court judges and bankruptcy judges and continuing legal education programs conducted by various state and local bar associations.  He serves as an officer and member of the Executive Committee of the National Bankruptcy Conference, as the Reporter for the National Bankruptcy Conference's Working Group on Executory Contracts, as a member of the editorial board of the <EM>American Bankruptcy Law Journal, </EM>as a member of the Practising Law Institute Bankruptcy Planning Group, as a member of the Board of Directors of the Southeastern Bankruptcy Law Institute, as an elected member of the American College of Bankruptcy Lawyers and the American Law Institute, and as a contributing editor of <EM>Collier on Bankruptcy </EM>and the <EM>Collier Bankruptcy Manual.  </EM>In 1992, Mr. Epstein coauthored a three-volume bankruptcy text for lawyers and judges published by West Publishing Company. 
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/bankrupt.htm">Bankruptcy & Commercial Litigation Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
