<HEADER>
<TITLE>Patricia Ferrari</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Patricia Ferrari</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/ferrari.jpg">

Patricia Ferrari is a partner in the Banking and Finance Practice Group of King & Spalding. Although she resides in the New York office, Ms. Ferrari maintains an active practice in New York as well as the southeast through King & Spalding's Atlanta office.
<P>
Ms. Ferrari represents insurance companies, banks and other financial institutions in a wide variety of transactions, including private placements of debt, syndicated financings, multiple interest rate and currency option loans, asset based loans and factoring, structured financings, interest rate protection products, credit enhancement transactions and debt restructurings. Ms. Ferrari is the client relationship partner for one of the largest insurance companies in the United State, one of the largest banks in the United States, and one of the largest banks in the Netherlands.
<P>
Selected recent transactions include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Representation of insurance company investors in a $150,000,000 private debt placement in Seneca Foods Corporation in connection with the acquisition by Seneca from The Pillsbury Company of canning operations and certain operating plants located in five states.<P>
<LI>Representation of the bank syndicate in several acquisition financings, totaling over $100,000,000, to Castleberry's Food Company in connection with its purchase of certain seafood operations of Borden and meat operations of Smithfield.<P>
<LI>Restructuring and workout of convertible preferred stock and $140,000,000 of debt of a large minerals extraction and processing company, publicly-held and headquartered in Pennsylvania. This matter involved a debt-for-equity swap and senior and subordinated debt secured by mineral rights, real estate and improvements. It also required the structuring of a liquidity facility and resolution of intercreditor issues.<P>
<LI>Structuring and closing a $380,000,000 multi-currency bid rate loan program and liquidity facility for a diversified retail company based in Nashville.

</UL>
<P>
Ms. Ferrari serves as a contributing editor to Banking and Lending Institution Forms (Warren Gorham Lamont). She is a member of the bar associations of the States of New York and Georgia and of the American Bar Association. Additionally, Ms. Ferrari is a fellow of the American College of Investment Counsel.
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/bankfin.htm">Banking & Finance Practice </A><P>
<p><center>
<HR>
</center><p><center>
</a>
