<HEAD>
<TITLE>Harry L. Gutman</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Harry L. Gutman</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/gutman.jpg">
<P>Hank Gutman, formerly Chief of Staff of the Joint Committee on Taxation of
the U.S. Congress, joined King &amp; Spalding in 1994 as a partner in the Firm's
Washington office.  In the position of Joint Committee Chief of Staff from 1991
through 1993, Mr. Gutman was the primary nonpartisan advisor to the House Ways
and Means Committee and the Senate Finance Committee concerning the technical,
economic and revenue aspects of tax legislative matters.  Mr. Gutman has
substantial experience in business tax matters, including income and estate tax
planning for closely held businesses.  He also represents clients in legislative
and administrative matters before the Congress, the Treasury Department and the
Internal Revenue Service.</P>
<P>Mr. Gutman was the Reporter for the American Law Institute
Generation-Skipping Tax Project and for Arden House III, an ALI-ABA Conference
on Continuing Legal Education.  He was also a consultant to the ALI Subchapter J
Income Tax Project.  He has served as Chairman of the Tax Policy Committee of
the ABA Tax Section and has been a member of the Board of Advisors of the
NYU/IRS Continuing Legal Education Program.  He is currently a member of the Tax
Advisory Group of the American Law Institute, the American College of Tax
Counsel and the District of Columbia Bar. </P>
<P>He is the author of articles on a variety of tax subjects and the co-author
of a casebook on wealth transfer taxes.  He has lectured extensively on
substantive and tax legislative matters.</P>
<P>Mr. Gutman received his undergraduate degree from Princeton University and
his law degree at Harvard University.  He also received a B.A. degree from
University College, Oxford, England.  Mr. Gutman served as Deputy Tax
Legislative Counsel at the U.S. Treasury Department during the Carter
administration, where he received the Treasury Exceptional Service Award.  He
was Associate Professor of Law at the University of Virginia from 1980 to 1984
and Professor of Law at the University of Pennsylvania from 1984 to 1989.  Mr.
Gutman, who began his legal career in private practice in Boston, was in private
practice in Philadelphia when he was named as Joint Committee Chief of Staff in
1991.</P>
<P></P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/tax.htm">Tax Practice</A></P>
