<HEAD>
<TITLE>Edward J. Hawie</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Edward J. Hawie</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/hawie.jpg">
<P>Edward Hawie has over 34 years of experience in the corporate and securities
law practice.  With his extensive knowledge of federal and state regulation of
securities, he has represented various underwriters and issuers in connection
with capital raising efforts as well as securities law compliance.  Also, he has
been involved in many business acquisitions and a wide range of corporate
transactions. </P>
<P>Currently, Mr. Hawie is concentrating his efforts on developing the Firm's
Latin American practice, particularly in Argentina and Mexico.  He has spent a
significant amount of time in those countries during the past four years and has
been involved in a number of joint ventures and other transactions there.</P>
<P>He is a director of the John H. Harland Company (NYSE), the second largest
check printer in the country.  He has been a member of King &amp; Spalding's
Policy Committee, is a member of the State Bar of Georgia, and is a former
Chairman of the Bar's Corporate and Banking Section.  Mr. Hawie was a member of
the committee that rewrote the Georgia Corporation Law enacted in 1988 and
chaired the State Bar Corporate Code Revision Committee.  He lectures on a wide
range of corporate and securities laws subjects in various forums.</P>
<P>A 1959 graduate of The Wharton School of Finance and Commerce of the
University of Pennsylvania, he received his law degree <I>magna cum laude</I>
in 1962 from Boston University School of Law, where he was ranked first in his
class.  In 1962, he joined Shearman &amp; Sterling in New York City as an
associate and remained there until 1968 when he became an associate with King &amp;
Spalding.  He was named a partner in 1970.</P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/corp.htm">Corporate Practice</A></P>
