<HEADER>
<TITLE>Bruce N. Hawthorne</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Bruce N. Hawthorne</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/hawthorn.jpg">

Bruce Hawthorne joined King & Spalding in 1975 and was elected partner
in 1982. He has extensive knowledge of the securities laws and broad
experience in corporate and partnership financing transactions, mergers
and acquisitions, and securities offerings.
<P>
In the corporate finance area, he has worked extensively in the representation
of issuers, underwriters and institutional investors in connection with
public offerings and private placements of a wide range of debt and
equity securities.
<P>
In the mergers and acquisitions area, Mr. Hawthorne's recent work has included acting as lead outside transaction counsel for a large telecommunications company in its proposed $30 billion merger with a large data processing company; its international joint venture to provide global telecommunications services; and its multi-billion dollar domestic alliance with three leading U.S. cable companies to create an alternative national telephone company and a new national wireless carrier.
<P>
Mr. Hawthorne attended the University of Michigan (B.B.A., with distinction,
1971), the University of Detroit (M.B.A., 1972) and Vanderbilt University
(J.D., 1975). He was a member of Beta Gamma Sigma, the Order of the
Coif, and Managing Editor of the <EM>Vanderbilt Law Review.</EM>  He is a member
of the State Bar of Georgia, the Atlanta Bar Association and the American
Bar Association.  He is also a member of the Federal Regulation of Securities
Committee of the Corporate Banking and Business Law Section of the American
Bar Association.
<P>
<P>
