<HEADER>
<TITLE>William C. Hendricks III</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>William C. Hendricks III</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/hendrix.jpg">

Since joining King & Spalding in 1989, Bill Hendricks has continued
his practice in all phases of criminal law and criminal fraud.  A partner
in the Special Matters Group, he practices in the Firm's Washington, D.C. office.
<P>
Mr. Hendricks began his career at the United States Department of Justice,
serving as a trial attorney in the Criminal Fraud Section from 1972-77.  He served as Assistant United States Attorney for the District
of Maryland from 1977-1978.  Returning to the Justice Department in
1980, he served as Deputy Chief of the Public Integrity Section from
1980 until 1987.  He received the John Marshall Award for Outstanding
Legal Achievement in Litigation in the Justice Department in 1986.
<P>
Mr. Hendricks was Chief, Criminal Fraud Section of the United States Justice Department from 1987 until 1989 when he joined King & Spalding. During that period, Mr. Hendricks was also the Executive Director of the Attorney General's Economic Crime Council. 
<P>
During his career in public service, Mr. Hendricks obtained  experience
in the investigation, prosecution and trial of numerous criminal matters
involving political, corporate, judicial and governmental misconduct.
His cases included the investigation and prosecution of EPA Assistant
Administrator Rita M. LaVelle for perjury in 1983; the investigation
and successful prosecution of United States District Judge Harry Claiborne
in 1984; and the establishment of the Dallas Bank Fraud Task Force to
prosecute financial institution fraud cases, resulting in more than
50 convictions.
<P>
Mr. Hendricks graduated from the University of North Carolina in 1966 and received his J.D., cum laude, from George Washington University in 1971.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/special.htm">Special Matters Practice</A><P>
