<TITLE>William E. Hoffmann, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>William E. Hoffmann, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/hoffmann.jpg">

William Hoffmann has practiced law in Atlanta since 1978 and has been a partner at King & Spalding since 1985.  As a member of the Litigation and Healthcare Practice Groups, he represents healthcare providers and other corporations in a variety of cases, including commercial disputes, personal injury litigation and proceedings before
administrative agencies.
<P>
Mr. Hoffmann has lectured at programs of the National Health Lawyers Association, and served on the ethics committee and the publications committee of that organization.  He is the author of the chapter on Treatment of Mental Health Patients in the <EM>Clark Boardman Treatise on Health Law Practice </EM>and coauthor of the chapter on Patient Information and Confidentiality in the <EM>Matthew Bender Treatise on Health Law, </EM>as well as author of other publications relating to healthcare litigation.
<P>
A native of Savannah, Georgia, Mr. Hoffmann has a B.A. degree from
the College of William and Mary, M.A. and Ph.D. degrees from the University
of Georgia and his J.D. degree from the College of William and Mary
where he graduated first in his class and was Editor-in-Chief of the<EM>
William and Mary Law Review.</EM>  Upon graduation from law school, Mr. Hoffmann
served as law clerk to the Honorable Francis L. Van Dusen of the United
States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit in Philadelphia.  Prior
to attending law school, Mr. Hoffmann was Assistant Professor of Philosophy
and Assistant Dean of the School of Humanities and Sciences at Ithaca
College in Ithaca, New York.
<P>
<P>
