<HEADER>
<TITLE>Frank C. Jones</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Frank C. Jones</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/jonesf.jpg">

After practicing law in Macon, GA for a number of years, Frank Jones joined King & Spalding as a partner in 1977. He served as Chairman of the Management Committee in 1983-1984, as Chairman of the Policy Committee in 1988-1990, and as the Coordinator of the Litigation Group in 1991-1992.
<P>
The focus of Mr. Jones' practice is commercial litigation, and he has represented numerous clients of the Firm in complex cases in state and federal courts, both in Georgia and in other parts of the country. 
<P>
He has been actively involved in the Georgia Bar and related professional organizations, serving as President of the State Bar of Georgia, 1968-1969, and as President of the Younger Lawyers Section, Georgia Bar Association, 1956-1957. For 22 years (1972-1994) he served as a member of the ABA House of Delegates and was on the ABA's Federal Judiciary Committee from 1977-1982. He was inducted into the American College of Trial Lawyers in 1971, became a Regent in 1986, and was President in 1993-94. He is also a Fellow of the American Academy of Appellate Lawyers and the American Bar Foundation.
<P>
Mr. Jones has also been active in civic, community and charitable undertakings. Currently he is Chairman of the Georgia Public Telecommunications Commission, which has responsibility for public television and radio in the state, and the Michael C. Carlos Museum (formerly the Emory University Museum of Art and Archaeology). At different times in recent years he has chaired the Great Park Authority, the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra League and the Metropolitan Atlanta Chapter of the American Red Cross. He is a Trustee of Emory University; The Carter Center, Inc.; and Wesleyan College, Macon, Georgia; and is on the Board of Directors of The Commerce Club. He is a Vice President and Trustee of the Supreme Court Historical Society, Washington, D.C.
<P>
Mr. Jones graduated from Emory University in 1947 and from the Mercer University Law School in 1950.<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/comlit.htm">Commercial Litigation Practice</A><P>
