<HEADER>
<TITLE>Mark A. Kuller</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Mark A. Kuller</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/kuller.jpg">

Mark Kuller is a tax partner in King & Spalding's Washington, D.C. office.  Mr. Kuller earned his B.S. degree (Finance) from New York University, cum laude, in 1975 and graduated from the U.C.L.A. School of Law in 1978.  Since joining King & Spalding in 1986, Mr. Kuller has concentrated in partnership taxation, corporate taxation, the taxation of financial instruments, and tax controversy
matters.
<P>
From 1984 to 1986, Mr. Kuller served as Special Assistant to the Chief
Counsel, Internal Revenue Service.  From 1982 to 1984, Mr. Kuller served
as Attorney-Advisor in the Treasury Department's Office of Tax Legislative
Counsel.  In those positions he assisted in numerous tax policy matters,
including the Treasury Department's recommendations for the Economic
Recovery Tax Act of 1982, the Deficit Reduction Act of 1984, and the
Tax Reform Act of 1986.  He also participated in the drafting of a number
of regulations and rulings involving partnerships, tax shelters, and
financial transactions.
<P>
Mr. Kuller is a coauthor of the treatise <EM>Federal Taxation of Partnerships
and Partners: Structuring and Drafting Agreements </EM>and a coauthor of
the treatise <EM>Federal Taxation of Debt Instruments.  </EM>Mr. Kuller was an
adjunct professor at Georgetown University Law Center from 1983 through
1989.  He lectures frequently throughout the country on partnership
tax matters and other tax topics.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/tax.htm">Tax Practice</A><P>
