<HEADER>
<TITLE>Nolan C. Leake</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Nolan C. Leake</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/leake.jpg">

Nolan Leake is a partner concentrating in complex civil litigation and toxic tort matters. He joined King & Spalding in 1973 and was elected a partner in 1979.
<P>
Mr. Leake has broad litigation experience in civil lawsuits, administrative
proceedings and arbitrations.  He has been lead counsel in major trials
in federal and state courts throughout the Southeast.  His practice
has concentrated on class actions, civil RICO, creditor liability, toxic
tort, tax, shareholder, insurance and other complex or multi-district
civil litigation.  At present, he acts as regional counsel for a large credit company, and oversees major tort litigation for one of the nation's largest food service companies on a national basis.
<P>
Mr. Leake is a member of the litigation and tax sections of the American
Bar, State Bar of Georgia and Atlanta Bar Associations.  He has published
the following articles: "Procedures and Problems in Georgia Ad Valorem
Tax Appeals" (<EM>Georgia State Bar Journal</EM>, 1990) and "Valuation of Computer Hardware for State and Local Taxation" (<EM>Georgia Tax Alert</EM>, 1993) and has lectured on cross-examination of expert witnesses and on litigation problems arising from state and local taxation.
<P>
Mr. Leake graduated cum laude from the University of the South in 1968,
where he was Phi Beta Kappa, and he received his law degree cum laude
from New York University Law School in 1971 where he was Editor-in-Chief
of the <EM>New York University Law Review </EM>and was elected to the Order of
the Coif.  From 1971 to 1973, Mr. Leake served as a captain in the United
States Air Force and was a Deputy Assistant to the General Counsel of
the United States Air Force in Washington, D.C.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/toxic.htm">Toxic Tort Practice</A><P>
