<HEADER>
<TITLE>Deborah M. Lerner</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Deborah M. Lerner</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/lerner.jpg">

<P>
Deborah Lerner is counsel to King & Spalding in the Washington, D.C. office,
practicing in the areas of civil and criminal litigation and antitrust.
She joined the Firm in 1995.
<P>
Ms. Lerner has had substantial experience in complex federal and state
civil litigation matters in a variety of areas, including antitrust,
franchising, intellectual property, contract, first amendment, and various
federal and state statutes, the False Claims Act, the Petroleum Marketing
Practice Act, and the Freedom of Information Act.
<P>
Before entering private practice in 1986, she served as a law clerk
to Chief Judge William C. Pryor of the District of Columbia Court of
Appeals. While in law school, she clerked in the United States Attorney's
office for the District of Columbia.  She has been a voting member of
the District of Columbia Judicial Conference since 1987, and is a member
of the American Bar Association and the Women's Bar Association.
<P>
Ms. Lerner has written in the area of civil practice, including co
authoring articles for <EM>Litigation </EM>magazine and the <EM>New York Law Journal.</EM>
She has spoken at programs addressing civil practice issues, including
a 1993 ALI-ABA course on "Civil Practice and Litigation Techniques in
the Federal Courts."  Ms. Lerner also has participated in a number of
National Institute for Trial Advocacy programs.
<P>
Ms. Lerner received her bachelor's degree, magna cum laude, in 1980 from
Barnard College and a J.D., with honors, from George Washington University,
where she was Managing Editor of the George Washington University Law
Review.  She is a member of The District of Columbia Bar and the New
York State Bar.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/anti.htm">Antitrust Practice </A><P>
