<HEADER>
<TITLE>Michael P. Mabile</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Michael P. Mabile</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/mabile.jpg">
<P>
Mike Mabile joined King & Spalding in 1994. He is a member of the Steering Group of the International Trade Committee of the International Law Section of the American Bar Association and has spoken before the Judicial Conference of the U.S. Court of International Trade and in ABA-sponsored seminars on advocacy in international trade law.
<P>
From 1987 to 1990, Mr. Mabile served on the staff of the U.S. Senate
Committee on Finance, where he was International Trade Counsel.  In
that capacity he participated in legislative activities leading to passage
of the Omnibus Trade and Competitiveness Act of 1988, the U.S.-Canada
Free Trade Agreement Implementation Act of 1988, and other trade and
customs legislation.
<P>
From 1980 to the beginning of 1987, Mr. Mabile served in the Office
of General Counsel of the U.S. International Trade Commission.  There,
he held the positions of Acting General Counsel and Assistant General
Counsel for Litigation.  In the latter post, which he held for three
years, he was responsible for all appeals challenging Commission decisions
and other litigation on behalf of the Commission.  He began his service
with the Commission as a staff attorney responsible for a variety of
trade remedy matters, including antidumping and countervailing duty
investigations and investigations of alleged infringement of patents,
trademarks and copyrights under Section 337 of the Tariff Act of 1990.
<P>
Mr. Mabile is admitted to practice in the District of Columbia and
in Florida.  He is a 1977 graduate of Florida State University's College
of Law, from which he graduated with high honors.  He also received
his bachelor's degree from Florida State University in 1973.  While
in law school, Mr. Mabile served as Articles Editor of the <EM>Florida State
University Law Review.  </EM>Immediately after law school, he was a law clerk
to U.S. District Judge William H. Stafford, Jr., in Tallahassee, Florida.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/itrc.htm">International Trade Regulation and Customs Practice</A><P>
