<HEADER>
<TITLE>James Dabney Miller</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>James Dabney Miller</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/millerj.jpg">

James Miller concentrates his practice on civil litigation in the Firm's Washington, D.C. office.  He joined King & Spalding in 1976 and was elected a partner in 1983.  His law degree is from Yale Law School (1975), where he was an editor of <EM>The Yale Law Journal.</EM>
<P>
Mr. Miller's practice focuses on medical devices, pharmaceuticals, chemicals, and medical research issues. His work in 1995 included:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The conclusion of a patent-related case against one of the Firm's European clients involving a complex chemical process.  Mr. Miller prevailed in the trial of this case in late 1994, and in 1996 the losing party dismissed its appeal as a result of a 'global' settlement Mr. Miller negotiated.</UL><P>
<UL>
<LI>The successful trial of an unfair competition case in federal court involving a genetically-engineered new animal drug.<P>
<LI>The settlement of a class action involving the use of a radiopharmaceutical in medical research. The Firm's client, a medical research foundation, was the defendant in this class action.  The federal court recently approved the settlement.  Mr. Miller also successfully represented this client in litigation against its insurers in connection with this class action.
</UL>
Mr. Miller has experience using the unfair competition laws to protect clients from violations of the Food, Drug & Cosmetic Act by their competitors and others.  Mr. Miller is currently defending three important radiation-related wrongful death cases in federal court in California.
<P>
Mr. Miller successfully argued the leading appeals court case on the Freedom of Information Act, <EM>Critical Mass v. NRC, </EM>975 F.2d 871 (D.C. Cir. 1992) (<EM>en banc</EM>), <EM>cert. denied</EM>, 507 U.S. 984 (1993).  He is the author of <EM>Joint & Several Liability, </EM>in State Civil Justice Reform 17 (Clegg ed. 1994).<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/comlit.htm">Commercial Litigation Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
