<TITLE>Paul B. Murphy</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Paul B. Murphy</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/murphy.jpg">

Since joining King & Spalding in 1988, Paul Murphy has been part of
the Firm's Litigation Practice.  His practice focuses on white collar
criminal and civil litigation, including grand jury investigations and
internal corporate investigations, antitrust, and RICO.  He was elected
partner in 1995.
<P>
His experience has involved a wide range of civil and criminal matters
for clients as varied as government contractors, healthcare providers
and financial institutions.  Mr. Murphy has co-authored articles on
white-collar crime for The Institute for Continuing Legal Education,
The District of Columbia Bar, and the South Carolina Bar.
<P>
Currently, Mr. Murphy is a member of the State Bar of Georgia, the
Atlanta Bar Association, and the American Bar Association, in which
he belongs to the Sections on Litigation and on Criminal Justice.  He
is an alumnus barrister of the Joseph Henry Lumpkin American Inn of
Court.
<P>
In 1985, Mr. Murphy received his B.A., magna cum laude, from Vanderbilt
University and, in 1988, earned his J.D., magna cum laude, from the University
of Georgia, where he was a member of the editorial board (1986-1987)
and the Research Editor (1987-1988) for the <EM>Georgia Law Review.  </EM>Mr.
Murphy is a member of Phi Beta Kappa and the Order of the Coif.
<P>
