<HEADER>
<TITLE>James A. Pardo, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>James A. Pardo, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/pardo.jpg">
Jim Pardo is the administrative head of the Firm's Bankruptcy and Commercial Litigation Group. Mr. Pardo joined King & Spalding as an associate in 1980 and was admitted to the partnership in 1986.
<P>
His practice focuses primarily on the representation of secured and unsecured creditors in both bankruptcy cases and out-of-court debt restructurings. He occasionally represents debtors (particularly with regard to their pre-bankruptcy concerns). Mr. Pardo often serves as special counsel in appeals involving significant issues of bankruptcy law.
<P>
Mr. Pardo lectures on bankruptcy and commercial litigation topics before bar groups and in continuing legal education programs. He is a former contributing editor of <EM>Collier on Bankruptcy </EM>and of the <EM>Collier Bankruptcy Manual</EM>. He is a member of the American Bankruptcy Institute, a director of the Southeastern Bankruptcy Law Institute, and a past Chairman of the Bankruptcy Section of the State Bar of Georgia. During 1992, Mr. Pardo was a visiting Lecturer in Law at the University of Virginia School of Law, where he taught an advanced business reorganization course, and in 1995 served as an adjunct Professor of Law at the Emory University Law School.
<P>
A Phi Beta Kappa graduate of the University of Virginia, Mr. Pardo received his B.A. with honors in economics in 1975 and his J.D. in 1979. During law school he served as Managing Editor of the <EM>Virginia Law Review </EM>and was elected to membership in the Order of the Coif. Subsequent to law school and prior to joining King & Spalding, Mr. Pardo served as a visiting foreign lawyer in London, England, and as law clerk to the Hon. Judge Charles Clark on the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/bankrupt.htm">Bankruptcy & Commercial Litigation Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
<HR>
