<HEADER>
<TITLE>Eugene C. Partain</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Eugene C. Partain</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/partain.jpg">

Gene Partain joined King & Spalding in 1991 and practices in the Toxic Tort Practice Group. He has a national practice covering a broad spectrum of litigation. He was lead counsel in the successful trial defense of
two major dioxin exposure jury trials (one of which was listed in the
November, 1989 issue of the <EM>American Bar Association Journal </EM>as one
of the biggest defense wins in a special article on the subject, the
other listed in a separate <EM>National Law Journal </EM>article on the five
most significant defense wins of 1990) and led the litigation team that
successfully defended a major airline against pilots' age discrimination
claims. 
<P>
In addition to product liability, environmental and toxic tort litigation,
and employer/employee relations cases, he has successfully defended
diverse clients in a variety of complex cases, including professional
liability, general commercial litigation, personal injury, defamation,
and intellectual property and arbitration proceedings.
<P>
Mr.  Partain was one of 10 of the country's leading
litigators on the faculty at CLE International's 1992 and 1993 Advanced
Trial Techniques seminars.  He is listed as one of 33 leading trial
lawyers illustrating methodologies in the 1993 Prentice Hall book, <EM>Jury
Persuasion: Psychological Strategies and Trial Techniques.  </EM>He also
has spoken on a number of litigation topics, including toxic tort litigation
and product liability, as well as discovery and trial advocacy techniques
at Emory University and the University of Georgia law schools, and at
various local, state, and national bar association seminars and programs.
<P>
Mr.  Partain has written articles on the defense of chemical manufacturers,
the liability of hospitals, courtroom access and the fairness doctrine,
and the use of broadcast media in congressional, legislative, and quasi
judicial proceedings.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/toxic.htm">Toxic Tort Practice</A><P>
