<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>Katherine L. Rhyne</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Katherine L. Rhyne</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/rhyne.jpg">
<P>
Kathy Rhyne heads King & Spalding's Environmental Practice Group in Washington. Her practice focuses on issues relating to the Clean Water Act, Superfund, occupational health and safety, and chemical risk assessment issues under all the environmental statutes or in toxic tort litigation.
<P>
Ms. Rhyne has successfully defended EPA and OSHA enforcement actions and citizens' suits, including the first appellate case to establish the requirement of continuing violations in citizens' suits.  She has negotiated NPDES permits for facilities in over a dozen states.
<P>
Ms. Rhyne has a flair for presenting technical information in a comprehensible fashion to regulators, judges and juries.  She has applied this knowledge: 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>preparing expert witnesses for jury trials in dioxin and pesticide cases;<P>
<P>
<LI>persuading a number of Southeastern states to reject EPA's recommended water quality  standard of dioxin;<P>
<P>
<LI>persuading EPA to stay its listing of hydrogen sulfide and methyl mercaptan on the Toxic Release Inventory;<P>
<P>
<LI>addressing human health and ecological risk assessments as well as other technical and legal issues at Superfund sites;<P>
<P>
<LI>litigating OSHA standards on formaldehyde, wood dust, welding fumes, and chloroform; and<P>
<P>
<LI>advising clients on significant risk reporting, chemical labeling, Hazard Communication and other OSHA standards, NIOSH health hazard evaluations, and MACT rulemakings.

</UL>
<P>
Ms. Rhyne graduated Phi Beta Kappa from the University of Virginia, where she received both her undergraduate and law degrees.<P>
<A HREF="/menu/envir.htm">Environmental Practice</A><P>
<p><center>
<HR>
</center><p><center>
