<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Clarence H. Ridley</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/ridley.jpg">
<P>Clancy Ridley is a partner in the Atlanta office of King &amp; Spalding and
is Chairman of the Firm's Policy Committee. His practice focuses upon domestic
and international transactions involving technology-based businesses, including
the formation of technology ventures, technology marketing alliances, technology
licensing transactions, and merger and acquisition transactions.</P>
<P>He is a co-author of <I>Computer Software Agreements: Forms and Commentary,</I>
published in 1987 by Warren, Gorham &amp; Lamont, and supplemented semiannually
thereafter and now being published in its Second Edition. He is a regular
lecturer on technology law matters.</P>
<P>Mr. Ridley earned his undergraduate degree at Yale University and an M.B.A.
from Harvard University Business School. After service as an Army officer in
Korea, he attended the University of Virginia Law School, finishing there in
1971. He served on the Editorial Board and then as Executive Editor of the <I>Virginia
Law Review</I>. </P>
