<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Charles M. Shaffer, Jr.</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Charles M. Shaffer, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10" SRC="/gif/shaffer.jpg">
<P>Charlie Shaffer joined King &amp; Spalding in 1967 and was elected partner
in 1974. He has served as Chair of the Litigation Department at King &amp;
Spalding for the past four years.</P>
<P>Throughout his 29 years of practice, Charlie Shaffer has served as lead
counsel in civil jury trials in commercial litigation of all types. He has
extensive litigation experience in antitrust, commercial fraud and other complex
business matters, and he has also been actively involved in product liability,
securities, RICO, healthcare, and real estate litigation. Mr. Shaffer has
experience in internal corporate investigations and related shareholder
derivative suits and civil litigation involving concurrent grand jury
investigations. </P>
<P>Representative matters in which Mr. Shaffer has recently appeared as lead
counsel include the following:</P>
<UL>
<LI> Lead trial counsel for a large food company, a large telecommunications
company, a large delivery service, and a large anchor manufacturer in four
extensive antitrust lawsuits, including two lengthy jury trials.
<P></P>
</LI>
<LI> Lead counsel in <I>U.S. Anchor Mfg Co. v. Rule Industries Inc.</I>, 77
F.3d 986 (11th Cir. 1993), <I>cert. denied</I> 114 S. Ct. 2710 (1994).  This is
an important antitrust decision in the 11th Circuit, which ruled in favor of Mr.
Shaffer's client in reversing a jury verdict after a seven week antitrust jury
trial.
</LI>
<LI> Defense of a televised shopping company in intensive and protracted
litigation brought by the company's former General Counsel.  This highly
publicized litigation involved numerous claims between the company and its
former General Counsel in State Court in St. Petersburg, Florida, and after
extensive discovery, the litigation was resolved pursuant to a Confidentiality
Agreement.
<P></P></LI>
<LI> Representing one of the nation's largest Medicare carriers in parallel
criminal and civil proceedings under the False Claims Act. This litigation
extended over six years and involved two separate lawsuits and a separate
federal criminal investigation, which was concluded with a formal declination. 
<P></P></LI>
<LI> Has been retained on appeal to represent a large Japanese auto
manufacturer in the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in a product liability case
from the Southern District of Georgia in which the trial judge struck the auto
manufacturer's Answer and entered default judgment against the company for
alleged discovery violations.
</LI>
<LI> Extensive ADR experience in arbitration of an aircraft contract claim;
mediation of a failed savings and loan lawsuit involving the RTC; mediation of a
contract claim against a large food distribution company; and a mock jury trial
involving two companies in the trucking industry.
<P></P></LI>
<LI> Represented a Swiss company in the lengthy and expedited trial and appeal
of a patent infringement proceeding before the International Trade Commission in
1990, where international discovery, the trial and the appeal were resolved
successfully in favor of Mr. Shaffer's client and were completed within 12
months.
<P></P></LI></UL>
<P>Mr. Shaffer has served as President of the Atlanta Bar Association during
1980-81 and as a member of the Council of the Litigation Section of the American
Bar Association from 1988-91. He was elected to the Policy Committee (Board of
Directors) of King &amp; Spalding for two terms:  1985-87 and 1991-93. </P>
<P>Mr. Shaffer was elected to the American College of Trial Lawyers in 1986 and
delivered the acceptance speech for the 1986 Inductees at the ACTL Induction
Ceremony in New York. He is listed in <I>The Best Lawyers In America</I> for
Georgia in business litigation. He has co-authored and co-edited a book entitled<I>Sanctions:
Rule 11 and Other Powers</I> (1986 and Second Edition, 1988), published by the
Litigation Section of the American Bar Association. He lectures frequently on
civil procedure.</P>
<P>A 1964 Phi Beta Kappa graduate of the University of North Carolina, Mr.
Shaffer received his J.D. from the University of North Carolina Law School in
1967.</P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/special.htm">Special Matters Practice</A></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
