<HEADER>
<TITLE>Michael R. Smith</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Michael R. Smith</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/smithm.jpg">

Michael Smith is a partner in King & Spalding's Litigation Practice Group, focusing on business and finance litigation.  Mr. Smith joined King & Spalding in 1983 after receiving his law degree cum laude from Harvard Law School.  He has been a partner of the Firm since 1990.
<P>
Mr. Smith has had litigation and trial experience in a wide range of civil matters, including banking and financial services litigation, securities and shareholder litigation, and other business torts litigation.  He has appeared in courts in Georgia, New York, Illinois,  Delaware, North Carolina, South Carolina, Florida, and Texas.  Representative matters in which Mr. Smith has appeared as lead counsel over the last two years include the following:
<P>
<UL>
<li>Defense of a well-known software producer in a securities class action challenging the adequacy of the company's disclosures in connection with its November 1995 IPO.<P>
<LI>Defense of former top officers and directors of a large banking corporation in multiple civil actions in Miami and Orlando, Florida seeking over $400 million in damages arising out of the nation's fourth largest bank failure.  In 1996, the officer and director defendants won summary judgment dismissing all claims against them by the RTC.<P>
<P>
<LI>Defense of a television shopping channel company in a number of significant litigation matters, including a shareholder action seeking to enjoin a tender offer; shareholder securities fraud and derivative actions seeking over $300 million in damages; and parallel grand jury and SEC investigations.  Settled shareholder suits in 1995 after defeating plaintiffs' attempt to enjoin the tender offer; the grand jury and SEC investigations were terminated in 1994 and 1996, respectively, with no indictment or other action brought against the company.<P>
<P>
<LI>Defense of a property trust in federal litigation seeking damages and an injunction blocking the merger of the trust with another subsidiary of its parent. Won motion to dismiss all claims in 1995.<P>
<P>
<LI>Representation a former White House chief of staff and an investment partnership as plaintiffs in federal litigation against an NFL expansion team arising out of a complicated shareholder squeeze out transaction.  Settled in 1996 on the eve of trial.<P>
</UL>
<P>
Mr. Smith is active in the American Bar Association Section of Litigation, where he served from 1991 to 1994 as Chairman of the Civil RICO sub-committee of the Committee on Business Torts.  
<P>
Mr. Smith also serves on the Firm's Technology Committee, and is experienced in the use of a wide range of litigation support technologies which help reduce the cost of managing large, document intensive litigation matters.<P>
<P>
Mr. Smith received his law degree <EM>cum laude </EM>from Harvard Law School in 1983.<P>
<A HREF="/menu/comlit.htm">Commercial Litigation Practice</A><P>
