<TITLE>John C. Staton, Jr.</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>John C. Staton, Jr.</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/staton.jpg">

John Staton has represented both public and private companies in a
variety of patent, trademark, copyright and antitrust matters.  In addition,
he has been particularly active in helping clients with various problems
associated with the introduction, marketing, advertising, pricing, and
distribution of products in a wide variety of industries.
<P>
Mr. Staton has lectured to the American Management Association, Canadian
Consulate, The Carpet and Rug Institute, Georgia Institute of Technology,
Georgia World Congress Institute and International Franchise Association.
He co-authored two antitrust articles for the <EM>Mercer Law Review </EM>entitled
"Antitrust Developments in the Fifth Circuit" and "Of Bicycles and Beer:
Vertical Territorial and Customer Restraints From Schwinn To Coors."
<P>
Active in a number of civic activities, Mr. Staton has served as President
of the Georgia Tech Alumni Association.  He is currently a Trustee of
the Georgia Tech Foundation, Chairman of the Investment Committee and
a member of the Executive Committee.
<P>
Mr. Staton graduated from the Georgia Institute of Technology in 1960.
He received his law degree from Emory University School of Law in 1963.
From 1963-1964, Mr. Staton served as a Law Clerk to The Honorable Griffin
B. Bell, Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals.  In 1964 Mr. Staton joined
King & Spalding and became a partner in 1970.
<P>
