<HEADER>
<TITLE>Lloyd Sutter</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Lloyd Sutter</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/sutter.jpg">

As counsel to King & Spalding, Lloyd Sutter has represented management
in labor and employment law matters since 1969.  He has represented
major airline, communication, oil and chemical, packaging, paper, construction,
trucking, and retail companies in union avoidance, NLRB election and
unfair labor practice proceedings, labor negotiations and arbitrations,
as well as labor, EEO, OSHA, and ERISA litigation at both the trial
and appellate levels.
<P>
Between 1976 and 1982, Mr. Sutter was Chief Counsel, Labor and Employment
Law, for Owens-Illinois, Inc., then a Toledo, Ohio-domiciled, multinational
Fortune 100 corporation with 68,000 employees employed in over 100 manufacturing and sales facilities in 38 states.
<P>
Mr. Sutter is a former Remedies Subcommittee Chairman and former Southeastern
Region OFCCP Liaison of the EEO Committee of the Labor and Employment
Law Section of the American Bar Association.  He has been an Adjunct
Professor of Labor and Employment Law at the law schools of Emory University
and the University of Georgia, as well as a writer and a speaker on
a wide range of employment law subjects for the Defense Research Institute
EEO Committee's Annual Seminar and for various State and local bar associations.
He is a former Commissioner of the Housing Authority of Fulton County
and has been actively involved in the religious education program for
St. Andrew Catholic Church.
<P>
Mr. Sutter is a graduate of Emory University and the University of
Georgia School of Law (1968).  While in law school, he was a member
of the editorial board of the <EM>Georgia Law Review </EM>and a member of the
National Moot Court team.  He was a law clerk to the Honorable Richard
T. Rives of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit.  He joined
King & Spalding as a partner in 1985.  He is admitted to the bar in
the States of Georgia, Florida and Ohio.
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/labor.htm">Labor, ERISA & Employment Practice</A><P>
