<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Michael R. Taylor</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#00009c" VLINK="#8e2323">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H3><B>Michael R. Taylor</B></H3></CENTER><IMG
SRC="/gif/taylor.jpg" ALIGN="LEFT" VSPACE="10" HSPACE="10">
<P>Mike Taylor recently rejoined King &amp; Spalding after five years in public
service as Deputy Commissioner for Policy at the Food and Drug Administration
(1991-1994) and as Administrator of the Food Safety and Inspection Service
(FSIS) at the U.S. Department of Agriculture (1994-1996). During most of his
tenure at USDA, Mr. Taylor also served as Acting Under Secretary for Food
Safety. </P>
<P>As Deputy Commissioner for Policy at FDA, Mr. Taylor was responsible for all
FDA rulemaking and policy development activities, including the development of
agency positions on legislative matters. Mr. Taylor was heavily involved in
FDA's implementation of the Nutrition Labeling and Education Act of 1990 and the
Safe Medical Device Amendments of 1990, as well as the development of agency
policies and programs concerning drug promotion, human tissue transplantation,
GATT negotiations (Uruguay Round), international harmonization of food and drug
regulatory requirements, biotechnology, food additives, medical foods, dietary
supplements, and seafood safety. As Administrator of FSIS, Mr. Taylor led a
major overhaul of the USDA food safety program, including a reorganization of
FSIS and adoption of Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points (HACCP) as the
framework for USDA's inspection of meat and poultry. Mr. Taylor has worked
extensively with Congress on matters involving FDA and USDA. </P>
<P>Before entering government service, Mr. Taylor practiced food and drug law
for ten years at King &amp; Spalding, beginning in 1981 as the Firm's first food
and drug lawyer and becoming the first food and drug partner in 1984. Mr. Taylor
managed the expansion of the practice into all areas of FDA regulation,
concentrating his personal practice in the area of food law and chemical risk
regulation. Mr. Taylor was a member of the National Academy of Sciences
Committee that published the 1986 <I>Delaney Paradox </I>report, which laid the
scientific and policy foundations for the modernization of the Delaney Clause
for pesticide residues as part of the recently enacted Food Quality Protection
Act of 1996. </P>
<P>Prior to joining King &amp; Spalding in 1981, Mr. Taylor served as Executive
Assistant to the Commissioner of FDA and in FDA's Office of Chief Counsel as
Assistant Chief Counsel for Medical Devices and Associate Chief Counsel for
Foods. Mr. Taylor received a B.A. in political science from Davidson College in
1971 and his law degree in 1976 from the University of Virginia School of Law.
</P>
<P><A HREF="/menu/food.htm">Food &amp; Drug Practice</A></P>
