<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>Chilton Davis Varner</TITLE>
</HEADER><body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><IMG SRC="/gif/k-s2b.gif"></CENTER>
<CENTER><HR></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><B>Chilton Davis Varner</B></H3></CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 SRC="/gif/varner.jpg">
<P>
Chilton Varner has 20 years of courtroom experience as a trial lawyer defending corporations in product liability and commercial disputes.  One of the few women to be elected a fellow in the American College of Trial Lawyers, she has served as trial and appellate counsel for some of the country's largest automotive, pharmaceutical, and medical device manufacturers.  She has also developed "preventive law" strategies for those corporations to assist them in avoiding future claims and in preparing them to defend such claims should they arise.  She has substantial experience in mass tort litigation and class actions, including the complex issues of discovery and attorney-client privilege which accompany such suits.  
<P>Examples of Mrs. Varner's experience include:
<P><UL>
<LI>She is one of approximately 40 lawyers selected by a major automobile manufacturer as lead counsel for the company's product liability litigation nationwide.  In the past year she has obtained defense verdicts in three cases against the client: a case in Georgia involving a recalled product; a death case in Tennessee involving claims of a defective restraint system; and a death case in Kentucky involving a post-collision fire.
<P><LI>She is a member of the national trial team representing a client in breast implant suits, with lead counsel responsibility for all cases in Georgia, Alabama, Tennessee, and South Carolina, as well as selected cases in Texas and elsewhere in the United States.
<P><LI>As trial counsel, she successfully defended an international food and beverage company in a class action brought by a group of approximately one hundred independent bottlers claiming over $100 million in damages for alleged violation of their bottling contracts.  The case lasted 11 years and was the largest ever tried in the United States District Court for the District of Delaware: it involved three separate trials, an appeal to the Third Circuit and a petition for certiorari to the United States Supreme Court.
<P><LI>She defends the country's largest group of private laboratories against claims of malpractice, including lawsuits arising out of pap smears, drug screens, and AIDS testing.
<P><LI>On behalf of a major automobile manufacturer, she argued the appeals of the largest product liability verdicts ever awarded in Alabama and Mississippi.
<P><LI>She is a member of the Product Liability Advisory Council, a consortium of over one hundred of the country's major product manufacturers formed to file amicus briefs on critical issues of product liability.  She has authored a number of amicus briefs for PLAC, including a brief in Shelton v. American Motors, 805 F.2d 1323 (8th Cir. 1986) which successfully proposed a landmark test limiting the availability of depositions of in-house counsel.  She was also the first outside counsel to serve on PLAC's executive committee (1991-94).
<P><LI>She has been admitted to practice pro hac vice in the courts of Alabama, Tennessee, Florida, South Carolina, North Carolina, Mississippi, Texas, New York, Missouri, California, and Kentucky.
<P>
</UL>
<P>
Mrs. Varner has significant experience before the judges of the Eleventh Circuit and the Northern District of Georgia.  She was asked to chair the program of the Eleventh Circuit Judicial Conference in 1992, 1994 and 1995, and to chair the Magistrate Selection Committee for the Northern District of Georgia in 1995.  In addition, she was requested to represent the Eleventh Circuit at the Federal Judicial Center's First National Conference on Eliminating Racial and Ethnic Bias in the Courts. 
<P>
Mrs. Varner has published on areas of interest in her practice, including: Varner and Griffin:  Appellate Handbook for Georgia Lawyers, Lawyers Cooperative Publishing (1994); Bell, Varner and Gottschalk: "Automatic Disclosure and Discovery -- The Rush to Reform," 27 Ga. L. Rev. 1 (Fall 1992); Varner and Bayman: "Putting the Cart Before the Horse: Providing a Privilege Index Under Proposed Federal Rule of Civil Procedure Rule 26(b)(5)", ABA National Institutes on Emerging Issues in Automobile Product Liability Litigation (March 1991); and Jones and Varner: "Direct Examination: Making the Facts Understandable," Winning Strategies and Techniques for Civil Litigation (Lyons, ed.), Practicing Law Institute, New York (1992).
<P>
Mrs. Varner is a native of Opelika, Alabama.  She joined King & Spalding in 1976 after receiving her J.D., with distinction, Order of the Coif, from Emory University School of Law. She is a Phi Beta Kappa graduate of Smith College, Northampton, Massachusetts.  She became the second woman partner at King & Spalding in 1983 and the first woman partner in the Litigation Practice Group.  In 1995, she became the first woman to be elected to the Firm's management committee.  She is a trustee of Emory University.<P>
<P>
<A HREF="/menu/prodliab.htm">Product Liability Practice</A><P>
