<DOCOLDNO>IA023-000247-B020-135</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.kslaw.com:80/menu/revival.htm 155.229.224.122 19970108090559 text/html 64200
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Wed, 08 Jan 1997 09:17:26 GMT
Server: Microsoft-Internet-Information-Server/1.0
Content-Type: text/html
Last-Modified: Tue, 01 Oct 1996 18:10:39 GMT
Content-Length: 63999
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>The Revival of Vertical Merger Enforcement
</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">
<CENTER><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<h1>The Revival of Vertical Merger Enforcement
</h1>
<p>
<h2><a href="/htm/blumenth.htm">William Blumenthal</a> and Kara L. Bue</h2>
<H6>Copyright &copy; 1994 by Matthew Bender & Co., Inc. Reprinted with permission from the February 1994, <EM>Antitrust Report</EM>. All rights reserved.</H6>
<HR><p>
</CENTER>
<p>
After an extended period of dormancy, vertical merger enforcement by the U.S. Department of Justice and the Federal Trade Commission has revived.  Since the fourth quarter of 1993, the agencies have issued more vertical merger complaints than in the entire preceding fifteen-year period.  All of the complaints in the recent wave were resolved by consent agreements.  Although agency statements accompanying the complaints and consent agreements, together with speeches by enforcement officials, offer some indication of the agencies' current emerging standards, the specifics remain unclear in many important respects. 
<P>
<H4>	Background: A Brief History of Vertical Merger Policy
	<BR>Prior to the Recent Wave</H4>
<P>
	The first Supreme Court case to address vertical merger law was <EM>United States v. E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co.</EM>, 353 U.S. 586 (1957), <EM>rev'g and remanding </EM>126 F. Supp. 235 (N.D. Ill. 1954).  Decided under the original version of Section 7 of the Clayton Act and therefore of limited precedential value, the case arose from a 1949 complaint challenging du Pont's gradual acquisition of 23% of the stock of General Motors from 1917 to 1919.  At the time of the challenge, General Motors was the largest automobile manufacturer in the world; by 1955 it supplied 48.8% of the cars sold in the United States.  du Pont was the largest chemical company in the world and a major supplier of automobile finishes and fabrics.  In 1947 it supplied General Motors with 67% of its requirements for finishes and 35.7% of its requirements for fabrics.  The complaint alleged that du Pont's supply position with General Motors arose from its ownership interest and that the insulation of General Motors from market forces would substantially lessen competition and tend to create a monopoly.  
<P>
	The Supreme Court (in a four-to-two decision) held that du Pont's acquisition of General Motors stock was unlawful, and it remanded for determination of relief.  After holding that the Clayton Act applied to vertical mergers and defining the relevant markets, the Court stated a two-prong test for assessing the legality of a vertical merger: (1) the affected market must be substantial, and (2) foreclosure of competition in a substantial share of the market must be likely.  The Court readily found that the first prong was satisfied.  With respect to the second prong, the Court found that du Pont (despite its minority interest) was active and influential in General Motors' affairs and, at the time of the acquisition, had expressed its intent to use its interest to help secure business.  du Pont's power to influence General Motors' purchase decision on grounds unrelated to competitive merits "foreclosed" General Motors to du Pont's competitors, regardless of whether the power was actually exercised.
<P>
	The next vertical merger case to come before the Supreme Court -- and the first under the Celler-Kefauver Amendments to Section 7 -- was <EM>Brown Shoe Co. v. United States,</EM> 370 U.S. 294 (1962).  Largely by virtue of dearth of other authority, it remains the leading decision today.  The case arose from a 1955 complaint challenging the merger of Brown Shoe Company and G.R. Kinney Company.  Both companies manufactured and retailed men's, women's, and children's shoes, but Brown was primarily a manufacturer and Kinney primarily a retailer.  At the time of the merger, Brown was the fourth largest manufacturer of shoes in the United States, with a production market share of approximately four percent.  Kinney was the largest shoe retailer in the United States, with a retail market share of approximately 1.6%; it was also the twelfth largest manufacturer, with a production market share of approximately 0.5%.  Kinney's manufacturing facilities supplied about 20% of the shoes sold by Kinney retail stores.  At the time of the merger, Brown did not supply shoes to Kinney; but by 1957 Brown had become Kinney's largest outside source, supplying 7.9% of Kinney's retail needs. 
<P>
	The Supreme Court affirmed a district court finding that the acquisition violated the amended Section 7.  After reviewing the legislative history of the amendments, the Court turned to vertical aspects of the transaction.  Echoing the <EM>du Pont</EM> decision, the Court stated that the "primary vice of a vertical merger" is the foreclosure of competitors, which acts as a "clog on competition" and "deprive[s] . . . rivals of a fair opportunity to compete."  After defining the relevant markets, the Court stated that market share would be an important, but seldom determinative consideration.  (It would be determinative if it either approached monopoly proportions or fell below a <EM>de minimis</EM> threshold, which the Court implicitly set at something under two percent.)  The Court identified numerous other "economic and historical factors" that would go to legality.  The first and "most important such factor" was the nature and purpose of the arrangement.  Another was the trend towards concentration in the industry.
<P>
	The only other vertical merger case decided by the Supreme Court was <EM>Ford Motor Co. v. United States</EM>, 405 U.S. 562 (1972), <EM>aff'g </EM>286 F. Supp. 407 (E.D. Mich. 1968) & 315 F. Supp. 372 (E.D. Mich. 1970).  The case arose from a 1961 complaint challenging Ford's acquisition of certain assets of Electric Autolite Company.  Autolite was a leading manufacturer of automotive lighting and ignition systems.  From 1934 to 1955, it had been primary supplier of Chrysler's electrical needs.  Chrysler began to diversify its sources in 1956, however, and was purchasing two-thirds of its batteries from Autolite's competitors by 1960.  Autolite remained Chrysler's primary supplier of spark plugs, but feared that Chrysler would repeat its diversification, leaving Autolite with a large, fixed-volume facility with substantial overcapacity.  In response, Autolite sought to convince Ford, which had been buying exclusively from an Autolite competitor, to internalize its requirements by purchasing Autolite manufacturing facilities.  Ford and Autolite entered into a transaction pursuant to which Ford acquired Autolite's spark plug facility, one of Autolite's six battery facilities, and the Autolite trade name.  By virtue of the transaction, Ford became self-sufficient in spark plugs, but continued to purchase many of its batteries from outside sources.  Autolite continued to produce batteries, and it re-entered manufacture of spark plugs on a small scale for private label accounts (which included General Motors and Chrysler). 
<P>
	The district court had found a violation in both the battery and spark plug markets.  In batteries, the court had found that Ford's mere acquisition of the facility would not result in substantial foreclosure, but that Ford's additional acquisition of the Autolite name would result in goodwill leading to aftermarket sales, thus making inevitable total foreclosure on the order of 6.2% of industry shipments.  In spark plugs, the court had found that Autolite accounted for 15% of industry shipments, that Ford accounted for 9.6% of industry purchases, and that the elimination of Ford as an independent purchaser was sufficient to establish a "blatant" violation of Section 7.  In addition, the court wrote, taken together with General Motors' vertical integration in spark plugs, the transaction had raised barriers to entry into spark plug manufacture and removed a constraint on the pricing behavior of independent spark plug manufacturers.  The Supreme Court review was limited to the spark plug market.  After summarizing and quoting the district court, the Supreme Court affirmed.  It emphasized that Ford's argument that the acquisition had made Autolite a more effective competitor was irrelevant.
<P>
	For a number of years following <EM>Brown Shoe</EM> and <EM>Ford </EM>(<EM>Autolite</EM>), lower courts found various mergers unlawful on theories of vertical foreclosure.  Some of the cases also focused (as in <EM>Ford </EM>(<EM>Autolite</EM>)) on the horizontal effects of vertical mergers, either through elimination of potential entry or by increases in barriers to entry.  <EM>See generally </EM>1 <EM>ABA Antitrust Section, Antitrust Law Developments</EM> 330-31 (3d ed. 1992).  In conducting their analyses, courts focused on several questions:
<P>
	(1) what percentage of the market was foreclosed; (2) what was the purpose of the acquisition, particularly the degree to which the acquiring firm used or intended to use the acquired firm captively; (3) what was the effect of the acquisition on local businesses; (4) what was the degree of concentration in the relevant markets; (5) was there a trend toward vertical integration in the industry, and what was the historical role of the merging firms in contributing to any such trend; and (6) did or could the acquisition increase barriers to entry into either or both levels of manufacturing or distribution.
<P>
<H4><EM>ABA Antitrust Section,</EM> Monograph No. 14, <EM>Non-Horizontal Mergers: Law and Policy </EM>19-20 (1988).</H4>
<P>
	By the late 1970s, however, judicial attitudes towards vertical relationships had shifted substantially, as courts, commentators, and enforcement agencies began to focus on the efficiency-enhancing potential of vertical agreements and to question the competitive risks associated with foreclosure.  <EM>See, e.g.</EM>, <EM>Continental T.V., Inc. v. GTE Sylvania Inc.</EM>, 433 U.S. 36 (1977).  The receptiveness of courts to vertical merger challenges dropped off sharply.  In <EM>Alberta Gas Chemicals, Ltd. v. E.I. du Pont de Nemours & Co.</EM>, 826 F.2d 1235 (3d Cir. 1987), <EM>cert. denied</EM>, 486 U.S. 1059 (1988), for example, the circuit court rejected a private plaintiff's challenge to a vertical merger after observing that "respected scholars question the anticompetitive effects of vertical mergers" due to foreclosure risk and that the merger might well "result in efficiencies."  Other courts similarly have dismissed vertical merger challenges in recent years, either because foreclosure was <EM>de minimis</EM> or because foreclosure was not likely to injure competition.  <EM>See generally </EM>1 <EM>Antitrust Law Developments, supra,</EM> at 332 nn. 340-42.  The frequency of enforcement agency intervention against vertical mergers ground to a near-halt, although the agencies did not abandon the field entirely.  <EM>See Occidental Petroleum Corp.</EM>, 3 Trade Reg. Rep. (CCH)  22,349 (FTC Apr. 11, 1986); <EM>Arco Chemical Co.</EM>, 113 F.T.C. 1050 (1990).
<P>
	The shift in enforcement attitudes towards vertical mergers was reflected in the Antitrust Division's 1982 Merger Guidelines.  The Guidelines took no express account of adverse vertical competitive effects and instead treated vertical mergers under a discussion captioned "Horizontal Effect from Non-Horizontal Mergers."  Three adverse horizontal effects that might flow from vertical mergers were identified.  The first, echoing one of the theories of <EM>Ford (Autolite),</EM> was that vertical mergers might increase barriers to entry under specified, limited conditions.  The second possible effect was that vertical mergers might facilitate horizontal collusion, either by facilitating monitoring of prices at the retail level or by eliminating a disruptive buyer.  The third was that vertical mergers might facilitate the evasion of rate regulation.  The Antitrust Division's 1984 Merger Guidelines reiterated these provisions without material change.  The joint Antitrust Division/FTC 1992 Horizontal Merger Guidelines by their terms were limited to horizontal mergers, but a statement accompanying their release indicated that "[s]pecific guidance on non-horizontal mergers is provided in Section 4 of the Department's 1984 <EM>Merger Guidelines</EM>, read in the context of today's revisions to the treatment of horizontal mergers."  Reprinted in 2 <EM>Antitrust Law Developments, supra</EM>, at 1368.

<P>
<H4>	The Recent Enforcement Wave</H4>
<P>
	After their extended quiescence towards vertical mergers, the Antitrust Division and FTC have reawakened with vigor.  Some of their challenges to vertical mergers have been based upon theories articulated -- or at least hinted at -- in the Guidelines.  Others go considerably beyond the Guidelines, and some seem to go beyond even the old case law.  We summarize the cases here.
<P>
<strong>Paramount/QVC</strong>
<P>
	The first case in the recent enforcement wave was <EM>In the Matter of Tele-Communications, Inc. and Liberty Media Corporation, </EM>FTC File No. 941-0008 (Nov. 30, 1993), an FTC action involving the acquisition of Paramount by TCI and Liberty through QVC.  The allegations of the complaint were as follows:  TCI is the largest cable television multiple system operator ("MSO") in the United States.  Liberty, its programming affiliate, also owns cable television systems and provides satellite-delivered programming services to various distribution media, including cable television.  Together, the companies' affiliated cable systems control distribution of cable programming to approximately 25% of the total cable television subscriber base in the U.S.  In addition to their operations, TCI and Liberty hold substantial stock ownership in many popular cable television programming networks, including QVC.  Paramount is a major Hollywood studio that produces and licenses new theatrically released movies for transmission on cable television channels and owns a 50% interest in USA Networks.  In view of these facts, the FTC alleged that the effect of the acquisition likely would be to (1) reduce the output and quality of premium movie channels; (2) raise programming fees to cable operators; (3) raise cable television subscriber fees to consumers; (4) enhance coordinated interaction among vertically integrated MSOs; and (5) increase the difficulty of entry into the provision of subscription television programming distribution.
<P>
	Resolving these allegations, TCI and Liberty entered into an Agreement Containing Consent Order, pursuant to which TCI and Liberty are required subject to certain exceptions to (1) divest all ownership interest in QVC and (2) divest or terminate their voting interests in QVC stock.  The companies must complete the required divestitures and/or terminations within 18 months from the date the Consent Order becomes final.  The Agreement requires that TCI and Liberty divest their interests only after obtaining FTC approval; such approval is not required where TCI or Liberty divest some or all of their ownership or voting interests to QVC or its other named owners.
<P>
	The Agreement temporarily prohibits TCI and Liberty from entering into any agreement with QVC or Paramount that grants TCI or Liberty exclusive rights to recently released motion pictures after Paramount's current contract with certain other parties terminates.  TCI and Liberty are also prohibited from acquiring, directly or indirectly, any equity or ownership interest in QVC, Paramount, or USA Networks, without the prior approval of the FTC.  This prohibition is effective for a period beginning from the date the Consent Order becomes final and ends 3 years after the required divestitures or terminations of interest are complete.
<P>
	The Agreement provides that TCI and Liberty are not obligated to comply with the Consent Order if (1) QVC terminates or abandons the attempted acquisition of Paramount or (2) QVC does not acquire more than 10% of Paramount's common stock within 12 months of the date the Consent Order becomes final.
<P>
	According to the FTC, the Agreement's purpose is to preserve competition during the period prior to the final acceptance of the consent agreement and thereafter until the divestitures and terminations required of the consent agreement are completed.  Consistent with this purpose, the Agreement prohibits TCI and Liberty from (1) exercising direction or control over the management or operations of QVC or Paramount; (2) exercising any voting rights or agreements pursuant to Liberty's ownership in QVC; or (3) participating in any change in the composition of the management of QVC or Paramount.  Additionally, the Agreement provides that within 5 days after it is placed on the public record, any officers, directors, or employees of TCI or Liberty who are present members of the Board of Directors of QVC or Paramount must resign.
<P>
	<strong>TCI/Liberty</strong>
<P>
	In a separate action that also involved TCI and Liberty, <EM>U.S. v. Tele-Communications, Inc. and Liberty Media Corporation </EM>(No. 94-0948) (D.C. Cir. April 28, 1994), the Antitrust Division filed a complaint alleging that the proposed merger of the parties would lessen competition (1) among providers of video programming to United States multichannel subscription television distributors ("MSTD") and (2) among MSTDs in those areas where TCI and Liberty control cable systems.
<P>
	According to the complaint, the merger of TCI and Liberty would result in a vertically integrated firm with the ability and incentives to restrain competition in at least two ways.  First, a merged TCI/Liberty could discriminate against competing video programmers in favor of its affiliated programmers by refusing to carry programs or by denying similar terms or conditions to its competitors.  The Division contended that such conduct could create difficulties for competing programmers to operate profitably or to compete effectively against the TCI/Liberty programming services.  Second, a merged TCI/Liberty could deny competing MSTDs access to TCI/Liberty programming or discriminate against competing MSTDs as to the terms of access.  The Division contended that competitive distribution systems would find it difficult to obtain the programming necessary to compete effectively against TCI/Liberty's MSTDs.
<P>
	Resolving these allegations, the parties filed a Stipulation by which they consented to entry of a proposed Final Judgment.  The Consent Judgment enjoins TCI/Liberty from discriminating against unaffiliated video programmers in the selection, terms, or conditions of carriage of video programming offered by TCI/Liberty cable systems or MSTDs.  It also enjoins TCI/Liberty from refusing to sell or license to any competing MSTD, or from selling or licensing only on a discriminatory basis, video programming in which the firm has an interest.  The prohibitions apply where "the effect of such discrimination is to unreasonably restrain competition."  The Consent Judgment extends the prohibitions to prevent TCI and Liberty from seeking or supporting, with respect to any MSTD or video programming provider in which they have a financial interest but do not control, conduct that would violate the provisions if engaged in by the companies.
<P>
	The Consent Judgment will remain in effect for a term of 5 years.  According to the Antitrust Division, "[t]he length of this term reflects the Department's recognition that this industry is one that has experienced major changes in MSTD technologies that are on-going, and the effects of the 1992 Cable Act and its implementing FCC regulations."  
<P>
	<strong>BT/MCI</strong>
<P>
	In <EM>United States v. MCI Communications Corp.,</EM> No. 94-01317 (D.D.C. June 15, 1994), the Antitrust Division filed a complaint against MCI and BT Forty-Company alleging that the proposed acquisition of a 20% equity interest in MCI by British Telecommunications plc ("BT"), and the proposed formation of a joint venture between MCI and BT (the "Joint Venture") to provide international enhanced telecommunications services would violate antitrust laws by reducing competition in the markets for international telecommunications services between the United States and the United Kingdom and for global seamless telecommunications services.  According to the complaint, BT and MCI are, respectively, the fourth and fifth largest providers of telecommunications in the world.  MCI also carries approximately 20% of the United States international traffic to and from the United Kingdom.  The complaint alleged that BT's investment in MCI and the Joint Venture would likely increase BT's incentive and ability to:
<P>
<OL>
<LI>	use its market power in the provision of local and domestic and international long distance telecommunications services in the United Kingdom to discriminate in favor of MCI and the Joint Venture against other United States international telecommunications and enhanced telecommunications providers;
<LI>	provide to MCI and the Joint Venture confidential, competitively sensitive information obtained from MCI's and the Joint Venture's United States competitors through their correspondent relationships or their interconnection with BT, substantially lessening competition in the United States; and
<LI>	favor MCI over its competitors in the allocation of international telecommunications traffic from the United Kingdom. 
</OL>
<P>
	Resolving these concerns, the parties filed a Stipulation by which they consented to the entry of a proposed Final Judgment that contains the following substantive requirements meant to "diminish the risk of abuse of BT's market power to discriminate or otherwise afford anticompetitive advantages to MCI and [the Joint Venture]."  
<P>
	1.  <strong>Transparency Requirements.  </strong>Under the terms of the Consent Judgment, MCI and the Joint Venture are required to provide information to the Justice Department on (a) prices, terms and conditions, including discounts, on which telecommunications services are provided to the Joint Venture pursuant to interconnection agreements with BT; (b) MCI minutes to and from BT in each rate category; (c) schedules of facilities and circuits, including capacity, provided by BT and actual and average time intervals between fault report and restoration of service circuits; and (d) planned and authorized changes in BT's United Kingdom public network that would affect interconnection arrangements with any licensed operators.
<P>
	To ensure greater transparency in MCI's dealings with BT, the Consent Judgment also contains disclosure obligations specifically applicable to MCI.  Pursuant to such provisions, MCI must disclose the following information with regard to international switched and enhanced telecommunications: (a) accounting and settlement rates and other terms and conditions for the provision of services; (b) on an annual basis, minutes of traffic to and from BT for each accounting rate, for calculating proportionate return; and (c) for international private circuits it provides jointly with BT, the actual number of outages and actual average time intervals between fault report and restoration of service, average number of circuit equivalents available to MCI during certain hours.
<P>
	In connection with the transparency requirements, the Consent Judgment provides that the information submitted by MCI and the Joint Venture to the Justice Department may be disclosed to any United States corporation that holds or has applied for a license from either the United States or United Kingdom authorities to provide international telecommunications services between the United States and the United Kingdom.  According to the Antitrust Division, "this will enable the principal competitors of MCI and the Joint Venture to monitor whether either of these companies is receiving discriminatory treatment in their favor from BT, and provide them with evidence that could be used to make a complaint to any governmental authorities in the United States or the United Kingdom."
<P>
	2.  <strong>Confidentiality Requirements.  </strong>The Consent Judgment contains certain confidentiality requirements necessitated by what the Antitrust Division considered to be the inadequate protection provided by existing regulations.  Specifically, the Consent Judgment provides that BT may not provide to MCI or the Joint Venture (a) any data proprietary to other United States carriers; (b) any confidential, non-public data from other carriers; and (c) any non-public data about future prices or plans of other carriers.
<P>
	3.  <strong>International Simple Resale Requirements.  </strong>To prevent discrimination by BT in favor of MCI, including the diversion of BT's traffic from the United Kingdom through MCI and the Joint Venture, the Consent Judgment prohibits MCI and the Joint Venture from providing international simple resale between the United States and the United Kingdom until the United Kingdom permits simple resale by United States carriers from the United Kingdom and those carriers are able to interconnect with BT on "standard, nondiscriminatory terms."
<P>
	The Consent Judgment provides for modification of its terms upon a showing of changed circumstances or public interest.  Violations of the Consent Judgment subject the parties to civil penalties of up to $10 million.  The Consent Judgment expires by its terms after five years.  
<P>
	<strong>Martin Marietta/General Dynamics</strong>
<P>
	In <EM>In the Matter of Martin Marietta Corporation, </EM>FTC Docket No. C-3500 (June 22, 1994), the FTC challenged the proposed acquisition of General Dynamics' Space Systems Division by Martin Marietta.  The allegations of the complaint were as follows:  Martin is a significant competitor in the market for the manufacture and sale of satellites, and GD is a manufacturer of Atlas expendable launch vehicles ("ELV"), which are used to transport satellites into orbit.  The proposed acquisition would allow Martin, in its capacity as an ELV manufacturer, access to competitively significant and non-public information concerning other satellite suppliers' products.  Such access would decrease competition between satellite suppliers and reduce advancements in satellite research, innovation, and quality.  
<P>
	Resolving these allegations, Martin agreed to a Consent Order under which it would be prohibited from disclosing any non-public information received from satellite owners or manufacturers in its capacity as a provider of ELVs and is required to use such information only as a provider of ELVs.  Non-public information is defined in the Order as any information not in the public domain which is furnished by a satellite owner or manufacturer to Martin or GD in their capacity as providers of ELVs and is designated as proprietary.
<P>
	Martin is required to deliver a copy of the Consent Order to any United States satellite owner or manufacturer prior to obtaining any information that is outside the public domain.  One year from the date the Consent Order becomes final and annually thereafter for 9 years, Martin would also be required to provide to the FTC a report of its compliance.
<P>
	<strong>AT&T/McCaw</strong>
<P>
	In <EM>United States v. AT&T Corp.</EM>, No. 94-01555 (HHG) (D.D.C. July 15, 1994), the Antitrust Division filed a complaint against AT&T and McCaw Cellular Communications, Inc. alleging that their proposed merger would violate antitrust laws by reducing competition in United States markets for cellular service, cellular infrastructure equipment and long-distance services to cellular customers.  According to the complaint, AT&T is the dominant supplier of long-distance services to both landline and cellular customers and the largest supplier of cellular infrastructure equipment in the United States, and McCaw is the largest provider of cellular services in the United States and a major supplier of long-distance services to cellular customers in many domestic markets.  Consequently, the complaint alleged, the merger would likely 
<P>
<OL>
<LI>	increase AT&T's incentive and ability to disadvantage its "locked in" equipment customers that currently compete against McCaw in the provision of cellular services,
<LI>	provide AT&T with access to competitively sensitive information that McCaw obtains from its cellular infrastructure equipment supplier that currently competes with AT&T, and
<LI>	reduce competition in the provision of long-distance services to cellular customers.

</OL>
<P>
	Resolving these concerns, the parties filed a Stipulation consenting to entry of a proposed Final Judgment that contains, among other provisions, the following:
<P>
	1.  <strong>Separation of AT&T and McCaw.  </strong>McCaw and its affiliates involved in wireless services must operate separately from AT&T for the Consent Judgment's term (i.e., 10 years).  While McCaw may use the name "AT&T" or any trademark or trade name of AT&T in its corporate or service names, it may do so only after it has (a) completed conversion to equal access and (b) balloted existing customers regarding their preference among long-distance carriers.  Additionally, the defendants may not use the name "AT&T" or any trademark or trade name of AT&T in the national marketing or advertising of any cellular service until 60% of McCaw cellular systems have been converted to equal access.
<P>
	2.  <strong>Equal Access.  </strong>Within 21 months following the filing of the complaint, McCaw must provide competing long-distance carriers with equal access to its cellular subscribers.  Such access requires that McCaw (a) allow new and existing customers to designate the long-distance carrier of their choice and (b) provide complete lists of its cellular service customers to unaffiliated long-distance carriers for use in marketing their services to McCaw customers.  After its conversion to equal access, McCaw must provide all long-distance carriers access to its services on an unbundled basis that is equal in type, quality, and price to that provided to AT&T.  The Consent Judgment prohibits McCaw from discriminating in favor of AT&T in (a) the provision of technical or other information about its cellular system or customers; (b) the interconnection or use of its services, facilities, or charges for each element of service; or (c) the provision of exchange access services.
<P>
	3.  <strong>Manufacturing.  </strong>The Consent Judgment prohibits the Defendants from disclosing confidential information relating to each other or third parties obtained through the Defendants' provision of equipment or services.  The Consent Judgment addresses the issue of "lock-in" by allowing AT&T's cellular equipment customers to sell back their equipment to AT&T, under certain circumstances, at cost minus a reasonable allowance for depreciation.  In addition, AT&T is required to provide technical assistance to facilitate the use of AT&T equipment with that of other manufacturers.
<P>
	To ensure compliance with the terms of the Consent Judgment, AT&T and/or McCaw are required to file implementation plans for each of the above provisions with the Antitrust Division no later than 90 days after the Judgment's entry.  These plans are to be effective 90 days after their submission.  Additionally, the Defendants are required to advise their management personnel of the obligations imposed by the judgment and to obtain certificates from each such employee acknowledging the Judgment's terms.
<P>
	The Consent Judgment shall expire by its terms ten years after the date of entry.  Until then, if BOC cellular systems receive relief from equal access or nondiscrimination provisions of the MFJ, the Consent Judgment shall be modified or vacated to provide AT&T or McCaw with the same relief upon a showing that competitive conditions do not require a different obligation and that the obligation is equitable and in the public interest.  In addition, upon a showing that certain types of services have developed as effective competitive alternatives to cellular services or that other changes or developments affect a relevant market, the Consent Judgment shall be modified if its provisions are inequitable, irrespective of whether the intervening changes or developments were foreseen or foreseeable.
<P>
	The Division had foretold its views of the merger in response to an earlier motion brought by AT&T with regard to the MFJ.  AT&T had sought to modify Section I(D) of the MFJ, which prohibited AT&T from acquiring stock or assets of any Bell Operating Company ("BOC"), a term arguably defined in a manner that reached McCaw.  In a memorandum supporting AT&T's motion after earlier procedural jockeying, the Antitrust Division framed the issue at hand as whether AT&T's acquisition of BOC cellular systems currently providing equal access would (1) reduce competition by threatening the equal access provided by those systems or (2) otherwise frustrate the objective of the MFJ.  <EM>See </EM>Memorandum of the United States In Support of AT&T's Motion for a Waiver of Section I(D) of the Decree, <EM>Western Electric Co.</EM> (No. 82-0192) (D.C. Cir. July 15, 1994).  According to the Memorandum, any concerns in that regard could be resolved through appropriate safeguards to protect equal access.  The Division conditioned its support of AT&T's motion to entry of a proposed order that would require AT&T and McCaw to use their ownership interest in BOC cellular systems to reinforce the requirements of equal access.
<P>
	<strong>U S West/TimeWarner</strong>
<P>
	In another matter arising from the MFJ, U S West filed a motion for waiver of the line of business restrictions under Section II(D).  U S West sought the waiver to enable it to engage solely through its affiliate, Time Warner Entertainment, in certain interexchange telecommunications and manufacturing activities from which TimeWarner would otherwise be barred as an affiliate of U S West.  As with <EM>AT&T/McCaw</EM>, this motion was granted by the court with the support of the Antitrust Division, subject to certain conditions.
<P>
	Pursuant to the Waiver issued in this case, TimeWarner may, subject to certain limitations, enter six market categories from which it was previously barred.  First, TimeWarner may provide local cable distribution services that would use receive-only interexchange facilities and would cross LATA boundaries to a limited extent for both one- and two-way telecommunications services.  TimeWarner is required, however, to remain a separate legal entity from U S West, with U S West holding no more than a minority noncontrolling interest in the company.  Additionally, the Waiver prohibits TimeWarner from selecting interLATA transmission facilities to be used to deliver programming for an unaffiliated programmer.
<P>
	Second, TimeWarner may provide one-way transmissions of video and audio programming signals across LATA boundaries, but only to a limited extent.  The Waiver generally excludes from relief two-way transmissions of voice or data, as well as one-way transmission for entities unaffiliated with U S West, and prohibits U S West from discriminating between TimeWarner and any other person in providing exchange or exchange access services.
<P>
	Third, TimeWarner may provide both one-way and two-way video, data, voice and other telecommunications services across LATA boundaries, but only between points in a cable system that satisfy a number of conditions enumerated in the Waiver.  With respect to any two-way services provided in these cable systems, the Waiver also imposes certain equal access conditions. 
<P>
	Fourth, the Waiver authorizes TimeWarner to provide information services used in cable systems to customers in one LATA from an information storage or processing facility in another.  These services, however, may only be provided by means of interexchange services obtained from an unaffiliated interexchange carrier, and may not include TimeWarner's use of any exchange or exchange access services or facilities provided by U S West.  Additionally, the Waiver (1) prohibits billing of a separate charge for an interexchange call unless the customer selects the carrier; (2) requires that the bundled charges on an aggregated basis for each functionally different or separate interexchange information service be at least 175% of the charge for the interexchange services obtained from the unaffiliated carrier; and (3) states that the information services cannot be the functional equivalent of real time voice or data transmission services.
<P>
	Fifth, the Waiver permits TimeWarner to manufacture various types of customer premises equipment and multimedia storage and retrieval equipment, other than that used for voice telephony.  In connection with this provision, however, the Waiver imposes several restrictions on U S West's relationship with TimeWarner's manufacturing activities.  
<P>
	Sixth, the Waiver allows TimeWarner to own and operate television and radio broadcast stations that transmit one-way video and audio programming signals across LATA boundaries by means of terrestrial broadcast facilities.  
  <P>
	In supporting the motion, the Division noted in particular that (1) the proposed Waiver is limited to TimeWarner activities in which U S West has only a minority interest, (2) the authorizations provided by the Waiver with regard to cable television systems engaged in interexchange activities apply only to those systems outside of U S West's telephone service region, and (3) U S West and TimeWarner have committed to the FCC to divest TimeWarner's cable systems within the U S West region within 18 months following the acquisition.  According to the Division, however, direct entry by the Regional Bell Operating Companies or majority-owned affiliates into these markets, or entry through minority-owned affiliates without the same safeguards may present substantially different competitive issues.  See Response of the United States to US West's Motion for a Waiver of the Decree to Permit U S West, Inc., Through its Minority Partnership Investment in Time Warner Entertainment Company, L.P., to Provide Limited Interlata Services and Engage in Limited Manufacturing Activities, <EM>Western Electric Co. </EM>(No. 82-0192) (D.C. Cir. Sept. 27, 1994).   
<P>
	<strong>Lilly/PCS</strong>
<P>
	<EM>In the Matter of Eli Lilly and Company, Inc., </EM>FTC File No. 941-0102 (Oct. 26, 1994), relates to the acquisition of McKesson Corporation by Eli Lilly.  Lilly is a leading producer of pharmaceutical products, including Prozac, an antidepressant; Ceclor, an oral antibiotic; Axid, and anti-ulcer drug; and Humulin, an injectable insulin.  McKesson, through its subsidiary PCS Health Systems, Inc. ("PCS"), provides pharmacy-benefit management ("PBM") services to insurance companies, third-party payors, and other members of the healthcare industry.  According to the complaint, Lilly's acquisition of McKesson and PCS could reduce competition in violation of antitrust laws at two levels of the pharmaceutical industry: (1) the provision of PBM services by national, full-service firms, and (2) the development, manufacture and sale of pharmaceuticals of certain therapeutic types.
<P>
	Specifically, as described in the complaint, PCS maintains a "drug formulary" -- a list of drugs it gives to pharmacies, physicians, and third-party payors to guide them in prescribing and dispensing prescriptions to health plan beneficiaries -- on which Lilly's drug products are listed.  PCS provides claims processing, drug-utilization review, and other PBM services and, according to the complaint, influences the prices and availability of pharmaceutical products under its pharmacy benefit plan.  Lilly and McKesson had entered into a Memorandum of Understanding to discuss whether Lilly might close its distribution centers after the acquisition, and use McKesson as its sole distributor.
<P>
	The complaint alleged that the acquisition (1) would likely lead to the foreclosure of drugs manufactured by companies other than Lilly from the PCS formulary; (2) would enhance the chances for collusion and other illegal anticompetitive conduct among Lilly and other vertically-integrated drug companies; (3) would eliminate PCS as an independent negotiator of pharmaceutical prices with manufacturers; (4) would reduce other manufacturers' incentives to develop innovative pharmaceuticals; (5) could make entry into the relevant markets more difficult, because companies will be required to enter at more than one market level; and (6) could reduce competition among drug wholesalers, because the competitive advantage that control over Lilly drugs will give McKesson.
<P>
	Resolving the allegations, Lilly agreed to a Consent Order requiring the company to ensure that PCS maintain an "open formulary."  Lilly must appoint an independent "Pharmacy and Therapeutics (P&T) Committee" of health care professionals, a majority of whom are unaffiliated with Lilly or PCS, to objectively evaluate drugs for inclusion in the PCS formulary.  As contemplated by the Consent Order, only independent members may cast a vote on P&T Committee decisions.
<P>
	The Consent Order also requires Lilly to ensure that PCS accepts all discounts, rebates, or other concessions offered by Lilly's competitors for drugs that are listed on the formulary and to accurately reflect such discounts in ranking the drugs on the formulary.  Moreover, PCS and Lilly are prohibited from sharing proprietary or other non-public information (e.g., price data) from competitors whose drugs may be placed on a PCS formulary.
<P>
	The Consent Order contains provisions which require Lilly, for a period of five years from the date the Order becomes final, to obtain FTC approval before acquiring an interest in any firm that provides formulary services to more than 2 million people within the U.S.  This five-year prior approval requirement also applies to any exclusive distribution agreement between Lilly and McKesson or any other pharmaceutical wholesaler that would distribute Lilly pharmaceutical products.  Finally, the Consent Order contains various reporting provisions to assist the FTC in monitoring Lilly's compliance.	
<P>
	<strong>Hercules/Alliant</strong>
<P>
	<EM>In the Matter of Alliant Techsystems Inc., </EM>FTC File No. 941-0123 (Nov. 16, 1994), arose from the proposed acquisition of substantially all of the stock and assets of Hercules Aerospace Company by Alliant.  Alliant is a significant competitor in the market for ammunition and munitions, and Hercules is the only United States supplier of propellant used in large caliber ammunition.  According to the complaint, the transaction would allow Alliant's ammunition and munitions division to gain access to competitively significant and non-public information concerning other ammunition and munitions suppliers' products through its new role as a supplier of propellant.  Consequently, the complaint alleged, (1) the acquisition would increase the likelihood that competition between ammunition and munitions suppliers would decrease and (2) advancements in ammunition and munitions research, innovation, and quality would be reduced.  
<P>
	Resolving these concerns, Alliant agreed to a Consent Order under which its  ammunition and munitions division would be prohibited from certain activities.  In particular, the Consent Order prohibits Alliant from disclosing to its ammunition or munitions division any non-public information received in its capacity as a provider of propellant from ammunition or munitions manufacturers.  Alliant is required to use such information only in its capacity as a provider of propellant.  Non-public information is defined in the Consent Order as any information not in the public domain which is furnished by an ammunition or munitions manufacturer to Alliant's propellant division and is designated as proprietary.
<P>
	The Consent Order also requires Alliant to deliver a copy of the Order to any domestic propellant customers prior to obtaining from them any non-public information.  One year from the date the Consent Order becomes final, and annually thereafter for 9 years, Alliant is required to submit to the Commission a report of its compliance with the terms of the Order.
<P>
	<strong>Lockheed/Martin Marietta</strong>
<P>
	<EM>In the Matter of Lockheed Corporation, </EM>FTC File No. 941-0005 (Jan. 13, 1995), arose from the Agreement and Plan of Reorganization entered into by Lockheed and Martin Marietta Corporation whereby the companies agreed to merge their businesses into a newly created corporation, Lockheed Martin.  According to the complaint, Lockheed and Martin compete in the research, development, manufacture, and sale of satellites and expendable satellite launch vehicles.  Lockheed and Martin also have exclusive teaming arrangements, respectively, with Hughes Aircraft Co. and Northrop Grumman Corp. to develop and manufacture satellites for use in space-based early warning systems.  Hughes and Northrop are two of the leading producers of electro-optical sensors for use in military satellites.  Under the companies' teaming arrangements, Hughes and Northrop are barred from bidding on their own or teaming with other firms to bid on Defense Department contracts for space-based early warning systems.  Accordingly, the complaint alleged, the merger would enable Lockheed Martin to tie up two of the leading producers of sensors for space-based early warning systems.
<P>
	The complaint also alleged that the merger would increase the vertical integration in the markets for satellites and expendable launch vehicles ("ELV").  If Lockheed Martin were to launch its satellites on vehicles supplied by its competitors, the merged entity's satellite divisions would obtain proprietary information about these vehicles and would, itself, be able to adjust its prices and services accordingly.  Additionally, the complaint alleged, advancements in ELV research, innovation, and quality would suffer because Lockheed Martin's competitors would fear that the company could "free ride" on their technological developments.
<P>
	With regard to the military aircraft market, the complaint alleged that Martin is the sole manufacturer of the LANTIRN infrared navigation device used in military aircraft and, as such, obtains proprietary information from the aircraft manufacturers who use the device.  Because Lockheed is a significant competitor in the military aircraft market, the complaint alleged that the merged entity's military aircraft division could gain access to its competitors' proprietary data and use that data to determine its own prices and services.  In this way, the merger would raise the same "free rider" problems in the military aircraft market that it would in the markets for satellites and ELVs.  Furthermore, the complaint alleged, Lockheed Martin could modify the LANTIRN in a manner that discriminates against its military aircraft competitors.
<P>
	Resolving these concerns, Lockheed and Martin agreed to a Consent Order under which Lockheed Martin would be prohibited from certain activities.  The Consent Order bars Lockheed Martin from enforcing the exclusivity provision in the teaming agreements; this enables Hughes and Northrop to bid on providing space-based early warning systems to the Defense Department either on their own or in teaming arrangements with other companies.
<P>
	The Consent Order also prohibits Lockheed Martin from gaining access to certain non-public information about its competitors through its satellite and LANTIRN system divisions.  Specifically, the Consent Order prohibits the company from gaining access through its satellite division to information about its competitors' launch vehicles when launching Lockheed Martin satellites on their vehicles.  The Consent Order also bars Lockheed Martin's military aircraft division from gaining access to information not otherwise publicly available about its competitors' military aircraft when providing competitors with the LANTIRN system.  Finally, the Consent Order prohibits Lockheed Martin from modifying the system in such a way as to discriminate against competing military aircraft producers, unless such modifications are sanctioned by the Secretary of Defense or are necessary to meet competitors' technological advancements.

<P>
<H4>Commentary</H4>
<P>
	The wave of recent enforcement activity raises numerous policy issues.  We discuss several important ones here.
<P>
	<strong>The General Attitude towards Vertical Mergers</strong>
<P>
	Enforcement officials, scholars, and others who have considered vertical mergers agree widely on two propositions:  (1) vertical mergers can yield substantial efficiencies, and (2) vertical mergers can result in anticompetitive effects, at least in limited circumstances.  The central problem in framing rules of law with respect to vertical mergers is to balance the conflicting policy implications of those two propositions, and to do so in a manner that does not impose exorbitant transactions costs on private parties and enforcement officials.  The enforcement practices that prevailed through the 1980s and into 1993 reflected an underlying judgment that the prospective anticompetitive effects from vertical mergers would arise so rarely or to such a limited degree, or that the prospective efficiencies from vertical mergers were so overwhelming, that the allocation of resources to identify and challenge adverse transactions was unjustified.  The recent enforcement wave reflects a fundamental rethinking of that earlier assessment.
<P>
	The sources of prospective efficiencies seem to be widely accepted.  According to one commentary,
<P>
	Firms vertically integrate for a variety of reasons, the most common being: (1) to reduce uncertainty over the availability or quality of supplies or the demand for output; (2) to take advantage of available economies of integration that result from eliminating the "middleman"; (3) to protect against monopolistic or oligopolistic behavior of either suppliers or buyers with whom the firm must otherwise deal; and (4) to reduce transactions costs (including sales taxes, marketing expenditures, and the monitoring of contractual performance and externalities, such as "free-rider" problems in connection with point-of-sale services.  Each of these reasons can be procompetitive.  Each may lower the cost of production and distribution to the surviving firm, possibly benefitting consumers in the form of lower resources and, in any event, making more productive use of resources.
<P>
<EM>Non-Horizontal Mergers: Law and Policy, supra, </EM>at 8 (footnotes omitted).  Commentators disagree as to the magnitude of such efficiencies.
<P>
	Similarly, certain sources of prospective anticompetitive effect also seem to be widely accepted; most commentators regard the theories expressed in the <EM>1984 </EM><EM>Merger Guidelines </EM>as valid.  There is disagreement, however, as to the frequency with which the factual basis for invoking such theories is found in the real world.  
<P>
	Some commentators, particularly those applying tools of game theory, also would go beyond the Guidelines and recognize additional theories of anticompetitive effect.  <EM>See, e.g., </EM>Michael H. Riordan and Steven C. Salop, <EM>Evaluating Vertical Mergers: A Post-Chicago Approach, </EM>63 <EM>Antitrust L.J. </EM>513 (1995) (modifying foreclosure theory to take account of raising rivals' costs).  Other commentators, however, question whether such theories are robust and suggest that it may be premature to rely upon them as a basis for legal rules.  <EM>See, e.g., </EM>B. Douglas Bernheim and Robert D. Willig, <EM>Economic Foundations for Vertical Merger Guidelines, </EM>in Course Materials, "Post-Chicago Economics: New Theories -- New Cases?" (Georgetown University Law Center May 1994).  The expansionist view clearly has caught the attention of the enforcement agencies.  <EM>See, e.g., FTC Vertical Enforcement: What's New in RPM and Vertical Mergers, </EM>Prepared Remarks of Mary Lou Steptoe, Acting Director, FTC Bureau of Competition, before the ABA Section of Antitrust Law Program on Distribution Issues (Nov. 4, 1994), at 21-22 (favorably citing Riordan and Salop article).  
<P>
	<strong>The Theories of Adverse Competitive Effect
</strong><P>
	The two main traditional theories of challenge to vertical mergers derived from cases such as <EM>Brown Shoe </EM>and <EM>Ford (Autolite)</EM>: (1) that the merger might foreclose access to customers or (2) that the merger might foreclose access to inputs.  These theories lay dormant for many years; and they were not explicitly recognized in the <EM>1984 Merger Guidelines, </EM>which sanctioned three different theories of challenge, <EM>See generally </EM><EM>supra.  </EM>They were resuscitated, however, in 1994:  the analysis of the long distance market in AT&T/McCaw largely reflected a customer foreclosure theory, and the analysis in <EM>TCI/Liberty </EM>largely reflected an input foreclosure theory.
<P>
	But the recent enforcement actions go considerably beyond the theories found in either the case law or the <EM>1984 Merger Guidelines </EM>in several important respects.  First, they extend beyond inputs and customers to reach complementary products.  <EM>Martin Marietta/General Dynamics </EM>provides an example.  Second and more generally, the actions extend beyond foreclosure (whether of customers, inputs, or complements) to reach discrimination.  Under the theories, even if competitors are not foreclosed, the vertically integrated firm's discrimination in one market might competitively disadvantage rivals in an adjacent market.  <EM>BT/MCI </EM>and the equipment market in <EM>AT&T/McCaw </EM>provide examples.  Third, the actions extend to possible misuse of information obtained from customers or suppliers in one market who are competitors in an adjacent market.  The spate of "firewall" cases -- <EM>Martin Marietta/General Dynamics, AT&T/McCaw, Lilly/PCS, Hercules/Alliant Lockheed/Martin Marietta -- </EM>provide examples.
<P>
	The extension from inputs to complements is easiest to explain and justify.  Inputs and complements are analytically similar, and market power in one has similar effects to market power in the other.  To take one illustration, competition in the market in assembled computer hardware could be affected as readily by power in software (a complement) as by power in chips (an input).
<P>
	The extension from foreclosure to discrimination is more noteworthy and significant, and one is not sure what to make of it.  First, the recent actions that are concerned with discrimination have different attitudes and remedies.  <EM>AT&T/McCaw, </EM>for example, requires equal access and prohibits discrimination.  <EM>Lilly/PCS, </EM>by contrast, contemplates that discrimination will be necessary to attain the transaction's procompetitive efficiencies, but it seeks to regulate the manner in which the discrimination will be exercised.  Second, at roughly the same time that the enforcement agencies were pressing for consent order provisions limiting discrimination, they were challenging private contract provisions that had similar purposes.  <EM>See, e.g., </EM>Proposed Final Judgment and Competitive Impact Statement, <EM>United States v. Delta Dental Plan of Arizona,</EM>  59 Fed. Reg. 47349 (Sept. 15, 1994) (consent order barring most-favored-nation clause, under which dominant dental insurer would have received the lowest price charged by the provider to any patient or competing dental plan); Proposed Final Judgment and Competitive Impact Statement, <EM>United States v. Vision Service Plan,</EM> 60 Fed. Reg. 5210 (Jan. 26, 1995) (consent order barring most-favored-nation clause in agreements of national vision plan insurer).  Perhaps the lesson is that provisions limiting discrimination must arise from public regulation, not private contract.  Or perhaps the lesson is that leading firms cannot discriminate against others, but must suffer discrimination directed against themselves.  (But if the latter is the case, why do some of the complaints lack allegations of market power?) The ambiguity and confusion over the treatment of discrimination is nothing new, of course  -- as seen in the history of Robinson-Patman enforcement and policy, antitrust has long had a schizoid view towards discrimination.
<P>
	The other new theory of vertical challenge -- anticompetitive information transfer to be remedied through firewalls -- also holds significant policy intrigue.  First, it is difficult to characterize the theory as an extension of any of the historical theories of challenge.  The closest prior theory is probably the section of the <EM>1984 Merger Guidelines </EM>relating to monitoring of prices at the retail level, but that theory seems fundamentally different, limited as it is to horizontal effects and consumer products.  Second, the mechanism by which information transfer will have adverse competitive effect is unclear.  Would the vertically integrated firm use the newly-acquired proprietary information of its rival to predate against the rival?  Or would the vertically integrated firm use the information to elevate prices artificially in tacit horizontal collusion with the rival?  Viewed ex ante, one scenario seems as likely as the other; it is far from clear, however, that the first scenario (excessive rivalry) involves an interest deserving of antitrust protection.  Third, there is some question as to whether the protections afforded by consent order are necessary.  Private firms enter into confidentiality agreements all the time.  Unless the market power involved in the transaction is overwhelming, one would expect rival/customers or rival/suppliers to impose their own restrictions on information transfer as a condition of dealing with the vertically integrated firm.  One FTC Commissioner thoughtfully raised the same question in dissenting from <EM>Martin Marietta/General Dynamics.  See </EM>Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Deborah K. Owen on Proposed Consent Agreement with Martin Marietta Corp., File No. 941-0038  ("Vertical integration, and combinations designed to achieve the efficiencies of such integration, are common phenomena, particularly in the aerospace industry.  Accordingly, it would seem that there are already ample opportunities for the sort of abuse of information-sharing which concerns the Commission.  However, equally common are contractual obligations between vertically integrated companies, and firms that do business with one of their divisions, to prevent the sharing of those firms' confidential business information with other parts of the conglomerate with which they compete.")
<P>
	<strong>Important Procedural Considerations</strong>
<P>
	The consent settlements resolving the various vertical enforcement actions have several important procedural aspects that warrant mention.
<P>
	First, it should be underscored that all of the Orders and Judgments in the current enforcement wave are <EM>consent </EM>resolutions.  The attitude of the courts towards vertical mergers remains untested, and the willingness of the courts to adopt some of the more novel theories being advanced by the enforcement agencies in the current wave is far from clear.  Regrettably, until the courts are heard on these issues, the enforcement agencies are likely to persevere in researching the law by reading their own releases.
<P>
	Second, the consent settlements are behavioral, not structural, in nature.  Unlike the typical horizontal merger consent order, which addresses competitive concerns by structuring a limited, one-time divestiture (perhaps with ancillary requirements or fencing-in provisions), the typical vertical merger consent order is proving to address competitive concerns by regulating the vertically integrated firm's conduct on an ongoing basis.  This has two immediate implications: (a) the consent settlements frequently contain provisions that are highly regulatory in nature, and (b) the enforcement agencies almost certainly will have an unusually active monitoring role and will sometimes be cast in the role of industry regulator.  The most striking example is <EM>BT/MCI, </EM>in which the Antitrust Division has elected to become the conduit by which information is circulated through the industry.
<P>
	Third, because the consent settlements impose ongoing restrictions on the manner in which the defendant(s) or respondent(s) conduct business, the duration of the Order or Judgment has greater significance than in the usual merger matter.  Some of the Orders and Judgments, particularly those in industries in which competitive conditions are rapidly evolving, provide for quick expiration.  <EM>BT/MCI </EM>is a five-year decree.  <EM>AT&T/McCaw </EM>and <EM>Lilly/PCS </EM>are ten-year decrees.  (Dissenting from <EM>Lilly/PCS, </EM>one Commissioner complained that "there is no justification for making the duration of the order half that of other Commission orders." Dissenting Statement of Commissioner Mary L. Azcuenaga.)
<P>
	Fourth and related, the anticipation of changed competitive conditions has caused the parties in some instances to include non-standard modification provisions.  The most noteworthy is in <EM>AT&T/McCaw.  </EM>At least two factors -- the auctioning of spectrum that will be used for new technology that will compete with cellular service, and the possibility of fundamental change in the MFJ, through either legislation or other means -- make changed conditions of law and fact foreseeable within the term of the Consent Judgment.  Under traditional standards, if changed conditions are foreseeable when a consent order is under negotiation, the changes cannot be considered as justifications supporting modification.  
<P><EM>See </EM><EM>United States v. Swift & Co.</EM>, 286 U.S. 106, 119 (1932) ("Nothing less than a clear showing of grievous wrong evoked by new and unforeseen conditions should lead us to change what was decreed after years of litigation with the consent of all concerned").  The <EM>Swift </EM>standard has been relaxed in recent years, <EM>see </EM><EM>Rufo v. Inmates of Suffolk County Jail</EM>, 112 S. Ct. 748, 760 (1992) (revision of decree warranted by "significant change in factual conditions or in law" or when "enforcement of the decree without modification would be detrimental to the public interest"); <EM>United States v. Western Electric Co</EM>., 154 F.R.D. 1, 78 (D.D.C. 1994) (decision arising from <EM>AT&T/McCaw </EM>determining "not without considerable hesititation" that <EM>Rufo, </EM>not <EM>Swift, </EM>is correct standard for evaluating contested modification petitions).  The modification standard in the <EM>AT&T/McCaw </EM>Consent Judgment is drafted so as to permit modifications more readily than under either a <EM>Swift </EM>standard or a <EM>Rufo </EM>standard.<P>
<center><HR><p>
<A HREF="http:/default.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/hp.gif" ALT="[Home Page]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/groups.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/pg.gif" ALT="[Practice Groups]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/attorn.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/atty.gif" alt="[Attorneys]"></A><br><A HREF="http:/menu/articles.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/art1.gif" alt="[Articles]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/leglink.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/lr.gif" alt="[Legal Resources]"></A> <A HREF="http:/menu/recruit.htm"><IMG SRC="/gif/recruit.jpg" ALT="Recruiting"></A></center>
</body>
</html>
