<html>
<head>
<title>United States Antitrust Implications of Doing Business Overseas: Basic Principles</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="ffffff" body text="#000000" body link="#00009c" body vlink="#8e2323">

<CENTER><img src="/gif/k-s2b.gif"><p>
<HR><p>
<h1>United States Antitrust Implications of Doing Business Overseas: Basic Principles</h1>
<p>
<h2><a href="/htm/blumenth.htm">William Blumenthal</a> and David L. Finnegan</h2>
<H6>Originally prepared for program materials before Institute of Continuing Legal Education in Georgia, <EM>Antitrust in a Global Economy</EM> (Oct. 13, 1995)</H6>
<HR><p>
</CENTER>
<p>
The antitrust laws of the United States apply in general terms to business abroad, but the specifics of their application present numerous special issues.  The first family of issues relates to United States jurisdiction over extraterritorial conduct.  The second family of issues relates to exemptions, defenses, and immunities arising from national policies that may be in conflict with the policies underlying the antitrust laws.  Other families of issues relate to discovery, remedies, and relief.  
<P>
This paper is intended to provide a brief summary of basic principles in the field.  For more detailed treatment the reader may wish to consult the following sources: 2 ABA Antitrust Section, <EM>Antitrust Law Developments </EM>(3d ed. 1992) [hereinafter <EM>Antitrust Law Developments</EM>]; 1 Phillip E. Areeda & Donald F. Turner, <EM>Antitrust Law</EM> (1978); James R. Atwood & Kingman Brewster, <EM>Antitrust and American Business Abroad</EM> (2d ed. 1981); Barry E. Hawk, United States, <EM>Common Market and International Antitrust: A Comparative Guide </EM>(1994 supp.); U.S. Department of Justice & Federal Trade Commission, <EM>Antitrust Enforcement Guidelines for International Operations</EM> (1995) [hereinafter <EM>Federal Guidelines</EM>].
<P>
<H3>I. Extraterritorial Application of the Antitrust Laws</H3>
<P>
The reach of the United States antitrust laws is not limited to conduct that occurs within the territorial boundaries of the United States.  As a general jurisdictional principle, the United States antitrust laws reach conduct that affects the domestic or foreign commerce of the United States, regardless of the location of the conduct or the nationality of the participants.   The specifics depend on the particular antitrust statute involved.  In the discussion that follows, we consider subject matter jurisdiction first under the Sherman Act and then under certain other antitrust statutes -- the Federal Trade Commission Act, the Clayton Act, and the Robinson-Patman Act.  We then turn to the  related issues of venue, personal jurisdiction, and service of process.
<P>
<STRONG>A.  Sherman Act</STRONG>
<P>
The Sherman Act proscribes anticompetitive contracts, combinations and conspiracies in restraint of trade or commerce, 15 U.S.C.  1, and monopolization or attempts to monopolize trade or commerce, id.  2, "among the several states or with foreign nations."
<P>
<STRONG>1.  Subject Matter Jurisdiction
</STRONG><P>
Anticompetitive conduct may violate the Sherman Act regardless of where the conduct occurs or the nationalities of the persons involved.  Federal Guidelines   3.1.  As a general matter, an "effects" test is used to determine subject matter jurisdiction over the conduct in question.  See, e.g., <EM>United Phosphorous, Ltd. v. Angus Chemical Co.</EM>, 1994 U.S. Dist. LEXIS 14786 (N.D. Ill. Oct. 13, 1994) (collecting authority and stating "conduct on American soil is not always sufficient to prove effect on domestic commerce because it is the situs of the effect, not the conduct, which is crucial").  This effects test takes similar, but slightly different forms depending on whether it is being applied to import commerce or other foreign commerce. 
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Import Commerce</STRONG></EM>.   With respect to foreign import commerce, "the Sherman Act applies to foreign conduct that was meant to produce and did in fact produce some substantial effect in the United States."  <EM>Hartford Fire Ins. Co. v. California</EM>, 113 S.Ct. 2891, 2909 (1993).
<P>
<EM><STRONG>Other Foreign Commerce</STRONG></EM>.   The Foreign Trade Antitrust Improvements Act, codified at 15 U.S.C.  6a, governs the determination of subject matter jurisdiction with respect to foreign commerce other than imports.  The FTAIA limits subject matter jurisdiction over United States export commerce to conduct having a "direct, substantial and reasonably foreseeable" effect on domestic United States commerce, on United States import trade, or on the export commerce of a person engaged in such commerce in the United States.
<P>
<STRONG>2.  Standing</STRONG>
<P>
As with any antitrust action, a plaintiff must establish valid antitrust injury.   See generally <EM>Associated General Contractors, Inc. V. California State Council of Carpenters</EM>, 459 U.S. 519 (1983); 1 <EM>Antitrust Law Developments</EM> 643-65.  In actions involving export commerce, the FTAIA limits recovery only to "injury to export business in the United States."  If the private antitrust plaintiff is not among the class of injured United States exporters, it will not have standing to bring suit.  This tends to limit the rights of foreign corporations under United States antitrust laws.
<P>
<STRONG>3.  Comity Considerations in Asserting Jurisdiction
</STRONG><P>
International comity is an extension of the principle of sovereignty,  "the recognition which one nation allows within its territory to the legislative, executive and judicial acts of another nation."  <EM>Hilton v. Guyot</EM>, 159 U.S. 113, 164 (1895).  Courts may refrain from exercising jurisdiction over a dispute if the exercise of such jurisdiction would in some manner affect the significant interests of a foreign nation.  
<P>
In <EM>Hartford Fire Insurance Co. v. California</EM>, 113 S. Ct. 2891 (1993), the Supreme Court evaluated whether the district court had properly exercised subject matter jurisdiction over allegedly anticompetitive conduct by foreign reinsurers in the United Kingdom.  The Court held that comity requires abstention in this context only where "there is in fact a true conflict between domestic and foreign law."  Id. at 2910  No true conflict existed in Hartford Fire because the foreign reinsurers did not face conflicting requirements under the United States and United Kingdom regulatory regimes.  The result of this holding may be that fewer courts will refuse to exercise jurisdiction on international comity grounds.
<P>
While recognizing the Supreme Court's decision in Hartford Fire, the 1995 <EM>Federal Guidelines</EM> identify various relevant factors that will be weighed by the enforcement agencies in determining whether to bring an enforcement action:  (a) the relative significance to the alleged violation of conduct within the United States as compared to conduct abroad;  (b) the nationality of the persons involved in or affected by the conduct;  (c) the presence or absence of a purpose to affect United States consumers, markets and exporters;  (d) the relative significance and foreseeability of the effects of the conduct on the United States as compared to the effects abroad;  (e) the existence of reasonable expectations that would be furthered or defeated by the action;  (f) the degree of conflict with foreign law or articulated foreign economic policies;  (g) the extent to which the enforcement activities of another country with respect to the same persons, including remedies resulting from those activities, may be affected; and  (h) the effectiveness of foreign enforcement as compared to U.S. enforcement action.  See <EM>Federal Guidelines</EM>  3.2.
<P>
"Reasonableness" tests employing similar relevant factors have been formulated by the courts, e.g., <EM>Timberlane Lumber Co. v. Bank of America National Trust & Savings Ass'n</EM>, 549 F.2d 597, 614 (9th Cir. 1976), and in the Restatement (Third) of the Foreign Relations Law of the United States  403(2)  (1987).
<P>
<STRONG>B.  Related Issues under Other Antitrust Statutes
</STRONG><P>
<STRONG>1.  Federal Trade Commission Act
</STRONG><P>
The Federal Trade Commission Act prohibits "[u]nfair methods of competition in or affecting commerce, and unfair or deceptive acts or practices in or affecting commerce." 15 U.S.C.  45(a)(3).  The FTC Act defines the term "commerce" to mean "commerce among the several states or with foreign nations."  A 1982 amendment limited the extraterritorial reach of the FTC Act to only those unfair methods of competition that involve United States domestic and import commerce unless the methods "have a direct, substantial and reasonably foreseeable effect" on United States domestic or import commerce or on the export commerce of a person engaged in such commerce in the United States.
<P>
<STRONG>2.  Clayton Act
</STRONG><P>
Section 1 of the Clayton Act defines commerce to include "commerce with foreign nations."  15 U.S.C.  12.  Section 3 of the Clayton Act reaches certain types of exclusive dealing relating to the sale of goods and commodities, but only when sold "for use, consumption or resale in the United States."  Id.  14.  
<P>
Section 7 of the Clayton Act applies to mergers and acquisitions between persons engaged "in commerce" or whose activities "effect commerce."  Id.  18.  Acquisitions involving foreign companies may thus be covered by this provision.  See generally ABA Antitrust Section, Monograph No. 12, Horizontal Mergers: Law and Policy 141-42 (1986).
<P>
<STRONG>3.  Robinson-Patman Act
</STRONG><P>
The price discrimination provision of Section 2(a) of the Robinson-Patman Act applies only to transaction involving goods and commodities "for use, consumption or resale in the United States."  15 U.S.C.  13(a).  Other provisions of the Robinson-Patman Act -- Sections 2(c), (d), (e) and (f) --  contain no requirement that goods be used or resold in the United States.  See id.  13(c-f).  As such, these provisions may apply to export commerce.  See, e.g., <EM>Baysoy v. Jessup Steel Co.</EM>, 90 F. Supp. 303 (W.D. Pa. 1950).
<P>
The United States antidumping laws include prohibitions on certain types of predatory pricing by U.S. importers.  15 U.S.C.  72.  Antidumping remedies are available for relief against other types of illegal "less-than-fair-value" sales. 
<P>
<STRONG>C. Venue
</STRONG><P>
Depending on the identities of the parties, the venue provisions of the federal antitrust laws may also be material to cases involving extraterritorial conduct.   Section 4 of the Clayton Act provides that private actions for treble damages may be brought in any district "in which the defendant resides or is found or has an agent."  15 U.S.C.  15.  A Clayton Act suit involving a corporate defendant may be brought in the district where the defendant "is an inhabitant, but also in any district where it may be found or transacts business."  15 U.S.C.  22.  A corporate defendant is "found" if there is "proof of continuous local activities" in the district.  Such a defendant has an agent in the district if it has an employee or other representative conducting business in the district on its behalf.  Several factors relating to the defendant's contacts with a district will be evaluated by the court in determining whether a corporate defendant "transacts business" in the district.  See generally <EM>United States v. Scophony Co.</EM>, 33 U.S. 795 (1948).
<P>
The general federal venue statute may also provide a basis for determining proper venue in antitrust litigation.  28 U.S.C.  1391.  The statute makes clear that "an alien may be sued in any district." 28 U.S.C.  1391(d).  
<P>
<STRONG>D.  Personal Jurisdiction
</STRONG><P>
Personal jurisdiction in antitrust suits is determined in the same manner as other suits brought in federal court.  Thus, the "minimum contacts" and fairness/convenience test established by <EM>International Shoe Co. v. Washington</EM>, 326 U.S. 310 (1945), and its progeny apply.  Personal jurisdiction will be recognized where the defendant acts affirmatively to "purposefully avail" himself of the privilege of transacting business in the jurisdiction.  <EM>Burger King v. Rudzewicz</EM>, 471 U.S. 462, 474 (1985).
<P>
In certain antitrust cases, activities by foreigners in foreign countries that are directed towards the United States or that are designed to affect the United States may give rise to personal jurisdiction.  Consolidated Gold Fields, <EM>PLC v. Anglo American Corp</EM>., 698 F. Supp. 487 (S.D.N.Y. 1988), aff'd in part and rev'd in part sub nom. Consolidated Gold Fields, <EM>PLC v. Minorco</EM>, SA, 871 F.2d 252 (2d Cir.), cert. dismissed, 492 U.S. 939 (1989). 
<P>
<STRONG>E.  Service of Process
</STRONG><P>
Section 12 of the Clayton Act authorizes service of process on corporate defendants "in the district in which it is an inhabitant, or wherever it may be found."  15 U.S.C.  22.  Under the Clayton Act, extraterritorial service of process is thus permitted.  See <EM>Hoffman Motors Corp. v. Alfa Romeo</EM>, SpA, 244 F. Supp. 70, 79-80 (S.D.N.Y. 1965) (service on a corporation at its overseas corporate headquarters permitted).  Such service is governed by Fed. R. Civ. P. 4.
<P>
<H3>II.     Exemptions, Defenses, and Immunities
</H3><P>

Many national policies other than antitrust relate to foreign commerce.  The various policies are not always in harmony, and in numerous instances Congress and the courts have elected to subordinate antitrust and competition considerations to other policies that are viewed as more vital.  In the discussion that follows we review a variety of exemptions, defenses, and immunities that come into play in connection with foreign commerce.
<P>
<STRONG>A.  Sovereign Immunity 
</STRONG><P>
United States courts have traditionally recognized the immunity of a foreign sovereign from suit in the United States.  See, e.g., <EM>The Schooner Exchange v. M'Faddon</EM>, 11 U.S. (7 Cranch) 116 (1812) (Marshall, C.J.) (first recognition of doctrine before Supreme Court).  Through 1976 this principle applied to suits brought under the United States antitrust laws; and questions of sovereign immunity were commonly addressed by both the executive and judicial branches, with the views of the executive commonly regarded as binding on the courts.  See generally 2 <EM>Antitrust Law Developments</EM> 899.
<P>
With its enactment in 1976 of the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act, 28 U.S.C.  1602-11, Congress provided an important exception to this general principle. The Act permits antitrust and other civil actions against the instrumentalities of foreign sovereigns for conduct while engaging in commercial activities.  The FSIA is the exclusive source in the United States of subject matter jurisdiction over suits involving foreign states or instrumentalities.  Republic of <EM>Argentina v. Weltover, Inc.</EM>, 112 S.Ct. 2160, 2164 (1992).
<P>
The key distinction for purposes of the FSIA is between "commercial" activity and "governmental" activity.  Under the FSIA, a commercial activity is "either a regular course of commercial conduct or a particular commercial transaction or act."  The character of the act is determined "by reference to the nature of the course of conduct or particular transaction or act, rather than by reference to its purpose."  28 U.S.C.  1603(d).  See Weltover, 112 S.Ct. at 2166 ("when a foreign government acts, not as a regulator of a market, but in the manner of a private player within it, the foreign sovereign's actions are commercial' within the meaning of the FSIA").  In making its determination, a court will consider whether the conduct is of a type that only sovereign governments can perform.  <EM>Saudi Arabia v. Nelson</EM>, 113 S.Ct. 1471 (1993).  Interpreting the state of the law, the <EM>Federal Guidelines</EM> state at   3.31:  "As a practical matter, most activities of foreign government-owned corporations operating in the commercial marketplace will be subject to U.S. antitrust laws to the same extent as the activities of foreign privately-owned firms."
<P>
A suit subject to FSIA jurisdiction must possess a substantial United States nexus.  The suit must be based on (1) a commercial activity carried on in the United States by a foreign state or (2) an act performed in the United States in connection with a commercial activity carried on elsewhere or (3) an act outside the United States in connection with a commercial activity provided that the act causes a "direct effect" in the U.S.  28 U.S.C.  1605(a)(3).   See <EM>United World Trade, Inc. v. Mangyshlakneft Oil Production Ass'n,</EM> 33 F.3d 1232, 1238 (10th Cir. 1994)  (in dispute involving oil transaction in Kazakhstan, contract requirement that payment be made in dollars through a United States bank insufficient to invoke jurisdiction under FSIA because "Congress did not intend to provide jurisdiction whenever the ripples caused by an overseas transaction manage eventually to reach the shores of the United States").
<P>
<STRONG>B.  Act of State
</STRONG><P>
The "act of state" doctrine is a federal common law rule that requires judicial abstention where the specific conduct complained of is a public act of the foreign sovereign within its territorial jurisdiction on matters pertaining to its governmental sovereignty.  <EM>W.S. Kirkpatrick & Co. v. Environmental Tectonics Corp.</EM>, 493 U.S. 400, 409 (1990) ("The act of state doctrine . . . merely requires that . . . the acts of foreign sovereigns taken within their own jurisdictions shall be deemed valid").  Under the doctrine, courts have refused to adjudicate claims or issues that would require the court to judge the legality of the sovereign act of a foreign state.  The trend, however, is toward narrow construction and application of the doctrine.  See, e.g., <EM>Grupo Protexa, S.A. v. All American Marine Slip</EM>, 20 F.3d 1224 (3d Cir.), cert. denied, 115 S.Ct. 481 (1994) (examination of the validity of a Mexican decision to remove a sunken wreck from a bay off the coast of Mexico not barred by act of state doctrine).  Courts have generally held that the act of state doctrine applies only to a sovereign's public, as opposed to private or commercial acts. 
<P>
Under the <EM>Federal Guidelines</EM>  3.33, the enforcement agencies may refrain from bringing an enforcement action based on the act of state doctrine where a restraint on competition arises directly from the act of a foreign sovereign, such as the grant of a license, award of a contract, or expropriation of property.  The agencies will not challenge foreign acts of state if the facts and circumstances indicate that (1) the specific conduct complained of is a public act of a sovereign, (2) the act was taken within the territorial jurisdiction of the sovereign, and (3) the matter is governmental rather than commercial.
<P>
<STRONG>C.  Foreign Sovereign Compulsion
</STRONG><P>
Although conduct by private parties in violation of United States antitrust laws is not immunized from prosecution by virtue of having been encouraged or approved by a foreign sovereign, courts generally will not impose antitrust liability if the offending conduct results from the compulsion of a foreign government.  (This doctrine may be viewed as foreign-conduct analogue to the domestic-conduct "state action doctrine," see generally 2 <EM>Antitrust Law</EM> Developments 965-89.)  Compulsion is a basis for determining that a true conflict of laws existed between United States law and that of a foreign country.  <EM>Hartford Fire Insurance Co. v. California</EM>, 113 S.Ct. 2891, 2910-11 (1993).  This doctrine is generally interpreted narrowly.  It will not be applied where private conduct was simply sanctioned or assisted by a foreign government.
<P>
The foreign sovereign compulsion defense has been successfully invoked in at least one reported case.  <EM>Interamerican Refining Corp. v. Texaco Maracaibo, Inc.</EM>, 307 F.Supp. 1291 (D. Del. 1970) (defendant not liable under Sherman Act for an illegal group boycott where ordered by foreign government not to sell oil to a particular refiner).
<P>
<STRONG>D.  <EM>Noerr-Pennington</EM>
</STRONG><P>
The "<EM>Noerr-Pennington </EM>doctrine" refers to a body of principles under which legitimate efforts to solicit government action have received antitrust immunity, notwithstanding the fact that those efforts may handicap competitors, suppress rivalry, or otherwise restrict competition.  See generally 2 <EM>Antitrust Law Developments</EM> 989-1016 (discussing <EM>Eastern Railroad Presidents Conference v. Noerr Motor Freight, Inc.</EM>, 365 U.S. 127 (1961); <EM>United Mine Workers v. Pennington</EM>, 381 U.S. 657 (1965); and related cases).  The Supreme Court has not ruled on whether the doctrine applies to petitioning of foreign governments, and lower courts are split on the issue. 
<P>
In particular, several courts have questioned the applicability of the doctrine outside the context of the United States political process.  See, e.g., <EM>Occidental Petroleum Corp. v. Buttes Gas & Oil Co.,</EM> 331 F. Supp. 92, 108 (C.D. Cal. 1971), aff'd per curiam, 461 F.2d 1261 (9th Cir.), cert. denied, 409 U.S. 950 (1972);<EM> Laker Airways v. Pan Am. World Airways</EM>, 604 F. Supp. 280, 287 n.20 (D.D.C. 1984).  Other courts have exhibited a willingness to apply the doctrine in the international context.  See, e.g., <EM>Coastal States Marketing, Inc. v. Hunt</EM>, 694 F.2d 1358, 1372 (5th Cir. 1983).
<P>
The enforcement agencies have stated that they will apply the <EM>Noerr-Pennington </EM>doctrine to conduct designed to influence foreign governments in the same manner that the doctrine is applied in the context of the United States government.  <EM>Federal Guidelines</EM>  3.34. 
<P>
<STRONG>E.  Statutory Exemptions
</STRONG><P>
<STRONG>1.  Webb-Pomerene Act
</STRONG><P>
Enacted in 1918, the Webb-Pomerene Act, 15 U.S.C.  61-65, provides antitrust immunity for trade associations engaged exclusively in the export "of goods, wares and merchandise."  This immunity does not extend to any conduct by trade associations that has an anticompetitive impact in the United States or that injures its domestic competitors.  In order to be eligible for this protection, trade associations must file articles of incorporation and annual reports with the FTC.
<P>
<STRONG>2.  Certificates of Review
</STRONG><P>
Under the Export Trading Company Act of 1982, persons may obtain export trade certificates of review from the Secretary of Commerce with the concurrence of the Attorney General.  15 U.S.C.  4011-21.  Persons named in the certificate obtain limited immunity from the application of state and federal antitrust laws for activities falling within and complying with the terms of the certificate.
<P>
In order to obtain a certificate, the applicant must show that the export conduct in question (a) will result in neither a substantial lessening of competition or restraint of trade within the United States nor a substantial restraint of the export trade of any competitor; (b) will not unreasonably enhance, stabilize or depress prices in the United States for the class of goods or services covered by the certificate; (c) will not constitute unfair methods of competition against competitors engaged in the export of the class of goods or services; and (d) will not include any act that may reasonably be expected to result in the sale for consumption or resale in the United States of such goods or services.  15 U.S.C.  4013(a).
<P>
Certificate holders are protected against criminal and treble damage liability under the antitrust laws for all conduct specified in the certificate, 15 U.S.C.  4016(b), but a plaintiff may still obtain actual damages or injunctive relief.  Certificate holders remain liable in both private and government enforcement actions for anticompetitive conduct falling outside the terms of the certificate.  
<P>
Certificates may be revoked at any time by the Secretary of Commerce or Attorney General if a determination is made that the certificate holder's activities cease to comply with any of the statutory criteria. Certificates procured by fraud are void ab initio.  15 U.S.C.  4013(f).
<P>
<STRONG>3.  Cooperative Research and Production
</STRONG><P>
The National Cooperative Research and Production Act, 15 U.S.C.  4301-06, establishes a voluntary reporting mechanism under which parties may notify the Attorney General and FTC about joint research and development and joint production ventures.  The Act requires courts to apply a rule of reason test to activities within the scope of the notification:  conduct "shall be judged on the basis of its reasonableness, taking into account all relevant factors affecting competition, including, but not limited to, effects on competition in properly defined, relevant research, development, product, process and service markets."  15 U.S.C.  4302.  Where private plaintiffs are able to establish that the conduct is unlawful under the reasonableness standard, the Act limits the antitrust relief to actual rather than treble damages, provided that a production joint ventures will benefit from the detrebling provision only if (a) its principal production facilities are located within the U.S. or its territories and (b) "each person who controls any party to such venture (including the party itself) is a United States person, or a foreign person from a country whose law accords antitrust treatment no less favorable to United States persons than to such country's domestic persons with respect to participation in joint ventures for production."  15 U.S.C.  4306(2).
<P>
<STRONG>4.  National Defense
</STRONG><P>
The Defense Production Act of 1950 establishes antitrust immunity for persons who participate at the request of the President in certain national defense programs relating to preparedness, production, and supply.  50 U.S.C. App.  2158.  The immunity also extends to certain voluntary agreements and plans of action for international allocation of petroleum products.  50 U.S.C. App.  2158a.
<P>
<H3>III.     Discovery, Remedies, and Relief in Foreign Commerce Cases
</H3><P>
Operations outside of the United States also complicate discovery and relief in antitrust cases.  We summarize related issues here.
<P>
<STRONG>A.  Procedures for Obtaining Foreign Documents
</STRONG><P>
If a court has proper jurisdiction over a party and that party has "possession, custody or control" of documents subject to a discovery request, the physical location of documents does not determine whether they must be produced.  Fed. R. Civ. P. 34.  The court, however, generally will weigh the national interests of the country in which the documents are located in determining whether to exercise its power to compel production. See <EM>Societe Nationale Industrielle Aerospatiale v. United States District Court</EM>, 482 U.S. 522, 546 (1987).  The factors to be weighed include the importance of the requested discovery, the degree of specificity of the request, the country of origin of the requested material, the availability of alternative means of obtaining the requested material, and the extent to which important interests of the countries involved would be undermined.  Id.
<P>
Courts may use letters rogatory as a means of to facilitate discovery.  Such letters are essentially a request to the courts of another country to use their powers and procedures as a matter of comity to assist discovery in the United States.  Letters rogatory may be transmitted directly by the United States court or sent via the U.S. Department of State.  28 U.S.C.  1781.  See also Hague Convention on the Taking of Evidence Abroad in Civil or Commercial Matters, 28 U.S.T. 2555, T.I.A.S. No. 7444, reprinted in 28 U.S.C.  1781.
<P>
<STRONG>B. Foreign Blocking Statutes
</STRONG><P>
Because of concerns over United States intrusion into sovereign matters, several countries have enacted "blocking statutes" that limit the extent to which persons subject to their jurisdiction may comply with foreign discovery requests.  Prominent examples include Australia, Canada, France, South Africa, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom.
<P>
<STRONG>C.  International Cooperative Enforcement 
</STRONG><P>
The International Antitrust Enforcement Assistance Act was signed into law in November 1994.  Pub. L. No. 103-438.  The IAEAA provides United States enforcement agencies with the authority to enter into mutual assistance agreements with foreign antitrust authorities pursuant to which, among other things, the governments may exchange evidence that would otherwise be protected from disclosure.
<P>
In 1991, prior to the passage of the IAEAA, the United States had entered into an antitrust cooperation agreement with the European Union.  A similar cooperation agreement with Canada became effective on August 3, 1995.  That agreement contains provisions for the exchange of information about enforcement activities and cooperation and coordination in the enforcement of antitrust laws.  See 69 Antitrust & Trade Reg. Rep. (BNA) 174 (Aug. 10, 1995).
<P>
<STRONG>D. Comity Considerations in Fashioning Relief
</STRONG><P>
United States courts have the authority to order affirmative relief abroad.  See <EM>United States v. Holophane Co</EM>., 1954 Trade Cas. (CCH)  67,679 (S.D. Ohio 1954), aff'd per curiam, 352 U.S. 903 (1956).  In ordering relief for anticompetitive conduct that has a foreign nexus, particularly injunctive relief,  courts will consider the difficulty of enforcing the antitrust decree abroad and will take international comity into account.  See, e.g., <EM>United States v. Watchmakers of Switzerland Information Center, Inc.</EM>,1963 Trade Cas. (CCH)  70,600 (S.D.N.Y. 1962), order modified, 1965 Trade Cas. (CCH)  71,352 (S.D.N.Y. 1965).
<P>
<STRONG>E. Sovereignty and Extraterritoriality Considerations in Fashioning Relief
</STRONG><P>
Extraterritorial application and enforcement of  antitrust laws has sometimes engendered concern and even resentment among foreign countries, many of which view such action as a violation of their national sovereignty. Many countries have reacted by enacting blocking statutes that, in addition to limiting discovery within their territorial jurisdictions, see supra Part III.B, serve to bar certain types of enforcement.  In the United Kingdom, for example, the Secretary of Trade may bar enforcement of foreign judgments that involve multiple damage awards.  To address and remedy such concerns, the United States and a number of other countries have entered into bilateral cooperation agreements that facilitate enforcement of both United States and foreign antitrust laws.<P>
